<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOUSTON-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ For the longest time, the Houston Cougars whirred along
like a sleek, fine-tuned car out for a Sunday drive as they played
on even terms with No. 18 Texas at the Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   Then the battery that fires the Cougars _ the senior tandem of
Gee Gervin and Kenny Younger _ went to the sideline in the second
half because of foul problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns used their absence and some inspired defensive
play from reserve William Wyatt to break out of a 57-all tie and
cruise to a 90-80 victory before a crowd of 7,926.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a close game,'' said UH coach Clyde Drexler. ``I
thought the difference in the game was the fact that Kenny Younger
was in foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that we put in to replace Kenny were not playing at
the same level that everyone else on the floor was. That really
cost us about 10 to 15 points at a stretch in the game that was
really crucial for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although four Longhorns scored in double figures and 7-foot
center Chris Mihm tied his career high and school record with seven
blocked shots, coach Rick Barnes wasn't hesitant about who he felt
was most instrumental in Texas' improving to 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, the most valuable player of this game was William
Wyatt,'' he said of the reserve center who has been injured much of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Gervin and Younger are the fire for the Cougars. But when they
went out, the bulk of the offensive burden fell to George Williams,
who had matched Younger over the first 20 minutes with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt, however, shut down the 6-8 freshman when it counted most.
</P>
<P>
   Over the final 12:22, after a follow tip by Williams tied the
game for the final time at 57, he made just one basket, a jumper at
the 9:59 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role on this team is to play hard and play good defense,''
said Wyatt. ``When I came in, I did what I wanted to do, and that
was to shut down George Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished with a game-high 23 points and 12 rebounds.
Younger had 16 points and Gervin 20 for the Cougars (6-7), who were
held to 38-percent shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Four games ago, Barnes, in an effort to inspire more movement
from the Longhorns, went to a starting lineup that features three
guards, Mihm and forward Gabe Muoneke.
</P>
<P>
   Though it had the desired effect offensively Sunday, Barnes said
it proved detrimental on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have gone to the bigger lineup sooner,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams bedeviled the shorter Longhorns in and around the paint
until Wyatt was summoned from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, meanwhile, got offense from everyone to hit the
floor. Mihm led with 20 points and 13 rebounds, his eighth double
double in 11 games and the 35th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke garnered 17 points while shooting 6-for-10 from the
floor. Backup center Chris Owens (6-for-9 from the field) was good
for 14 points, and guard William Clay added 12.
</P>
<P>
   Texas shot 52.4 percent (54.8 percent in the second half) and
outrebounded the Cougars 46-39.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was upset, however, over a 19-for-30 performance from the
free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured five ties in the first half. And while the
Longhorns were up 36-25 with five minutes left in the half, they
led by only 40-37 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   There were another seven ties over the first seven minutes of
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   After the tie at 57, Gervin was called for charging and took a
seat with his third personal foul with 11:17 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Younger was already there, having picked up his fourth personal
at the 15:28 mark.
</P>
<P>
   By the time both returned to the floor, Texas had gone ahead
71-61.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer by Muoneke broke the final tie. Two free throws by
Mihm with 7:19 left put Texas up 71-61.
</P>
<P>
   A dunk by Darren Kelly (nine points) that finished a fast break
gave Texas a 78-65 lead, and when Muoneke hit two free throws to
make it 82-69 with 2:15 to play, the game was effectively over.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns avenged a 71-69 loss to the Cougars in last year's
season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good about the game,'' Gervin said afterward.
``They are a nationally ranked team for a reason. And they play
well. But we have a lot of heart and won't just roll over and die.
We try to play right down to th NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT 3 &Cx1f; tat-z r nbx NT26  &QL; 
rgbx  &UR; NYTR-;PEANUTS;FAREWELLBy GEORGE LAUER NYT Regional Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, CALIF. -- With heartfelt words like ``gentleness,
insight, warmth and love'' readers from all over the country bid
farewell today to ``Peanuts,'' a comic strip with a bunch of
ageless grammar school kids and a grinning, long-snouted dog who
became part of America's extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Charles M. Schulz, after a remarkable run of almost 50 years,
offers his final daily comic strip today. The final edition of
Sunday ``Peanuts,'' which he did in advance, appears Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things I'm going to miss,'' Schulz said
Sunday, his voice cracking with emotion. ``''I've been thinking
about this, and I think what I'm going to miss the most is Lucy
holding the football and looking up and then the big bonk when
Charlie comes down,'' Schulz said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to lighten the weight of what clearly has been the
toughest decision of his life, Schulz said he was coping with his
physical problems ``But the big thing is I lost my job,'' he said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Snoopy will be the most sorely missed member of the gang,
judging from more than 350 responses to The Press Democrat's
question, ``Which character will you miss the most?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all I will miss Snoopy -- a dog who was usually
smarter than those humans around him,'' said Laurie Martin of Santa
Rosa. ``Drinking root beer in a World War I tavern or kicking
tumbleweed in a desert or simply waiting for his supper on top of
the doghouse, Snoopy always made me laugh. These are wonderful
memories of characters that have become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have to hold him back,'' Schulz said. ``Snoopy could
easily take over the strip. I'm sure going to miss all those
guys,'' Schulz said, barely winning a struggle to hold back tears.
</P>
<P>
   For several generations of newspaper readers, today marks the
end of an era. It also is a time for tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Schulz's colleagues pay homage to ``Peanuts'' in today's
comic strips. Garry Trudeau, in ``Doonesbury'' shows Zonker in a
Charlie Brown-style striped shirt, reclining Snoopy-like on top of
a doghouse in an early version of the strip that was rejected as
``too derivative.'' In ``The Norm'' by Michael Jantze, the main
character, drawn as a young kid, stands on a pitcher's mound
watching Charlie Brown heading for the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Although Snoopy gets the most fan mail, readers also identified
with Charlie Brown, Linus, Woodstock, even Lucy, often suggesting
they saw themselves reflected in an emotional mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Simple characters, young forever and rarely swayed by the fad of
the day, spoke to readers' deepest feelings and aspirations. From
Snoopy's rich life of imagination to the dependable frustrations of
round-headed Charlie Brown, Peanuts offered universal truths in
personal, non-threatening portions.
</P>
<P>
   And readers appreciated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have revealed yourself to us over the years and we have
come to love you,'' wrote Jean Langford of Santa Rosa. ``Your
gentleness, your wisdom, your affinity and empathy for the human
condition, your daily interpretation and distillation of universal
problems to a dimension we can understand. What a genius it takes
to transform the philosophy of life and living into Snoopy's words,
and with such humor!''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't all larger-than-life praise. Some readers offered
concrete examples of how Peanuts affected their everyday life.
Laurie Brock of Healdsburg remembers how her resemblance to
Peppermint Patty helped her make new friends as a newcomer in the
fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really helped break the ice with the other kids,'' Brock
wrote. ``Thank you Mr. Schulz, for inventing a plain-speaking,
straight haired little girl that looked just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many readers didn't like being asked to choose a favorite
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good grief, Press Democrat! How do you choose which of your
family you'll miss the most? They're all loved,'' wrote Carol Bobst
of Angwin.
</P>
<P>
   Another writer said, ``asking which 'Peanuts' character I will
miss the most is sort of like asking which of my internal organs I
could do without.''
</P>
<P>
   Most letter writers said they understood the need for the comic
strip to end and many sent their prayers for Schulz, 77, who is
battling colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And fans are happy that many newspapers across the country
--including The Press Democrat -- are planning to reprint
``Peanuts'' strips from yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers tried to explain the importance the ``Peanuts''
gang --and in some cases Schulz himself -- has had in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   One letter writer sent money inscribed with inspirational
messages in her get-well wishes for Schulz. One reader wrote the
same letter twice -- on Peanuts stationery -- after evidently
forgetting she had already written and sent it. One woman wrote
that a smile and a wave from Schulz in the rear view mirror of his
car is one of her first and fondest memories of Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   Some readers were moved to poetry and a few offered artwork of
their own. Often, letters included descriptions or reproductions of
a ``Peanuts'' strip from decades ago, faded but still attached to
the refrigerator door.
</P>
<P>
   Many letters came from the generation that grew old with
``Peanuts,'' even if their favorite characters didn't. Readers in
their 70s and 80s said losing ``Peanuts'' was like losing an old
friend.
</P>
<P>
   And there were letters from the middle of the timeline. Betsy
Dorsey Schott, 33, of Green Bay, Wis., wrote about her lifelong
love of ``Peanuts'' and her recent ``pilgrimage to Santa Rosa'' to
see where ``my life-long hero lived.'' As he has for so many fans,
Schulz graciously said hello and posed for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I had imagined, you are a kind and gentle man,'' Schott
wrote. ``I will remember that moment for as long as I live. Thank
you, Mr. Schulz.''
</P>
<P>
   And there were letters from the youngest side of the timeline as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Five-year-old Fred Matalon of Santa Rosa and his little brother
Jake, 1, collaborated on a letter that says ``We're sad (with a
frowning face). We'll miss the Peanuts. Thank you for the gift of
the Peanuts, Sincerely, Fred.'' (Jake scribbled a little at the
bottom for a signature).
</P>
<P>
   Some writers went so far as to suggest the strip and Schulz are
nothing less than national treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Mansfield of Petaluma wrote: ``In a world of few real
national heros today, you are, Charles Schulz, my hero of moral
character and steadfastness.'' George Lauer is a staff writer for
the Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS DEMOCRAT, SANTA ROSA, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
