u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     01-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ Well, four more victories and the Cowboys are world
champions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, that would require a five-game winning streak,
something Dallas hasn't managed since it last won a Super Bowl four
Januaries ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the first of those wins, the one they needed to have the
opportunity to go forth, is in the bag. The Cowboys gave themselves
at least a chance to atone for a humdrum regular season by
qualifying for the postseason with a 26-18 victory Sunday over a
New York Giants team that had its suitcases packed. Hence, a trip
to Minnesota is in the offing, as is a chance to make history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a position to do something nobody's ever
done,'' said coach Chan Gailey, who might have put himself in a
position to keep his job after back-to-back losses to the Jets and
the lowly Saints had owner Jerry Jones on the verge of a conniption
fit. Remember, it took a series of correctly falling dominoes the
previous weekend to allow the Cowboys (8-8) to control their
destiny entering Armaggedon/redemption Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of the six previous playoff qualifiers with a
.500-or-worse record has won a game in the NFL's second season _
never mind four in a row. Dallas and Detroit, which revved up for
its own pie-in-the-sky run to Atlanta by losing four in a row,
increase the number of statistically suspect qualifiers to eight.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Cowboys, unlike the disgraced Lions, go in on a
measurable high, although it should be pointed out the Giants
scored 18 points over the last 20{ minutes while contemplating
their pending winter vacation options.
</P>
<P>
   Does Dallas truly deserve its playoff shot? Doesn't much matter.
They got it, what with most of the competition furiously
backstroking out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We earned what we got,'' Gailey said, taking a defiant stance
to a question he interpreted to be hostile. ``Nobody gave it to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, he softened his tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful (to be going to Minnesota),'' he said. ``Now
we're eager to see what we can do with the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Gailey also be personally grateful to remain in Jones'
employ? The owner, as hands-on as they come, was pointedly
defensive of Troy Aikman last week, meaning he blamed the strategic
philosophy rather than the quarterback's on-field interpretation
for Dallas' offensive lethargy of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coach as hard as I can every week,'' Gailey said. ``That's
all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Aikman insisted the Cowboys always play as hard as they can.
Just some days things fall into place better. Sunday was one of
them. Dallas managed 437 total yards while suffering neither a sack
nor a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   For a half, they were remarkably penalty-free as well, before
committing a more typical seven the rest of the way to maintain
their NFL lead in this dubious-achievement category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play great,'' Gailey said, ``but we played well.
Everybody contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   Aging war horse Emmitt Smith ran for 122 yards, the same figure
compiled by fresh-faced phenom Jason Tucker's four receptions. Most
conspicuously, Tucker turned an ordinary slant pattern Aikman said
was designed only to give the Cowboys breathing room into a 90-yard
touchdown that put Dallas up by 20 late in the third quarter. And
provided redemption for his dropped TD pass just before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of year for the Cowboys. On any given
Sunday, on any given play, you've never been sure of what you would
get, effort- or execution-wise. Dallas hardly resembles Jimmy
Johnson's juggernaut playoff teams, or the one Barry Switzer
baby-sat to a third Super Bowl championship in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their travails, these Cowboys aren't markedly
distinguishable from the 10-6 division champions of a year ago who
lost ignominiously to Arizona at home in the first round. Aikman
endorsed that observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haood (a chance to advance) as we did last season,''
he said. ``The only difference is we're on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this team might have a slightly better chance, never
mind the '99 Vikings' presumed superiority to the '98 Cardinals.
The NFC's surviving six are a flawed lot through and through. That
St. Louis (13-3) could surrender 38 points to the dreadful Eagles
on Sunday _ while claiming these Giants to be the only ``quality''
opponent they beat all season _ proves the Rams' fallibility. It
also sets the most generous curve for the NFC's five other playoff
contestants.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys seem closer to being the worst of a bad lot than the
best, but the spectrum is considerably narrower than usual. If 8-8
is ever going to be a good enough springboard for a truly Super NO
CARRIER
RING
CONNECT LAPM
</P>
