<HEADER>
A4942 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-HNS &LR;      01-03 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW ORLEANS _ As impressive as Florida State has been the last 13
seasons, there is something missing _ a shelf full of national
championship trophies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are some beautiful numbers and statistics that give many
reason to believe Florida State is the college football team of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive of those numbers are these:
2-3-3-4-4-2-1-4-4-3-3-3.
</P>
<P>
   No football team ever has matched that run of finishes in the
Associated Press rankings. That is 12 consecutive rankings of top
four or better at the end of the season. Florida State is almost
assured of stretching that streak to 13 even if it loses to
Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   During that same stretch, the next-highest number of
top-four-or-better finishes is Miami's six (1987-92).
</P>
<P>
   No other team has more than three in a row, and only two teams _
Notre Dame (1988, '89, '92, '93) and Nebraska (1993, '94, '95, '97)
_ make the ledger with four such finishes in those 12 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But there is only one national championship (1993) among Florida
State's lottery numbers. So, as close to the prize as Florida State
has been since 1987, No. 2-ranked Virginia Tech can match the
Seminoles in titles with a win Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose, boy, you can bet people will come out with `Ol'
Bowden can't win the big one,''' Florida State coach Bobby Bowden
said. ``I said a long time ago that the only big games are the ones
you lose. Even with all of our wins over great teams, people will
focus on the ones that got away. We know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from the other side of the tracks. I'm not spoiled. I can
live with being No. 2. I want No. 1, but I'm just happy to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden might be trying to convince people that losing this game
would not be that big of a deal, but his players know different.
Finishing near the top is not the same as at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's tough on him because he's had so many wide rights
and wide lefts and he thinks about that,'' senior split end Ron
Dugans said. ``(He thinks about) being in so many national
championship games and not winning them. Being Bobby Bowden and
always being in the top five at the end of the year, I know he's
tired of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to that group of seniors, who as redshirt
freshmen entered the 1997 Sugar Bowl unbeaten and ranked No. 1
before being defeated by Florida in the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Junior linebacker Tommy Polley said he thinks this group should
have won another title, as a three-point loss to Florida in the
1997 season finale was the lone blemish for the Seminoles that
year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State bounced back from an early loss to North Carolina
State last season to make its way to the national title game
against Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl and lost again.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team we haven't looked at the game (film) and talked
about it much, but I have watched it 50 times, knowing that we were
there and we killed ourselves with penalties and dumb mistakes,''
Dugans said. ``We're just tired of finishing the season not No. 1.
It hurts when you look at yourself in the mirror and know that
maybe you didn't give it your best or your team didn't give its
best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles said they went into that game unprepared,
overconfident and without the intensity they will bring to the
Superdome on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the main things that got us fired up over the
summer,'' center Eric Thomas said. ``All the seniors made a pact to
get to New Orleans and do whatever it takes to come out with a
national championship. We'll meet again (before the game) to
reflect over the years. It helps (us) focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had an Orange Bowl championship (1996) and a Sugar Bowl
championship (1998), but your career is really judged by whether
you have a national championship ring or not. I don't know about a
lot of programs, but at Florida State if you don't win a national
championship, it's a disappointing year.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, there have been many disappointments for the
Seminoles and Bowden, who has had eight teams finish the season
with only one loss; none has gone unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game will be the third opportunity for the Seminoles'
fifth-year seniors to play in the national title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the other two,'' receiver Peter Warrick said. ``This
is our last chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And should they fail, Dugans said there would be only one way to
describe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one word, I would say underachievers,'' Dugans said. ``That
would mean we were 0-3 in championship ballgames, and that would
hurt coach Bowden, as well as the coaching staff and the team
members, especially the seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very big for me. I am telling guys if we lost, I
wouldn't go back to Tal NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT LAPM
</P>
</TEXT>
