<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS &AMP; STRIPES BEATS PRADA IN CHOPPY SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Stars &AMP; Stripes is a money boat. The
aged team from San Diego knows when to play it close to the vest
and when to show its cards. In this six-boat semifinal round of the
Louis Vuitton Cup, only two boats will survive, and once again, the
Dennis Conner machine has chosen its moment to play.
</P>
<P>
   With gusty southwesterly winds kicking up a steep chop on
Hauraki Gulf Sunday, Stars &AMP; Stripes showed its mettle in the heavy
stuff by thoroughly thrashing Italy's Prada in boat speed, tactics,
and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 miles of bashing through the chop, Stars &AMP; Stripes
crossed the finish a solid 1 minute 7 seconds ahead of the regatta
favorite, posting its second win in two races, while Prada drops to
1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes' Ken Read and the Italian Luna Rossa's Francesco
de Angelis mixed it up in a prerace sparring session, with American
tactician Tom Whidden fighting for the left side. Stars &AMP; Stripes
won the left and parlayed it to an advantage all day.
</P>
<P>
   The race started in 18-knot winds, but by the third leg, the big
gusts were busting gear and blowing out sails all over the course
as six boats sailed the same track, staggered by time.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Whidden said, gusts whipped over the 120-foot-high
masthead at 35 knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hairy out there,'' said Whidden. ``I think our
experience in Fremantle (Australia in 1986) helped us out today.
There were times when we were letting out the sails in some of the
puffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes went left immediately and sailed a straight line
until Prada made its first attack from the right, finding itself a
boat length behind. The left was working well early on, as Prada
was forced back to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after split tacks, Prada made another attack from the
right and was content to eventually get in tack behind Stars &AMP;
Stripes, which had developed enough lead to cover only loosely for
the rest of the leg. At the top mark, Stars &AMP; Stripes led Prada by
17 seconds, about 1 1/2 boat lengths.
</P>
<P>
   The first run was the only time the Italians made things
interesting. With their big white spinnaker trying to blanket Stars
&AMP; Stripes, Prada drafted closer and closer, at some points right on
top of the US boat's stern, sometimes jibing into phase nearly
beside Team Dennis Conner.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway down the run, Prada had closed from 120 meters to 50
meters and at the bottom mark, trailed Stars &AMP; Stripes by just 10
seconds. But then Whidden put the blue boat in a groove she
wouldn't slip out of the rest of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Staying left and allowing Prada the whole right side of the
course without covering, Stars &AMP; Stripes turned on the raw speed in
the heavier wind ranges, which is her forte. Halfway up the leg,
Prada's boom vang cracked, though it had little effect on the
outcome, Italian sailors said.
</P>
<P>
   As Whidden capitalized on gains, Prada went looking for
windshifts, then tried to suck the US boat into tacking and jibing
duels. But the margin was too great for these tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the luxury some other programs did, so I think
we built our boat a little more bulletproof than some,'' said
Whidden. ``And Mick Harvey and our shore crew have the gear in good
shape. I think with luck, we're not going to break down. We can
sail in a strong breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' added the 52-year-old president of North Sails
from Essex, Conn., with a chuckle, ``I'm at the age when I don't
need this much breeze to enjoy a day of sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other races, gear breakdown played a big factor. Paul
Cayard led his cross-town rival, Dawn Riley, around the course most
of the day until a snapped halyard tore up a piece of the headfoil
track, and Cayard's crew was unable to raise another headsail.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing his opening, helmsman John Cutler drove the canary yellow
America True past Cayard for an easy win.
</P>
<P>
   On the last course, Japan nearly let Le Defi Francais come back
from its deficit when the jib halyard broke near the fifth mark.
Sending a man up the mast to reeve the halyard as France closed
from astern, it looked as if the race might turn around. But again,
quickness ruled the race, as the Japanese crew fixed its headsail
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The points table now has Stars &AMP; Stripes 2-0, AmericaOne 1-1,
America True 1-1, Prada 1-1, Nippon Challenge 1-1, France 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nice for us,'' said Peter Holmberg, Stars &AMP; Stripes
strategist. ``I really like our boat speed. But these are only two
races. We have a lot of racing to go out here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's pairings, the feature match is AmericaOne against
Prada, Stars &AMP; Stripes against France, and America True against
Nippon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
