<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FIND THEMSELVES OFF CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins' woeful 2-9-5 slump can be traced to a
number of problems, but none is more significant than the club's
struggle in the faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Jason Allison's wrist injury, the team has one
natural center: Joe Thornton. Everyone else being asked to play the
position is struggling because of the lack of familiarity, which
has led to chaos in the defensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   When you lose faceoffs, you chase the puck virtually the entire
game and the Bruins do it far too often. With Allison out of the
center mix, Dave Andreychuk, Rob DiMaio, and Anson Carter have
attempted to answer the bell, but not one of them is a center, nor
should be playing center.
</P>
<P>
   Penalty killing is a particularly gruesome aspect of the Bruins'
game right now, and that's also tied to losing faceoffs and people
playing out of position.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio, who would crawl through shards of glass on his hands and
knees if he thought it would help his team, seems particularly
stressed at trying to play a position he's not familiar with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very honest, it's tough for me to play there
consistently every night,'' said DiMaio. ``It's just a totally
different position for me and that can be frustrating. And taking
faceoffs, I'm so programmed in my game to be in certain spots at
certain times and to be very effective doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm everywhere and it's just a different responsibility.
To be a good centerman, you have to learn that position real well.
I'm definitely more comfortable on the wing, but as it stands now,
this is what we have and this is what is being asked of me, so I'll
do the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the challenge of playing center that is different from
the wing is coverage. Some of the Bruins look particularly
confused, and that leads to opponents being left wide open in front
of the net. As much as he concentrates on playing center, DiMaio
said he finds himself drifting back to the wing out of habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a natural thing to look for my D man and to look for
the responsibility of a winger instead of being in support of our
defensemen in the corner or in front of the net,'' said DiMaio.
``Sometimes I'm a step late in doing that. That gives other teams
opportunities. That's just the frustrating part of it. I guess I'll
get better as time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   In coach Pat Burns's first two seasons, he had a solid checking
combination. Particularly in that first season, P.J. Axelsson, Tim
Taylor, and DiMaio were the most consistent trio and often shut
down opponents' best lines. DiMaio said it's difficult for Burns to
match lines now because of the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as a line, the job that we have, I think I'm more
effective being on the wing,'' he said. ``I don't know if Pat
really knows who to put us up against right now, the top lines or
not, just because I'm not in my normal position and we don't have a
set winger on (the right side). There are a lot of question marks.
I have them and I imagine (my linemates) have them also. Hopefully
that works itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio said he believes there has been a bit of a domino effect
because so many forwards are playing out of position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one real natural centerman right now and that's Joe,''
he said. ``And Jason, when he's healthy, but he's not, so he's
playing the wing more or less most of the time. Battling down low
is hard for him. So, it's different positions for all of us. The
penalty killing suffers because of it. Faceoffs are suffering and
time of possession with the puck is suffering because the faceoffs
aren't being won consistently. In that respect, you miss some of
the guys that we had just because of those few reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have played better of late, particularly during
Saturday night's 2-2 tie with New Jersey, but some of their
troubles would be alleviated with the acquisition of a defensive
center. Allison could be facing surgery on his ailing right wrist
soon. But even if he stays and nurses the injury through the
season, he will not be a true center. That leaves the Bruins
hamstrung at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' said DiMaio. ``You're in the position
where you have to do the job, but reality says that somebody
natural in that position is probably going to be more comfortable
and do a better job and make everybody around him that much more
comfortable because you can rely on that. In that respect, I really
feel it's important that guys are comfortable in their positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were trying to remain positive despite their slump.
DiMaio said with the way they've played lately, even though they
are winless in seven games (0-5-2), there are positives,
particularly against the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are building toward something, which is good,'' he
said. ``It was a good point to get against a very good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
