<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEINKE LENDS MATURITY AT HELM 
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-WEINKE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Consider some numbers first. When Chris Weinke
first was being recruited by Florida State back in 1989, his
counterpart at Virginia Tech, Michael Vick, was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   When the junior quarterback takes the field in the Superdome
Tuesday night as No. 1 Florida State meets No. 2 Virginia Tech in
the Sugar Bowl for the national championship, Weinke will be 27
years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Weinke,'' said Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, ``is
not a senior. He's a senior citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bowden cuts to the chase. ``Chris Weinke,'' said the
70-year-old Bowden, ``is the best thing going for us. It's his
emotion. His composure. His patience. He has more of an effect on
our team than any one player. Whatever happens out there, he won't
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should he? At 27 _ he reached that milestone last July _
Weinke's story reads like some fantasy camp.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, he was what Vick and most of the players on both
teams are today _ a hotshot teenager with a wish to play big-time
college football.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Florida State with great expectations. But he also
had another itch. Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He was good at it, too. So good the Toronto Blue Jays gave him a
million-dollar contract. He tried it for six seasons. It didn't
work out the way Weinke wanted: with a career in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Weinke had to make a career choice. He could
stick it out for a few more years in baseball, he could give it up,
or he could go back to football _ he still had three years of
eligibility in college.
</P>
<P>
   He chose football, coming back with maturity and money,
something that few college players have when they leave, much less
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Weinke thought his dream would end with a national
championship. Instead, it concluded in midseaason with a
career-threatening herniated disk that not only knocked him out of
last season's title game against Tennessee, but raised doubts about
his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago,'' said Weinke, who is one of the reasons Florida
State is favored to complete its first unbeaten, untied season, ``I
was just wondering if I would ever play again. I didn't know if I
would be healthy again to play for a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Weinke, the Seminoles lost to Tennessee in the Fiesta
Bowl. With him this season, they have won every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him back there,'' said wide receiver Peter Warrick,
``things are different. He reads defenses. He does things. It's
great to have him back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, whose record is 20-1 as a starter, has had a spectacular
season statistically, throwing for 3,103 yards, 255 TDs, and only
14 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Weinke's presence that has made the difference. ``I've
always been a leader,'' said Weinke. ``And I feel I have used that
leadership on and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke's tact is matter of fact. He is no wide-eyed college
junior. His relationship with his teammates is based on what
happens on the field. His interests and lifestyle are different
from most of his teammates, who were in grade school during
Weinke's first stint at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke's maturity will be a key factor in Tuesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Weinke is a full-grown man,'' said Florida State
offensive coordinator Mark R`There's not much hair on the
top. He does a super job of staying calm under the pressure
situations. Most kids coming to college have been stars. The first
time they fail, according to fans or the media, they tend not to
respond very well. Chris has been through the bad times in making
the major leagues. He knows how to handle things better than some.
He knows how to handle things he still has to learn. He wants to be
coached. He doesn't act like a kid, so I don't have to treat him as
a kid. He treats everything professionally and that's how we treat
him.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's likely Tuesday's game will be his last, Weinke's
focus is on right now. He has a 12-inch scar down the middle of his
back as a reminder of his athletic mortality. He has the memory of
watching the Seminoles lose a title game a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will approach Tuesday night's game with a degree of
measured excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a human being,'' he said. ``I will be excited. But I have
to control that excitement somewhat to be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke is not dismissing what Tech can do to stop him, or what
it can do on offense with Vick to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes the game, the season, and the ultimate moment of
his career are in his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Bowden with a smile, ``is fine with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
