<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4966 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-LOUIS     01-03 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CONNECTICUT-LOUISIANA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S PERFECT RECORD INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ The undefeated University of Connecticut women's
basketball team, which has been atop the national rankings all
season, might have been a little worried Sunday &UR;  &LR; night when No. 3
Louisiana Tech came to town.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the soldout crowd of 10,027 had plenty to cheer about
as the Huskies (10-0) kept their record unblemished and soundly
defeated the Lady Techsters (10-2), 90-63. The crowd cheered when
sophomore Tamika Williams _  been sidelined six weeks with a
stress fracture _ entered the game with 9:20 to go, and practically
gave her an ovation when she scored a basket. They roared more when
bench warmer Christine Rigby came in to play and hit the team's
last 5 points.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech, meanwhile, looked nothing like the team that
went to the Final Four last year, or that racked up wins against
Tennessee and defending champion Purdue this season. Instead, coach
Leon Barmore watched sullenly as the Huskies took off on a 16-2 run
and never looked back. By the end of the half, UConn had a 47-30
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did everything a team had to do,'' said Barmore, whose
500th win still eludes him (he is 499-75, and is the all-time
winningest active Division 1 men's or women's coach).
</P>
<P>
   Barmore's team beat up UConn last year, but lost three seniors
to graduation. He acknowledged that even high scorers Betty Lennox
(27 points) and Tamicha Jackson (14) can't pick up all the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not using this as an excuse, but we're a very young
basketball team,'' he said. ``You've got to learn to pass the ball,
to distribute the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Distributing the ball is what UConn did best, as the team handed
out 26 assists compared with Louisiana Tech's 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting their pressure, and I think we were ready to
play tonight,'' said junior guard Shea Ralph, who had 15 points and
eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   UConn forward Svetlana Abrosimova had 25 points, including three
3-pointers, as she drilled the hapless Tech defense. She said that
if her team had played the way the opponents did, ``coach would
just kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   The UConn defense pressed the Lady Techsters so much that they'd
rush the ball down cour fire away.
</P>
<P>
   UConn made 54.5 percent (18 of 33) of its shots in the first
half to 31 (13 of 42) for Louisiana Tech. For the game, Louisiana
Tech shot just 34 percent from the field, while the Huskies shot 51
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to do it by themselves, but I think we played more
as a team and passed it around,'' Abrosimova said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Jackson went down when she attempted to block a
UConn pick. She was helped off the court after a stop in action,
but returned for the final minutes of the half.
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Geno Auriemma said he's glad to be No. 1 and
unbeaten, but he tried to put the midseason win in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're pretty good, and I think we're going to get
better,'' he said. ``Time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like tonight kind of reinforce the fact that we think
we're pretty good, but we take it with a grain of salt,'' Auriemma
said. ``Sometime down the road, we're going to have to beat this
team again, or somebody like them, so you know, it's one day. We
were better than they were today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     01-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ There are people who fit comfortably into the mold
and others who shatter it.
</P>
<P>
   Like Muggsy Bogues, the 5-3 professional basketball player;
Sonny Bono, the U.S. congressman; Tonya Harding, the trailer-trash
figure skater.
</P>
<P>
   And Sebastian Janikowski, the larger-than-life placekicker.
</P>
<P>
   Much larger.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-2 and 260 pounds, Janikowski looks like he could be a
linebacker. Which is fitting, because that's the position he
jokingly has demanded to play next year to spurn the riches of the
NFL and return for his senior season at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Or is he joking? With Janikowski, it seems, you never can tell.
</P>
<P>
   Back again at the Nokia Sugar Bowl, where his No. 1-ranked
Seminoles have virtually taken up residence in recent years,
Janikowski is a hulking, movable version of Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Polish-born son of a father who had his own dreams of
becoming a pro soccer player, Janikowski is a combination of the
21st-century American dream, a stand-up comic at open-mike night
and a bar bouncer's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's a party on legs, and the left one in particular
makes most of the noise.
</P>
<P>
   While so much of the attention surrounding the Seminoles'
offense focuses on wide receiver Peter Warrick and quarterback
Chris Weinke, the truth is that the most potent and consistent
weapon in coach Bobby Bowden's arsenal is his slightly
out-of-kilter placekicker.
</P>
<P>
   His accuracy and sheer power make Janikowski, when compared to
most kickers, the same as an atomic warhead measured against a
Civil War cannon. He did not miss a field goal inside 45 yards this
season, while connecting on 23 of 30 overall, going a perfect
47-for-47 on extra points and scoring 116 points.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, an incredible 57 of his 83 kickoffs went into or
out of the end zone for touchbacks, and four of them sailed between
the uprights 75 yards away. Of the 26 kickoffs returned, only four
were carried out past the 24-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Makes for a pretty long field for the other guys,'' Bowden
said in his down-home drawl.
</P>
<P>
   One day a couple of special-teamers and assistant coaches got
into a discussion about how much they would have to be paid to take
the place of the football and be on the receiving end of one of
Janikowski's kicks. $100,000?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them it would cost more than that to put the body parts
back together,'' said safety Jean Jeune.
</P>
<P>
   Boom! It is a deafening roar up close and often can be heard in
the stands when Janikowski's left foot connects with the football.
He once broke several of an opponent's ribs with an inadvertent
kick in a soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have good time,'' he says with strong traces of his Polish
accent. ``I can kick any ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Boom! It is the roar of life anywhere near Janikowski, who
admits he barely tolerates the school part of going to college and
is always on the lookout for his next good time.
</P>
<P>
   Last season as a sophomore, Janikowski kicked three field goals
in the Noles' 23-12 win at Florida, then turned to the opposing
sideline to mock coach Steve Spurrier and the Gators fans by
opening and closing his arms in a version of the Gators chomp.
</P>
<P>
   He shaves his head and looks like a pro wrestler. He got into a
scrape at a bar last summer and was slapped with a misdemeanor
charge of disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People not understand,'' Janikowski said. ``Do not know my
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy,'' said long snapper Clay Ingram.
</P>
<P>
   Janikowski emigrated from Poland to Florida in 1994 and at age
17 turned down a $2 million offer to play professional soccer in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money isn't everything,'' he said. ``Besides, I just get to
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody showed Janikowski a football. He kicked it. It made the
sound of a shotgun blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can kick football,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he told coach Kerry Kramer the day he showed up at
practice at Seabreeze High in Daytona Beach wearing jeans and
sneakers. One look at balls sailing 70 and 80 yards, and Kramer had
himself a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Bowden. A Florida State assistant scouted a game in
which Janikowski boomed a 60-yard field goal and barely missed from
71 yards. The assistant rushed back to Tallahassee with a tape for
Bowden, who insisted he already had his kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just watch, coach,'' the assistant begged.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden did.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing sitting here?'' Bowden soon bellowed. ``Go
sign that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the kid is projected as an early second- or maybe even late
first-round draft choice by NFL expert Mel Kiper Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he can play linebacker?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm going pro,'' Janikowski said.
</P>
<P>
   To break the bank, break records, maybe a few ribs and ce NO
CARRIER
RING
CONNECT LAPM $s;J918006350017 ;
</P>
</TEXT>
