<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS FILL OPEN SPACE BETWEEN DOWN AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They say it doesn't matter how they got
into the playoffs. The Seahawks say what matters is, they're in.
</P>
<P>
   After stinking up the other half of Jersey Sunday in a 19-9 loss
to the New York Jets _ and still making the playoffs, thanks to the
cursed (?) Raiders _ what else can the Seahawks say?
</P>
<P>
   That as one of the coldest teams heading into the postseason,
they'll decline the invitation until they figure out exactly what
Mike Holmgren and the new coaching staff are asking them to do?
</P>
<P>
   That they'll wait until their defense can stop the run? Until
arm tackling is in vogue?
</P>
<P>
   Until Jon Kitna and his many-man catching crew can hook up for
something resembling a touchdown drive?
</P>
<P>
   Until someone can get a play into the huddle before Kitna has to
burn timeouts?
</P>
<P>
   Until Joey Galloway is either a true deep threat or trade bait
for future draft picks whom Holmgren can actually put to work in
his by-the-book West Coast offense?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't work that way.
</P>
<P>
   They're in, baby. They're in because the Raiders lived by Al
Davis' credo: Just win, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Who ever would have thought that the Seahawks would have warm
and fuzzy feelings for the Raiders' quirky owner?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as luck would have it, the Seahawks get the Dolphins _
the other coldest team in the NFL heading into the first playoffs
of the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Da Fish. With Dan Marino wearing more protective gear than
Seattle police during the WTO riots. With Jimmy Johnson so
exasperated that the National Weather Service has issued a warning
for the possible eruption of Johnson's infamous coiffure.
</P>
<P>
   And break out the ``Huard Brothers Reunited'' feature stories,
grandma.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even addressed the ``Kingdome Lives'' theme yet.
</P>
<P>
   But we will.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you know we will.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the real season,'' Chad Brown said after the Hawks
backed into the playoffs like a broken-down Trailways bus limping
into the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preseason is fake and the regular season is just a chance
to see who gets into the real season. And it's a whole different
level of football coming up,'' said the former Steeler, who knows
what it's like when you get to January in the NFL. ``This is what
it's all about. This is why you play football.''
</P>
<P>
   But even knowing what he knows about how tough playoff football
gets, not even Brown was willing to toss this opportunity back like
some undersized steelhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the season, there's only one team out there, and
we now have a chance to be one of those teams,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that would be talk about the road to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And who are we to argue?
</P>
<P>
   Who are we to point out that it was a bit odd, the way the
Seahawks expended more energy cheering when the Raiders beat the
Chiefs in overtime than they did during their own critical game at
the Meadowlands, when their fate was in their own hands?
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the weirdest scenes in recent sporting memory.
</P>
<P>
   After the lackluster game, some Seahawks players dressed and
quickly headed out to the team bus as the Raiders-Chiefs game was
still going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I watch somebody else's game?'' Ricky Watters said
in an angry huff as he exited the locker room before knowing the
Seahawks' fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I watch to see if somebody else is going to lose
when we didn't go out there and take care of our own business?''
</P>
<P>
   In his frustration and anger, Watters was on the right track _
unwilling to accept that the only way the Hawks would make the
postseason is if somebody else did them a favor.
</P>
<P>
   And inside the locker room, as the other half of the team
watched and waited, veteran receiver Mike Pritchard said he was
shocked by the contrast between the Seahawks he saw during the game
and the ones celebrating after the Raiders' hit the game-winning
field goal to beat the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was this energy on the sideline? Where was this energy
during the game?'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have words to describe it but how can this team play
like it did last week against Kansas City and then come out here
today and lay an egg like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this unpleasant moment of truth will have a short
lifespan.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger reality may have been unthinkable without the help of
the Raiders, but the bigger reality is that the Hawks have survived
_ a feat capable of prompting a party mood.
</P>
<P>
   It's been so long since Seattle has had a whiff of a playoff
game, the town's going to have little choice but to go ga-ga over
the first NFL postseason game at the soon-to-be-doomed Kingdome
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Now Seattle can have a little bit of faux New Year's a little
too late, but maybe the city deserves a break.
</P>
<P>
   After the ugliness of the WTO riots and then the threat of
terrorism that forced a frightened Mayor Paul Schell to cancel the
Seattle Center New Year's celebration, maybe this is the payback
Seattle gets for being the world's Y2K sacrificial lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our butts kicked,'' Christian Fauria said after the
news was in from Kansas City. ``But I couldn't care less how we got
in.''
</P>
<P>
   They say it doesn't matter how it happened, just that it did.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the Dolphins. Break out the hats and confetti. By the
opening kickoff in the Kingdome next Sunday, no one's going to
remember the Hawks almost didn't make it there.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
