<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLED HAWKS BACK INTO PLAYOFFS, THANKS TO RAIDERS' WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Maybe there is something to this Mike
Holmgren magic stuff after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks had just laid an egg in their 19-9 loss to the New
York Jets Sunday in Giants Stadium, a loss so sorry that it should
have ended Seattle's season.
</P>
<P>
   But right in the middle of offering what was as much an apology
as it was an explanation, quarterback Jon Kitna discovered the
Oakland Raiders had just kicked a field goal in overtime to defeat
the Kansas City Chiefs, 41-38.
</P>
<P>
   The double setbacks gave the Seahawks the AFC West championship
and lifted them into the playoffs for the first time since 1988 _
which also happens to be the last time the Raiders beat the Chiefs
in Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? You go from the depths of despair to
euphoria,'' said Holmgren, who is six days shy of completing his
first year as coach and general manager of a franchise that hadn't
tasted so much as a winning season since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed in how we played today, and I think we're
capable of (playing) better.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how poorly the Seahawks played Sunday, and have
played in dropping five of their final six regular-season games,
they will host the Miami Dolphins in the Kingdome next Sunday. It
will be the Seahawks' first home playoff game since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to control your own destiny,'' Kitna said. ``But on
the other hand, I don't care how we get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna's postgame postmortem was interrupted by shouts and
cheering from the next room, where teammates were watching the
Raiders do them a huge favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was saying,'' offered Kitna, his solemn expression
quickly replaced by a huge grin, ``the next season just started.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is any consolation on this day when the Seahawks were
handed the ultimate consolation prize, the Dolphins also are
entering the playoffs through the back door. Once 7-1, Miami needed
either a loss by the Seahawks or the Chiefs to earn a playoff spot.
The Dolphins' 21-10 loss to the Redskins Sunday also was their
fifth in the past six games and left them 9-7 as well.
</P>
<P>
   That old saying about anything happening once a team makes the
playoffs proved true for the Seahawks and Dolphins when the
Raiders, a team that has struggled with its field-goal kickers all
season, got a 33-yarder from recently signed Joe Nedney to oust the
Chiefs, 41-38.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying, `Please don't let me go in the tank again,'''
said defensive tackle Cortez Kennedy, who will play in the first
playoff game of his 10-year career. ``I've been in the tank 10
years and I was just about to go in the tank again. But the Raiders
pulled me out.''
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the Seahawks were not kidding themselves about
being playoff-ready or worthy after the odd twist of events Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly thought things had changed around here. I honestly
thought there was an opportunity to do something special,'' wide
receiver Mike Pritchard said. ``Nobody came to play. People who
were on the field, I don't know if they couldn't figure out the
importance of the game or what it was. But nobody came to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sad to say, but it's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsh words to match what was harsh reality for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was shredded by Jets running back Curtis Martin, who
carried the ball 34 times for 158 yards and the only touchdown of
the game and also caught three passes for 45 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just small little breakdowns by different guys,'' said
Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown, who finished as the team's leading
tackler for the third consecutive season. ``I definitely had my
share of breakdowns today. I didn't play even what I would call an
average game for me. It was below average. I offer no excuses in
that I didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   More honesty from the leader of a defense that allowed the Jets
to control the ball for 37{ minutes and compile 379 yards _ in part
because Jets quarterback Ray Lucas hit some passes at critical
junctures.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' offense, meanwhile, failed to score a touchdown
for the second time in six weeks, but for only the third time in
the past 32 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming down the stretch, I didn't play well,'' Kitna said
after his 21 of 45, 237-yard performance that included missed
throws and dropped passes. ``We just couldn't make the plays. I
couldn't make the right throws. It just didn't happen at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   More honesty from the leader of an offense who completed 12 of
16 passes in leading the Seahawks on drives to three field goals,
but could generate only 103 yards on the team's other nine
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the sum of these numbers added up to the Seahawks'
first playoff berth since '88, ending the longest postseason
drought in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have gone in kicking through the door
today,'' said Holmgren, who led the Packers into the playoffs in
each of his final six seasons in Green Bay. ``We didn't do that.
But, hey, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
