<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     01-03 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL OUT OF TOUCH, TIME 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll will arrive at Foxboro Stadium
Monday morning not quite sure if he'll be able to unlock the door
to his office.
</P>
<P>
   The Carroll Error came to a close Sunday with a weird 20-3
Patriot victory over the Baltimore Ravens, and Pete was true to the
finish. He was goofy.
</P>
<P>
   He came off the field, escorted by the ubiquitous Frank Mendes,
and went over to the stands to high-five some exuberant fans. He
looked like Carl Yastrzemski taking the victory lap in 1983, or Cal
Ripken Jr. thanking all of America in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Pete (it was always ``Poor Pete'') paid no heed to those
nasty signs in the stands: ``Had the Tuna, but ended up with a
Flounder''; ``Hey Bob, no re-Pete''; and ``Pete's Last Stand,
1-2-2000, R.I.P.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was oblivious. Watching him touching the masses, an
uninformed observer might have wondered, ``When do the playoffs
start? Will the Patriots be playing at home or on the road in the
NFL tournament?''
</P>
<P>
   They will not be playing at all, of course, because they
disgraced their own talent in the second half of this season. But
like their leader, they were clueless to the finish _ dancing in
the end zone and savoring a hollow victory when they should have
worn bags on their heads, pledged to do better, and gone home
quietly after a workmanlike win.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was buoyant at the postgame podium. In PeteSpeak, he was
downright pumped and jacked. He began his remarks with a tribute to
the Patriot defense (remember he is a career defensive coordinator
soon to be in search of a new job), then said, ``Our whole deal was
to have some fun playing today and we did. I want to look at the
moment in front of me and enjoy it to the fullest. That's the way I
am. I'm savoring it. That was a great event and I wanted to make
sure I felt it in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   As he began his remarks, Jonathan Kraft, the Pocket Rocket of
the Kraft leadership tandem, walked past the interview room door
without breaking stride. There was no locker room sighting of
tanned owner Robert Kraft. Not long ago, the Krafts enjoyed
standing in the back of the room and listening to their coach's
postgame remarks. Now they scoot away from games like they're
leaving South Boston town meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he spoke with Kraft earlier in the day. Routine
stuff. He described the conversations as good and upbeat. That's
what Gov. John Rowland said before Kraft bailed out of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would like to say to the fans, Carroll launched
into a favorite topic: fans who care too much and a negative media
that feeds the beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dike to deal with the sports you follow?'' he
asked. ``I get letters, tremendous notes with a lot of positive
things (Red Sox manager John McNamara cited his positive mailbag
right up until he was fired in 1988). Sometimes we get caught up
because of some guy on the radio or a writer who is critical.
Sometimes, in the bitterness, we miss the fun and why we are here
to play the game and to have fun with the game itself. I know our
fans love and support our team. But sometimes we get on a subject
or a topic and it gets so nasty and cynical.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Folks in these parts probably take their sports too
seriously and life is harsh for those who fail to live up to
expectations in the local arenas. Joe Morgan understood this. So
did Bill Parcells. Butch Hobson never got it. Ditto for Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe, beaten to a pulp in what had to be the
most trying season of his career, doesn't like the sports zeal of
our region, but has accepted it as a fact of his professional life.
He summed up the three-year Carroll regime as well as anybody:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete walked into an extremely difficult situation. We were a
Super Bowl team, but he was also following one of the biggest and
strongest personalities in sports in a very tough sports town. Was
it fair? Probably not, but nobody said life is fair. We just let
him down.''
</P>
<P>
   They let him down. He messed up; he trusted them. He treated
them like men.
</P>
<P>
   We probably never would have gotten used to Carroll's
sophomoric, Richie Cunningham/boola-boola antics on the sideline.
It seemed ridiculous to see a professional coach hugging his
players just for doing their jobs. But it would have worked if
they'd kept winning.
</P>
<P>
   They did not. The bottom line on the Carroll Error is that he
inherited a young Super Bowl team and rode it into last place
(that's right folks, technically, the Patriots finished behind the
Jets) in three seasons. The win total went from 11 to 10 to nine to
eight. Super Bowl, to one playoff win, to zero playoff wins, to
zero playoffs. There were 10,000 no-shows for the last game of the
Carroll Error and all of Route 1 looked like a special access road
for luxury box owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Carroll looked silly for punishing wide receiver
Terry Glenn when it was too late, and then he got sandbagged by
Bobby Grier, a drowning vice president of player personnel who was
trying to save his own butt.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Pete was a nice guy and that's probably what got him the
inflated five-year contract in the first place. But in the end, he
reaffirmed one of the oldest and cruelest cliches in sports: Nice
guys finish last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
