<HEADER>
A4973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     01-03 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENTLY, ARMSTRONG LAID IT ALL ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It was the morning after the debacle in
Philadelphia and Bruce Armstrong had a decision to make. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks earlier he had, as he liked to put it, ``popped my
ACL'' in a victory over the Arizona Cardinals. It was the kind of
debilitating knee injury that sends many men to the sideline for
the year the moment that popping is heard. The only place it sent
Armstrong was to the trainer's room a bit more frequently than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Although that pop meant his knee would have to be reconstructed
for the second time later this week, it did not, and it would not,
send him to the sidelines. Not while there was a playoff spot to
fight for and he had a leg to stand on.
</P>
<P>
   And so Armstrong silently played on, soldiering through five
losses in the next six weeks in which he and his offensive line
received more and more criticism for the sacking of Drew Bledsoe.
Through it all, he swore the few people who knew to secrecy until
he chose not to play.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was time to make that decision. In barely a minute or
two, it was made. Maintain the secret pact through two more
meaningless games. Games that said little for his team but much
about who he is and, perhaps, who some of his teammates are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't I keep playing?'' Armstrong said that day. ``My
father worked every day as a roofer in the sun. You think he wanted
to go to work every day? You think he felt good every day? Maybe he
didn't, but he went to work every day. Days when I didn't want to
go help him he went because it was his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my job. As long as I can do it, I'll do it. It doesn't
matter about the playoffs. We're out, but we still have games to
play. If I can play them, I'll play them.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did. Played every snap until the season ended with a
20-3 victory over the Baltimore Ravens Sunday. Played until there
was nothing left to play for, and then he played some more.
</P>
<P>
   He went down sometimes during those games but he got back up,
often slowly. But he got up.
</P>
<P>
   He was beaten sometimes, including during a long afternoon in
which the Eagles' Mike Mamula used his speed to overpower a man
with one leg who would have buried him if he had two. When that
happened he said nothing. Made no effort to use his injury as an
excuse.
</P>
<P>
   As the criticism of the Patriots' offense in general and the
pass protection in particular mounted, Armstrong took the hits off
the field the way Bledsoe took them on the field. He embraced the
code of silence. He said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He would give up his body to protect his quarterback but he
would not give up his injury to protect himself. That held true
even Sunday when Armstrong left the stadium without saying another
word about either his injury or the surgery he will face this week
because it was over now and there was nothing more to say and no
reason to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong could have thrown in the towel back on Oct. 31 in
Arizona, the day he was injured, and avoided much of what followed.
He could have thrown it in on many other days after that. Certainly
he could have brought his season to an early end _ and his
rehabilitation to a faster beginning _ after the 24-9 loss to the
Eagles because there was nothing more to play for after that.
Nothing more but pride.
</P>
<P>
   But then, that is why he plays. It's why he's been to six Pro
Bowls and survived some of the worst teams in pro football history
with his dignity intact. It's why he will be back next season to
try and do it again.
</P>
<P>
   And it's why Bledsoe could only shake his head in admiration
Sunday and remember the time a year ago when he broke his finger
and knew what he had to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I look Bruce in the eye if I go off the field with a
sore finger?'' Bledsoe said. ``It's inspirational to watch some
guys. Bruce, who has played the last seven games with, I think, the
MCL (actually the more serious ACL, but who's keeping track?) gone
in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody knows that, but he played for seven
games with no MCL in his knee. I don't know if you could find
another guy in the league that would be willing to do that. He put
it on the line for me, to protect my backside. Those are the kind
of things I take with me after a season, regardless of whether it
was a championship season of some sort or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, this was a season of a sort but not a championship one,
and when you have put in 13 such seasons and have not yet won that
elusive title, you play with injuries and pain and hope. Hope that
next season will be different. Hope that young players will watch
you play in pain and ignore the flu or a broken finger or a sore
ankle and play to win now as well because there may not be another
time for any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong understands this, which is why he played eight games
with a knee that was falling apart. He did what Shawn Jefferson
understood to be the requirements of a very difficult job,
requirements that frankly not everyone in Foxborough understood
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came into this league my receiver coach was Chris
Palmer,'' Jefferson recalled. ``He taught me a lot and he told me
you do things in this league that don't make sense to other people.
You gut it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce did that. He certainly is a warrior. You hope the
younger players around here see that and learn from it. He's
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember years ago coach (Bobby) Ross asked me to stand up
and define courage. I said it was someone who was brave. He told
me, `No. It's a guy who's scared and hurting but he does what he
has to do anyway.' That's courage. That's what Bruce is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jefferson spoke, Armstrong walked through the locker room
dressed in black from head to toe. He walked to his locker, slipped
on a heavy overcoat, picked up his briefcase, and said nothing
about his knee or his fate or much of anything else, except to
mention he was going to see the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was gone, like this season was gone. All that was left
behind were two hard plastic knee braces hanging in his locker.
</P>
<P>
   Like the player who wore them the past eight weeks, they said
nothing. And like that player, they didn't have to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
