<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BROWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT APPEARS BROWN SOON MAY BE IN GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If the Patriots wish to take care of
important business first, before they hire a coach and/or a general
manager, they should sit down by the side of their most inspiring
offensive player and keep him on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay here,'' said wide receiver Troy Brown time and
again after he Sunday again showed his mates how football should be
played. ``But I can't really answer what's going to happen. But if
all goes well, I'll probably be back here.''
</P>
<P>
   As Brown spoke, tackle Bruce Armstrong came to his locker, next
to Brown's, and sang, ``Troy Brown! . . . Troy Brown! . . . I'd
really like to be Troy Brown right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And not far away, quarterback Drew Bledsoe said, ``I remember my
first training camp when I was talking to my dad and the only
player I mentioned by name was Troy. He was that special. I just
hope he'll continue to be an asset for us . . . and not for
somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is held in such high regard by his teammates that more
than a few are looking to see if the Patriots keep him before they
decide how committed New England is to winning. Typical was
defensive lineman Willie McGinest, who still has three years to go
on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy is a very special athlete,'' said McGinest. ``Troy's
definitely the type of guy you want to fight for. It all depends on
Troy, and if they're going to sign him or whatever and whether
they're going to keep guys like Troy, guys who are not going to
quit on you.'' Whether the Patriots sign Brown, McGinest went on,
``will affect the decisions of guys about staying in Foxborough or
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is in ideal position, surviving the huge risk when he
turned down a $1.5 million offer and continued to play this season
for approximately a paltry $450,000, but now sure to receive
lucrative free agent offers. As any Patriot fan could see, Brown is
worth close to his weight in gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous risk I took,'' said Brown, who endured
ankle injuries the last two seasons. ``I had a whole year and a
half to go before I became a free agent and I had a couple of ankle
injuries. I guess that's why I'm a punt returner: It takes guts (to
turn down a contract extension and wait for free agency). What I
did was take a tremendous chance, and it almost backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots' offense an offense in name only the last half
of the season, Brown often was the only player who stepped up to
make huge play after huge play. And Sunday was no different. As the
offense continued its deep hibernation, Brown returned kickoffs 54
and 49 yards and a punt 52 yards; two of those returns led directly
to 10 New England points.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a guy . . . what a guy,'' enthused coach Pete Carroll.
``He makes it look so easy. To put Troy out there and all of a
sudden we're getting 50 yards a pop (on returns). And the other
guys have such a tremendous respect for Troy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the intangible that Brown _ a small man neither overly
fast nor overly shifty _ brings to the team that makes him so
invaluable. Carroll and vice president of player personnel Bobby
Grier have learned too late that it is this intangible, which Sam
Gash personified, that means as much to a team as size and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it depends on your attitude,'' said Brown, explaining
his credo while trying to pinpoint how and why the Patriots'
offense went so bad this season. `` `You can't be stopped, you
can't be tackled,' is how I approach the game. And, `I'm not going
to be tackled by one guy,' and `I'm not going to go down.' I'm
going to make a play. I'm going to make something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans chanted his name as Brown was the last player to leave
the field, ``and that was great,'' he said. ``I think it showed
that people appreciate hard work, and that's what I've done since
I've been here: work hard to get better. I'm just looking to create
a special edge for myself. A lot of it depends on what you tell
yourself in your attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   His success and the Patriots' success _ or lack of it _ ``all
goes back to your attitude and what you believe.'' The same will be
said of the Patriots' organization as Brown, and other Patriots,
wait to see what New England does about re-signing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on when the Patriots come to me,'' said Brown of
his prospects of returning. ``I can't sit here and say I'm going to
let (other offers) pass me by while sitting around and waiting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
