<HEADLINE>
RESTRUCTURING OF BLEDSOE DEAL ON TAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After the Patriots sort out their
coaching/management situation in the days to come, one of the first
orders of business will be to restructure Drew Bledsoe's contract,
according to a team official.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots must get Bledsoe's cap number down to ease the $8.6
million hit they're scheduled to take with his current deal next
season, and the $9.8 million whack set for 2001, the final year of
his pact.
</P>
<P>
   New England will have to come up with a huge signing bonus,
likely in the vicinity of $20 million on a four- or five-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe fell 15 yards short of his third 4,000-yard season,
going 15 for 25 for only 108 yards, with one touchdown and one
interception. He finished with 19 touchdowns and 21 interceptions
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe played all of Sunday's 20-3 win over the Ravens, ending
speculation that fan favorite Michael Bishop might get a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole, it was a very disappointing year for us,'' said
Bledsoe. ``We had high hopes coming in, high hopes after 11 weeks,
and we just couldn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Of coach Pete Carroll's postgame speech to the team, Bledsoe
said, ``He said he was proud of our effort in the game. He wasn't
sure under the circumstances of this team not having much
experience of handling things (while being) out of the playoffs
that the effort would be there. We gave the effort and we won. Last
week we lost in OT, but the effort was there as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he felt exhausted after the game. He was sacked
twice, making it 55 on the season, and was knocked down more than
100 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I'll be fine,'' he said. ``I came out of it
relatively healthy. Mentally, this one's going to take a little
while. Right now, I'm just extremely tired mentally, emotionally,
and physically. I just need to go to sleep for a couple of days and
get rested and then start working toward recharging the
batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe lauded left tackle Bruce Armstrong for playing with a
torn knee ligament for the last seven games and said he wasn't sure
whether Shawn Jefferson, Troy Brown, Tedy Bruschi, or Lawyer Milloy
would be back.
</P>
<P>
   But he was certain about the return of one man _ wide receiver
Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry Glenn is going to be back on this team,'' said Bledsoe.
``He'll be an important part of this team in the future. I have no
doubt about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
