<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVENS DIDN'T HEED BILLICK'S SAGE ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Baltimore Ravens coach Brian Billick was
uneasy about Sunday's game a few hours before it started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I was in this stadium, I was coaching with
Minnesota,'' he said. ``We had a (20-3) lead at halftime, and got
beat (26-20, in 1994). They came out and threw something like 62
passes in the game and beat us in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my players that. We have to get them down and keep them
down. We have to stay on top of them all the way. The one thing we
don't want to do _ and I emphasized this with our team _ is turn
the ball over. We don't want to give them the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick's worst fears were realized. His Ravens, who entered
with a four-game win streak, went down in flames as they
disintegrated on special teams and offense.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again his coverage teams were embarrassed by the
brilliance of return man Troy Brown, who gave the Patriots all the
field position they needed.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a great showing on offense by the Patriots by any
means, but their defense and Brown made it easy for them. Their one
touchdown drive went all of 23 yards; their other touchdown came on
defensive tackle Chad Eaton's return of a recovered fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first three quarters, Brown had 173 yards on kick
returns. During the same period, the entire Patriots offense
totaled 153.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Brown, there were two other keys to the New England win.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Patriots got more pressure on Tony Banks than they
had on any other quarterback all year. And Banks eventually folded
in the face of the blitz.
</P>
<P>
   With the Patriots ahead, 13-3, in the third quarter, linebacker
Ted Johnson blitzed up the middle and decked Banks, who fumbled.
Eaton picked up the ball and ran it in.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell seemed to sense
that Baltimore, which had averaged 28 points per game the last
month, was not handling the blitz well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in this game is in interrelated,'' he said.
``Today, we had the chance to get consistent pressure on the
quarterback because we had the lead. Once you get in front and have
a cushion, you can think about stopping the ball and get after it.
You can't always do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pressure today was effective. They ran the ball well,
better than I thought they would, but once they got behind and had
to go with the pass, we had the chance to get some pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our guys before the game that Banks has been bothered
by pressure in the past, and if we could get some hits on him, he
would probably give us a fumble, because he has a history of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Henry Thomas had a big day working on the
inside. He got off the ball fast, making for a better push up the
middle than the Patriots have had all year. Johnson, not usually a
blitzer, had two sacks in the first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   On one of those hits Banks was injured, and he had to give way
to Stoney Case. Banks had been sacked four times before he left.
Case was sacked thrice and threw an interception. The Patriots had
seven sacks to the Ravens' two. The Patriots had three penalties to
the Ravens' nine, and the Patriots had one turnover to the Ravens'
four.
</P>
<P>
   In view of everything swirling around the team this week, with
speculation about coach Pete Carroll, the team played remarkably
well.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Bill Parcells has said over the years that he can
tell how well his team wants to play by how it does on special
teams and in the turnover department. The Patriots' special teams
dominated their counterparts, and New England won the turnover
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore thought it would be able to attack the depleted New
England secondary with the deep ball, but just couldn't get it
done.
</P>
<P>
   Starters Ty Law, Steve Israel, and Chris Carter were out of the
lineup. The top backup, Tebucky Jones, was also injured and
inactive.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had to dress players nobody's ever heard of, such
as Terry Billups, Rico Clark, and Corey Ivy. Two weeks ago, Billups
was selling music videos in Dallas. Clark was just cut by
Cincinnati. Ivy was called up from the practice squad. Free safety
Tony George was starting his first game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Ravens could not take advantage. They ran the ball
extremely well, outgaining New England on the ground, 119-49. But
when they got behind and had to throw, they couldn't get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   Banks has a history of being erratic. He was in this game, too,
and because of that took his team out of the big finish it
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Billick told his team: ``You thought you could just
walk in here and win. I told you we couldn't think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for him, his players did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
