<HEADLINE>
NATO'S TRAP AT RAMBOUILLET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sixth of 8-part series, `My Return to Kosovo's Killing Fields')   (This provocative 925-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article _
sixth of an eight-part special report by Robert Fisk, ``My Return
to Kosovo's Killing Fields'' _ is from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS AN EDITOR-FRIENDLY 325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 825; UNCUT
VERSION IS 1,250 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``i''
international news files.)  
  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: IN HIS UNCOMPROMISING DISPATCHES FROM THE FRONT
LINES, THE INDEPENDENT'S VETERAN CORRESPONDENT ROBERT FISK WAS
NATO'S STERNEST CRITIC DURING THE WAR IN KOSOVO. FISK RECENTLY
``RETURNED TO THE SCENE OF THE CRIME'' OF 1999'S TOP INTERNATIONAL
NEWS STORY, TO SEARCH FOR THE WAR'S FIRST CASUALTY: TRUTH. AND TO
COUNT THE CONFLICT'S REAL _ AND CONTINUING _ HUMAN TOLL. THE NEW
YORK TIMES SYNDICATE IS PLEASED TO SHARE THIS EXCELLENT,
HARD-HITTING EIGHT-PART EXCLUSIVE REPORT WITH YOU AND YOUR
READERS.)  
 &HT;    _ 1. Exhuming Bodies _ and Truth _ in NATO's Kosovo Killing
Fields 
 &HT;    _ 2. NATO Cover-Up Of Kosovo's Uranium Poisoning Exposed 
 &HT;    _ 3. Kosovo's Religious Desecration Is NATO's Shame 
 &HT;    _ 4. Postwar Kosovo `Ethnically Cleansed' of Serbs _ On NATO's
Watch 
 &HT;    _ 5. Serb Vengeance Flows Through NATO-Bombed Danube 
 &HT;    _ 6. NATO's Trap At Rambouillet 
 &HT;    _ 7. NATO Opened Pandora's Box In Kosovo _ And Must Now Cope
With It 
 &HT;    _ 8. `Frothers' And `Sheep': The Journalists Who Bleated NATO's
Lies 
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BELGRADE _ In the last days of the Paris peace talks on
Yugoslavia last March, something extraordinary happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb delegation _ after agreeing to a political resolution
in Kosovo _ were presented with a military appendix to the treaty
which demanded the virtual NATO occupation of all Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs turned it down and NATO went to war. Yet 79 days
later, NATO _ which had refused to contemplate a change in the
military document _ lost all interest in the annex and at the final
dramatic meetings on the Macedonian border was content with a force
only inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Official obfuscation and confusion has ever since surrounded
this all-important, last-minute addition to the Paris ``peace''
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Was it presented by the Americans in order to force President
Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia to reject the whole peace package and
permit NATO to bomb Serbia?
</P>
<P>
   NATO sources claim the Serbs would anyway never have abided by
the Kosovo political accords _ in which case, why did the West
negotiate with Belgrade in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   Even the text of the military appendix was not known to
journalists reporting the two sets of ``peace'' talks in
Rambouillet and Paris. The Serbs say they denounced it at their
last Paris press conference _ an ill attended gathering at the
Yugoslav Embassy at 11 p.m. on March 18, too late for that day's
television news and the next day's papers.
</P>
<P>
   Although a summary of an early draft of the peace treaty was
placed in the House of Commons library on March 1, the full treaty
and the military annexes together were not put in the House library
until April 1 _ the first day of the parliamentary recess and a
week after NATO's bombing campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   The full annexes demanded NATO rights of road, rail and air
passage across all of Yugoslavia, the use of radio stations, even
the waiving of any claims of damages against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   For any state _ even one as grotesque as Serbia _ this would
have amounted to occupation.
</P>
<P>
   French Foreign Minister Hubert Vidrine says that the military
appendix was similar to that used by NATO when it moved troops into
Bosnia and that NATO forces needed access to Kosovo through
Belgrade. But he has never explained why this supposedly essential
part of the treaty was abandoned once NATO troops moved into the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Komnenic, who was the Yugoslav Federal information
minister and a member of Vuk Draskovic's Serbian Renewal Movement
(then in government but soon to be in opposition), was in Paris
during the talks and has become preoccupied with the military
annex.
</P>
<P>
   He is writing a book about the negotiations entitled: ``The Trap
of Rambouillet.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, bespectacled figure with a reputation for intelligence
and integrity _ he admits that atrocities were carried out by Serbs
in Kosovo _ he says he still does not understand why the war
started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know when the Russians found out about paragraphs 6,
7 and 8 of the annex. Igor Ivanov (the Russian foreign minister)
claimed the Russian side didn't know about the annex at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surprise is that besides the Americans, no one knew about
the annex. We were given it one day before the end of the Paris
talks _ at `a minute before midnight.' Before that, we heard only
rumors about the implementation of the political agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Komnenic, U.S. negotiator Christopher Hill and the
Austrian diplomat at the talks, Boris Petritsch, insisted on the
annex while Boris Mayorski, the Russian negotiator _ who later
refused to attend the Kosovo Albanian signing of the ``peace''
agreement _ abstained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hill and Petritsch were `for' the annex and (British Foreign
Secretary Robin) Cook and Vidrine apparently agreed with a version
_ not identical to the final annex _ which was called an
`explanation' of the political agreement and which said there could
be no implementation with a NATO presence only in Kosovo,''
Komnenic adds.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo Albanian newspaper Koha Ditore in January Komnenic
says, the Hill plan was published without annex B. ``And Hill gave
Mr. Draskovic and myself a copy of the plan in February _ calling
for a military presence in Kosovo but not in all of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then in Paris, Hill opened his bag and put annex B on the
table _ one day before the collapse. I don't even know if our side
knew till then about the Annex... But when we realized the danger
of war was threatening, we `de facto' accepted the political
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the Americans were surprised by our acceptance of
the agreement. So they were preparing their trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the military annex became widely known, western leaders
have either tried to explain it away as a routine addendum to any
peace implementation or an essential mechanism to get NATO into
Kosovo. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 825) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cook has adopted both tactics. Replying to Sir Peter Emery in
the Commons foreign affairs committee on April 28 _ when the NATO
bombardment had been going on for more than a month while half the
Albanian population of Kosovo was being ``ethnically cleansed'' by
the Serbs _ Cook stated that: ``The proposal for a military
presence in Kosovo was one confined to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   This, he said, would require a ``force agreement'' with the
Yugoslav government ``that may (sic) be the text which has
appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue, he went on, had never been raised by the Serb
delegation ``which suggests to me that there is something deeply
false about the idea that this is now the basis on which talks
broke down.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the military annex was the ``casus belli'' was a
``canard.''
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic, a minister in Milosevic's government and a close
friend of the president, says that the European Contact Group
designed the political framework for the Rambouillet talks and that
at one meeting the Russians refused to discuss the political and
military annex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the end of the second week of March, our delegation
received the paper which contained the military annex,'' Matic
says. The Contact Group had managed to present the paper without
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our delegation, together with Mayorski, decided to withdraw
acceptance of the paper because it wasn't produced by all the
Contact Group. For this reason, we said the paper was only
`informal.' But the Americans were trying to `legalize' the paper _
which wasn't acceptable to the Russians. Mayorski put in a written
objection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to accept the political solution of the Kosovo
problem and U.N. troops to regulate the implementation, but not
NATO troops in occupation,'' Matic says. ``United Nations Security
Council resolution 1244 (which ended the conflict) could have been
accepted before the bombing.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF 325-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,250) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In any event, when NATO commanders met the Serbs for the
``military-technical agreement'' at the end of the war _ after
thousands of Kosovo Albanians had been murdered by Serb forces and
as many as 1,500 Serb and Albanian civilians slaughtered by NATO
bombs _ the supposedly crucial military annex was never mentioned
by the victors.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, NATO _ with 40,000 troops to move into the
province (10,000 more than originally envisaged at Rambouillet) _
no longer needed appendix B. Not a single NATO soldier moved north
of Kosovo into the rest of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   So the question remains: ``What was the real purpose of NATO's
last-minute demand? Saving the peace? Or Sabotage? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
