OFFERS TWO EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS _ AT 475 (100 WORDS) AND
775 (50 WORDS). TOTAL OF UNCUT VERSION IS 1,025.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``i''
international news files.)  
  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: IN HIS UNCOMPROMISING DISPATCHES FROM THE FRONT
LINES, THE INDEPENDENT'S VETERAN CORRESPONDENT ROBERT FISK WAS
NATO'S STERNEST CRITIC DURING THE WAR IN KOSOVO. FISK RECENTLY
``RETURNED TO THE SCENE OF THE CRIME'' OF 1999'S TOP INTERNATIONAL
NEWS STORY, TO SEARCH FOR THE WAR'S FIRST CASUALTY: TRUTH. AND TO
COUNT THE CONFLICT'S REAL _ AND CONTINUING _ HUMAN TOLL. THE NEW
YORK TIMES SYNDICATE IS PLEASED TO SHARE THIS EXCELLENT,
HARD-HITTING EIGHT-PART EXCLUSIVE REPORT WITH YOU AND YOUR
READERS.)  
 &HT;    _ 1. Exhuming Bodies _ and Truth _ in NATO's Kosovo Killing
Fields 
 &HT;    _ 2. NATO Cover-Up Of Kosovo's Uranium Poisoning Exposed 
 &HT;    _ 3. Kosovo's Religious Desecration Is NATO's Shame 
 &HT;    _ 4. Postwar Kosovo `Ethnically Cleansed' of Serbs _ On NATO's
Watch 
 &HT;    _ 5. Serb Vengeance Flows Through NATO-Bombed Danube 
 &HT;    _ 6. NATO's Trap At Rambouillet 
 &HT;    _ 7. NATO Opened Pandora's Box In Kosovo _ And Must Now Cope
With It 
 &HT;    _ 8. `Frothers' And `Sheep': The Journalists Who Bleated NATO's
Lies 
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   PRISTINA _ When gunmen tried to murder the local Serb leader
Momcilo Trajkovic in Pristina in October, the daily Kosovo Albanian
newspaper, Koha Ditore _ with a circulation of around 20,000 _ put
his picture on page one.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that day alone, we lost 5,000 readers _ just because we put
his picture on the front,'' one of the paper's journalists says.
``Our readers wouldn't buy our paper because they saw Trajkovic's
photograph.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the ``forgiveness'' which U.S. President Bill
Clinton recently asked of the Albanians in his best supermarket
style. No wonder Koha Ditore lost readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a debate over what to do,'' the young journalist told
me. ``Do we carry on reporting the news as we wish and lose
thousands of readers? Or do we wait until public opinion changes
before we do something like this again?''
</P>
<P>
   Over at one of Pristina's numerous human-rights groups, there
are no doubts about the template of Kosovo Albanian opinion.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke to a man who has witnessed as much carnage in the Middle
East as many Albanians have seen here. ``Can you imagine what these
people felt in the camps in Macedonia when they listened to some of
the stories I heard there?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a man telling of how a Serb paramilitary had pulled a
girl off a truck and cut out her eyes and then left her lying on
the road. Two hours later, he came back and killed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we took evidence from a man who'd seen seven Albanians
tied to a haystack; after they were tied, the haystack was set
alight.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there were atrocities. Many of the paramilitaries, it
seems, were on hard drugs _ how else could a man put out the eyes
of a fellow human? _ but NATO let them leave Kosovo untouched.
</P>
<P>
   I recall last June standing by the roadside in Kosovo Polje
beside a British armored vehicle whose soldiers were watching with
amusement as a truckload of Serb gunmen, threading its way through
a Yugoslav army column, passed them by.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs were wearing shades _ one of them wore a hood _ and
several were swigging from brandy bottles. They had painted ``F___
(expletive) the Shipters'' (Albanians) on their truck along with
crudely drawn pictures of skulls and they were making ``V'' signs
at us. But the NATO boys did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Potential war criminals could leave with the Yugoslav army if
that meant a peaceful NATO entry into Kosovo. That, minus the
diplomatic phrases, was part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, the war-crimes officials here would like the
names and identities of the Serb gunmen whose departure NATO did
nothing to prevent. But without the evidence of these men, their
admissions, their defense, there will be precious few arrests. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 475) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And atrocity stories are almost as easy to deny as they are to
be believed. ``There was another story I heard,'' the human-rights
official said. ``And I'm not certain it's true. I was told that a
man was put in the bucket of a JCB truck _ the kind you use to
hoist electricity workers up to mend power lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I was told the Serbs put an Albanian in the bucket and
then, using the vehicle, tossed him onto high-tension power lines
where he burned to death. But it was a story, third-hand. We could
find no witnesses.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there is still no code of law in Kosovo and no
real police force. A constabulary is being trained, it's true _
Serbs as well as Albanians _ but the U.N. police are coming under
constant abuse. Several of their vehicles have been stoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to make crime enquiries when everything you say
has to go through a third party, the interpreter,'' the
human-rights worker says. ``People don't want to talk. There's a
lot of intimidation. And the Albanian mafia is working hard here.''
</P>
<P>
   He is right. At night, the sleek guys from Tirana turn up to
drink cappuccino and brandy in the revamped coffee shop of the
ghastly old Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Their fingers are dripping rings, their hair damp over velvet
collars, their creepy bodyguards working mobile phones at the next
table. They are collecting taxes from the shopkeepers (Deutschmarks
only), deciding who should run the growing street market of
vegetable, meat and CD stalls.
</P>
<P>
   They don't even bother to look at the U.N. cops cruising the
streets in their little red cars. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 50 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 775) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 28 the Kosovo Albanians celebrated a 15th-century
Albanian uprising against Ottoman rule, and the 1912 declaration of
Albanian independence. In the early hours of the following day, a
mob in Pristina hauled three elderly Serbs from their car, shot the
man dead and assaulted the two women. And outside, in the
countryside, houses still burn. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,025) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real flaw not to have police coming in here with
KFOR,'' the human-rights official says. ``There is going to have to
be some form of international law to cover the interim period after
a war. These are topics for a major debate in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, NATO blames the U.N. for not putting more
policemen into Kosovo more quickly. But when NATO was at war, it
didn't want any United Nations involvement. It didn't want to talk
about policemen with the bureaucrats on Manhattan's East River.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the war was over, when it needed cops, did NATO expect
the U.N. to snap to attention and provide a ready-made police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, with the last gypsies herded into camps _ there
are 740 in a camp at Pristina and another 460 in Macedonia _ the
West's determination to maintain an Albanian-Serb society in the
province appears futile.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, KFOR _ with its British, American, Turkish, Emirate,
German and other peacekeeping contingents _ is now the only
multi-ethnic society in Kosovo. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
