<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-CO     01-03 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: U.S. needs to reclaim its borders
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, Jan. 5, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ No sooner had the calendar flipped to a new year,
century and millennium than the same old dilemma was upon us again.
</P>
<P>
   A shabby wooden vessel carrying 411 Haitians, Dominicans and
Chinese ran aground just off the Miami area. None of the passengers
had gone through the formal process of immigration to the United
States, and authorities suspect professional smugglers had a hand
in their voyage.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard followed its instructions and shipped them back
from whence they came. This act brought out the ethnic protesters
on the first day of the new millennium. They paraded around Coast
Guard headquarters and at the Immigration and Naturalization
Service building, their placards calling on the U.S. to let in all
411, or give immigrant Haitians the same justice as the U.S. gives
to Cubans fleeing their island.
</P>
<P>
   Any Cuban who makes it to shore gets to stay, but the permission
is not extended to Haitians or others. The deal the U.S. has with
Cuba is for the legal migration of 20,000 Cubans to the U.S.
annually. If 150 come in illegally on rafts, they don't count
against the number.
</P>
<P>
   With Miami so heavily populated with Cuban and Haitian refugees,
it is difficult to enforce U.S. immigration laws. A case in point
is the little boy who came floating in on Thanksgiving Day after
his mother died at sea. He's still here, being exploited by his
guardians and TV cameras, while his father _ in Cuba _ calls for
his return. Whether or not the father is a communist should not be
the basis for legal judgment. His father is the child's living
parent.
</P>
<P>
   So much of the illegal refugee situation is one fought in the
streets and on the airwaves. ``Let 'em all in,'' would be the cry
of those who entered before them, many illegally.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner or later, the U.S. has to put a cap on who gets here.
The first thing that ought be done is to differentiate between the
words ``legal'' and ``illegal.'' Illegal means they skipped the
process, violated U.S. immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Should they be afforded the same welcome as those who went
through the process, likely waiting years for the paperwork to
clear?
</P>
<P>
   When the Lyndon Johnson administration first made it possible
for Cubans to flee Fidel Castro for Miami, it was because the
refugees truly were political refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But now, things are different. Cubans, Haitians, Mexicans and
others from Latin America don't necessarily come here because they
fear for their lives based on politics _ i.e., political asylum _
but because they want to earn money, buy food, have a roof over
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying that these are people in need, but does that
also mean that everyone who feels like coming to the U.S. can set
out tomorrow? These are not political refugees; they are economic
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   INS is caught in a vise. So is the Coast Guard. They both are
subject to erratic policy decisions and alterations by whomever is
occupying the White House. Remember Jimmy Carter's Mariel boatlift
policy, which he kept changing every six hours as more than 100,000
Cubans shuttled across the Straits of Florida in just a couple of
weeks?
</P>
<P>
   I believe that Americans truly want to reach out and help the
unfortunate others. But it's got to be done in an orderly (legal)
fashion. Those who have reached this country from elsewhere, either
legally or illegally, have got to understand that the situation is
out of control, and that their protests against U.S. agencies for
enforcing existing laws are obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Often, when dealing with our immigrant history, reference is
made to those 19th and early 20th century days when immigrants from
Italy, Ireland, Germany, Poland, etc., sailed for Ellis Island in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between that traffic and what we now are enduring
is that the earlier refugees came in legally. To me, that's a
distinction with a huge difference.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
