<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5102 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX     01-03 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: One last volley in Kosovo conflict
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no great harm will have been done if U.N. prosecutors
quickly dispose of the tendentious charges that NATO committed war
crimes in Serbia and Kosovo and go back to the tribunal's serious
business.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably, investigators then could say they'd shown
even-handedness by reviewing the representations, making the
investigation and sustained charges against virtually self-evident
war criminals all the more credible.
</P>
<P>
   But if this farce is allowed to drag on _ or, worse, if charges
actually are extruded from the thin goods agenda-driven complainers
have brought to the tribunal _ then the U.N. will have effectively
given future license to the crudest human-rights abusers. For who
will oppose them if errors in the opposition are accounted crime?
</P>
<P>
   The details are few and the waters murky around this part of the
investigations by the war-crimes tribunal, but apparently the
claims against NATO have been pressed by a group of Russian
legislators, a Canadian law professor and one or more human-rights
advocacy organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Cited are the bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, air
attacks on s and roads that killed civilians, and civilian
casualties incidental to the bombing of military sites and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The hit on the embassy was clearly the result of miscalculation,
not calculation, freely admitted by Washington and compensated for
in a negotiated, bilateral agreement. It is simply impossible to
know whether civilians are interlaced with military convoys or to
time an attack on a bridge so that missiles will arrive only when a
military train is crossing.
</P>
<P>
   And would war-crime investigators care to validate the ploy of
putting strategic facilities in civilian areas as a way to immunize
them from attack? If so, then the United Nations would be in the
very odd business of encouraging even more eventual civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Look, wars are distinctly nasty affairs. There can be righteous
ones but there are no pretty ones.
</P>
<P>
   NATO went to elaborate lengths to minimize collateral damage _
in lives and property _ as it forced Serbia to end its mass murders
of Muslim Kosovars and its expulsions of the survivors from their
homes. But not even the newest, neatest gee-whiz weapons can seine
combatants from noncombatants or culpable policymakers from mere
bureaucrats where they are muddled together.
</P>
<P>
   Further, there is simply no moral equivalency _ none, zero,
zilch _ between atrocities committed with calculated malice in the
service of deliberated policy and inadvertent casualties that occur
in resisting atrocity. Even self-defense doesn't allow for
retributive warfare, but surely neither victims nor their defenders
are obliged to defer to abuse lest their resistance go awry.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. tribunal's chief prosecutor, Carla Del Ponte, is
downplaying her NATO investigation, suggesting it is marginal. But
now that it has surfaced, in the name not just of justice but of
simple sanity, it needs to be definitively retired.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
