A5108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN04-COX     01-03 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resolving to find a husband
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My friend Alice called early this morning to
fill me in on her New Year's resolution. It's pretty
straightforward. ``I'm going to be married before the end of the
year,'' is exactly what she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still dark out,'' I mumble rolling over to see if I can
detect a glimmer of anything on the horizon. Still a bit groggy, it
takes me a minute to catch on to the giant star I see rising in the
east and remember it's the one on top of the grain elevator a block
away, lighted for the holidays. ``Who's the guy?''
</P>
<P>
   Alice admits she hasn't met him yet but she knows he will be
tall, handsome, and a professional man more concerned with
character than beauty. I tell her I have just the guy for her. She
isn't really interested, which is probably a good thing since all I
have to go on is a ``Brides Wanted'' classified page ripped from a
1998 edition of The Hindu, an English language newspaper from
Chennai, India, that I found stuffed in a toiletries kit I'd
ordered from an in-flight shopping magazine.
</P>
<P>
   I fish the rumpled paper out of my night table drawer and read
it to her anyway: ``Settled, handsome, well-employed professional,
seeking homely girl above 160 cms, preferably software
professional. Send horoscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice remarks, almost indifferently, that she has never thought
of herself as homely, only plain. I suggest that possibly we're
misinterpreting the intent of the word and that maybe in India it
means a girl who'll be willing to hang around the house and stir
the curry. ``So why the `software professional' stipulation?'' she
asks. I confess ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how tall is 160 cms anyway?'' We play with that one for a
while until Alice remembers that old cigarette commercial _ the one
that advertised ``just a silly millimeter more'' and decides what
he means is that anyone taller than a Virginia Slim might apply.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Alice hasn plan for snagging a mate. First thing
Monday morning she's calling some lady in New York to sign up for a
276-hour, $9,600 course designed to put her psyche on the fast
track to a more man-receptive mind set. ``A consultant will even
come to my house and show me how to make my closets `man-ready'.''
</P>
<P>
   My timing stinks, but I can't help it. A chuckle breaks loose as
I tell Alice I can handle that from here and for free. She dares
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just throw away the hangers and nail the closet door shut,'' I
tell her. ``All any man really needs is enough open floor for his
dirty underwear and adequate chair space to accommodate his suits
until you get around to taking them to the cleaners.'' She suggests
those are pretty loose words coming from a woman who's been single
for over 20 years. I remind her I'm not the one in the market for a
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good thing,'' she wisecracks, explaining that no sensible man
would consider spending the rest of his life with a woman who lies
in bed eating dry Cheerios and listening to Edward Gibbon's ``Fall
of the Roman Empire'' on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Alice is deadly serious about going to New York and investing a
pot full of money in an attempt to render herself (and her closets)
husband-ready. I suggest that first she try a new hairdo and some
lacy Victoria's Secret stuff. She says she likes her hair ne
and it's the wrong time of year for flimsy undies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice,'' I begin sternly, deciding to get down and dirty
before my old friend reaches for her checkbook, ``you've had three
husbwo died, and one you didn't even like. Don't you think
it's time you forgot marriage and took up kayak portaging or whale
blubber rendering? Just think, maybe you could chew your own
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice giggles politely but insists married is the only way she
wants to be and this time she's looking for a young one who won't
up and die on her. I make a joke about starting a family (she's 63)
and she tells me not to sweat the details.
</P>
<P>
   Gotta' love her attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GADGETS04-COX     01-03 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GADGETS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dentist's tool attacks bad breath at source
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ According to dentist Clifford Yudelman, 90
percent of bad breath originates in the crevices at the back of the
tongue, not in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Yudelman says he invented the Breath-So-Fresh Tongue
Cleaner, a device that uses a scraping tool and gel to clean debris
from the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tongue cleaners have been around since 100 A.D. and were
common until the turn of the century,'' Yudelman said. ``People are
just starting to rediscover the benefits of cleaning the back of
the tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Price, D.M.D., a spokesman for the American Dental
Association, agreed that cleaning the tongue is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad breath is caused by anaerobic bacteria that settle on the
tongue,'' Price said. ``Living at the back of the tongue where they
can be coated by post-nasal drip is like a trip to Club Med for
anaerobic bacteria. Scraping the tongue exposes them to air and
kills them.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said any device that allows the user to scrape the back of
the tongue without causing too much of a gagging reflex is helpful.
He said a toothbrush works for some people, but because a
toothbrush sits up high on the tongue it causes some people to gag.
</P>
<P>
   The Breath-So-Fresh is shaped like a miniature tennis racket
frame. To use it, you place some of the breath gel that comes with
the product into the frame and pull the cleaner gently forward from
the back of the tongue to the front.
</P>
<P>
   The product sells for about $5 and should be available at Target
stores.
</P>
