<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online security fears exaggerated, but use common sense
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If people worried as deeply and constantly about the
security of their homes as they do about online security, most
burglars would be in the unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   The same folks who go to a restaurant and happily hand a credit
card over to a waiter they've never seen before worry about using
the same credit card to order from Amazon.com. People who fear that
some 13-year-old genius will invade their e-mail to Aunt Sally live
in houses with plastic unlocked mailboxes in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about a new threat that makes it seem more
important than the old one.
</P>
<P>
   But there are dangers online, and they are gradually getting
worse. They may someday even catch up with the hysterical fears _
fanned nicely by newspapers, television and magazines _ of the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at some of the ways you can protect yourself online.
</P>
<P>
   Passwords: Think of the password as the direct equivalent of
your house key. Once someone has that password _ or guesses it _
you are, in technical terms, dog meat. But many people figuratively
leave that password hanging on a string by the front door. Ask any
computer network administrator ... way too many people, worried
about forgetting their passwords, use the name of a spouse, their
birthday or telephone number as a password.
</P>
<P>
   The fix: Use ord that is a combination of numbers and
letters. Some automated hacking programs use words in the
dictionary and _ with the endless patience of a computer _ can
eventually find the right password if it is listed there.
Especially on AOL, you are likely to get e-mail or a chat message
that purports to be from AOL itself asking for your password, or
asking you to sign on a Web site using the AOL password. Don't.
Also, make sure that you change your password every couple of
months. Don't use the same password for all your online accounts.
Don't tell anyone your password. And don't _ as I've seen happen _
write your password down and paste it to your computer monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Credit cards online: The fear is that some young person will
intercept your credit card number and retire happily to a life of
leisure on Maui. Like a lot of fears, there is an element of truth
here. There have been times when academic computer experts have
discovered holes in even the best encryption. But if you look for
merchants that advertise ``secure servers,'' the chances of someone
breaking in are on a par with lightning striking your car as you
drive to work.
</P>
<P>
   The fix: Deal with trusted and recognized ``brand name''
companies on the Web. Then stop worrying so much. Your credit card
number is much more vulnerable in the real world. One of the
least-risky ways to conduct business on the Net is by using a
credit card since the credit card company itself will reimburse
most if not all your losses from fraud or theft.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: Even if you aren't a spy or a crook, you probably don't
want some hacker reading your e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The fix: Like many crimes, you are most vulnerable from those
who know you. Frankly, strangers probably have very little interest
in your mail. So if others share your computer, don't use the
option offered by many e-mail programs of saving your password.
Also, if you use e-mail at work, log off the system before leaving
your desk for any extended period. Keep in mind, too, that any
saved e-mail messages are stored on your hard disk and easily
accessible _ without a password _ to anyone who has access to your
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Attachments: Many viruses _ including some that will forward the
e-mail in your outbox to the addresses it finds in your e-mail
program _ arrive as an attachment to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The fix: Discourage attachments. Don't open e-mails with an
attachment when it comes from a stranger. Use an anti-virus program
to scan attachments, even when it is one that you requested. Manses are transmitted unwittingly from person to person, so your
friend may not even realize he's sending an infected file.
</P>
<P>
   All these precautions are worthwhile. But once you've covered
the obvious bases, do something that will really improve your
security. Buy good deadbolt locks for the doors of your home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
