<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spell Catcher 8 a universal standout
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine if you could have one dictionary, spell
checker and thesaurus that worked in every program, whether
QuarkXPress or Microsoft Outlook.
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind Casady &AMP; Greene's Spell Catcher 8. It's a
systemwide utility that consolidates most text-editing features
into one place, one interface.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most programs today, whether Microsoft Word or
Netscape Navigator, have some text-editing features, such as
spell-checking.
</P>
<P>
   But Spell Catcher trumps them all on two counts: Its
dictionaries and thesauruses are bigger than those of other
programs, and it lets you keep one list of expandable glossary
terms rather than many.
</P>
<P>
   With Spell Catcher, you no longer have to type a new expandable
glossary term into each dictionary on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a quick look at each of Spell Catcher's main
features. The first thing you'll notice is that Spell Catcher
automatically inserts itself into every program after installation.
It appears as a green check mark in the menu bar. You can turn
Spell Catcher off for any program through its preference dialogue
box, easily available from the menu bar.
</P>
<P>
   Spell Catcher watches as you work. It knows lots of words,
recognizing 1,166 common misspellings, which the program corrects
as you type.
</P>
<P>
   For misspellings it doesn't recognize, Spell Catcher will either
flash or beep, depending on your preference.
</P>
<P>
   When beeped, you just pull down the Spell Catcher menu under the
green check mark. You can do it via the mouse or through a key
command, which you can set. In fact, you can assign key commands to
almost any feature in Spell Catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Spell Catcher presents a dialogue box that lists suggested
spellings. You can pick one, choose to add the word to Spell
Catcher's dictionary or hear the word pronounced.ou can do much more than check spelling with Spell Catcher. It
includes a dictionary with 102,000 definitions. To look up a
definition, highlight the word and then choose the ``look up''
command from the dialogue box.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Word, of course, doesn't include a dictionary. The
only Mac word processor that does is Nisus Writer, and that
dictionary is not as extensive as Spell Catcher's.
</P>
<P>
   Spell Catcher also includes a thesaurus with 550,000 entries.
</P>
<P>
   One of Spell Catcher's most powerful features is its glossary.
Type in an abbreviation for a word, phrase or passage, and it will
expand as you write it in any program.
</P>
<P>
   Other text-editing features include sentence capitalization,
adding smart quotes and eliminating extra tabs and other spaces.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite extra feature is the ability to convert text grabbed
from Web pages into formatted paragraphs in a word processor.
</P>
<P>
   If Spell Catcher has any weakness it is this: The program comes
without a detailed bound manual, a shortcoming unfortunately common
to most software today.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Spell Catcher will not work with older Mac
operating systems. You need at least OS 8.1 and 2 megabytes of
available system memory, or RAM.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find Spell Catcher online or in most computer stores that
sell Macs. The program retails for about $50 in a box and costs $10
less if you download it. An upgrade from an earlier version costs
$20.
</P>
<P>
   Casady &AMP; Greene keeps the latest versions and free demos of
Spell Catcher at its site, which you'll find at www.spellcatcher
</P>
<P>
   .com/8/default.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
