<HEADER>
A5136 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-GAMER04-COX     01-03 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gear for the gamers
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   You gotta pay attention when the guys who mad e the super-freaky
``Neverhood'' come out with a game. That's why I have met
Southpeak's Boombots ($40, www.southpeak.com) with so much
excitement. The game is simple, alien cats are poised to take over
the world and you must fight your way through a myriad of Boombots
(of which you are one) and fight Mandu, the king of the cats. The
game is funny, twisted and a blast to play. But what else would you
expect from the guys from the Neverhood?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of fighting games, have you seen Sega's Dynamite Cop
($50, www.dreamcast.com)? What a game! Based heavily on the arcade
game (with a few extras), you take on the role of a commando in
search of the president's daughter. But what do you use to take on
a boatload of bad guys? Whatever you have. In Dynamite Cop, you can
fight with anything from a bazooka to a missile launcher to a
frozen fish. And fight you do. This game totally pumps the adrenal
gland and leaves you breathless as you fight man after man, woman
after woman, weird creature after weird creature.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   For action game fans, the wait is over _ Id Software has finally
unleashed Quake III Arena ($55, www.quake3arena.com) on a
death-matching public. But is it too little, too late? The
excellent, recently released Unreal Tournament offers a bigger
variety of game modes and a greater variation of levels. Quake III,
unfortunately, is still stuck in its brown, gothic corridor motifs.
But, lest you think Quake III is a disappointment, Id Software has
packed the game with incredible new player models, some innovative
space levels, better and faster online play and gorgeous curved
surfaces. And with a huge community of gamers who will add their
own levels and modifications, the game will only get better with
time. So who wins the Unreal Tournament vs. Quake III battle? Who
cares _ if you like first-person shooters, you should have both.
</P>
<P>
   Theme Park, a game that addicted many a gamer by enticing us
with the ability to create our own roller coasters, has gotten a
facelift with Electronic Arts' SimTheme Park ($40, www.
simthemepark.com), an addictive and playful playground. Here, you
create and monitor an amusement park, hiring employees, building
rides and sending janitors to clean up vomit and trash. Best of
all, you can take a ride on any of your roller coasters, or sit
back and hope the cash rolls in.
</P>
<P>
   The minutely detailed terrain of the Pacific Northwest makes
Flight Unlimited III ($40 for the PC, www.flight3.com) a great
flight simulator for sightseeing _ challenging enough for hard-core
sim fans who savor the nuances of navigation and flight modeling
while providing a detailed tutorial for the newcomer. The look of
the airplanes, however, is not up to the standards of Jane's, the
bible of plane illustrations. And the program, when set for
detailed graphics, clicks by slowly on anything but the fastest
machine. That said, there's a lot here to love: Fly a dozen planes,
from Fokker tri-plane to Beechjet luxury craft, through a wide
range of programmable _ and great-looking _ weather patterns and
seasons, or tackle dozens of challenges from volcano-top landings
to James Bond-style boat chases, plus problems such as turbulence,
wind sheers and crowded airports. The cityscapes, notably Seattle,
are detailed and fun while the sounds, from engine noise to radio
chatter, are first-rate. On the downside, the game has no
multiplayer options.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
