<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-TOOLS04-COX     01-03 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thinking small: Programs to tackle narrow missions
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let us today consider small things, little programs
aimed at solving specific problems.
</P>
<P>
   First comes Aladdin System's DragStrip, another in that long and
noble line of attempts to build the better mousetrap for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   DragStrip really does nothing for you that you can't already do
with a couple of extra mouse clicks. But it's a neat little
program, and I imagine a lot of users will like it.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the idea is to let you call up other applications or
documents without leaving the application or document you are in.
It saves a couple of clicks. The tradeoff is having this little
strip of iconated (if I may coin a nasty little word) buttons
hanging about on your screen.
</P>
<P>
   You can accomplish the same thing by clicking on the little
desktop icon to the right of the start button to jump out of the
current application and go to the desktop, if the program you wish
to open is on the desktop. If it's not, then there's always the
Start button, followed by the Programs button.
</P>
<P>
   I've put my Internet connection, my mail program, my browser,
Windows Explorer, Word, WordPad and the little calendar that comes
with DragStrip on my applications bar. On the Documents bar I put a
project I'm working on. There's also a folders bar, but I can't
imagine what I'd want to put there.
</P>
<P>
   You can put frequently visited Web pages on DragStrip, and if
you have your Internet connection established it will summon your
browser and take you there forthwith.
</P>
<P>
   DragStrip won me over with the inclusion of the calendar. It's
just a calendar; you can't keep track of appointments with it. But
a calendar is essential.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to use it, at least for a while. The only question is
whether its presence will become annoying while I'm working on a
full-screen document. There's not much point in using DragStrip
unless it's kept in the ``always on top'' mode.
</P>
<P>
   But for $20, it's hard to go wrong. For more information, go to
www
</P>
<P>
   .aladdinsys.com.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator, published by a firm with the hectic name of
WinWhatWhere, is a rather sinister piece of work that nonetheless
might be of interest to parents who want to monitor their
children's computing activities. It would be of even more interest
to employers who want to spy on their workers, I suppose, but I'd
rather not think about that.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator, once installed and set up, can be made pretty much
invisible. I think someone with good computer skills who suspected
it was there could find it, but children probably wouldn't suspect
it.
</P>
<P>
   It monitors activity in programs you choose, including Internet
browsers and mail readers. You can see what Web sites and
newsgroups are being visited, although unless keyboard activity is
involved, you won't be able to tell what exactly went on there.
</P>
<P>
   There is even an option to send a ``stealth message,'' invisible
to anyone using the computer, to any selected e-mail address at
specified times reporting usage, which is displayed in a
spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   It does not appear to monitor the activity of programs running
in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator, which might more accurately have been named Big
Brother, can be installed across a network as well as on a single
machine. More information is available at www.winwhatwhere.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
