<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A04-COX     01-03 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I'm looking for someone who can help me with
behavioral problems in a cat. My kitty constantly cries and whines
and meows, and I've ruled out health problems and am now looking
for someone to help me ``train'' her (if you can train a cat!). Do
you have any ideas? _ Kim Brill
</P>
<P>
   A: Train a cat? I am good, but I am not that good. By ruling out
health problems, I hope you mean a full examination (blood tests,
etc.) by a vet. Animal behaviorist Diana Smith, Hearts and Paws,
notes cats may reach sexual maturity as early as four months, so
that is a possibility. Veterinarian Ed Childress of Highland's Pet
Medical Clinic says other indications that this is the cause of the
whining include thrusting her derriere in the air and rubbing her
chest on the ground. This will pass in a few weeks. Remember too,
some breeds such as Siamese are more vocal than others, adds
Childress. Anxiety (over the holidays, the Christmas tree, a stray
in the front yard, house guests, etc.) could also trigger such
behavior. Remove the anxiety and improve the behavior. Q: I am
looking for a specific mailbox for my new house. The box is iron
(heavy), and stands on a pedestal that is usually bolted down. The
slot on front says ``LETTERS,'' and mail is retrieved from the back
from a locked door. This box comes in black, white or green. I want
black. I saw some in a catalog last year, but don't remember which
one. Can you help? _Jan Fulgham
</P>
<P>
   A: Try Renovator's Supply catalog, (800) 659-2211.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a dinnerware set that has been in storage, and it has
gray/black markings on it. What can I use to safely clean it
without affecting the finish? The set was purchased about 25 years
ago. Also, is the company still making this pattern? _ Carolyn
Burton
</P>
<P>
   A: This poppytrail dinnerware in the antique grape by Metlox is
no longer being made. Pieces are only available from companies such
as Retrospective Modern Designs at (712) 653-3678 or online at
retrospective.net. Tips from the professionals who buy and sell
this dinnerware: Try removing the black marks with silver polish or
that miracle cleanser, Bar Keeper's Friend. When storing pottery or
china, separate (and protect) plates with coffee filters or paper
plates. Cuts down on the scratch marks! Q: In the last month or so,
pigeons have moved into my neighborhood. Lots of them! I don't mind
Californians moving in, but pigeons just won't do! Why have they
suddenly invaded the neighborhood, and how can we encourage them to
move on?
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Allen
</P>
<P>
   A: Pigeons are attracted by a good food source and a nice place
to live _ who isn't? Ray Taylor of the Austin Area Pigeon Club says
to look for neighbors who may be putting out food or a vacant
building that provides protection from the elements. Remove the
home and the food and the pigeons might take a hike. Pigeons also
like to roost in high places _ crevices of tall buildings are
attractive because they provide safety from predators like cats.
While you are at it, pick up some inflatable owls _ they scare
pigeons but won't do much to the Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I need you to settle something. My sister says that
millennium is spelled with two n's and I say it is spelled with
one. She said it was a word on her spelling test at school, so it
is correct with two n's. We were at a restaurant and I saw it
spelled with one. Please tell us which one is correct!
</P>
<P>
   _ Brian and Amber Nunnery
</P>
<P>
   A: Amber is correct, big brother. Two n's, two m's, two l's and
two i's. The word comes from the Latin ``mille'' meaning 1,000 and
``annus,'' meaning year. In the Bible, Revelations 20 refers to
this time period when followers ``reigned with Christ a thousand
years.'' Lately, it has come to mean a period of 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago I received a doll catalog called My Twinn.
This company makes a doll from a picture. The dolls are very
detailed and lifelike. Help me to find the company and how I can
get another catalog or e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Request a catalog at mytwinn.com/default.asp or by calling
(800) 4-MY-TWINN (800-469-8946). It takes four weeks for a doll to
be completed. The process begins by matching the child's head _
facial structure, eyes and lips _ so two to three pictures of the
child and a lock of hair are requested. Poseable dolls start at
$149.95; nonposeable, $120.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently went to an evening wedding and was surprised at
the number of women wearing black. Is this OK for an evening
wedding?
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, for an evening wedding black is fine. Remember, in some
Asian cultures, black is considered an unlucky color. No guest
should outshine the bride at a wedding, so steer clear of white.
</P>
<P>
   Q: T.A. Brown Elementary School offers an after-school program
called Prime Time. We would like to offer guitar lessons to
students, but guitars are costly. Are your readers willing to
donate acoustic, six-string guitars (steel strings preferred) to
our school?
</P>
<P>
   _Judy Howard
</P>
<P>
   A: Maybe you will. Readers, call Howard at (512) 414-4295 and
arrange for your dusty guitar to get into eager hands.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently heard on the radio they are looking for people to
help take the census. If you can find out where or whom to contact
I would appreciate it. _ William H.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Census Bureau needs to fill more than 800,000 temporary,
short-term positions to conduct the 2000 census. For information on
where and how to apply for a census job, visit
www.census.gov/jobs2000/www/index.html or call (888) 325-7733. The
bureau estimates that to hire and retain enough staff, it must
attract at least 3 million applicants. Q: My dad recently visited
from Illinois and he fell in love with the metal cafe tables and
chairs at the airport. He would like to know where they were
purchased and their cost. _ Christy Turner
</P>
<P>
   A: The Knoll-designed chairs and table are available, but does
your dad love them several thousand dollars' worth? Each chair is
about $632; tables begin at $460. Austin-Bergstrom received a
discount for ordering in bulk. Call Judy Shelton at Shelton-Keller
Group, (512) 481-1500, to order this aluminum dining furniture
(also seen in trendy museums). Sound expensive? The set will last
forever. So if you amortize $5,000 over the years for uses during
the furniture's life, it is a pittance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please help solve a long-standing argument. What was Guy
Lombardo's theme song? If you are too young to remember, Guy
Lombardo and his orchestra _ was it the Royal Canadians? _ welcomed
the new year over the radio for years and years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mary K. Earney
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Boo-hoo. You got me crying for you ... '' by Gaetano's
brother, Carmen, was his theme song. Of course, Guy brought the
world ``the sweetest music this side of heaven,'' according to his
motto. And his rendition of the Scottish classic ``Auld Lang Syne''
by Robert Burns is a New Year's Eve staple. For those who need to
know, auld lang syne means ``old long since.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read about Bill Gates giving scholarships for minorities.
I'd like to know where to contact his foundation for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   _ A.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Do you have at least a 3.3 average on a 4.0 scale? Have you
exhibited leadership through community service? These are just two
of the selection criteria. The Gates Millennium Scholars,
administered by the United Negro College Fund, will provide
scholarships and fellowships for African-American, Native American,
Hispanic American and Asian-Pacific American students.
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to obtain an application, call (877)
690-GMSP (4677) or visit www.gmsp.org. This year's application
deadline has been extended to Feb. 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar
</P>
<P>
   Reader Larry Drake advises harmonica wannabes to visit
www.klutz.com and order ``Country &AMP; Blues Harmonica for the
Musically Hopeless,'' by Jon Gindick. The book arrives with a
cassette and a harmonica for about $15. Learn in the privacy of
your home. Bonus: No teacher to reprimand you for not practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
