<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-FUTURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How will kids live in the next century?
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We asked kids around metro Atlanta to haul out their
crystal balls and predict what the new century will bring.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 of you responded and let your imaginations run
wild. You envisioned flying cars similar to George Jetson's, flying
school buses and even flying bathtubs. We saw teleporters shaped
like satellite dishes and a microchip in a fingertip to be used
like a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Robots frequently took center stage. They could help you clean
your room or even assist a handicapped person.
</P>
<P>
   You were concerned about the fate of serious things, too, such
as AIDS, the environment and endangered species. You also wrote to
us about a better society, one in which people are treated equally.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some more examples of the future you see:
</P>
<P>
   _ Amanda Havriluk, a fifth-grader at the Wesleyan School in
Gwinnett County, told us: ``The planets will be used for different
things. You will go to Earth to work and get food to eat. You will
fly to Uranus for vacations. You will go to Mars to party! You will
go to Saturn to shop, especially for rings, because Saturn is the
ringed planet! You will go to Venus to get beautiful like Venus the
goddess! You will go to jumping Jupiter to play sports. You will go
to Mercury when you get really old to retire. And all the bad
people will go to Pluto to be in jail. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things will be easier in the new millennium. Showers
will be like car washes _ automatic! And, when you step out, you
are blown dry. ... Everyone speaks the same language _ Universal
Space Language.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Delores Cooper, a seventh-grader at Peachtree Middle School in
DeKalb County, wrote about a healing machine to make people well.
Patients would pass through it on a conveyor belt while lying on
their backs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Garrik Hughes, an eighth-grader at Peachtree Middle School in
DeKalb County, envisions a ``machine that makes what your heart
desires.'' He would ``only give it to people who are not
criminals.'' You would wear a hat with wires sticking out to send
signals to a tower shaped like a pyramid. Then the pyramid would
turn your fondest wishes into reality.
</P>
<P>
   _ Demetrius Brown, a seventh-grader at Peachtree Middle School
in DeKalb County, wrote us about a smart pill that kids could take
so they wouldn't have to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diedre f Smyrna (her grade and school were
unavailable), predicted, ``There will be a cure for AIDS and HIV.
There will be no slavery in countries, cities, states or towns!
There will be equal rights for all minority people. There will be
skilled and smarter students. ... There will be better paying
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Sanders, a third-grader at Fountain Elementary in
Clayton County, told us, ``In the next millennium, there will be no
endangered animals.'' He drew animals living in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   _ Katherine Chou, a seventh-grader at Dickerson Middle School in
Cobb County, wrote us a short story with a moral about our
environment. Here is an excerpt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Katherine noticed the sun was coming up, and what she saw made
her gasp. As far as she could see, the world was nothing more than
a big, black, crusty thing. There were a couple of trees, and lucky
for her she was next to one. The only source of oxygen for a good
mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, make a difference, help our Earth and be kind to it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Quang Danh, a second-grader at Morrow Elementary in Clayton
County, would be happy with one change: ``School computers will
have letters in alphabetical order.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
