r l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH04-COX     01-03 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The crisis that fizzled
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The electricity stayed on, planes stayed in the air,
trains chugged along right on schedule, computers didn't conk out,
no banks ran out of money, and the millennium bug didn't kill the
monsters on your PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   For months _ actually years _ we've been deluged with scary
reports that computers might blink out like fireflys when the
clocks rolled over from 1999 to 2000. It didn't happen. It was New
Year's Eve as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Which means your parents might feel a little foolish now if they
stocked up on food, water and gasoline, or even bought an expensive
electric generator, just in case something happened. But they
shouldn't. Millions of people did the same thing. Remember, many of
the world's best computer experts warned us all to be prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those experts are being compared to the boy who cried
``wolf.'' But that's not fair. The experts' warnings made banks,
companies, the government and others fix their computers to squash
any Y2K bugs before they could bite. Which is why everything was
working fine on New Year's morning _ and why you're going back to
school today.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON TOY RECALLED
</P>
<P>
   If you got a Pokemon toy from Burger King, be careful with the
container it came in. The red-and-white ball, which opens to reveal
a toy inside, could hurt you.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-month-old girl in California died when half of the ball
covered her nose and mouth, preventing her from breathing.
</P>
<P>
   If you have one of these balls, give it to your parents. They
can return it to Burger King through March 15 and receive a free
order of french fries in its place.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon toy promotion was one of the largest in fast-food
history. It lasted 56 days.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST DAILY `PEANUTS'
</P>
<P>
   Good grief, Charlie Brown! Today is the last time we'll see a
new weekday ``Peanuts'' comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Charles M. Schulz, who created Snoopy, Linus, Lucy
and the other ``Peanuts'' characters, is retiring after almost 50
years of drawing the comic. Schulz, 77, is recovering from cancer
and says the daily deadlines are too hard to meet.
</P>
<P>
   His last Sunday ``Peanuts'' strip will run Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be too sad, Charlie Brown. We'll still be able to see
the ``Peanuts'' gang in action, as newspapers run daily and Sunday
reprints from the past 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many younger readers, the '70s strips will be new,'' says
Lisa Wilson of United Media, the company that sends the comic strip
to newspapers. ``We hope that, with these reprints, we can cushion
the shock of Mr. Schulz's retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert, Bill Hendrick and news services
</P>
<P>
   If you got a Pokemon toy from Burger King, be careful with the
container it came in. The red-and-white ball, which opens to reveal
a toy inside, could hurt you.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-month-old girl in California died when half of the ball
covered her nose and mouth, preventing her from breathing.
</P>
<P>
   If you have one of these balls, give it to your parents. They
can return it to Burger King through March 15 and receive a free
order of french fries in its place.
</P>
<P>
   The Pokemon toy promotion was one of the largest in fast-food
history. It lasted 56 days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
