<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5155 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-GORBACHEV-PUTIN-YELTS     01-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORBACHEV-PUTIN-YELTSIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO WE ENTER THE NEW CENTURY IN A STATE OF `COLD PEACE'? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish it as a ``separate
buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _
from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The resignation of President Boris Yeltsin has created a new
political situation in Russia. Probably he should have resigned
sooner, even before it was so advantageous to ride the victorious
wave of popular support for his hand-picked successor.
 &HT;    Time will pass judgment on Yeltsin's record in office. What's
needed now, however, is to concentrate on what lies ahead.
 &HT;    Above all, in the coming months, it will be necessary to
strictly follow the Russian constitution. The new presidential
election must take place, as prescribed, and Russia must enter a
new period in its history with dignity and in accordance with
democratic norms.
 &HT;    This is extremely important, but there is something else that we
need to bear in mind.
 &HT;    I hope that the bitter experience of recent years has taught all
of us not to expect miracles. By now we have seen that overnight
revolutions and shocks make good headlines; so do flashy ideas from
``whizz kids'' with little or no experience outside the ivory
tower. But we need long-term, persistent work to build a civil
society and a healthy economy that serves the people.
 &HT;    Russia's politicians, parties and associations will serve the
country well if they dedicate their thoughts and efforts to this
task.
 &HT;    In an interconnected world, any error, especially one made by a
great power, can resonate throughout the world. Events in Moscow
affect every continent; the dangers that pose the greatest threat
one nation also threaten another. It is fitting to use our wisdom
for the good of the worldwide human community.
 &HT;    For example, in what may be termed a new arms race, we see the
most dangerous types of military technology continuing to spread
across the continents. Military technology is being refined and
perfected, and conventional weapons are acquiring the capacity to
function as ``absolute weapons.''
 &HT;    In the more developed countries, new techniques for killing or
paralyzing the enemy are being developed, including psychotropic,
electronic and laser weapons. There is a creeping expansion of the
technological capability for the production of nuclear weapons and
other weapons of mass destruction.
 &HT;    Even while our leaders may honestly grapple with the means to
govern democratically and secure the rule of law, perhaps the
disastrous consequences of the arms race that was part of the Cold
War are being ignored.
 &HT;    That contest not only oppressed everyone with its state of
mutual fear and terrible tension. It also drained the economic
potential of all the participating states. It had extremely
negative political and psychological consequences as well,
strengthening the positions of the most military-minded elements in
society who are well known for their intolerance and cruelty. The
most striking examples in recent years _ although they are by far
not the only ones _ have been in Yugoslavia, the second Persian
Gulf crisis and the ongoing Chechnya war.
 &HT;    I wish we might have entered this new century with the ability
to assert, without question, that the trend toward eliminating
confrontation is irreversible.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, we can only remark that confrontational elements
are still very much woven into the fabric of world politics. The
confrontational approach is consistent with political traditions
having deep historical roots _ traditions based on the notion of
winners and losers in a world balance of power. These tendencies
continue to exist, although often in disguised form.
 &HT;    To be sure, there is progress. World public opinion has been
activated to some degree to infuse universal human values and
principles of morality into global affairs and the resolution of
major problems.
 &HT;    But the political behavior of some countries still shows that
they see the resort to arms as a viable _ a primary _ way of
resolving problems. This should constitute a serious warning.
 &HT;    In view of all this, how do we see the world today? Is there a
``Cold Peace,'' so to speak? A reversion to confrontation, granted
that it is not full-fledged?
 &HT;    In my view, what we see now _ in Russia and elsewhere _ is not
just a transitional period in time but also a special kind of
transitional order _ one that could exist for a long time, one that
may be characterized by instability, conflict and the strong
influence of spontaneous forces in world relations.
 &HT;    Even an enlightened future with civil leadership entails
complications. Absolutely! But perhaps our future politics _ with
its outmoded desires to assert hegemony, to establish spheres of
influence _ will not lag so far in back of our people's urgent need
for the practical application of universal human values.
 &HT;     c.2000 Mikhail Gorbachev  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow. He
addressed the German Parliament on Nov. 9 in a special ceremony to
honor the 10th anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
