<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-2000-HNS &LR;      01-03 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TV RINGS IN A NEW ERA IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once it became clear that it was not going to be, in the words
of R.E.M., the end of the world as we know it, the television story
of the new year switched from fear to partying, from breaking news
to garden-variety New Year's Eve bedlam.
</P>
<P>
   It was fortunate, then, that the networks and even the
affiliates had back-up plans when no planes fell from the sky and
nobody blew up the Space Needle in Seattle or landmarks between New
York and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It was, as high-tech people began dubbing it, Apocalypse Not.
Still, it made for surprisingly entertaining viewing. From Peter
Jennings' marathon anchoring to Worldwide Culture 101 put on by PBS
and a ton of CNN international events in between, it was something
special.
</P>
<P>
   Because the United States was one of the last to celebrate the
new millennium, one of the great TV spectacles happened in the
middle of the day. As the rest of the world ushered in the new
year, a great many Americans probably were working or shopping. Too
bad. They missed what amounted to one of the most intriguing
television events of the year.
</P>
<P>
   While we are used to Dick Clark counting down the ball drop, the
rest of the world showed that in various ways a blowout is a
blowout, and you don't need Times Square to make an impact. With
ABC, CNN and PBS leading the way, midday viewers were treated to
real-time midnight strokes throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   People were doing the pogo in New Delhi. In Moscow's Red Square,
St. Basil's was bathed in the light of fireworks as the first great
test of Y2K technology (and the focus of many fears) passed
innocently without a nuclear meltdown or even a city-block power
outage. The Russians, who switched presidents in a pre-millennium
changing of the guard, proved they could party with anyone. Events
at the stroke of midnight in other countries paled compared with
the chill you felt watching Moscow roll over into the 21st century,
because, if for nothing else, the bogeyman of technology and retro
Cold War nuclear fears were fading away.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, at the Opera House, there was an astounding
pyrotechnics display that would be topped later in Paris, as the
Eiffel Tower became the center of one of the most spectacular,
sustained light shows anybody has seen, until Britain topped
everyone with a record-breaking, explosion-filled, 17-minute
blowout.
</P>
<P>
   If you were lucky enough to decide to sit down in front of the
tube early (rather than get truncated recaps later in the evening,
which did no justice to the live events and expanded coverage),
then you saw technology at its finest. ABC, CNN and PBS did
masterful jobs of giving viewers live coverage, interviews and some
historical insight to the rest of the world. It amounted to a
surprise travelogue and riveting television.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings' desire to anchor the entire evening had ups and downs
but mostly proved he is calm and clear in a major event. The ABC
production was entertaining enough to stick with the entire night,
but the other networks provided their own unique elements. PBS, for
example, had a much more subdued delivery, forgoing hype for
information, letting its anchors and guests add historical
significance to the pictures on display. And more than any network,
PBS emphasized cultural traditions, from ice music in Lapland to
singers in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   CNN and PBS knew when to stay quiet, while the urge to yak often
overcame the high-priced anchors working as reporters at ABC. But
that was only a slight blemish to what was a mighty good effort all
around.
</P>
<P>
   As midnight came to various countries, the joy spilled out in
sometimes odd, amusing and endearing ways. No one partied or
cheered in Djibouti, East Africa, because there was nothing to be
happy about in poverty. It's only 1420 on the Muslim calendar and
many cities, such as Baghdad, were observing religious rites that
banned celebrations. In Egypt (6240 on the calendar, if you are
counting), the millennium doesn't mean anything except tourist
dollars, so they played along, though the fog obscured planned
fireworks near the pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to look away from the beauty of the fireworks
exploding off the Acropolis in Athens, or wonder if something were
going to go awry in Bethlehem's Manger Square. But the peace doves
quickly erased fears. Although some religious extremists thought
there would be a Second Coming of Jesus in Jerusalem, only two men
were arrested at the stroke of midnight as they tried to go over
the wall of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
   People waltzed in Vienna and went absolutely nuts in Amsterdam,
dancing to ``YMCA'' in a nod to cheesy fun and lowered inhibitions.
For those counting _ or watching _ China's official celebration
lasted all of eight minutes. But that country invented fireworks,
the ubiquitous party favor of choice across the planet. And no
millennium coverage would be complete without a prolonged
conversation about Greenwich Mean Time and how, when it comes to
time, Greenwich, England, is the center of the world. And so we
learned a lot about the Millennium Dome (the largest ``roofed''
building in the world, twice as large as the Georgia Dome), but we
are still uncertain about what will happen to the structure
post-New Year, because Greenwich hardly is London.
</P>
<P>
   Around the globe the coverage captured all kinds of joyous
moments, filling the midday viewing with what amounted to the most
interesting material of the day. In comparison to the celebrations
around the world, the New York ball drop was boring, a been-there,
done-that moment that didn't satisfy. Not even 2 million people,
3,500 pounds of confetti shot out of cannons and Dick Clark could
elevate the event above a tired cliche.
</P>
<P>
   As for news coverage, it all became repetitive once Australia
didn't go dark. Reporters repeated stories about how all the
computers came through without glitches, how airplanes were safe,
and how terrorism here and abroad was eerily silent.
</P>
<P>
   Once midnight came to San Francisco, all the stories were told.
And though the fireworks were nice in a provincial kind of way, the
overall effect was roughly the same as it was in New York. If you
only watched for three hours as the time change rolled West, you
already had a sense of redundancy. But if you spent the day
watching the world step into the unknown, you already had
experienced the zenith of history's march.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting our history, the United States, it seems, already had
been upstaged by the time we got to the zeros. And it was a
wonderful thing to behold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
