<HEADLINE>
BONDS HAD A BAD YEAR BUT SHOULD BOUNCE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 55 and my wife is 48. My annual income is $85,000 and
our only debt is a $140,000 mortgage on a new home purchased two
years ago. We currently pay an extra $200 per month toward the
principal. I have a 401(k) plan with a current balance of $243,807,
almost entirely invested in stock funds. I have been contributing
18 percent of my salary to this account, but based on my last pay
raise I will henceforth be limited to 13 percent contributions.
Both of us have traditional IRAs, to which we each contribute
$2,000 a year; the combined balance is $32,400. We also own 100
shares of Black &AMP; Decker common stock. Finally, we have credit
union accounts totaling $36,400, earning at rates ranging from 2.75
percent to 3.5 percent. To these accounts we add $1,070 a month
from a military pension and the income from my wife's part-time
bookkeeping work, which will amount to $15,000 to $20,000 for 1999.
At the present time, I would feel comfortable retiring with 75
percent of my current income stream, or $5,300 a month. I estimate
a Social Security income of $1,120 a month, and my military pension
(which has a small cost-of-living adjustment each year) will
provide a$1,070. Is my target attainable? What suggestions
would you make to change the portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   D.F., Alpine, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Given your very substantial savings levels, you should be in
good shape _ but not quite as good as it may at first seem.
</P>
<P>
   Using a mid-range figure of $17,500 a year saved from your
wife's earnings, you will be putting away a total of $45,390 a
year, and if you achieve overall portfolio returns of 8 percent
over the next seven years, the pool would grow to $964,317.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pool that is certainly capable of comfortably
delivering a $3,110 monthly income stream, with plenty left over
for continued principal growth.
</P>
<P>
   But when you calculate the effects of inflation on the formula,
it looks a bit murkier. If inflation averages 3.5 percent over the
next seven years, you will need $6,743 to buy what $5,300 buys
today.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, instead of $3,110 a month, you would be looking for your
savings to produce a $4,553 income stream. If you established a
fixed-income portfolio to produce this without invading the
principal, you would need $825,000, provided your average yield
from the fixed-income investments was 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave you with $139,317, which you could leave in
stock investments that might protect you against the effects of
inflation in the later years of retirement; I say might, because it
probably isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of factors that should make things brighter.
One is that I haven't factored in the COLA that's associated with
the military pension.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that the accumulation would be larger if you held
your contributions to the 401(k) to the current percentage,
increasing the dollar contributions every time you get a raise. If
your wife's earnings exceed that $17,500 midpoint, you would also
have a larger accumulation.
</P>
<P>
   But most important, if you were to divert the 5 percent of your
earnings that you are no longer allowed to put in the 401(k) into a
taxable savings program, the accumulation would reach $1,012,938,
using the same assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   As for your investment vehicles, obviously the weak element here
is the low-interest credit union accounts. If you simply
transferred those balances to a good money market account with a
mutual fund family, you would realize a notable improvement.
</P>
<P>
   But I would establish a level that represents what you believe
you need as emergency savings, and put only that much into the
money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   I would then take the rest, and all of the ongoing contributions
from your wife's earnings and the military pension, and begin
building that fixed-income portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that bond funds are a tough sell after their bad year
in 1999, but if you take a longer view, they should be attractive.
I'd suggest a three-pronged approach, with half of the money in an
intermediate-term fund such as one holding government securities or
GNMAs, with a further 25 percent each in a short-term corporate
bond fund and a high-yield corporate bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you began with half of the money now at the credit union, and
added at the rate of $30,340 per year, you would build a $291,473
fixed-income portfolio by the time you retire, based on
expectations of 6.5 percent average annual total returns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 77 and a widower planning marriage in March. I receive a
check each month of approximately $2,500 from my investments, and
live comfortably on this and Social Security. My investments are
Franklin High Income Trust Class A, Franklin Municipal Securities
Trust, California High Yield, and Prudential Municipal Bond fund. I
am happy with my monthly check. However, I see my fund value
decrease each month. This worries me. If this continues I could be
wiped out. Do I have to worry?
</P>
<P>
   J.A., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. First, congratulations on your upcoming marriage, which is a
much nicer thing to think about than the bond markets of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not certain what the first holding you cite is; perhaps it's
Franklin Age High Income fund, or perhaps Franklin High-Yield
Tax-Free fund. In any event, what you are seeing in your portfolio
is what happens to your principal balance when bond funds have bad
years and you withdraw the income; your balance is not only
depleted by the amount of the losses suffered by the funds, but in
addition by the $30,000 in distributions that you have taken.
</P>
<P>
   It also appears likely that your sequence of withdrawals
probaeeds by a bit the amount of the yields, so the decline
in your balance was thus aggravated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, I don't think you should worry overmuch. Bond
funds periodically suffer bad years, almost always caused by
increases in interest rates, and/or fears of future increases.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the interest rate cycle turns the other way
eventually, and the better funds recoup their losses of the bad
years. The two funds I can identify precisely are excellent funds,
but both hold long-term portfolios, which makes them suffer more in
a bad interest-rate climate that shorter-term funds.
</P>
<P>
   I think the worm will turn for this portfolio, although perhaps
not in the short term. I suggest you ride it out, and if the
decline in the current portfolio value bothers you, you could
reduce the effect by slightly reducing the amount of your
withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 86, so my working years were spent when wages were low.
My savings are mostly invested in bond funds. I have several
questions. I am thinking of investing in a Vanguard fund. Do you
think it would be sensible to buy it in my son's name? I don't need
the money. Also, how is it that one is able to accumulate hundreds
of thousands of dollars in an IRA by contributing the maximum of
$2,000 a year?
</P>
<P>
   P.H., Cape Cod, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a potential tax advantage in buying the fund
position in your name, and then leaving it to your son in your
will. That is what is called the step-up provision in the tax laws,
which allows a person inheriting securities to treat the value of
the holding at the time of the donor's death as his or her base
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, if you put the investment in your name and the value of
the holding advances during the balance of your lifetime, the
amount of that gain would be tax-free, and your son would be liable
for capital gains taxes only on any appreciation in the fund
position that comes after he inherits the shares.
</P>
<P>
   As for those mammoth IRA accounts that surface from time to time
in letters to this column, you can fund an IRA by rolling over
other tax-deferred savings programs such as 401(k)s, 403(b)s, or
lump-sum pension distributions into an IRA, thus allowing the
balances to far exceed what a person might have accumulated through
a sequence of $2,000-a-year contributions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
