<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      01-03 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY REVEALED! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
 HILLARY'S CHOICE  
By Gail Sheehy 
Random House. 389 pp. $23.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is hardly the worst book about Hillary Rodham Clinton, but
it might well be the sloppiest.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Sheehy, author of ``Passages'' and several psycho-political
profiles in Vanity Fair magazine, asks the question: Why did this
smart, ambitious woman, who seemed destined for her own great
career, give it up and tie her fate to Bill Clinton's?
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Sheehy never provides an answer. Or rather, she
offers several explanations, some truistic, others rickety.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy owns the cake of lather when it comes to barber-shop
Freudianism, so much blame gets brushed on Hillary's ``drillmaster
father,'' whose ``demand for perfection'' and ``readiness to
demean'' were ``internalized'' by her ``overactive superego.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sheehy fails to support her premise, much less the analysis.
Hugh Rodham seems to have been strict and undemonstrative, but so
were many fathers of the era. Sheehy's piece de resistance _ that
he didn't even attend Hillary's college graduation, where she
delivered a famlazing commencement speech _ has been flatly
denied by the First Lady's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy's claim that Bill Clinton represented Hillary's first
``taste of freedom . . . an escape from her father,'' is diluted by
her own revelation that, before meeting Bill, Hillary enjoyed a
three-year relationship with a handsome Georgetown student with
whom she had sex and may have smoked pot. ``Get her away on a
weekend,'' she writes of Hillary in those randy days, ``and she
could be playful.'' So Bill wasn't her first ``taste''? Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Her portrait of the Clintons' marriage is at least as strange as
the marriage itself. She may be right that Hillary plays
``enabler'' to Bill's antics. (``He lied to her. And she let
him.'') But what does it mean to find in their relationship
``echoes of Eleanor and Franklin, or Tracy and Hepburn, with
undertones of Bonnie and Clyde''?
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``White House aides'' who ``puzzle over why the Clintons
make a display of physical affection,'' Sheehy speculates, ``Maybe
he does it to make her feel good, to make it look like he's turned
on by her.'' She doesn't consider maybe he is turned on by her.
</P>
<P>
   As the book trundles on, Sheehy grows desperate. At one point,
she cites a ``highly qualified mental health professional who works
too close to the White House to be identified'' as diagnosing the
president with multiple-personalities disorder: He's not lying
about his sexual affairs _ he doesn't know he's having them!
</P>
<P>
   However, 10 pages later, Sheehy notes that the presi
dalliance with Monica Lewinsky coincided with ``three major
personal marker events'' _ his mother's death, his daughter's
departure for college, and his knee injury, which made him hobble
``like an old man'' and remember that his father died young.
</P>
<P>
   But does this mean he's not schizophrenic? And what about his
countless earlier affairs? What ``marker events'' triggered them?
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy's description of young Hillary's evolution from Goldwater
Republican to liberal Democrat is interesting. Her big scoop was
persuading a childhood friend named John Peavoy to turn over a
bundle of letters Hillary wrote him from college. It's fascinating
to read the future steely First Lady describe herself as a
``compassionate misanthrope.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, how much can one infer about a grown woman's
character from letters she wrote at 19? Sheehy puts especial stock
in one letter where Hillary remembers dancing in her backyard as a
little girl, pretending there were ``heavenly movie cameras
watching my every move.'' But don't most children imagine being the
stars of their own movies?
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate flaw of Sheehy's book may be that she's working the
wrong angle. In explaining why Hillary didn't pursue her own
career, she latches onto a letter from college, describing a brief
funk over who-am-I-really and the-meaning-of-life _ standard
late-teen angst. But Sheehy interprets it as a full-blown
``identity crisis'' and a fear of introspection that Hillary
allayed by turning ``her attention to advising others on how to
live their lives. . . . This became a lifelong pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   Weak. Very weak.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy might have done better by looking a bit at the world
around her subject. Hillary graduated from Wellesley in 1969, on
the cusp of the feminist revolution, when _ as her classmate Miriam
Horn has written elsewhere _ half the graduates followed the girls'
school tradition of catching a man, while the other half carved out
their own paths. Hillary, clearly, was caught in the middle. Had
she come of age a few years later, it is doubtful she would have
played second-fiddle to a Bill Clinton, no matter how mean her
daddy was.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Fred Kaplan is chief of the Globe's New York bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
