<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED MARRIAGES ALTER LONGTIME BOUNDARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A constant question in Jamy Gaynor's mind is what will her
children look like. Will they take the strong cheekbones and cocoa
skin from her father's West Indian heritage or the hazel eyes and
lean stature from her mother's English and Slavic stock? Or will
her children bare the flawless olive skin and almond eyes of her
fiance's Asian parents?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for sure, Gaynor, 23, of Fitchburg, Mass., who is
biracial, and her fiance, Souvanna Sommala, 24, who is Thai and
Laotian, don't share the same feelings of alienation that afflicted
her parents a quarter of a century ago, when friends abandoned them
and local realtors shut doors in their faces. To them, race lines
are blurred, faded and antiquated. Gaynor's sister Nicole dates an
Irish-American man; Sommala's nephew is black and Asian, and their
friends cross racial and ethnic divides.
</P>
<P>
   With roots in four continents, the extended Gaynor family is the
face of the new millennium, demographers say. As immigrants
continue to stream across the nation's borders, and with the number
of interracial marriages projected to double during the next
century, social historians are predicting that the racial
distinctions that have defined American history will slowly melt
away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the younger Gaynors move toward a world where they
say race won't matter, they are still faced with questions of
identity. Jamy Gaynor and Sommala wonder whether their children
will choose to be Buddhists or Christians. And Jamy still struggles
to master the native tongue of her future in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boyfriend and I perceive things differently, from foods to
the way we raise children. . . . He eats bland food. I like spicy
foods,'' said Nicole Gaynor, Jamy's younger sister. ``It's going to
be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Some sociologists fear that as the old racial boundaries fade,
pockets of hatred will become all the more rabid. Some people will
be threatened by the nation's changing complexion, sparking hate
crimes such as cross burnings and more serious violence, said Paul
Watanabe, a political science professor at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, these sociologists say, people are
unlikely to lose their deep need for cultural identity. The
Gaynors, and the burgeoning number of multiracial families like
them, are at the forefront of the difficult questions many
Americans will face in the 2000s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the real debate and dialogue will fall in the 21st
century will be culture versus race,'' said Regina
Rodriguez-Mitchell, assistant director of the William Monroe
Trotter Institute in Boston. ``What are the leading elements that
govern our behavior? What guides and centers us? What marks your
identity, where do your values and belief systems spring from?''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, American society insisted on clear divisions
between races. Census takers in the 19th century considered anyone
with ``one drop'' of blood to be blmer Plessy, the
African-American plaintiff who was part of the 1896 landmark Plessy
v. Ferguson decision that preserved racial segregation in Southern
schools, was only one-eighth black. Across the South, miscegenation
laws prohibited black and white people from marrying. Slowly those
lines began to blur, though, as the last of the legal barriers
banning interracial marriages were dismantled more than two decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the number of mixed marriages has blossomed.
Interracial marriages have increased tenfold since 1960, according
to the 1990 census, and the number of offspring from these
marriages has reached 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Their growing numbers and their rejection of old racial
categories forced the census for the first time this year to allow
people to identify themselves by more than one race.
</P>
<P>
   Other sociologists saypulation of families who cross all
blood lines will change racial attitudes in a way that new laws and
political speeches never could. Groups that historically have
separated themselves will sit together at family reunion picnics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interracial marriages provide the death knell to racist
thinking,'' said Sally Engle Merry of Wellesley College. ``Pretty
soon you can classify people into one group or another, then the
whole system of race begins to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as race becomes less prevalent in their lives, sisters
Nicole and Jamy Gaynor say cultural issues like religion and
language can also create tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Protestant and we are not supposed to pray to other
gods, but in the Buddhist religion you are constantly on your knees
praying. So it can be a little hard going to the gatherings and
just standing there,'' Jamy said.
</P>
<P>
   But their differences, they say, are minor compared with the
hatred that their parents confronted years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Gaynor, a son of Jamaican and Barbados immigrants, and
Sharon, a farm girl from northern Massachusetts whose father
emigrated from Czechoslovakia, met in Boston during the early 1970s
while she was a student at Boston University and he was a student
at UMass. They shared a love for education that soon blossomed into
romance. But during one of the most turbulent times in the city's
history, their union was not accepted by strangers and many of
their friends. Dirty looks and comments were common, they said.
Twice, they were ready to put a down payment on a house, only to be
told that someone else had bought the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because other people saw us as interracial _ it brought us
closer. It was like you and me against the world,'' said Clarence
Gaynor, 51, an administrator at Cambridge Rindge and Latin School
in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Even their parents were skeptical about their decision to get
married, he said, ``not because I was black and she was white but
what other people projected upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   They eventually moved to Brockton, Mass., where they've lived
for the past 26 years. But, although the parents taught their
children to not focus on race, Nicole says that she has not been
able to escape society's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little girl in school, I was always teased by
black and white kids,'' she said. ``The black kids told me I was
black and should be proud of it and that my mother was a whore, and
the white kids said my father is nothing.'' The other children
wanted her to choose between being black and white, Nicole said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sommala and Jamy Gaynor say race has not been an issue for
them and that it won't be for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to teach them to consider themselves
multiracial,'' said Gaynor. ``And we will expose them to both
religions.''
</P>
<P>
   When the children become adults, said Gaynor, they can choose
their religion, their culture, even their race. It will be up to
them, she said, to make a world for themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
