<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ICELAND-GENETICS-BOS &LR;      01-03 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICELAND-GENETICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICELANDERS WARY OF GENETIC RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland _ In this land of fire and ice, where natural
creation is still unfurling, two grand creations of the human mind
_ morality and science _ are locked in a classic
turn-of-the-millennium struggle.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a genetic research project putting the private
medical records, sophisticated DNA tests, and detailed genealogical
histories of an entire nation under the microscope _ and, more to
the point, into a massive, computerized database capable of
tracking mutant genes over centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious project represents an effort to learn all there is
to know medically about nearly every Icelander who has lived, a
search stretching back almost to the days of Leif Ericson and the
Viking Sagas. The research by Iceland's first biotechnology firm,
Decode Genetics, brainchild of a former Harvard Medical School
professor, Kari Stefansson, aims to unlock the genetic causes of
the worst diseases afflicting humankind, and possibly to find
cures.
</P>
<P>
   It is an audacious quest for the genetic grail, the
infinitesimal scraps of coding within each cell that put some
individuals at higher risk than others of developing a certain
disease.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the undertaking represents a potentially
dangerous invasion of privacy, warning that the fusion of
genealogy, health data, and supercomputers might take medical
research into frightening Orwellian realms where Big Doctor knows
all.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland may be the best place on earth to search for the mutant
genes that make people susceptible to cancer, stroke, heart
disease, and myriad other ills. The country's 273,000 people form
the most homogenous population on earth, a gene pool hardly rippled
by new infusions since the year 1000. So the isolation of aberrant
genes, scientists hope, will be much easier to find here than in
the genetic seas of the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers for the Icelandic Cancer Society sought to
better understand breast cancer, for example, they were able to
track the arrival of a defective gene, now called BRCA2, to a 16th
century cleric named Einar.
</P>
<P>
   In other societih a search would be impossible. But in
Iceland, people can commonly trace their ancestors back 30
generations to the Norse seafarers who settled the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a society obsessed with who we are, who we were, and who
we come from,'' said Stefansson, who created Decode Genetics three
years ago with $12 million in venture capital raised mainly in the
Unates. ``We've been marrying among ourselves for 1,000
years, and we've kept very detailed records.''
</P>
<P>
   The research has turned an unaccustomed spotlight on Iceland,
whose parliament, the Althing, enacted a special law granting
Decode exclusive rights to national health records to build the
electronic database.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, perhaps, the government also granted Decode a
12-year license to market whatever discoveries come from the data,
a deal that could be worth billions of dollars. The arrangement has
drawn much angry criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even aside from the privacy issue, which we feel is the
critical issue, there is the question of why one private company is
being allowed to take so much from Iceland,'' said Tomas Zoega,
psychiatrist and chairman of the ethics committee of the Icelandic
Medical Association, which opposes certain aspects of the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, this is too much about money,'' Zoega said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the controversy also seems to center on Stefansson, a
51-year-old neurologist whose piercing gaze and pale features are
as typically Icelandic as his thick wool sweater, but whose
larger-than-life flamboyance stands out among a people known for
their reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The more emotional criticisms of Stefansson seem to stem from
the fact that, in forming Decode, he has shed his skin as a
``pure'' scientist to become a corporate CEO. Decode, which was
incorporated in Delaware and will soon make its first public stock
offering in the United States, is very much a capitalist
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   But Stefansson makes no apologies for the pursuit of profits.
``Health care is a business, top to bottom,'' he said. ``What is a
doctor other than a professional selling services to the sick,
wounded, and dying? Put that way, it sounds indecent. Just as you
can make it sound indecent that this company might profit through
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefansson stressed that the company will use an advanced
computer encryption system that will prevent individual health
records in the database from becoming public. Although any
Icelander has the right to withhold records from the study, only a
few thousand have opted to do so _ and polls show a majority of
Icelanders not only support the project but are proud to be a part
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Geneticists in the United States are following the Decode debate
closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing strikes me as sinister about this research, and
there's much good that could come from it,'' said Philip R. Reilly,
clinical geneticist and director of Waltham's Eunice Kennedy
Shriver Center for Mental Retardation. ``It's just become
fashionable with the bioethics crowd to pin the word `Orwellian' on
anything related to genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the fear is that insurance companies will
misuse the fruits of genetics research to deny medical coverage to
people with ``bad'' genes. Fear in Iceland is less specific because
the country's socialized medical system makes it impossible for
anyone to be denied treatment, but it seems to stem at least partly
from the perception that Iceland is being used as a test lab for
giant multinational pharmaceutical interests.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the project, including many of Iceland's top
politicians, are excited by the medical possibilities of the
research and the potential economic spinoffs. They envision Iceland
becoming a world center for biotechnology, creating high-paying
jobs in a country far too reliant on fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with nearly 300 people working in Decode's research and
administrative building near Reykjavik, Decode employs more than
one out of every 1,000 Icelanders. Meanwhile, it has signed a $200
million contract with Swiss pharmaceutical giant Hoffman-La Roche
to identify genes that lead to a dozen deadly ailments, including
heart disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see our Iceland scientists coming back from Cambridge or
Chicago to do important research at home is exciting,'' said
Ragnheidur Haraldsdottir, deputy secretary of the national health
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Tte over Decode Genetics has been the most bitter and
extensive national controversy since Iceland gained independence
from Denmark in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Decode's detractors insist that Iceland risks turning its people
and their health histories into a commodity, like codfish, to be
bought and sold. They paint Stefansson as part slick entrepreneur,
part mad scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kari is using a great talent for salesmanship to take over a
country's medical records and exclude other scientists,'' said
Jorunn Erla Eyfjord, a prominent researcher who heads the molecular
and cell biology laboratory of the Icelandic Cancer Society. ``I
don't oppose the research. I am troubled by the scale of the Decode
project, and how this data could be misused.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the project is moving quickly even as ethicists
urge caution and more debate about the implications.
</P>
<P>
   Their pleading irks Stefansson. ``Tell a 25-year-old patient
with multiple sclerosis there is no hurry, that every moral angle
should be examined at leisure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is possible because Iceland is Europe's most remote
and northerly nation, and its historic isolation _ coupled with the
fact that many Icelanders have an interest in genealogy that
borders on obsession _ means family trees can be traced with an
ease and accuracy impossible elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Stefansson, for example, can rattle off generations of his
ancestry back to Egill Skallagrimsson, a warrior-poet born in AD
910 and one of the heroes of the Icelandic sagas, the nation's
ancient chronicles.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, almost any Icelander can do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icelanders have no grand monuments, no great palaces,'' said
Thordur Kristjansson, a genealogist. ``The only thing we have had
to remind us of our past is our family memory. Our genealogy is our
monument.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Icelandic gene pool is remarkable. Most inhabitants are
descendants of the original Vikings and Gaels who planted roots
here from AD 870 to 930. Meanwhile, centuries of famine, bubonic
plague, deadly volcanic eruptions, and other disasters have so
culled the population that nearly every inhabitant is part of the
trunk, limbs, and branches of the same hardy tree.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Iceland is a highly literate society, with
vital statistics _ births, deaths, marriages _ dating back
centuries, and centralized modern medical histories kept since
1915.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Hoffman-La Roche represents one of the largest
agreements ever forged between a genetic research company and a
major drug firm. But the money involved may be peanuts compared to
what Iceland's genetic secrets may ultimately be worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iceland could become the cutting edge of a revolution in
genomics-genetic knowledge,'' said Terry McGuire, a founding
partner of Polaris Venture Partners, a Massachusetts firm that
invests in Decode. ``Obviously, we hope Decode will be profitable.
But there is also real excitement over research that could benefit
mankind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
