<SLUG> BC-VIET-MIAS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES OF VIETNAM MIAS STILL STRUGGLING WITH LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (a and i coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Pentagon announced last week that it had identified the
remains of a Massachusetts man missing in action in Vietnam since
1968, Eleanor Gregory resigned herself to entering a new century
still holding a vigil for the brother she has not seen for half of
her lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 66-year-old Shrewsbury, Mass. woman's emotions remain
jagged and raw. Her voice wells up as she speaks about her brother,
Russell Peter Bott, a Green Beret last seen in Laos on Dec. 2,
1966, when he was 30 years old and the father of a baby he never
had the chance to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory believes her brother may have been a prisoner of war,
and that he may still be one. But, in a way, it is Gregory who has
been a prisoner for more than three decades. She and other family
members of missing servicemen are held captive by an anguish that
for most Americans _ even those who lost loved ones _ long ago
receded to the pages of history books or family albums.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even as remains continue to be identified in Vietnam, the
dawn of the 21st century raises a question for some people who are
close to the search for MIAs and POWs: How long is too long to
suspend life for love of a missing relative?
</P>
<P>
   The wives of many MIAs have never remarried. They and other
family members have not been able to mourn and move on, and their
quest for answers costs the United States $55 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get easier _ it gets harder as it goes along,
Gregory said. ``It's been 33 years, and it's just like this all
happened yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others in her place, Gregory curses the government. And
also like others she clings to the hope that after all these years
her brother might turn up alive, perhapsfrom some jail
hidden on the outskirts of Hanoi or tucked in the depths of the
Laotian jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he alive? I have to believe he is, of course, until they
can prove further,'' Gregory said. ``Why would it seem unlikely if
(the Vietnamese) can't come up with my brother?''
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century after the fall of Saigon, the search for
missing servicemen continues to be a major uing. The $55
million a year the Pentagon spends on its program with the
government of Vietnam is used to excavate grave sites, pore over
documents, and test remains at a laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The POW/MIA cause has also become a part of the American
landscape. Under Massachusetts law, every city and town must fly
the black POW/MIA flag over at least one municipal building and at
every police and fire station. It is the only flag other than the
Stars and Stripes ever flown over the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the results have been slow. With the recent accounting for
Air olonel Robert M. Elliot, 2,031 servicemen remain on the
POW/MIA roster. The remains of another 552 have been identified and
returned to their families, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Of the men Massachusetts sent to war, the remains of 17
considered MIAs have been recovered and another 47 are still
unaccounted for, according to Maureen Dunn of Randolph, Mass.,
regional coordinator for the National League of POW/MIA Families.
Dunn said the Bay State has the highest per-capita rate of
recovered MIAs in the nation, perhaps due to the vigorous activism
of local families.
</P>
<P>
   To many families, the government's efforts are not enough to
make up for what they call years of government lies and neglect. To
critics, however, the POW/MIA issue is a bogus distraction that has
cruelly kept families in suspense and diverted money and attention
from worthier causes, such as the well-being of living Vietnam
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me most is what gets displaced by the MIA concern
_ the problems faced by the living veterans of the war,'' said
Vietnam scholar Christian G. Appy, speaking of the homelessness and
substance abuse problems that have plagued veterans. ``Some people
argue (troubled veterans) are the true missing of the war _ missing
in Amnot missing in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans dwell on the servicemen listed as POW/MIAs in
Indochina, said Appy, because the return of the missing offers a
national redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this idea that some part of us had not come home,'' he
said. ``We lost something more than a war in Vietnam _ we lost our
innocence, our youth. These POWs represented something we had left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of MIAs from Vietnam is tiny compared to World
War II or the Korean War, said Appy, who wrote ``Working Class War:
American Combat Soldiers in Vietnam.'' And estimates of the number
of MIAs on the Vietnamese side range from 200,000 to 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   H. Bruce Franklin, author of ``M.I.A. or Mythmaking in
America,'' argues that all evidence suggests that there have never
been any living POWs held in Vietnam since the United States and
North Vietnam signed a peace treaty in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Still, POW/MIA family members lead suspended lives, still
waiting for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole idea has kept alive in a very cruel way for some
survivors of these dead soldiers the fraudulent hope that they may
still be alive,'' Appy said. ``It's prevented a closure that should
have happened decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing the fate of a loved one is a form of torture that
Pauline Boss, a professor of family social sciences at the
University of Minnesota, has studied for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most difficult loss of all, the loss that is never
certain, because there is grief that is essentially frozen,'' said
Boss, author of ``Ambiguous Loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Cleary O'Connor, 53, of Wayland, Mass. faced such a task
when her husband, Air Force pilot Peter Cleary, disappeared over
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea what it's like to have to come to your own
conclusions as time passes by,'' she said. ``You think: `I hope
he's alive.' Then: `Maybe he's alive.' `Maybe he isn't alive.'
Finally: `I guess he's dead.' It's very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was able to grieve for his death after a few years, and
she eventually remarried. Many wives, however, are paralyzed by the
uncertain circumstances and can bring themselves to do neither.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, Boss said, experience depression, anger,
psychosomatic symptoms, and family conflict that can last for two
or three generations.
</P>
<P>
   Family members are brutal in their condemnation of the
government. Some single out two prominent Vietnam veterans _
Arizona Senator John McCain, who was himself a POW, and
Massachusetts Senator John Kerry. Both ``sold out'' the missing
servicemen, Gregory said, when they supported the diplomatic and
trade ties the United States established with Vietnam during the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry deflected such criticism in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are angry, unfortunately, because their personal
loss has not been resolved,'' he said. ``But we have in place the
most extraordinary accountability process in the history of human
warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   As that process grinds forward, many parents, wives, and
children of the missing servicemen cling to the hope that they,
too, will be as lucky as Elliot's family. To them, it would make
all the difference to receive a couple of teeth or some bones. One
is Dunn, whose husband, Joseph Dunn, was shot down in the South
China Sea the same day Elliot crashed _ Valentine's Day, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I still go to bed at night and see that
25-year-old kid in a raft, saying, `Where are they? Why aren't they
coming to get me?' '' said Dunn, who never remarried. ``To get his
remains would mean as much to me as if he walked through the door
alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
