<HEADER>
A5291 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CYBER-TERROR-BOS &LR;      01-03 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TERROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH BUILDS FOR CRACKDOWN ON WEB THREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the weeks after his stepdaughter, Amy Boyer, was killed by a
stalker she barely knew who detailed his plans on a Web page, Tim
Remsburg figured the odds of anyone else facing such a bizarre
crime were ``like winning the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, though, Remsburg has taken his family's story
public, and drawn national attention from a network of people who
see the murder of the Nashua, N.H. woman as emblematic of a
dangerous new world. The Internet age, they say, has ushered in a
spectrum of threatening activity that service providers are not
willing to monitor, and law enforcement is not prepared to address.
</P>
<P>
   As Remsburg prepares to file lawsuits against various Internet
businesses he insists assisted his -old stepdaughter's
killer, he has found a deep vein of support from Internet safety
advocates who hope Boyer's murder will draw more attention to gaps
in accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Yahoo and Tripod had reviewed (Liam Youens's) page two
years ago, . . . the Remsburgs would be having a very merry
Christmas. If the people who run the Net don't start taking
responsibility now, laws are going to get passed whether they want
them or not,'' said Jayne Hitchcock, who began pushing for the
passage of federal and state cyberstalking laws after a
correspondent flooded newsgroups with messages designed to harrass
her.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Internet crime resonated particularly with Vice
President Al Gore, who this year commissioned a study on
``cyberstalking'' and went out of his way to mh Remsburg and
his wife during a campaign trip to New Hampshire. The report Gore
commissioned, which was released in August by US Attorney General
Janet Reno's office, concluded that most law enforcement agencies
do not recognize the seriousness of on-line threats, and in some
cases, ``victims have been told . . . simply to turn their
computers off.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the incidence of on-line threats appears to be
rising. Twenty percent of the cases handled by the Manhattan
district attorney's Sex Crimes Unit involve cyberstalking, as do 20
percent of Los Angeles disttorney's Stalking and Threat
Assessment Unit, the report said. Hitchcock, who advises victims of
on-line crime through her Web site, said that although on-line
harassment was rare when she first raised the issue three years
ago, she now gets 100 complaints every week.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts has included e-mail in its stalking statute since
1997, but Kurt Schwartz, deputy chief of the Massachusetts attorney
general's criminal bureau, said the four State Police officers in
his computer crimes division have trouble keeping up with all the
complaints referred to them by local police departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at law enforcement five years from now, you're
going to find a lot of resources. Right now, we're behind,''
Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Criminologists who have worked with e-mail threats say Internet
techhas changed the nature of crime by giving criminals a
new tool before police are ready to catch up. And the anonymity
available on the Web also has created a new criminal personality,
with people more willing to act impulsively than they would in
real-life, face-to-face encounters, said one specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the history of crime, there were a lot of
people who didn't commit crimes in their hometowns, but when you
first get automobiles and planes, because they're mobile, they're
more apt to commit crimes, because of the veil of anonymity. And
that's what we have here,'' said Terry Gudaitis, a former CIA
criminologist now working with the Virginia-based Global Integrity
Corp., which helps private corporations handle e-mail threats and
on-line stalking cases.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said most of the complaints she received originated
from disagreements born in on-line chatrooms or newsgroups.
Hitchcock herself moved from her Maryland home to New England to
escape escalating harassment from people in an on-line newsgroup,
an experience she detailed in her upcoming book, ``The Wild, Wild
Web: Danger on Your Computer.'' At one point, her on-line
correspondent sent out a rash of e-mail that contained her address
and phone number, saying she was interested in sado-masochistic
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said one case investigated by Massachusetts Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly's computer crimes division involved a
woman who had received e-mail from a correspondent who described
what she had purchased at a grocery store deli counter one day. The
next day, the person e-mailed her a layout of her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will do evil things much more quickly when they think
they can do it anonymously,'' he said. ``If you're sitting at home
using a screen name, it's very easy to send threats aimed at
terrorizing people a world away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wattendorf and Hitchcock also see substance in Remsburg's
personal agenda _ holding various Internet businesses responsible
for assisting Liam Youens in killing his stepdaughter. Throughout
the late summer and early fall, Youens had tracked Boyer down using
Internet-based private detectives, and narrated his progress,
chillingly, on a Web site named after his victim. On Oct. 15, 1999
Youens shot Boyers in front of the dentist's office where she
worked, and then turned the gun on himself. Remsburg first learned
of the ``Amy Boyer'' site that night, and was infuriated that the
service providers that hosted Youens's pages _ Geocities and Tripod
_ did not monitor for hate speech or death threats on the Web pages
they host.
</P>
<P>
   Although they may prohibit members from posting pornography,
hate speech, libel or threats of violence on their home pages,
Internet service providers are not required by law to search for
violations. Most providers ``do not monitor content, period,'' said
Barbara Dooley, president of the Commercial Internet Exchange, an
association of 150 Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock said it's worth pushing the companies to police
themselves voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the technology,'' she said. ``You can do it if you
really want to; it just costs money. In the long run, you'll make
it a lot safer, and we won't have to get laws passed.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the law regards Internet service providers as
closer to a telephone company than a publishing house. Earlier this
month, the New York Court of Appeals ruled that Prodigy, a
provider, could not be held liable for a 1994 incident in which
someone created accounts in the name of Alexander Lunney, now a
college student, and used those accounts to send sexually explicit
material and death threats to a local scoutmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Schwartz, a policy analyst for the Center for Democracy and
Technology in Washington, said that holding providers responsible
for content on the Web would ``tear down its basic fabric'' by
setting up a central censoring entity. With billions of Web pages
out there, systematic screening for threats on pages that can be
changed at any moment would require human intervention on a massive
scale, Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is not a book publisher. It is something new,'' said
Dooley. ``The standards of book publishing are not completely
transferable when every single person can be a publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first generation of Internet offenders is going
to jail. California this spring successfully prosecuted a
51-year-old security guard who had posted e-mail impersonating a
woman who had rejected his romantic advances. The messages included
the woman's address and said she wanted to be raped; at least six
men came to her door and said they had come to rape her. A second
defendant sent hundreds of threatening e-mails to five university
students. Both men face up to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a rapid education for Remsburg, who never took much
interest in the Internet until Boyer's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get the word out there,'' he said. ``If enough
of us band together, we can make change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
