<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-CRITIC-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      01-03 1768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRITIC-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TALENTED FOLKS AT BLACK LIZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mysteries have always offered readers a vicarious walk on the
wild side. Edgar Allan Poe and Arthur Conan Doyle would take us on
a guided tour of the underworld, and their alter egos, Dupin and
Sherlock Holmes, would lead us back to a world where crime always
had its punishment. But the 20th-century crime novel, at its best,
leaves the reader with no such return ticket to safety. Instead,
Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler gave us existential
meditations on morality; Jim Thompson takes an immoral universe as
a given.
</P>
<P>
   It's to this genre of writing that Anthony Minghella's movie
adaptation of ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' belongs. On its own terms
it's an excellent film, maybe even worth the Oscar (though the
Academy is always inclined to walk on the safer, more uplifting
side of the street). Despite the intelligence of his adaptation,
however, Minghella's terms are not those of Patricia Highsmith, the
undervalued writer of the novel. She didn't like the movies made of
her novels _ which included Alfred Hitchcock's ``Strangers on a
Train'' (adapted by Chandler); Rene Clement's ``Purple Noon'' (also
based on ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''); and Wim Wenders's ``The
American Friend'' (based on a sequel, ``Ripley's Game''). Minghella
comes closer than his illustrious predecessors to capturing the
seductive logic of evil, but still, chances are that Highsmith will
be turning in her four-year-old grave at the compromises and
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Minghella's movie, though, is cause for celebration _ not only
because it uses the filmmaker's art to create an elaborate
fictional world (out of the glow of Italian sunshine and the
jazz-inflected dark side of the 1950s) but also because it will
inevitably lead some readers to discover Highsmith's richer,
subtler psychopathology. It may also lead them to the publishing
enterprise that has reissued all five of the Ripley books,
Vintage's delectable Black Lizard paperback series.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage began reprinting the masters _ Chandler, Hammett, James
M. Cain _ under the banner of Vintage Crime in 1989. When the
editor in charge of the series, Edward Kastenmeier, looked into the
rights for Thompson's books, he found they were owned by Black
Lizard and ``in order to acquire Jim Thompson we bought the whole
Black Lizard line _ hook, line, and sinker _ which also included
writers like Charles Willeford and David Goodis.''
</P>
<P>
   With the elegant Ross Macdonald and Chester Himes in tow (Himes
was the author of the Harlem series of crime fiction in which the
police can be more dangerous than the thieves), Kastenmeier went on
the search for more contemporary thrills _ Michael Dibdin's Aurelio
Zen Italian mysteries, Maj Sjowall's and Per Wahloo's Martin Beck
series from Sweden; Andrew Vachss's nails-for-breakfast
investigator Burke; and Highsmith's equally intriguing soul mate,
Ruth Rendell. Black Lizard will publish two of Rendell's creepiest
books, ``A Judgement in Stone'' and ``A Demon in My View,'' this
month , and is taking on her frontlist as well as her backlist,
starting with ``Harm Done,'' the latest of her Inspector Wexford
mysteries. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A shiver runs through it &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing that unites the Black Lizard writers is that they are
as noir as noir can be. (Although even in this company, everyone
looks like Steve Forbes or Dr. Laura next to Thompson. Stanley
Kubrick said that Thompson's ``The Killer Inside Me'' was
``probably the most chilling and believable first-person story of a
criminally warped mind I have ever encountered.'') The other common
feature is that they have the feel of first-class modernist
literature, a quality underscored by the artful packaging that
gives them the look and heft of the Vintage International series,
home to the likes of Vladimir Nabokov, William Faulkner, and
Guenter Grass, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't go as far as the genre's champions and put the
mystery and crime writers in the same class _ the form boxes them
in more than it frees them _ but at their best they come awfully
close. As Chandler says of Hammett in his essay ``The Simple Art of
Murder,'' which is part of the series: ``He demonstrated that the
detective story can be important writing. `The Maltese Falcon' may
or may not be a work of genius, but an art which is capable of it
is not `by hypothesis' incapable of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Dibdin's explanation of the title to his ``Ratking,'' with
all of its chilling metaphorical possibilities _ ``A ratking is
what happens when too many rats have to live in too small a space
under too much pressure. Their tails become entwined and the more
they stretch and strain to free themselves the tighter grows the
knot binding them, until at last it becomes a solid mass of
embedded tissue.'' Not exactly Agatha Christie.
</P>
<P>
   Or take this dialogue between Macdonald's detective Lew Archer
and a sociology student he's interviewing in 1961's ``The Wycherly
Woman.'' She asks him: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `` `Is it the parents or the children who are responsible for j.
d.? I can't make up my quote mind unquote.' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `` `I wish you'd stop saying that about your quote mind
unquote.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Is it boring? My apologies. Do you blame the parents or the
child?'
</P>
<P>
   `` `I don't blame anybody, if you want an honest answer. I think
blame is one of the things we have to get rid of. When children
blame their parents for what's happened to them, or parents blame
their children for what they've done, it's part of the problem, and
it makes the problem worse. People should take a close look at
themselves. Blaming is the opposite of that.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bit simplistic, perhaps, in terms of causality, but good
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Black Lizard will publish Dan Fesperman's ``Lie
in the Dark.'' Much of contemporary crime fiction deals with the
futility of catching criminals in the midst of so much evil.
Imagine how Fesperman's detective, Vlado Petric, feels. His beat is
war-torn Yugoslavia, and all his friends think he's a fool to be
``plumbing toilets in the midst of a flood.'' Often he agrees. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Making skin crawl &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But of all the writers, the ones who get under the skin, like
the best of contemporary writers in any genre, are Highsmith and
Rendell. Highsmith _ who was born in Texas in 1921, but lived in
Europe, where she was more appreciated _ hated being thought of as
a suspense writer. Perhaps because she and Rendell aren't
responding to testosteronic hyperbole, they are freer than their
male counterparts to go into less-explored psychological terrain.
(It may also have something to do with the fact that Highsmith's
mother tried to abort her by drinking turpentine.) Kastenmeier
isn't sure there will be more Highsmith coming from Black Lizard,
but ``Strangers on a Train'' would seem to be a natural. As good as
the movie is, Highsmith intertwines the liBruno and Guy in
ways that Hitchcock and Chandler backed away from in favor of more
conventional morality and characterization.
</P>
<P>
   That's what separates Highsmith's ``Ripley'' from Minghella's.
Without giving away the endings, Minghella's isn't nearly as
cowardly as Clement's, but he still felt it necessary to tack on a
layer of guilt that subverts the power of the novel. It's Ripley's
ability to actualize himself through murder, really, and get on
with his life that makes the first two in the series (``Ripley
Under Ground'' being the second) so chilling. Ripley pays no
apparent price and, oddly, the reader roots even harder for him
than for the Matt Damon character in the film. Writing in a clear,
spare style, Highsmith stays resolute in her determination not to
give her characters or her readers easy ways out. No wonder Graham
Greene and Gore Vidal were such fans.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith was not Thompson, though. They both wrote crime
fiction as opposed to mysteries, but there is a central mystery in
her writing: Where is the moral center? That there is one is
evidenced by her dedication to ``Ripley Under Water'' in 1991: ``To
the dead and the dying among the Intifadeh and the Kurds, to those
who fight oppression in whatever land, and stand up not only to be
counted but to be shot.'' But try finding anything that unambiguous
in her texts.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's Highsmith's ability to make us see the Ripley
within ourselves that makes her such a compelling writer. One of
the negative results of the movie is that Arthur Tress's creepy
matte cover of a faceless Ripley (it's in keeping with the rest of
the series) has been replaced with a glossy collage of Damon, Jude
Law, and Gwyneth Paltrow. It is always somewhat troubling to have
television or the movies replace the images that we come up with
ourselves in reading a book, but more so here. If we look closer at
Tress's Ripley photos, instead of seeing Damon we might see
ourselves. (The first three Ripleys have also just been published
in one hardback volume by Everyman.)
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, too, describes a frighteningly ambiguous moral
universe. ``Evil was a stupid word,'' she says in ``Fatal
Inversion,'' written under the alias of Barbara Vine. Her Inspector
Wexford novels are a cut above P. D. James's Dalgliesh and a cut
below Colin Dexter's Morse, though the plot dealing with his
assistant, Mike Burden in ``No More Dying Then'' is exceptional.
Most detectives are, in fact, the moral center of their authors'
writing, so it's in her non-Wexford books that Rendell's eerier
voice shines.
</P>
<P>
   Take the first sentences of ``A Judgement in Stone:'' ``Eunice
Parchman killed the Coverdale family because she could not read or
write. There was no real motive and no premeditation. No money was
gained and no security.'' As in Highsmith books, the randomness of
life is a recurring, haunting theme.
</P>
<P>
   If Highsmith and Rendell offer no easy psychological motivation
or conventional moral resolution, neither do they revel in chaos.
We shudder not in escapism, but in confrontation with reality. They
reflect our world too frighteningly. What Julian Symons says about
Highsmith in the recently published ``Oxford Companion to Crime
Mystery and Writing'' applies to Rendell as well: ``She has also
been, without intending it, a prophet. The terrors and delusions
driving her psychopaths to violent action are the ones we see
enacted now in the apparently motiveless crimes recorded in our
daily newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   For the latest variations, turn back to the news section. But
for a creepier context of today's violence, pick up a novel by
Highsmith or Rendell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
