<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYLAND-MILLENNIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE HOLYLAND, A YEAR FOR THE AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The world did not end.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the land of panic and prophecies, of hype and holiness,
we seem to have survived New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   And amid all the frenzy in the weeks that led up to the arrival
of the number 2000 on our calendars, digital watches, laptop
computers, and Palm Pilots, it seemed the actual event that this
round and imposing number marks was obscured by us all.
</P>
<P>
   I mean the media, specifically, and I am as guilty as the next
reporter for being lured into front-page stories with big
millennial headlines and chilling vignettes about the ``End of
Days,'' as the Book of Revelations calls the violent upheaval
prophesied to precede the return of the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations, including the Globe, also assigned seemingly
endless coverage to the whole ``Y2K bug'' scenario, deciding that
in this milestone they would focus on ways to prevent computer
viruses rather than deal with something we can't control. The
passing of time, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But in the quiet morning after, perhaps it is time to ask, ``Two
thousand years of what?'' What exactly are we measuring with this
millennium?
</P>
<P>
   The answer here in the Holy Land is tangible; it is grounded in
the hills of Galilee near Nazareth and the narrow cobblestone
streets of Bethlehem and Jerusalem; it stares you in the face. It
is the history of the life of Jesus Christ, born 2,000 or so years
ago, in a grotto on a rocky, terraced hillside in the ancient town
of Bethlehem, just a five-minute drive from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   With all the live network news coverage of the ball dropping in
New York's Times Square, of standups from Britain's Royal Greenwich
Observatory, the fireworks displays at Florida's Disney World, the
glitter and champagne in Las Vegas, the sleepy town of Bethlehem
and the site where people believe Jesus was born can't hold a
candle when it comes to packaging live television.
</P>
<P>
   In advisories printed by big media organizations, the planning
was intense and meticulous for coverage of the millennium. In the
Reuters news agency's advisory, there was a menu of offerings
focused on stories about ``how the world is ready to cope with the
millennium bug.'' There were feature packages available on ``how
science, medicine, and technology have progressed through the
millennium.'' There were messages for the millennium from
``entertainers, athletes, and politicians.'' Even a poll selecting
``the personalities of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The one personality noticeably absent from the vast millennial
coverage plan was Jesus. This historical figure whose birth marks
the beginning of the calendar we use in daily life was not
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true of the Globe's millennium coverage plan.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is simply easier to make this celebration secular and
inclusive and part of a collective measure of time for the whole
world. We have globalized the event.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps the Christian churches themselves prefer this. There
may be wisdom in a quiet, internal reflection on a faith that has
had its dark chapters in a millennium that began with the Crusades
and finished with the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But the inescapable fact is that the chronology that brings us
to 2000 derives from the Christian calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian chronology was established in the 6th century AD
by Dionysius Exiguus, who was the first to mark the beginning of
the year with the birth of Jesus. This was a change in chronology
from the Julian calendar established by Julius Caesar in 46 BC, the
calendar in place during the time of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Exiguus fixed the year 1 as the birth of Jesus by dating nine
months from the Annunciation (when Mary learned she was pregnant
with Jesus), which was believed then to have been March 25. But
Exiguus miscalculated, many historians now believe, and Jesus'
birth would have taken place four to eight years earlier than
Exiguus's estimation.
</P>
<P>
   This first Christian calendar also had a built-in error that led
to losing a day every 128 years. So in 1582, Pope Gregory XIII
overhauled the calendar by lopping off 10 days and building in a
system of leap years to avert the occurrence of discrepancies. The
Gregorian calendar also restored New Year's Day to Jan. 1. Thus,
here we are today, the whole calendar more of an art than the
science of dating the exact birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The Gregorian calendar was not immediately adopted by
Christendom. England did not accept it until 1752. Some
denominations within the Eastern Orthodox Church still have not
adopted it, which explains why Greek Orthodox Christmas falls on
Jan. 6, and Armenian Orthodox Christmas on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in our modern era, the Gregorian calendar has become the
measure of time _ with some significant secular modifications. For
example, rather than marking the years as AD, or ``Anno Domini,''
which translates from the Latin as ``the year of the Lord,'' it is
now generally accepted in scholarly circles to refer to CE, or
Common Era. Similarly, BC or ``before Christ,'' is now referred to
as BCE, or ``Before the Common Era.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations officially adopted the Gregorian calendar,
and therefore it has become in effect the global standard. The
advent of computers afirmed its place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   UN recognition of the calendar led The New York Times to
conclude last month, ``Within this context, 2000 no longer refers
to the cyclical, ritual time of a particular faith, but to the more
linear chronology of historical time.''
</P>
<P>
   This conclusion is puzzling. In other words, because the United
Nations adopted the Christian calendar it is no longer a Christian
calendar? Perhaps this is putting too fine a point on it, but
shouldn't it be seen as, in addition to being the Christian
calendar or a ritual time for that specific faith, it also is a
universally accepted chronology of historical time. One concept
does not exclude the other.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if we want to be precise in the matter, this
Christmas actually marks the 1,999th birthday of Jesus even if the
Vatican has said that it is the Jubilee celebration of 2,000 years
of Christianity. And for that matter, the official starting point
of the new millennium is not until Jan. 1, 2001, according to the
US Naval Observatory in Washington, D.C., the nation's official
timekeeper. But that didn't stop the media, nor the parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian calendar and the turning of the year 2000 seem
perhaps more stark here in the Holy Land because there are two
other religious calendars observed, the Jewish and the Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   On the Jewish calendar, the year is 5760. Regarding the arrival
of the third millennium, Jews have ``been there, at,'' as
Micah Halpern, an Israeli who writes the ``Onsite insights'' column
for America Online, put it in a Dec. 20 column titled ``Whose
Millennium Is It Anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims start their calendar counting at September 622 CE.
This commemorates the prophet Mohammed's exodus from Mecca and
arrival in Medina. It was there that the ``Age of Ignorance''
ended. And according to this calendar, which is lunar-based and has
354 days to a year, we are currently in the year 1420. So the
second millennium for Muslims is still 580 Muslim years away.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Fortin, an Assumptionist priest born in
Worcester who heads the Holy Land celebrations in Bethlehem for the
Vatican, stood in the desert expanse known as Shepherds' Field,
where it is believed that angels came 2,000 years ago and heralded
to local shepherds ``good tidings and joy'' at the coming of the
Lord in the form of the infant Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Fortin was preparing for a Christmas Eve celebration, and
stopped to make a point: ``There is so much hype with all this. The
millennium! Two thousand years. But 2,000 years of what? It seems
everyone has forgotten the origin of the calendar and that is the
birth of Jesus, which was first announced right here where you are
standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have to be wary of hype and commercialism at
Christmas, but with the millennium . . . now we have to be extra
vigilant to keep in mind what it is all about,'' Fortin said.
</P>
<P>
   The mainstream denominations, Roman Catholic and Protestant, may
also bear some blame, according to Stephen O'Leary, who teaches a
course on ``The Millennium and the Media'' at the University of
Southern California, and wrote the book ``Arguing the Apocalypse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mainstream Christian denominations have missed the
opportunity to present this as the 2,000th birthday for Jesus, and
as a genuine time to reflect on the faith's history,'' O'Leary
said. ``I think they feared it would be seen as a crackpot
approach, and so they missed the historic moment. They abandoned
the field to the millennial secular hype and all its hucksters. So
that is what we are stuck with now. And that is a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Charles M. Sennott is the Globe's Middle East bureau chief. He is
writing a book on Christians of the Holy Land.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
