<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      01-03 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WASN'T THE PANAMA CANAL DUG DEEPER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. When the Panama Canal was constructed, was it possible to cut
the channel deep enough to eliminate the locks necessary to raise
the ships, allowing the oceans to seek a common level?
</P>
<P>
   RC Jr., Goodyear, AZ
</P>
<P>
   A. The Panama Canal, which officially passed out of U.S. hands
Jan. 1, was an amazing feat of human science, technology, and will.
But nature also taught humans a humbling lesson there about just
how far technology and science could go.
</P>
<P>
   The first one to learn them was the man who built The Suez
Canal, Ferdinand Vicomte de Lesseps.
</P>
<P>
   Ever hear the palindrome A man a plan a canal Panama? De Lesseps
was the man with the plan. At the time, in the 1870s, experts said
Nicaragua was the better site for the Atlantic-Pacific canal. Even
though the Nicaragua route was longer, it was lower, it had lakes
that could be incorporated into the waterway and it had a more
forgiving climate in which to work. But it didn't have one thing
Panama did; a railroad from the Atlantic to the Pacific, which had
been built to carry people across the isthmus to ships in the
Pacific headed up to the California Gold Rush. With the railroad,
De Lesseps was convinced that he could dig a sea level canal of
half the distance of Suez, in Panama.
</P>
<P>
   Work began in 1881. Within a year the first engineer quit,
saying it was impossible. The oppressive tropical climate was more
than a match for the French steam shovels that had done fine in the
dry heat of Suez. The rain was torrential, 51 feet between June and
October, 1884. The Chagres River, along the chosen route, could
rise ten feet in a day, flooding out all work.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the bugs and diseases of the rain forest killed 500 men
in 1882, 2,000 in 1883, 2,400 in 1884. In 1885, 20 of every 100 new
workers brought in died of yellow fever or malaria. A headline of
the day asked ``Is M. de Lesseps a canal digger, or a grave
digger?''
</P>
<P>
   Geology was another challenge. At the highest point they had to
dig through, the Culebra Cut, only 330 feet above sea level, the
Continental Divide was an unstable mix of soil, sedimentary and
igneous rocks. To dig a canal to sea level, with wide and
gentle-enough slopes to avoid disastrous mudslides, the Culebra Cut
would have had to be more than three quarters of a mile wide across
the top. Two engineering reviews said a sea-level canal was
impossible. De Lesseps, by all accounts an egotist and more a
salesman than an engineer, pressed on.
</P>
<P>
   Though he relented in 1887 and announced that Gustave Eiffel
would build locks for the Panama Canal, by 1889 his company was
bankrupt. (Another good thing. Eiffel was free to build his tower.)
Construction stopped. Eight years of work in what de Lesseps had
called ``le plus belle region du monde'' had excavated 30 million
cubic yards, dug 163 feet down into the Clubbed Cut, and killed
20,000 men.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Congress quickly chartered a company to build
a sea level canal. Not through Panama but Nicaragua. A stock market
crash in 1893 quashed that plan, but President William McKinley and
his successor, Theodore Roosevelt, pressed on with the Nicaragua
plan. Once again however, Panama came up with something Nicaragua
couldn't match. In 1902 the French investors in the first effort
decided to sell their partially dug canal, maps, and equipment, for
40 centimes on the franc (sixty percent off).
</P>
<P>
   After Colombia, which controlled the isthmus, refused a $35
million offer for the land from America, the United States put a
battleship off Panama. With Roosevelt waving a big stick, the
Panamanians declared their independence from Colombia and agreed to
let the United States dig.
</P>
<P>
   But nature would not give in to the Americans any more than it
had to the French. U.S. work began in 1904, but only months later,
three quarters of the Americans working on the canal fled as yellow
fever and malaria spread. Dr. William Gorgas, a Colonel in the Army
Corps of Engineers, was brought in. He had done pioneering work
with Dr. Walter Reed in Cuba, discovering that the Stegomyia
mosquito spread yellow fever. Gorgas and Reed learned its life
cycle, eliminated its breeding habitat, and all but wiped out
yellow fever in Havana. Within a year and a half of coming to
Panama, he eliminated yellow fever and greatly reduced other
malaria and other diseases. Digging resumed in earnest in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Roosevelt and others still hadn't decided whether to
dig down to sea level, or build a canal with locks and a lake in
the middle created by damming up the Chagres River. In 1905
Roosevelt became the first U.S. President in office to leave the
country, visiting the canal project. Reminiscent of de Lesseps, he
declared that he favored a sea level canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dignity and power of this great nation require that we
should treat this matter in a final, masterly way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1906, after engineers testified that a sea level canal would
take 18 years, and a locks and lake plan only 9, Congress went for
the locks and lake plan, by a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later the 50 mile-long Panama Canal opened.
</P>
<P>
   The first trip through the canal was by a cement barge, on
August 3, 1914. It was the first day of World War One.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mary in 1936 Was the first ship to big to fit. Today,
only modern supertankers are too big for the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the $25 million Woodrow Wilson paid Colombia years
later, the Panama Canal cost the United States $639 million
dollars, ($7 billion dollars today) including the $40 million paid
to the French. For perspective, the U.S. had spent a total of $75
million for the Louisiana Territory, Florida, California, New
Mexico, Arizona, Alaska, and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   It created a nation, and helped the world learn how to fight two
scourge diseases. (Gorgas went on to head the Army Medical Service
in World War I, and was knighted).
</P>
<P>
   It is a monument to the power of science, technology, and human
ego. The fact that it is not at sea level, and that it cost 25,000
lives, testify to the fact that science and technology and human
will have their limits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BARTOLI-BOS &LR;      01-03 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BARTOLI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 20TH-CENTURY STAR TURNS TO THE EIGHTEENTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000   The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sunny speaking voice of Cecilia Bartoli came onto the phone
from her hotel room in Frankfurt. The mezzo-soprano is probably the
most popular female classical singer before the public today, and
certainly the biggest recording star in her field, even if she has
yet to make a crossover album. Although she had sung an all-Vivaldi
concert the night before, she sounded eager to participate in a
telephone press conference about her adventures in Vivaldi,
documented on her best-selling CD ``The Vivaldi Album'' (Decca),
and in a brief tour that recently brought her to America for a
handful of concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Bartoli dedicated her new album to the memory of her brother
Gabriele, a violist and musicologist, who died of a brain tumor; he
was the first to draw his sister's attention to Vivaldi. ``My
brother was the one who showed the music of Vivaldi to me, the
sacred music, and we performed together some Vivaldi cantatas in
Europe and also in the States. It is because of him that now I sing
this music, and the recording is a sort of late present for him.
When I was working on the cantatas, I decided to look more to try
to discover more things about him and what he did in his time. I
found that Vivaldi was more famous as an opera composer than as a
composer for sacred music or even as an instrumental composer. At
the beginning, I went to Venice and then to Turin, where in the
National Library I found most of the manuscripts of Vivaldi _
incredible things, amazing really.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Vivaldi's operas, ``Orlando Furioso,'' has successfully
been revived in modern times, by Marilyn Horne. Bartoli says she is
not yet sure which of the others is worth reviving in full, or
which she would like to sing onstage. ``I really must study all of
them to see which one is the right one to start with. I think
`Farnace' may be a great opera, and probably also `La Griselda.' I
am looking forward to making one of these operas integrale onstage,
but it is difficult to say right now which one it should be.
Because of the work of so many different groups, and of conductors
like Nikolaus Harnoncourt and Christopher Hogwood, there is a
Baroque renaissance today. People are more used to listening to
Baroque music, and they understand what the structure of it is and
how it works. So now is the time to perform these operas onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vivaldi Album'' contains many examples of the kind of
spectacular but unorthodox coloratura singing that drives Bartoli's
audiences and critics crazy _ for different reasons. It also
contains a few slow arias that display her exceptional musicality,
beauty of tone, and pliant expressivity, most notably an aria from
``Farnace,'' ``Gelido in ogni vena,'' which must stand with the
singer's greatest recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have become very attached to the music of Vivaldi,'' Bartoli
says. ``This music is dramatic and it is lyric and there are
virtuoso moments as well. Sometimes I really feel that Vivaldi used
the voice the way he would use a violin. Also sometimes the voice
sings with the flutes, the strings, and the other instruments, and
it is very interesting to try to match all those colors, to find
more colors and nuances in the voice. Sometimes it is an echo,
sometimes a conversation, sometimes a contest. Always it is about
making an expression. The aria from `Farnace' is so sad _ the
father is standing in front of the bier of his son, and he knows
that everything that has happened was his own fault, and now it's
too late. There are similar bars of music in `Winter' from `The
Four Seasons.' The blood of this person becomes cold; it is also
winter inside the person, inside the soul of this father. For me,
this was the most difficult piece on the recording.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartoli has a very clear sense of her abilities and of the
direction she wants to take. She made her breakthrough as a Mozart
and a Rossini singer. Without renouncing either, she now wants to
concentrate on Handel, Vivaldi, and Haydn. ``It is important to
perform the music you feel, the music you believe in. I am trying
to take this direction; the Baroque direction is suitable to my
voice, to my temperament. I hope the opera houses will understand
that. This process is not just for a single singer _ it is for
everybody, because the audience can discover new things.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently Bartoli completed a tour and a recording of Handel's
``Rinaldo'' conducted by Christopher Hogwood. ``At first they
wanted me to sing the title part, but for this you need a different
type of voice from mine. This part was made for a castrato with an
alto color. I can sing some castrato parts, but the ones that were
written more between the soprano and mezzo ranges. Rinaldo calls
for a dark, low voice; I have another instrument, so I chose to
sing Almirena, the wife, and the countertenor David Daniels sang
Rinaldo. Singing Handel is very different from singing Vivaldi. The
Handel line is more pure in a way, more lyric. In Vivaldi you have
extremes; Vivaldi was more extreme as a composer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartoli was also scheduled to sing her first Melisande in
Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande'' this season, but did not.
``Melisande I was supposed to sing in Florence. Italy is a great
country, but sometimes things there are not so good organized, and
this was happening with `Pelleas.' Already they are asking me again
to do this role in Salzburg, with Simon Rattle conducting, but that
comes at a time when I will be at the Met in New York. Next year my
two new roles will be in the `Armida' of Haydn, in Vienna with
Nikolaus Harnoncourt conducting, and Fiordiligi in Mozart's `Cosi
fan tutte.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fiordiligi will be Bartoli's third role in this opera _ she
began as Dorabella, and then sang Despina for her Met debut. ``I am
so excited about this _ I am completely crazy about the women of
Mozart. As you know, when I was at the Met for `The Marriage of
Figaro,' I sang a different version of Susanna's role, with arias
Mozart wrote for Vienna. The singer who was performing this
version, Gabriella Dal Bene, `La Ferrarese,' was also the singer
for whom Mozart wrote the role of Fiordiligi, about two years
later. So now, about two years after Susanna, I will sing
Fiordiligi for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartoli's decision to sing the alternate operas created a
certain amount of controversy, at least in the columns of The New
York Times. ``I felt a little bit sad about this _ to attack not
me, but Mozart, this made me sad. Mozart wrote some different arias
for a different singer, and I thought it would be exciting to hear
these for the first time since then on the stage, to give the
audience to discover something.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Bartoli says she wants to extend her explorations
to other composers of Vivaldi's era, such as Riccardo Broschi, the
brother of the celebrated castrato Farinelli, and Geminaro
Giacomelli. She is also definitely interested in looking into some
more Spanish music; recently she added Falla's ``Seven Popular
Spanish Songs'' to her recital repertory. ``I will not be singing
just the Baroque music,'' she says. ``It is important for a
musician to explore, no?'' One role Bartoli says she will certainly
not be singing is Violetta in ``La Traviata,'' though rumors have
been circulating about that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   In America Bartoli has been seen exclusively in comic roles so
far, a fact that she regrets. ``I did some tragic, dramatic parts
in Europe, and I would really like to bring an opera like the
`Orfeo ed Euridice' of Haydn to America. The dramaticity of the
18th century is very different from the dramaticity of the 19th
century, and I feel closer to the 18th century.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her popularity on recordings and television, Bartoli
says she does not always feel satisfied with her work in media
other than live performance. ``On the recording it is always
difficult for me to recognize myself. When I sing, I have a
resonance in my head, in my body, and what the people get in the
hall is different, and what they get on the recording is also
different. I miss a little bit the three-dimensional part, which
you cannot have. On television you see just two dimensions, and in
a recording you can listen only to what the microphone or the
speakers give you. You don't have the three dimensions as in a live
perf. Still, it is great to have opera on TV, this is clear.
I do not like to watch myself on TV, but this is a way to learn.
When I look at myself on TV I can say, `This is good' or `This I
can do in a different way.' In any case, it is a lesson, a way of
learning to grow. What I do like to do is watch other singers and
musicians when they perform; this too is a way to learn. Acting is
part of being a singer. After all, a singer is a person who tells a
story, and you need to know how to do that, with your voice, with
your body, with your brain _ with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Bartoli unleashes a cascading coloratura laugh. ``I
don't even like to speak on the telephone. You know, I also talk
with my hands, the way all Italians do!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1405EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
