<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5316 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-03 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILIAD KILLJOY TAKES THE PULSE OF A NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime New Year's morning, the cat mistook the Christmas tree
skirt for his litter box. The cat clearly is not Y2K-compliant, but
neither am I, or the tree would have been dismantled long before
the glorious new chiliad.
</P>
<P>
   Chiliad, with a hard C, KIL-ee-ad. That's what my favorite
publication, the Fortean Times (``The Journal of Strange
Phenomena''), prefers to call the millennium. Chiliad is a Greek
word meaning any group of 1,000. Chiliasm, the FT editors note in
the current issue, is a belief in better times to come. We can
hope.
</P>
<P>
   At least we won't have to hear any more hysteria-provoking
blather about how Y2K techno failure will have us all hunkered down
in a new Dark Age with only our Coleman heaters and emergency
stores of water-packed tuna to warm and sustain us.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 dawned with a minimum of technological glitches.
Human error, though, is still very much with us, as reflected in
this line, heard on a New Year's Day radio report: ``The only power
outages reported were caused by drivers running into utility
poles.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology was ready for the turn of the millennium, but were
we? Are we? New Year's Eve, while watching Chet and Natalie, New
England's favorite TV newscouple, shepherd in the new millennium, I
found myself wondering about the dissolution of their
nonprofessional marriage. On air they're still so warm and loving.
Their electronic marriage is a model. What went wrong in ``real''
life?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe their relationship wasn't Y2K-ready. They're only human,
in spite of what some of Natalie's fans may believe. It's possible
that what made for a happy marriage in the 20th century doesn't
measure up in the 21st. Instead of poking my nose into their
marriage, I should examine my own. Is it ready for the Naughty
Oughties? How can it be, if I'm not?
</P>
<P>
   The news of the last two days has been full of people unprepared
for Y2K. One of my favorite examples was in a Globe news story, a
quote from a young Sturbridge woman who said she took her pulse
immediately after midnight. ``I thought I would feel a lot
differently, but here we are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   You'd never catch a computer making such an enigmatic statement.
But I know exacty what she meant. I didn't take my pulse on the
stroke of the year 2000, but I should have, just to prove to myself
that I was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   I'd been curled for hours in a semifetal position in front of
the TV, watching ABC's dazzling worldwide coverage of the turn of
the chiliad, from Tonga to Times Square. Peter Jennings's costume
changes alone had taxed my emotions to the limit, and there were
still three hours to go before the new century would creep up on
the Hollywood Hills. A little earlier, watching a musical interlude
featuring Harry Connick Jr. in Las Vegas, I finally understood the
advantage of drinking to excess on New Year's Eve. His performance
was not the sort of thing you want to face sober. Why hadn't I laid
in a stash of champagne?
</P>
<P>
   The network's coverage was a technological triumph, easily
spanning time zones, continents, countries. Unfort, some of
the entertainers ABC presented were definitely not Y2K ready.
There's something perverse about using the most sophisticated and
advanced communication technology in the world to bring the likes
of Neil Diamond and Barry Manilow and Billy Joel into our homes on
a night that we will remember the rest of our lives, no matter how
hard we may try to forget certain portions of it. Years from now,
when people speak of the turn of the 21st century, I will think of
Neil Diamond croaking ``America'' while spotlights dance off his
hairpiece. I want to feel chiliastic, but how?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
