<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVORCED-POET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEG CAMPBELL DISCOVERED HER VOICE AS A POET DURING A DIVORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that 1.3 million American marriages end in divorce
every year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Meg Campbell's marriage became one of them. Her story
might have ended there, in the mounting ash heap of terminated
relationships. But Campbell, an educator from Boston, did something
unexpected. She wrote ``Solo Crossing,'' a book of poetry about her
separation and divorce, although she had never been a poet. In the
process, she not only reinvented her life by discovering a new
metier but may have produced an overnight hit.
</P>
<P>
   The book was published two months ago, and ``it's just taken
off,'' says Campbell's publisher, Cynthia Navaretta of Midmarch
Arts Press, a small New York publishing house that specializes in
books on the arts. ``The book is selling better than any book I've
ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Campbell was the featured poet on
www.PoetryCentral.com _ a New York-based Web site promoting poets
and poetry events _ and it resulted in ``this incredible
word-of-mouth networking,'' says Campbell, still dazzled. ``It's
really feeding on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantaneously, she started getting invitations to give
readings around the country, including New York, San Antonio, and _
Campbell is ecstatic about this one _ Blytheville, Ark. The
bookstore owner in Blytheville, Mary Gay Shipley, was featured in a
New Yorker article in October that described her Oprah-like
prescience in anticipating books that will become hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just so excited,'' says Sherrie Casteel, who is
coordinating the reading for a monthly poet's group that meets at
That Bookstore in Blytheville. ``Her poetry is beautiful and it
speaks to everyone, whether it is my 14-year-old daughter or the
58-year-old retired English teacher in our group who is
African-American and writes his poetry in Zulu,'' she says. ``I
read the book and said, `Yes, this is wonderful.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet bookseller Amazon.com has ordered Campbell's book
in quantity and made it available on 24-hour shipment. Campbell
says she now receives e-mail every day from enthusiastic readers.
There was the woman in New York who had been married for 40 years
and divorced for five who ``told me she thought she'd put it all
behind her but was sobbing reading my book.'' That same day there
was a note from the African-American woman in San Antonio who
``said she felt it was her story.'' And there was ``some guy in
Chicago'' going through a divorce who read excerpts of the book on
the Internet and said he needed the rest of it _ immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people have told me, `I don't like poetry but I
like your book,' '' says Campbell, 47. She describes the book _ a
modestly designed, softcover collection of 61 poems _ as a ``memoir
of separation and divorce, the new life beyond, and the whole range
of emotions in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Like rage, for one:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now we are separated
</P>
<P>
   eight months. You live
</P>
<P>
   with another woman,
</P>
<P>
   take her to your uncle's wedding,
</P>
<P>
   tell me
</P>
<P>
   you have an open heart
</P>
<P>
   about us.
</P>
<P>
   What heart?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And loneliness:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I understand
</P>
<P>
   this is my life.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming
</P>
<P>
   alone.
</P>
<P>
   Tired. Afraid
</P>
<P>
   How much longer can I last?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (end poetry style)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And starting over:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even temporary celibacy, I've read,
</P>
<P>
   promises clarity, calm.
</P>
<P>
   Feelings pristine, detached.
</P>
<P>
   Then why am I undressing
</P>
<P>
   the Saturn repair associate
</P>
<P>
   or the man who comes to give my garden a bid?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have published much more intellectual poets and those with
bigger reputations,'' Navaretta says, noting that Campbell's book
sold about 600 copies in the first five weeks, ``which is a
phenomenal number for poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This poetry reaches people. It is easy to read. It is from the
heart. And there is an audience out there, which is apparently not
a poetry audience, of people who are attracted to the subject.
After all, the experience (of divorce) is so common now.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would have predicted an unknown poet could have generated
this kind of response, least of all Campbell, who graduated from
Radcliffe College to go on to a career that has included many
occupations, none of them poet. She has been a community organizer,
Massachusetts Senate legislative research director, teacher, and
school administrator. Currently she is a lecturer at the Harvard
Graduate School of Education and executive director of
Expeditionary Learning Outward Bound in Cambridge, Mass., a
comprehensive reform school that uses the teaching methods of the
Outward Bound wilderness programs.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of two daughters, both in college, Campbell declines
to discuss specific details of the dissolution of her
nearly-20-year marriage, except to say ``the breakup was not my
choice'' and to make reference to her poem called ``Court Date,''
which suggests there had been another woman in her husband's life.
</P>
<P>
   The end of her marriage was utterly ``paralyzing. There is a lot
of shame associated with separation and divorce,'' particularly,
she says, for Catholics like her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, divorce simply just wasn't an option
for Catholics,'' she says. ``It was unthinkable. I knew one
divorced family in my elementary school, and the father was
alcoholic and the mother (itals)had to go to work.(undated) It was
like something out of Charles Dickens.''
</P>
<P>
   After Campbell and her husband separated, she was consumed by
``shame, guilt, and failure. I had been a very proud person. This
whole experience was very humbling. I cried every day for the first
year.''
</P>
<P>
   She writes in the introduction to her book: ``Succeeding in
marriage was vitally important to me. I failed. I would have done
anything to spare my children pain. I could not. Dating in my
forties was not in my original life plan, nor was living alone with
a vociferous cat.''
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, she says, she discovered that ``life surprises
and teaches.'' She sought help from many sources _ her Catholic
faith, therapists, loving friends and family, books, a divorce
support group _ and unexpectedly, a catharsis came in the form of
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always kept a journal, but suddenly it was like a volcano,
and I started pouring forth (itals)stuff.''(unitals) Dream
fragments and poems appeared in her journal. When she showed the
first 10 to friends, they encouraged her to keep writing. Some 50
poems later, she had ``Solo Crossing.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is more to come. With a friend in New York, William
Duke, she is working on an anthology of poems about divorce, called
``Split Verse: Poems to Heal the Heart,'' which will also be
published by Midmarch. She believes it is the ``first ever
anthology of poems about divorce,'' containing more than 60 poems
from among 1,000 entries, submitted by poets around the country in
response to an advertisement in Poets &AMP; Writers magazine.
</P>
<P>
   What has she learned from this whole experience? That ``your
disability is your opportunity,'' says Campbell, quoting Kurt Hahn,
the founder of Outward Bound. She is happier now than she has been
in years, having discovered the support of a ``large, wonderful
extended family who was totally there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She has also learned _ from her new cadre of readers and from
the profuse interest in her anthology from other poets _ that her
solo experience has been shared by many.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we all feel vulnerable,'' says Campbell.
``Everyone in a way is on a solo crossing. But we all have safety
boats behind us even if we can't see them in the fog. And poetry is
a wonderful way for all those powerful emotions to be compressed
and distilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1408EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-WOMEN-CEOs-NYTSF &LR;      01-03 2477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-CEOs-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WOMEN CEOs: ARRIVAL TIME   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``f'' business news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By LISA LOCKWOOD  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Linda Wachner has company.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the corporate halls of fashion, retailing and beauty
were dominated by men. But women are hitting the industry's topmost
echelons in greater numbers and Wachner, Warnaco's high-profile
boss and a pioneer in the old boys' club, isn't the only woman
running the show anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Two developments last month presented further evidence that
there's a new breed of executive breaking into the top ranks:
Within days, Andrea Jung was appointed chief executive officer of
Avon and Christina Johnson was named ceo of Saks Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jung stands alone as the only female to be running a
Fortune 500 fashion or bempany. The three other female ceo's
in the Fortune 500 are Carleton S. Fiorina of Hewlett-Packard, Jill
E. Barad of Mattel and Marion D. Sandler of Golden West Financial.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of running multimillion- or even
multibillion-dollar corporations, women are well represented. In
addition to Wachner, Jung and Johnson, there's Lillian Vernon,
chairman and ceo of the firm bearing her name; Carolee Friedlander,
ceo of Carolee Designs; Josie Natori, ceo of Natori Co.; Josephine
Chaus, chairwoman of Chaus, Inc.; Jessica McClintock,
owner/designer of Jessica McClintock; Eileen Fisher, owner of the
sportswear firm bearing her name; Carole Hochman, ceo of Carole
Hochman Designs, and Diane Von Furstenberg, who heads her own
ready-to-wear company, DVF Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Also over the past several years, women have gained more ground
and more authority to run fashion and beauty divisions of larger
conglomerates. Companies such as T The Limited, Dayton
Hudson, Liz Claiborne, Federated and Jones Apparel Group are among
those that have steadily elevated women to top positions. In fact,
female division presidents are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   There's Jeanne Jackson, president of Banana Republic; Robin
Burns, president of IBI Intimate Beauty Corp.; Grace A. Nichols,
chief executive officer of Victoria's Secret Stores (a division of
Intimate Brands); Beth M. Pritchard, ceo of Bath &AMP; Body Works,
another division of IBI; Patricia DeRosa, president of Ann Taylor;
Marie Holman-Rao, president of Limited Design Services; Janet
Grove, chairman and ceo of the Federated Merchandising Group;
Vanessa Castagna, executive vice president and chief operating
officer of J.C. Penney Stores, merchandising and catalog, and Susan
Kronick, chairman of Burdine's, among others.
</P>
<P>
   On fashion's manufacturing side, there's Denise Seegal,
president of Liz Claiborne Inc.; Jackwyn Nemerov, president of the
Jones Apparel Group; Mindy Grossman, president and ceo of Polo
Jeans; Carol Hochman, chief executive officer of Danskin, and
Christa Michalaros, president of Tommy Hilfiger women's sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   And in the rapidly evolving world of e-commerce, women
executives are sprouting up all over the landscape. Meg Whitman,
chief executive officer of eBay; Candice Carpenter, chairman and
ceo of iVillage Inc., and Nancy Evans, president of iVillage, are
just a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see any ceilings in the world you and I live
in,'' said Hal Reiter, president and ceo of Herbert Mines
Associates, an executive search firm here. ``No one says to me, `I
want a guy.'' I don't even think it's an issue anymore. Women have
been very successful in fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we get an assignment for a ceo in the fashion
business, it's completely gender neutral. I always say, `Do you
have a preference?' and they say, `I'd love a woman. It's a
complete demonstration by women that they are as completely capable
as men, if not more,''' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerated growth of the Internet has created many
opportunities for women, since the rules of the game _ and the
necessary job skills _ haven't been clearly defined yet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the advances, women are still a minority in the
executive suites, and some recruiters say their take-home pay still
lags behind the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (women's) deals are perhaps not as lucrative since their
negotiating skills are not as inbred and honed as some of their
male counterparts,'' said Terre Simpson, owner of Simpson
Associates, an executive search firm here. She noted that some men,
whose skills might not be as good, are ``terrific negotiators,''
able to carve out larger packages for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But Herbert Mines's Reiter believes that women, at least on the
ceo level, are getting equal pay. ``Look at Linda Wachner,'' he
said, perennially one of the highest paid executives in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is women are being paid as much as men,'' said
Reiter. ``And they don't negotiate themselves. They usually have
their lawyer or headhunter do it.'' Plus, he said, these women
ceo's didn't get to the top posts by being shrinking violets when
it comes to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's Fiorina is said to have a total compensation
package worth $5.25 million, and Mattel's Barad's compensation is
$4.75 million. Meanwhile, the Gap's Drexler pulled in $7.8 million
in total compensation. Leonard Lauder's total compensation was $6.6
million, while the Limited's Wexner had a total compensation of
$2.7 million. In 1998, Jung, who was then president and chief
operating officer of Avon, received $5 million, largely reflecting
$3.8 million in restricted stock.
</P>
<P>
   Jung, 41, now runs a $5.2 billion conglomerate. She also serves
on the board of General Electric, the Fragrance Foundation,
Cosmetic Executive Women and Princeton University, of which she's a
graduate. She was named to Fortune's list of ``50 Most Powerful
Women in American Business,'' in both 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jung is a prime example of a woman who has handily cracked the
top tier and sees herself as a role model for her daughter. In an
interview following her appointment, Jung described being a working
mother as ``tough'' and ``challenging,'' but said she was excited
by setting an exar her 10-year-old daughter and her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest rounds of applause I got was when I walked
into a birthday party just yesterday and all of her friends thought
it was a great thing that a woman got to the top and they're all 10
years old ... I think there is something in that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dayton Hudson's Linda Ahlers was interviewed earlier this
year, she said she never found barriers to her advancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you create your own ceilings,'' said Ahlers.
``Personally, if I started to think there was a glass ceiling,
there would have been one for me. I won't let it exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the 48-year-old chief executive officer and president
of Saks Fifth Avenue here, said, ``I have been very fortunate in my
career. I worked for Philip Miller for 17 years and he's been a
huge mentor in terms of my professional growth. He fostered a
leadership style that's one of equality.'' Johnson noted that women
comprise 75 percent of the Saks Fifth Avenue's staff and 50 percent
of the executive board.
</P>
<P>
   Do women have to work harder than men to get ahead? Johnson
noted that results can be easily measured in fashion retailing, so
``performance is not gender-related ... (but) if anything, I
believe that women, because of the fact they've had a different
equality mechanism in the workplace, have an innate pressure to
perform. They are constantly aware of how they're perceived in the
workplace and have a much stronger need to excel.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest child in her family, Johnson said she was trained
at an early age to strive for achievement. Johnson majored in
sociology at Loyola University, which, she said, ``helped
tremendously in terms of development of people.'' And while she
described her ascension in retailing ``as a steady climb,'' she
attributed her success to a very diverse career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come up through the merchandising ranks,'' said
Johnson, noting she worked for Marshall Field's stand-alone catalog
and was a general merchandise manager at Saks before handling store
operations. ``The key for any woman in terms of running a company
today is to develop general management skills,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the defining moment was when she realized she had a
shot at the top post, she said: ``After the merger (with Profitt's)
and when Brad Martin became chairman of the company, he elevated me
to vice chairman. At this point I realized there was a significant
opportunity to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the path, management style has a lot to do with the
success of the industry's top female executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think I have a participatory management style,''
said Johnson. ``Am I tough? I've heard that said about me. Maybe. I
firmly believe it's a team that brings an organization to its
highest capability. I very much like to have my management style
reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Mines' Reiter said the reason there haven't been more
women in top positions is really based on numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only X amount of women in the business ... Because
there are fewer women to choose from, fewer women move to the
top,'' contended Reiter.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics differ by industry, however. Reiter said when he
conducts a beauty search, generally 75 percent of the candidates
are women. For a retail fashion position, usually 25 percent are
female candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more women in cosmetics and beauty than
anywhere else. It's where the inventory is,'' said Reiter. He said
that when he conducted the Ann Taylor (president) search, ``almost
every candidate they saw was a woman.'' They chose Patricia DeRosa,
former executive vice president of Charming Shoppes; before that,
she had been president of GapKids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skills are what's rising to the top, not the gender,''
said Terre Simpson of Simpson Associates. ``I think finally, after
much duress, it's beginning to be a level playing field. Women are
primed now and are moving up above the midmanagement level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the mind-set changing and acknowledging women's
contributions. Now, they assess a person on their business acumen
and contribution, rather than gender,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hart, partner in the executive search firm Spencer Stuart
and managing director of its North American retail practice,
observed that although fashion and beauty companies have
historically recruited women, women are now rising to the top
across virtually every industry.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that the Internet has created many such
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of the Internet, you can go off the big
corporate tracks and give them (women) the leverage of full
corporate responsibility,'' Hart said. ``What I do think about the
Internet is the rules aren't written yet _ who the right person has
to be and what traditional route you have to come up. It's not just
women, but diversity in the Internet. There are fabulous
opportunities for women. There used to be a premium for gray hair.
Now there's a premium for youth.''
</P>
<P>
   While some women may be attracted to Internet positions, others
are apparently content with more conventional venues. ``The lure of
potential compensation, to be part of something that will hopefully
go public, catches a lot of people's eyes. But some people are very
content in non e-commerce. Those channels won't go away. They have
some amazing business challenges running traditional companies with
traditional channels of distribution,'' said Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Jung and Johnson, she said these women have plenty
of opportunities to run huge management teams and global
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrea (Jung) is someone who is remarkably bright. She is one
of the most outstanding people in leadership. She has a delightful
personality. She's very determined and accomplished with huge
interpersonal skills,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   She said a lot of women are content running important divisions
_ if not exactly the ceo slot. ``There are fabulous women who are
running divisions of companies who will either be picked off and
become a ceo, or it may not be their total driving force. They
might have enough autonomy and are very satisfied,'' said Hart.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that a lot of men find satisfaction in the
decision-making and leadership role, but there are plenty of people
who can do that within the confines of a company. She pointed to
Ann Fudge, president of the Maxwell House and Post divisions of
Kraft Foods, who also sits on three boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're challenged and well respected, and treated well by
your company ... you add it all up in the end. By the time you
reach the top, the pay check is pretty good. Lots of women have
made self-selecting choices. Sometimes they're the candidates for
the ceo jobs, and they're the ones who pass,'' said Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she said, executives need a global perspective and
companies have to provide the experience to round out their skills.
She believes that many of today's female ceo's come from the
marketing ranks. ``Marketing tends to be the function that's king
in consumer companies. Those functions are cluttered with women,''
said Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Kusin, managing partner of the consumer practice at
Heidrick &AMP; Struggles, an executive search firm here, doesn't
believe that the fashion and beauty industries have lagged behind
other industries in naming female ceo's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In creatively driven businesses such as these, women have been
pulled to them. Any faster-paced businesses have been more
appealing to women,'' said Kusin.
</P>
<P>
   She said Jung's appointment at Avon gives other companies the
confidence that it can happen and that it's not that big a risk.
Like men, Kusin noted, some female ceo's will be successful, and
some won't. ``The issue of gender will become less important. Who
succeeds and who doesn't depends on leadership skills.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kusin agreed that e-businesses are a natural place
for women to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are geared to run these businesses based on the speed of
change and chaos, so it's common to see women in start-ups, because
of their sheer creativity and the ability to see where it all needs
to go. It plays to women's strong suits.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Lisa Lockwood is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
