<BODY>

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1410EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-WEST-BOS &LR;      01-03 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ADVENTURES OF TWO WHO EXPLORED THE WILD WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000   The Boston Globe  
 
A NEWER WORLD 
Kit Carson, John C. Fremont, and the Claiming of the American West 
By David Roberts 
Simon &AMP; Schuster. 320 pp. Illustrated. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They saved each other's lives. They served as foils for each
other. They assured each other's place in history, and in myth.
</P>
<P>
   They were John C. Fremont and Kit Carson, and in myth and even
in the sober annals of history they were wild-eyed adventurers,
explorers, wild men. They were also stubborn fools. But history _
of the American West, especially, but in a way all of history _ is
made by adventurers, explorers, wild men, and stubborn fools.
</P>
<P>
   David Roberts, a writer with a taste for adventurers and a soft
spot for stubborn fools, has taken a fresh look at some familiar
faces, and in ``A Newer World: Kit Carson, John C. Fremont, and the
Claiming of the American West,'' he gives new life to some of the
most vivid figures on the American canvas. He does one thing more,
too: He reminds us that historical figures, even the fabled loners
of the West, never actually accomplished very much of anything
alone.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly is the brilliant new truth that shines forth from
Roberts's book. Carson went from gung-ho Indian battler to
introspective Indian sympathizer. Fremont went from explorer to
senator. Carsknown as the Rope Thrower, Fremont as the
Pathfinder. Carson was modest, Fremont showy. And together, Roberts
tells us, they ``effectively closed the era of the discovery of the
West.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not a small thing, especially since it is historically
respectable to think that the exploration of the West _ the process
rather than any single, significant discovery _ was one of the
principal ways men and women of the 19th century discovered their
country, their notions of community, and their sense of selves.
Carson and Fremont were part of that, and they are part of the
folklore of the period and the region. But they were human, too,
and that's where the stereotypes break down.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts has written an ingenious and ingratiating volume,
focusing on two men who in a dozen years in the middle of the 19th
century conducted expeditions of exploration that changed the
history of America and, just as important, the way Americans looked
at their history.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this book _ more the chronicle of a partnership
than a double biography _ are four campaigns, beginning with the
1842 expedition to Wyoming's Wind River Range and concluding with
the infamous 1863-64 roundup of the Mescalero Apaches and Navajos
that led to the Long Walk. Roberts traced them all, in documents
and by car and foot, and the result is a sense of realism _ the
literary equivalent of the whiff of wood smoke, you might say _
rarely achieved in Western historical writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the 1842 expedition onward, their destinies and renown
would be intertwined,'' Roberts writes, adding: ``yet in all the
West, no pair of adventurers more different in character than
Carson and Fremont could be found.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the hard work of the campaigns was done by Carson, but
the dreamy one was Fremont. The son-in-law of Thomas Hart Benton, a
Missouri senator, and one of the theorists of continental
expansion, Fremont was a visionary, but a visionary with blind
spots. He pushed and pushed, which is sometimes an advantage in
human affairs, and sometimes he pushed too far, which is seldom an
advantage in snowy mountains, particularly those buried in snow
drifts reaching 40 feet. He was known as the conqueror of
Cali but throughout his expeditions he was nearly conquered
by the elements. He defied his enemies, the law, civil authorities
_ and, particularly in his drive to cross the Sierra Nevada in
midwinter, good sense. His expedition suffered such cold and
privation that the horses, not content with eating the pack
saddles, began to munch on one another's tails.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont was self-centered, he was vain, he was single-minded.
All of these were on full display in all of his missions, in none
more so than the expedition that led to the Bear Flag Revolt, the
declaration of the California Republic, his eagerness to describe
himself as ``Military Commander of US Forces in California,'' and
his court-martial. On horseback, in his memoirs, in the imagination
of the American people, and most of all in his own mind, he was a
giant. On the ground, he was human _ and flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Roberts's commentary about Fremont and the revolt in
California: ``Thus, as he began to grasp the opportunity of a
lifetime, Fremont allowed the grandiose self-importance that lay
always just beneath his surface to emerge. If the man had a tragic
flaw, this was it. Now he rode at the head of his battalion
surrounded by a personal body-guard of five fierce-looking Delaware
Indians; sometimes he tied green ribbons around his horse's neck
and tail. His dispatches took on an ex cathedra tone.''
</P>
<P>
   There were hardships aplenty in his expeditions (and nothing
makes for better reading iomfort of our own rocking chairs,
here in the 21st century, than accounts of hardship in the 19th).
But Fremont's men often were frost-bitten, often were in danger,
often were watching their mules die, or were slaughtering them
because they thought they might die any minute. (The mules had a
real hard time of it, sometimes eating the ropes and rawhide
lariats that were draped around their long necks.)
</P>
<P>
   In most of this, Fremont played the lead, giving an imperfect
performance, while Carson won credit for best supporting actor.
Roberts points out that Fremont had a ``self-conscious
preoccupation with how everything he did would look in the view of
history, which precluded the kind of thoughtless performance that,
at its purest, defines true heroism.'' He notes, moreover, that
Carson ``had that quality in his very blood.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Fremont was always bidding for history's approval.
Carson merely wanted to wander the West, catch deer, beaver, and
buffalo, and scoot home to visit his wife. He knew how to survive
four days in the desert without water. He knew his way around the
woods. His genius was in knowing how the West could be won.
Fremont's was in insisting that this was the time to win it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David M. Shribman is the Globe's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
