<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CRADLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBBINS ROCKS THEATER HISTORY IN `CRADLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000   The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What may be one of the greatest moments in American
theater history is also one of the least-known moments in American
theater history.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a theater major in college, Tim Robbins knew
nothing about how members of the Federal Theater Project defied
efforts by the US House of Representatives' Special Committee on
Un-American Activities  &UR; t &LR; o derail a production of Marc
Blitzstein's politically charged musical ``The Cradle Will Rock''
in the &UR;  &LR; 1930s. Though the play was directed by a then-22-year-old
Orson Welles and marked the beginning of congressional
investigations into anti-Communist activities, this chapter somehow
found itself consi history's shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I studied theater in college, and it wasn't covered,'' Robbins
said. ``Years later, someone told me the story, and approached me
about doing a movie about it. I immediately thought this was a
story screaming to be told, and I started doing research about this
incredible American achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The result of Robbins's research is the just-released ``Cradle
Will Rock,'' which strongly parallels today's ongoing battles over
artistic freedom, political opportunism, and government meddling.
The film blends real events and people such as Nelson Rockefeller,
Welles, John Houseman, and Diego Rivera with fictional characters.
The ensemble cast includes Hank Azaria, Susan Sarandon, John
Cusack, Joan Cusack, Vanessa Redgrave, John Turturro, Cherry Jones,
Emily Watson, Bill Murray, and Ruben Blades.
</P>
<P>
   On a Saturday morning in October, Robbins, a boyish 41-year-old
with a skullcap of salt-and-pepper hair, draped his impossibly long
frame over a club chair in a midtown Manhattan hotel suite. He's
itchy for a cup of coffee, and is still tender after the ouster of
his beloved New York Mets in game six of the National League
Championship Series by the hated Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   He's eager to talk about his film, his first directorial effort
since 1995's ``Dead Man Walking,'' which earned him an Academy
Award nomination. But first he's got to work out those
brokenhearted baseball blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a Vancouver hotel room for Game Six. I had my bags
packed, and a ticket for Game Seven in Atlanta,'' he said. ``I was
going. I was going.''
</P>
<P>
   That Robbins can hold the Mets so dear in a city loopy for
Yankee pinstripes _ especially on this, the day after a ticker-tape
parade for the Yankees' second consecutive World Series
championship _ says much about his affinity for underdogs. That
proclivity, and his opposition to government interference in the
creation and distribution of art, fueled his desire to make
``Cradle Will Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a politician, regardless of the era, who's
going to use the one piece of art they find that is controversial
for their own political gain,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of this interview, New York was all in a twist over
a Brooklyn Museum of Art exhibit of a Virgin Mary painting
incorporating elephant dung and snippets from pornographic photos.
The artwork incurred the wrath of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who went to great but ultimately unsuccessful lengths to shut the
exhibit _ and the museum _ down.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani ``got the press he wanted. He wound up alienating more
people than he thought, but he got his core voters. It's coldly
calculated politics,'' Robbins said. ``He's in that tradition of
politicians who use art for political gain, and in doing so,
compromise the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   To Robbins, Giuliani is no different from Committee Chairman
Martin Dies Jr., a Texas Democrat who believed the Federal Theater
was a hotbed of radical thought, and its plays little more than
Communist propaganda. A division of the New Deal's Works Progress
Administration, the Federal provided work for artists and
technicians, and offered inexpensive theater to a Depression-weary
public.
</P>
<P>
   During his research, Robbins was especially impressed with the
theater's director, Hallie Flanagan, played in the film by Cherry
Jones. Flanagan was eventually called to testify before the House
committee about the theater's works and members.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was _ wow! _ talk about an inspiring woman. She was so
open to different kinds of theater, and managed this incredibly
ambitious federal program that brought theater to one-quarter of
the population,'' said Robbins, who worked on the film's script for
nearly seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had never seen live theater before, and she wound up
reaching 25 million people with different interpretations of
classics and modern playwrights, but also experimental theater,
political theater, social theater,'' he said. ``The thing I was
most shocked about was that I hadn't heard about her. I wonder if a
man had been the head of it, or if it had been less controversial,
whether it would have been part of the curriculum of the theater
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Azaria, who portrays playwright Blitzstein, said he knew
``nothing, less than nothing'' about this period before reading
Robbins's script, although he, like the filmmaso studied
theater history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think this rather large moment in theater history would
be talked about,'' Azaria said. ``My theory is in that in the
1950s'' _ when redbaiting reached its demagogic height _ ``you
couldn't talk about it, and it probably just got lost in the
shuffle. But it's a fascinating time, and should be talked about.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its political viewpoints and clashing ideas and
ideologies, Robbins resists branding his film as political. He has
nothing against political films _ he wrote and directed a dandy one
in 1992 with his mock documentary, ``Bob Roberts,'' in which he
starred as the title character, a corrupt, folk-singing right-wing
politician. Political films have their place _ but ``Cradle Will
Rock,'' he said, just isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a political movie. `Political movie'
implies for me a whole different thing,'' Robbins said. ``This is
about human beings, passion, and courage _ all the kinds of words
you don't mention in the same sentence as politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sarandon, who plays fascist sympathizer Margherita Sarfatti,
disagreed with her director _ and her longtime companion. Every
film, she said, is a political film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you think `(Saving) Private Ryan' was political? `Private
Ryan' basically tells you if you want to be a guy you now have to
kill at point-blank range, and now you're a hero, and you're OK.
That's a political statement,'' she said. ``I think every film
contributes to your culture. They all give you permission, entitle
you, reinforce stereotypes, tell women what they need to look like,
what happens when you reach a certain age, tell guys what it means
to be a man. That's all political.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your definition of a political film?'' Sarandon asked.
``Every film is a political film, but you just don't notice the
ones that reinforce the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins has no interest in reinforcing the status quo in his
films, especially when he's behind the camera. In three films as a
writer-director, he has skewered the American political system and
its easily duped electorate in ``Bob Roberts''; thoughtfully
examined both sides of the death penalty debate in ``Dead Man
Walking''; and, with ``Cradle Will Rock,'' unearthed a
long-forgotten episode in theater history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmakers are storytellers, and it depends on what kind of
story you want to tell. If you keep wanting to tell the story of
`boy meets girl,' you can do that,'' he said. ``But this story
allows a larger canvas, and it's such a rich, interesting time.
There are many things here which are still issues today.
Ultimately, I find those actors standing up to be inspiring. It
really shows how an individual can have courage, the courage to
exercise your freedom of expression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
