<SLUG> BC-WINONA-RYDER-IN-GIRL-INTERRUPTED-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINONA RYDER'S TRIP TO THE EDGE OF SANITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Winona Ryder with Angelina Jolie in a
scene from ``Girl, Interrupted.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Reality bites again for Winona Ryder.
 &HT;    The petite actress, who's spent most of her career playing
emotionally troubled characters, reaches for the gold ring of angst
in her latest film, ``Girl, Interrupted.''
 &HT;    Opening nationwide on Jan. 14, the film is based on Susanna
Kaysen's best-selling memoir of her two-year stint at a mental
institution in the late 1960s, a story harrowing even by
contemporary standards _ and one which resonated strongly with
Ryder herself.
 &HT;    ``When I read the book I was about 21, and I was just floored,''
the 28-year-old actress says as she settles into a chair at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons hotel. As always, she's polite yet reserved,
and speaks in a voice barely louder than a whisper.
 &HT;    ``I found it to be incredibly captivating,'' she recalls. ``I
hadn't read a character so brutally honest since I'd read Salinger.
It's very rare in literature to find brutal honesty without
self-indulgence, and cut with such humor.
 &HT;    ``It's usually very self-indulgent if it's that honest, almost
nauseatingly so.''
 &HT;    Almost obsessed with Kaysen's saga, Ryder bought the film rights
to the book. As executive producer, she was determined to protect
the material and see to it that director James Mangold, whom Ryder
handpicked after seeing his film ``Heavy'' (1994), could craft a
film in line with their shared vision.
 &HT;    ``Girl, Interrupted'' introduces Kaysen (Ryder) as a depressed
teen who, like many of the young women on her ward at Claymoore
Hospital, is nonetheless anything but insane. During her stay at
the institution Kaysen encounters a variety of people who change
her life, including a beguiling sociopath (Angelina Jolie), an
understanding nurse (Whoopi Goldberg) and the facility's head
psychiatrist (Vanessa Redgrave).
 &HT;    Ryder didn't find it hard to relate to Kaysen. At 19, after
ending her romance with then-beau Johnny Depp and working too hard
for too long, the actress briefly checked herself into an
institution during the filming of ``The House of the Spirits''
(1993).
 &HT;    ``It was actually for five days,'' she says. ``I think anybody
would back me up and say 19 is a tough age for anyone, whether
you're an actress or cramming for exams, and your parents are
driving you crazy and you're breaking up with your first love.
Whatever you're going through, it's a tough year.
 &HT;    ``I was working back-to-back on movies,'' Ryder recalls, ``and I
had a week off from this film, in which I was playing a political
prisoner and doing torture scenes in Portugal. I've always been a
terrible insomniac. I came back, and was so exhausted that I
checked myself into a clinic for sleep deprivation. But it was a
psychiatric ward.''
 &HT;    Ryder reports, however, that she gained nothing from the
experience.
 &HT;    ``It didn't help me at all,'' she says. ``The thing I did get is
that those places really don't help.
 &HT;    ``You don't go to a place where they give you a pill that fixes
you,'' she says bluntly. ``They don't give you a sheet of secret
answers. You can't pay enough money to have a placeu, which
is incredibly upsetting when you think that you can. I thought, `I
have money, and if I pay them enough they're going to have to give
me some sort of cure for just feeling broken and confused and
ultra-too-sensitive for this world.'
 &HT;    ``But it didn't work like that,'' the actress says. ``I left
feeling just the same, pretty much, and just as tired. They really
didn't offer anything, except for group therapy, which was one hour
a day.
 &HT;    ``Then I went back to `House of the Spirits' _ and all of the
torture scenes got cut out! So I went through it for nothing.''
 &HT;    Ultimately, Ryder says, she found that she had to look within
herself to find any sort of healing.
 &HT;    ``It's what Susanna learns in the film, which is that there are
no answers,'' she says. ``When you finally accept that, that it's
OK not to have answers for everything, that it's OK not to be
perfect, that it's OK to be a human being and be confused, that
actually feeling crazy is normal ... ''
 &HT;    She trails off, groping for the right words, and starts again.
 &HT;    ``If you're sitting there and feeling that you understand the
world,'' she says, ``with war and disease and famine and violence
and assassinations, I'd worry about that person who understood all
of those things.
 &HT;    ``So feeling ... ''
 &HT;    A quizzical look crosses Ryder's face. She raises a finger to
her mouth.
 &HT;    `` ... granola in my teeth.''
 &HT;    The actress cracks up for a moment, then resumes her thought.
 &HT;    ``So feeling confused is actually just feeling like a human
being,'' she says. ``And it's important to understand that the only
place you can go to is yourself.''
 &HT;    It's been two years since Ryder's last film, ``Alien
Resurrection'' (1997), but it's unlikely that another hiatus of
comparable length will occur in the foreseeable future.
 &HT;    She's already completed the long-delayed supernatural thriller
``Lost Souls,'' and recently wrapped ``Autumn in New York.'' The
latter film, which she writes off as ``more of a job,'' is a drama
that casts her as a dying young woman who falls in love with
Richard Gere.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of jokes about the fact that Richard is old
enough to be my father,'' says Ryder, who lives in Manhattan,
reportedly with her boyfriend, actor Matt Damon.
 &HT;    Truth be told, she thinks Hollywood's fascination with pairing
older actors and younger actresses is a joke in and of itself.
 &HT;    ``It's really kind of gross,'' she says.
 &HT;    Later this year, Ryder intends to act in two additional
self-produced projects, including ``Roustabout,'' a small-scale
drama about the death of the American circus, and ``The Lambs of
God,'' which she describes as ``a socially conscious fairy tale.''
 &HT;    Ryder has long been regarded by many as the best actress of her
generation, and moviegoers and critics alike have been waiting for
her to find a film that befits her talent. Some might consider
``Girl, Interrupted'' that film, while one of those other personal
projects that she's developing might do the trick.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Ryder insists that she's enjoying herself as
much today as she did back in 1986, when she stepped onto the set
of ``Lucas,'' her big-screen debut.
 &HT;    ``It's weird, but I still feel like a kid in a way,'' she says.
``I still get really excited when I get a job, and I still get
really excited the first day of work. I'm still fascinated by the
camera, and I still love my job.
 &HT;    ``When I stop loving my job, I think that's when I'll stop,''
she adds. ``But I also know it's sort of up to the audience when
they stop liking me and stop going to see my movies.
 &HT;    ``That's when I'll stop, because I won't get hired!''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Girl, Interrupted,'' consult
the official Website at www.girlinterrupted.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
