<SLUG> BC-LUCY-LIU-IN-PLAY-IT-TO-THE-BONE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 `ALLY McBEAL'S' LUCY LIU HEADS FOR THE BIG SCREEN  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax a90-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Lucy Liu with Lolita Davidovich in a
scene from ``Play It to the Bone.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Being an angel can be hell.
 &HT;    Just ask Lucy Liu, who's late for Angels Training Camp.
 &HT;    The same way ``Saving Private Ryan'' (1998) staged a boot camp
for its actors, the new movie version of ``Charlie's Angels'' is
putting Liu, Drew Barrymore and Cameron Diaz through rigorous
training.
 &HT;    Of course, it's not exactly the same training.
 &HT;    Do they practice walking in bikinis? Are they learning to jiggle
like a bowl of Jello? Advanced students, perhaps, are mastering
walking with a slit in your skirt while yelling, ``Freeze,
scumbag!''
 &HT;    Liu laughs.
 &HT;    ``This is very serious business,'' the 31-year-old actress
insists. ``Our angels don't use guns at all. We just use our bodies
and whatever skills we can bring, both physically and mentally.
 &HT;    ``I've learned that patience is a virtue,'' she adds, ``and the
body is definitely breakable. And that I'm not immortal.''
 &HT;    Of course, they're not doing ``Serpico'' here.
 &HT;    ``It should be really fun,'' Liu says, ``which is the point of
it. Hopefully people aren't going to think it's Shakespeare. Drew,
Cameron and I just want to have a great time on the movie _ I think
that's going to show when we start shooting.''
 &HT;    Liu's entire life seems to be spent shooting one film or
television show or another these days _ in fact, she's speaking by
telephone from a courtroom set during a break in the taping of her
hit series, ``Ally McBeal.''
 &HT;    Besides her day job as ``Ally's'' vixen Ling Woo and the
upcoming ``Charlie's Angels,'' she co-stars in Ron Shelton's boxing
movie ``Play It To the Bone,'' opening Jan. 14, and will team with
Jackie Chan for next summer's ``Shanghai Noon.''
 &HT;    ``I haven't seen the light of day in months,'' she says only
half-jokingly. ``My only day off in the last year has been
Christmas.''
 &HT;    Liu didn't even make it to the recent cast screening of ``Play
It to the Bone,'' in which she plays a sultry hitchhiker who gets
picked up by two boxers (Woody Harrelson and Antonio Banderas) on
their way to Las Vegas.
 &HT;    ``From the minute I met Woody, it was just instant chemistry,''
she recalls. ``They basically hired me on the spot.''
 &HT;    Her scenes were shot in Las Vegas, but Liu says she didn't try
her luck at the casinos.
 &HT;    ``I didn't put one chip on the table,'' she says firmly. ``I
have an obsessive-compulsive personality _ if I put one chip down,
I'd be in jail for stealing somebody's car and trying to sell it to
get more money. I didn't even go there.''
 &HT;    Filmgoers may think she's come out of nowhere, but ``Ally
McBeal'' fans discovered Liu long since _ not that they necessarily
love her.
 &HT;    As she herself says, ``I hear from people who say, `The first
time I saw you on ``Ally McBeal,'' I was screaming at my TV set,
``Who is this bitch?'''
 &HT;    These days ``this bitch'' is perhaps a little less bitchy, Liu
adds. Ling is still a sharp-edged lawyer into fetishes, sex games
and tormenting men, but she's gained some depth this season.
 &HT;    ``I think I'm adding a softer element,'' Liu says. ``I want to
bring Ling around, so she's not flat. I don't want to get
pigeonholed as just playing the bitch _ it's boring. You want to
make sure you don't get bored yourself.''
 &HT;    As for ``the knee trick,'' the mysterious sexual technique which
is Ling's stock-in-trade, Liu pleads ignorance.
 &HT;    ``A lot of people come up to me on the street and ask about the
knee thing,'' the actress says. ``I say, `Don't ask me, ask (show
creator) David E. Kelley.' I don't even know what's involved _ all
we do is talk about it.''
 &HT;    Earlier this season, Liu and series star Calista Flockhart were
involved in a much-publicized lesbian kiss, a twist which caught
even Liu by surprise.
 &HT;    ``I opened the script one day,'' she recalls. ``I was reading
and said, `Oh, OK.' I kept reading and said, `That's funny.' Then I
got to the kiss and started screaming, `No way!'
 &HT;    ``That's the beauty of working with David E. Kelley.''
 &HT;    Both women were nervous shooting the scene, the actress admits.
 &HT;    ``We didn't chew a lot of minty gum,'' Liu says, laughing. ``We
were just very professional about it. We didn't talk about it a
lot, either _ we just said to each other, `How do you feel? Are you
OK? Great. Let's go.'''
 &HT;    In the end, Liu says, she enjoyed the episode.
 &HT;    ``The kiss was so simple and real,'' Liu says. ``It wasn't in
any way whoring the idea of two women kissing. It was a really
special moment.''
 &HT;    The show has had a lot of special moments for Liu since she
first auditioned _ for the role of Nellie Porter, which she didn't
get. But Kelley was so intrigued by her audition that he created
Ling specially for her.
 &HT;    ``I was shocked,'' Liu says.
 &HT;    Watching Ling on the prowl, it's hard to believe that, as a
girl, Lucy Alexis Liu had no thought of becoming an actress.
 &HT;    ``I was such a shy kid,'' she says. ``I would disappear into the
background. I had to learn that I could speak out and lightning
wouldn't strike me.''
 &HT;    A native of Queens, N.Y., Liu grew up in a family of serious
thinkers, her mother a biochemist and her father a civil engineer.
She earned a degree in Asian languages and cultures _ to please her
parents, she says _ at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor.
 &HT;    It was there that, on a whim, she auditioned for a college
production of ``Alice in Wonderland.'' She was cast as Alice, and
it changed her life.
 &HT;    ``It was either act or I couldn't do anything at all,'' Liu
says. ``I just couldn't live unless I was able to act _ it's in my
blood.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, her move to Los Angeles was initially unproductive,
leaving her working at a catering company to make ends meet. It was
not until she was cast in a small role in ``Gridlock'd'' (1997)
that her career took off, landing her other roles in ``City of
Industry'' (1997), ``True Crime'' (1998), ``Payback'' (1998) and
``Molly'' (1999).
 &HT;    Along the way came ``Ally McBeal,'' and suddenly Liu was a hot
actress, a fact which she admits isn't entirely gratifying.
 &HT;    ``I actually don't read my fan mail,'' she says. ``I have
somebody else do it for me, because it can get a little bit scary.
I did read the letters in the beginning, and I started to get a bit
paranoid. There were obsessives _ people told me too much about
themselves.
 &HT;    ``I think there is only so much time you have before one of
these people will come after you.''
 &HT;    Single, Liu spends her almost-nonexistent free time on
photography. She is also fluent in Mandarin Chinese, and practices
kali-eskrima-silat, a martial art which revolves around knife- and
stick-fighting.
 &HT;    A bit more sophisticated than you might expect from one of
Charlie's angels, but Ling promises that the film is more than
merely a reprise of the campy 1970s television hit.
 &HT;    ``My angel has her stuff together,'' she says. ``They're all
really intelligent. Each angel knows a lot about technology.
 &HT;    ``I can't really say if I'm more like Farrah Fawcett or Kate
Jackson,'' she adds. ``We're our own people. These are the modern
angels.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
