<SLUG> BC-NORMAN-JEWISON-DIRECTS-THE-HURRICANE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM WARNING: NORMAN JEWISON ON DENZEL WASHINGTON, `HURRICANE'
CARTER AND MAKING MOVIES WITH MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Norman Jewison directing Denzel
Washington in a scene from ``The Hurricane.'') 
 By JEANNE WOLHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Denzel Washington strapped on his boxing gloves, and Norman
Jewison blanched.
 &HT;    The veteran director hadn't realized how much it meant to the
Oscar-winning actor to play former middleweight champion Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter in ``The Hurricane'' until it came time to
film the boxing scenes.
 &HT;    ``Denzel went into the ring with a real boxer _ this guy wasn't
a stunt man, and they were throwing like 82 punches in a minute,''
the director recalls. ``They had to miss each other by just a
millimeter. Suddenly I thought, `What if somebody makes a
miscalculation?'
 &HT;    ``My greatest fear was that Denzel was going to end up with a
broken nose.''
 &HT;    Carter's ring career was cut short when he was wrongfully
convicted of a triple murder and sentenced to three consecutive
life terms in prison. It was more than 20 years before he was
finally freed through the efforts of a group of Canadian social
activists recruited by a young black boy who had read Carter's
story.
 &HT;    By that time, the former boxer had become an icon of racial
injustice in America, the subject of books, protest marches and
even a Bob Dylan song.
 &HT;    ``Denzel cared as much about being Rubin Carter as I've seen an
actor ever care about anything,'' Jewison says. ``Forget about the
money, forget about your agent, forget about your family, Denzel
felt he was destined to play this role. And that's great for a
director. He lost 44 pounds and he was solid muscle _ he'll never
look that good for the rest of his life.''
 &HT;    It was the opposite of what Jewison faced with Cher, who won a
Best Actress Oscar for her performance in his ``Moonstruck''
(1987).
 &HT;    ``She didn't want to play a 40-year-old Italian spinster with no
makeup,'' the director recalls. ``I told her, `You are my first
choice of any actress in the world and, if you don't take this
role, it's going to be the biggest mistake you ever made in your
life.'
 &HT;    ``So she said yes, and during filming she turned to me one day
and said, `Who was your second choice?'''
 &HT;    The Canadian-born Jewison has often been drawn to stories of
outsiders and minorities seeking justice, from ``In the Heat of the
Night'' (1967) to ``And Justice for All'' (1982) and ``A Soldier's
Story'' (1984). Carter's saga fascinated him.
 &HT;    ``I first read an article in Sports Illustrated,'' he recalls.
``Then I read the book Carter wrote in prison, `The Sixteenth
Round' (Viking, 1974). It won him support from everyone from Bob
Dylan, who wrote a song about him, to Muhammad Ali, but it wasn't
enough to get him his freedom. I thought, `This is a person who is
worth making a film about, because he never gave up _ he was able
to look at the concrete walls surrounding him and see beyond the
walls.'
 &HT;    ``It wasn't until after I'd made up my mind to do the film that
I actually met Rubin Carter,'' he adds. ``I found him totally
charismatic. He's incredible. I know Denzel had the same feeling
about him that I did. We both wished we could have found a part for
him, because he's that amazing _ not bitter or angry, in spite of
what he's been through.
 &HT;    ``As it was, he came to the set a few times and gave us all the
support he could.''
 &HT;    Washington and Jewison had first worked together on ``A
Soldier's Story,'' adapted from a play in which Washington had
earned an Obie Award. They had nearly reunited for ``Malcolm X''
(1992) _ Jewison had worked on the project for years before
director Spike Lee, after mounting a campaign insisting that the
film must have an African-American director, gained control of the
movie.
 &HT;    Jewison insists that he's not bitter toward Lee or toward
Washington, who was Oscar-nominated for the role.
 &HT;    ``I knew Denzel was destined to be Malcolm X,'' he says. ``I'm
not hurt, but I was surprised when Spike was making statements that
only a black artist could understand the black psyche. That's doing
a great disservice to art _ it's the kind of thing you might expect
a politician to say.''
 &HT;    Jewison had originally planned to make ``The Hurricane'' as a
television miniseries, he says, because of the epic scope of the
story.
 &HT;    ``Rubin's fight to regain his freedom spans decades,'' he
explains. ``It includes not only his own book but `Lazarus and the
Hurricane' (Viking, 1991), which focuses on the role of the young
black boy, Lesra Martin, who got his guardians involved.''
 &HT;    Eventually, Jewison chose to concentrate on Carter's
relationship with Lesra, who read ``The Sixteenth Round'' and began
to correspond with the ex-champion in prison.
 &HT;    ``I did have to leave a lot out,'' he admits. ``I'm certainly
not a fan of long movies, and I think too many are being made. The
one horror I have is boring the audience.
 &HT;    ``But I cut `Hurricane' from three hours and 10 minutes to a
little under two-and-a-half hours,'' he says. ``I couldn't make it
any shorter without sacrificing my artistic integrity.''
 &HT;    And, no, Jewison doesn't shy away from admitting that this is a
film with a message.
 &HT;    ``I'd like to think it's entertaining,'' he says. ``But I think
it's a reminder that, in a country that stands so strongly for
freedom, there's still a lot of racism. That is a fact. I think we
need to deal with it.
 &HT;    ``I think the time is right for that kind of message,'' he adds.
``When I did `In the Heat of the Night' , even though it was
at the height of the civil-rights movement, I didn't think anyone
would come to see it. Bobby Kennedy said to me, `This will be an
important film because the timing is right, Norman.'
 &HT;    ``I hope Bobby would have said the same thing about
`Hurricane,''' Jewish says. ``As we approach the millennium, it
isn't too bad to consider what Carter learned _ `Hate got me in
here, b can bust me out.'''
 &HT;    At 73, Jewison looks back on a career that has included four
Oscar nominations as Best Director _ he has never won, though he
received the prestigious Irving Thalberg Award at last year's
Academy Awards _ and finds perspective in the words of another
distinguished director.
 &HT;    ``The last time I saw the late John Huston, he was sitting on a
terrace looking out at the Pacific Ocean,'' he recalls. ``He had an
oxygen tank on his back because he had emphysema and, nevertheless,
he was smoking a cigar. I was terrified, because I thought he was
going to blow himself up.
 &HT;    ``He had just finished directing `The Dead,''' Jewison says,
``and I asked him what it was like. He took a sip of Cristal and
said, `Norman, it was just as tough to make as the first picture I
ever made.'''
 &HT;    Jewison pauses.
 &HT;    ``John's words were a reminder to me that you always have to
fight hard for the stories you want to tell,'' he says with a wry
smile. ``As you get older, there's just more at stake _ you're
starting to run out of time. But I'm proud of `Hurricane.' It took
eight or 10 years to get it to the screen, but it was worth it.
 &HT;    ``We all live by work and love,'' he concludes. ``And if you
don't love your work, life can be a little difficult.
 &HT;    ``I may be older, but I'm not cynical, not yet.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
