<HEADER>
A5345 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-AT-     01-03 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-AT-NYPD-BLUE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO `BLUE' VELVET: LIFE IS NEVER SMOOTH ON `NYPD BLUE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Dennis Franz, Rick Schroder and Gordon
Clapp in a scene from ``NYPD Blue.'') 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before Jan. 9, 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some days, it seems that Det. Andy Sipowicz is the most put-upon
person since the Book of Job.
</P>
<P>
   In that tale, you'll recall, God took away Job's family, his
health and all his material possessions, turning the poor fellow
into an icon of human suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 2,800 years and into the fictional world of ``NYPD
Blue,'' and you have Sipowicz (Dennis Franz), an Everyman living
his life cursed with alcoholism and illness, beset by his own
racism and inner turmoil, damaged by the deaths of a partner, his
wife and an estranged son. It often seemed as if life couldn't get
any worse.
</P>
<P>
   Then came last fall, when he almost lost his home.
</P>
<P>
   Not his real home, of course _ his home in our homes, the
television network where he had spent the last six years, the
channel from which he had been coming into our lives on a weekly
basis.
</P>
<P>
   In October, ABC delayed Sipowicz's return to the air when it
decided to use the 10 p.m. Tuesday slot usually occupied by ``NYPD
Blue'' to help boost its new drama ``Once and Again.'' The
long-running hit was elbowed aside, amid talk of a shift to ...
well, to some other night.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC hadn't counted on the response of the show's creator,
Steven Bochco, a veteran of shows such as ``Murder One'' and ``Hill
Street Blues.'' Exhibiting bulldog tendencies worthy of Sipowicz
himself, Bochco upped the ante, threatening to pull the show from
ABC and decamp to another network _ with NBC executives promising
to air the show Tuesdays at 10 if Bochco brought it their way.
</P>
<P>
   He was in a position to play hardball, though. Bolstered by a
unique blend of police procedural and personal drama, ``NYPD Blue''
consistently lands in the top 20 of the Nielsen ratings. In six
years on the air, it has won more than a dozen Emmys, including
three for Franz. Predictably, when the skirmishing was leaked to
the press, the show's fans reacted with outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is a od story, so there's a happy ending:
Starting Jan. 11, ``NYPD Blue'' will return to its usual time slot.
Furthermore, the network will run all 22 new episodes straight
through to May, without the usual frustrating pause for midseason
reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the controversy grabbed headlines and, as Franz
says, ``Controversy certainly is not detrimental to any show.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor is speaking on location, standing at the side of a
grimy street in the eastern-Manhattan neighborhood known as
Alphabet City, where the new season is in its first week of
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Law &AMP; Order'' or ``Spin City,'' New York-based shows
which are actually shot in the city, ``NYPD Blue'' is largely shot
in Los Angeles. But the show always kicks off a new season with a
week of outdoor location shooting in New York, which helps connect
the cast, crew and writers with the heat of the city's streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to start off that way, because you have the whole
energy of New York,'' says Kim Delaney, now entering her fifth
season as Det. Diane Russell. ``The cast hasn't seen each other for
a few months, so it's like going back to school, seeing everybody.
And we're in the same hotel here, as opposed to when we work in
L.A., where everybody goes home after work. You get connected to
each other faster like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After six years, Franz's identity is forever bound to that of
Sipowicz. Yet, along with head writer/co-executive producer David
Milch, Franz continues to find new angles on the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if Shakespeare had written about somebody, and had
been able to tell 125 or 130 stories about that person,'' the actor
says, referring to the number of existing ``NYPD Blue'' episodes.
``You really have a long time to completely investigate the
complexities of what makes up that person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writers have a fascination with the Sipowicz character and
continue to explore him in such a great depth,'' Franz adds. ``For
an actor, that is a rare opportunity, to get to the dark, sad and
tragic places that he sometimes goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's wearing his character's unfashionable wardrobe,
Franz seems nothing like Sipowicz. He looks smaller, more gentle _
especially since a substantial offseason weight loss. His eyes are
inquisitive and owlish, rather than fearful, deep-set and pinched,
as they appear on screen. Franz is a man at ease, in short, a world
away from the fitful Sipowicz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is an inspiration,'' says Rick Schroder, who joined
``NYPD Blue'' last season as Det. Danny Sorenson. ``Our show makes
demands that other shows don't _ we have rewrites at the last
minute, there are things that would drive most people batty. But
Dennis excels in that environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson became Sipowicz's partner last year, replacing Det.
Bobby Simone (Jimmy Smits) after the character died. A year later
Delaney, whose character was married to Simone, still hasn't
entirely adjusted to the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was tough,'' she says. ``I still think it feels
different. It's like having a new child or something, and bringing
that into the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Even wearing a police uniform, Delaney radiates a coy sex
appeal, underlined by her gently tousled hair. It makes her a
favorite of real cops here, some of whom are guarding the set from
passersby. She makes being a member of the force seem sexy, edgy
but alluring. And, like the rest of the cops on the show, Russell
seems a real, imperfect human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``These characters are all written with such complexities and
demons,'' Delaney says. ``There's so much underneath whatever we're
saying. When he writes something, David Milch will talk to me and
give me, you know, 10 things to think about that aren't even on the
page, things that Russell might feel in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the show is that it manages to balance those
personal stories with compelling tales about police work. Bill
Clark, a retired New York cop who serves as co-executive producer,
prides himself on getting all the details right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay by the rules that detectives have to live with,'' he
sniffs, ``not the Hollywood rules.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, for example, that Sipowicz can't get a search
warrant simply because it's convenient to the plot _ he must have
legally defined probable cause.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the show's distinguishing feature remains the personal
approach it takes to the detectives on the beat, and its
examination of their troubled lives. And Milch has no intention of
going any easier on his troubled leading man.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the third season, a priest said to Sipowicz, `Don't give up
on God, he may not be done with you yet,''' Milch says. ``I don't
intend to lay off. I don't think God is done with Sipowicz.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``NYPD Blue,'' consult the
official Website at www.nypdblue.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
