<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FAMILY (Moscow) _ When Boris Yeltsin picked Vladimir
Putin as prime minister in August, most saw the hand of an
influential group known as ``the Family.'' Now that he's president,
what does Putin do with the Family now? By Brian Whitmore. 1050
words.
</P>
<P>
   ICELAND-GENETICS (Rekyavik, Iceland) _ Iceland has become the
scene of a classic confrontation between science and moralists as
the world's most ambitious and controversial genetic research
project gets under way. By Colin Nickeson. 1640 words. (i and f
coding)
</P>
<P>
   HOLYLAND-MILLENNIUM (Jerusalem) _ Millennial coverage in the
secular media has focused on Y2K computer bugs, terrorism warnings
and the dangers of flying. But there has been little attention to
2,000 years of the Christian faith, which is what it's all about.
By Charles Sennott. 1570 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
