<HEADER>
A5448 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      01-03 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SAFETY: The Odds Against the Weary Driver &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who work night shifts or long hours (or who have more
than one job) are much more likely to be in car accidents caused by
being tired, a new study suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from the Highway Safety Research Center at the
University of North Carolina, said the study was the first of its
kind in which so many drivers involved in accidents had been
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Among its findings:
</P>
<P>
   _Drivers who had been in fatigue-related accidents were more
than four times as likely to work at night as members of a control
group of drivers who had had accidents not tied to fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   _Twenty-seven percent worked 60 or more hours a week (compared
with 17 percent in the control group), and those in accidents were
almost twice as likely to work more than one job.
</P>
<P>
   _Sleeping less than six hours a night, being awake more than 20
hours or driving from midnight to 6 a.m. were all associated with
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The safety center interviewed 1,403 North Carolina drivers who
had been in crashes, including 467 in which fatigue or falling
asleep had been blamed.
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers acknowledged that many people could do
little to change factors like working at night, they said they
wanted drivers to know how important it was not to drive when they
were tired. They even suggested roadside naps in extreme
situations.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that anyone who was chronically sleep-deprived
was at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could well happen to you,'' said Donald W. Reinfurt, the
deputy director of the highway center. ``When you think you're
doing fine, but you know you're beginning to get drowsy, don't push
it. It's not worth it because you're much more like to be in a
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TREATMENTS: For Hypertension, an Eye on Vitamin C &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The ever-versatile vitamin C may be put to new use.
</P>
<P>
   A daily supplement of the vitamin may help people who suffer
moderately high blood pressure, scientists from Boston University
and the Linus Pauling Institute at Oregon State University reported
recently in The Lancet, a medical journal.
</P>
<P>
   Pauling, the chemist twice honored with a Nobel Prize (Peace and
Chemistry), became a passionate proponent of vitamin C, an
antioxidant, in the 1970s, suggesting that large doses of it could
ward off diseases like cancer. Many other scientists remain
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that when high blood pressure patients _ 45
people whose pressure was more than 140 over 90 _ were given 500
milligrams a day of vitamin C, mean pressures were reduced an
average of 9 percent. The benefits began about a month after the
vitamin was added to their diets. The researchers said they were
not sure how the process worked, and added that more research
needed to be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a significant finding that may be of
considerable value to patients who have moderately elevated blood
pressure,'' Dr. Balz Frei, the director of the Pauling center, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In previous studies, Frei and other scientists found that taking
vitamin C seemed to help the body's blood vessels remain relaxed,
reducing pain in angina pectoris patients and lowering the risk of
heart attack and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has called on the government to double the
recommended dietary allowance of vitamin C to 120 milligrams a day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEHAVIOR: Seeking an Up Side to Traumatic Stress &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The damaging emotional legacy of traumatic events _ being held
as a prisoner of war, for example _ is well established. But some
researchers at the University of Michigan believe such experiences
may also have a positive side, bringing about deep changes in some
people.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are interested in what they say is the emerging
field of ``post-traumatic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   They define this as ``positive changes in self-perception,
interpersonal relationships and philosophy of life for people who
have undergone significant trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, using money from the Center for Naval Analysis, a
part of the Navy, plan to do a two-year study of Navy and Air Force
veterans who were POWs in Vietnam, comparing their findings with
studies of Vietnam War veterans who were not captured.
</P>
<P>
   Subjects will be sent detailed questionnaires, and the siblings
of some prisoners will also be surveyed to see if their impressions
match those of the former POW's.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope to be able to identify what factors make some
people more predisposed to benefit from trauma. Doing so, they say,
may make repatriating other former prisoners easier and may improve
treatments for people who undergo other types of trauma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PATTERNS: At Doctor's Office, a Cloud of Confusion &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who leaves a doctor's office with a passel of
prescriptions and in a fog of confusion about what is wrong is
likely to be in abundant company.
</P>
<P>
   Patients, in fact, seldom get complete, understandable
information, a new study says. The report, in a recent Journal of
the American Medical Association, examined how well doctors
explained a range of options to patients and how often doctors made
sure the patients understood.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers listened to tapes of patients' appointments with
59 primary care doctors and 65 surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   In only 9 percent of the cases did patients receive what the
researchers considered enough information to make informed
decisions. Simple procedures, like follow-up screenings or lab
tests, elicited the best information, they found, while complex
ones like screening for prostate cancer, elicited the least.
Surprisingly, despite their reputation for being the most
autocratic, surgeons fared better than primary physicians, the
study said. The study provided examples of good and bad ways
doctors could work with patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should check your thyroid level to see if that is
causing your fatigue,'' a doctor says in one positive example.
``Does that seem reasonable?''
</P>
<P>
   The other approach: ``I'd like to check some blood tests. Here's
the slip to take to the lab.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers suggested that growing time pressure on doctors, was
part of the explanation. But whatever the cause, Dr. Michael J.
Barry of Massachusetts General Hospital, in an accompanying
editorial, said the findings presented ``a challenge to the medical
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most physicians would accept the importance of informed
consent to patient management as something more than just medical
necessity,'' Barry wrote. ``If that is the case, we, as physicians,
must do a better job practicing what we preach.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MENTAL HEALTH: A Healthy Move and a Possible Setback &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Smokers who think a history of depression means that they will
have a harder time quitting are wrong, researchers from Rhode
Island have found, but giving up cigarettes will not necessarily
make them any happier.
</P>
<P>
   Their new study runs counter to earlier research that found that
people with depression had more trouble cutting back or quitting
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But the report, which appeared in the November issue of Nicotine
&AMP; Tobacco Research, documented an increase in symptoms of
depression that occurred about a month after the smokers began
trying to quit.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by researchers from Brown University and
Miriam Hospital in Providence, looked at 133 smokers, 41 of whom
had a history of depression.
</P>
<P>
   The smokers were given some self-help publications and
instructions to quit on a specific date, seven days after their
first interview with researchers.
</P>
<P>
   In later examinations, the researchers measured the smokers' and
former smokers' symptoms of nicotine withdrawal and depression, as
well as their success at giving up smoking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
