<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NY     01-03 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSE IS A RUSE IS A RUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 9)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's nothing but a  &UR; ploy &LR; ,'' said Bill Bradley to Al Gore on
``Meet the Press'' last month.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were locked in TV combat. Gore had just suggested
that the twoDemocratic candidates pledge to shun TV commercials
and engage only in debates. The vice president dramatically
extended his hand and said: ``I'm ready to agree right now. Debates
aren't  &UR; ploys &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley looked at his opponent's hand like an uninterested palm
reader; he wasn't having any part of the surprise offer: ``No, to
come here, shake my hand _ that's nothing but a  &UR; ploy &LR; .'' At Gore's
repeated usage of the word, Bradley edged it with increasing scorn,
adding, ``I'm not someone who's interested in  &UR; tactics &LR; , Al.''
</P>
<P>
   Across America, the question arose: Was the no-commercials
proposal a sincere suggestion, as Gore maintained, or was it merely
a  &UR; ploy &LR; ,  &UR; tactic &LR; ,  &UR; ruse &LR; ,  &UR; stratagem &LR;  or  &UR; trick &LR; , as Bradley
insisted? Around the world, viewers asked a more fundamental
question: What is a  &UR; ploy &LR; , anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The attack word is closely associated with the current campaign.
Two months ago, Cragg Hines of The Houston Chronicle wrote that
``Gore has repeatedly tried the weekly debate  &UR; ploy &LR;  against
Bradley, who has refused to take the bait.''
</P>
<P>
   A month before that, when Gore relocated his headquarters to
Nashville, Tenn. _ the better to detach from Washington Beltway
associations and re-establish middle-American roots _ Tex Austin, a
musician and cowboy-boot salesman, was quoted deriding the move in
The Chicago Tribune: ``This is obviously just a political  &UR; ploy &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   This drew an observation from James Dao, a New York Times
reporter: ``History may someday show that voters viewed Gore's
headquarters shift as a disingenuous  &UR; ploy &LR;  or, more likely, a move
that was forgotten the day after it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The word's origin is shrouded in mysterious Highland vapors.
Most etymologists believe it to be the product of aphesis, the
process by which we clip unaccented vowel syllables off a word's
stem. That is how  &UR; alone &LR;  becomes  &UR; lone &LR;  and  &UR; around &LR;  becomes
 &UR; round &LR; . (``Is the Lone Ranger round here, Tonto?'')
</P>
<P>
   In this hypothesis regarding the origin of  &UR; ploy &LR; , the Scottish
dialect clipped the  &UR; em &LR;  off the verb  &UR; employ &LR;  to create a noun
that meant ``activity'' and later ``an amusing way to pass the
time; an escapade, hobby or sport.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Stephen Potter, the British author of ``Gamesmanship''
and ``Lifemanship'' and the coiner of  &UR; one-upmanship &LR; , gave the
word a tongue-in-cheek sense of ``a maneuver to gain the better of
an opponent or co-worker.'' He wrote, ``Each one of us can, by
 &UR; ploy &LR;  or  &UR; gambit &LR; , most naturally gain the advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the following decade, the Potter sense of the word was
snatched up into the language of diplomacy. An occasional plot
device in the 19th century novels of Anthony Trollope involved the
misheard proposal or the misread caress. A man would say or do
something innocuous; a Victorian maiden would interpret that word
or gesture romantically and accept what she considered amounted to
a proposal of marriage; and the poor (or lucky) fellow found
himself affianced.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Rufford makes such a gesture to the husband-hunting
Arabella Trefoil in Trollope's 1875 ``American Senator'' and finds
himself in the center of Trefoil's formidable attempt at landing a
proper mate. (Her attempt does not succeed.) Trollope uses the same
 &UR; ploy &LR;  four years later in ``John Caldigate,'' in which John gets
thrown into a linen closet with his cousin Julia and comes out, ins and her mother's minds, engaged.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cuban missile crisis of 1962, President Kennedy
received two messages from the Soviet Union's Nikita Khrushchev:
One was informal and ambiguous, a later one more official and
threatening. He chose to ignore the later one and to interpret the
earlier one as an offer to remove Soviet missiles in return for a
pledge not to invade Cuba _ an inference that left Khrushchev with
his nonoffer ``accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   This deft maneuver was described in what some felt was the myth
making that followed as ``the Trollope  &UR; ploy &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   In current usage, a  &UR; ploy &LR;  is more cunning than a  &UR; subterfuge &LR; ,
not as overtly false or bookishly old-fashioned as a  &UR; ruse &LR;  and
somewhat more creative than a  &UR; tactic &LR; . It is not planned in as
much detail as a  &UR; stratagem &LR; , is less contrived than an  &UR; artifice &LR; 
and does not have the coquettish quality of a  &UR; wile &LR; . A  &UR; ploy &LR;  is
more underhanded than a  &UR; maneuver &LR;  and not as playful or artful as
a  &UR; dodge &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Another synonym is  &UR; gambit &LR; , which began as an opening move in
chess that sacrifices a pawn to gain position for a more powerful
piece. By metaphoric extension, a  &UR; gambit &LR;  can range from an
enticing opening in conversation to a  &UR; tactic &LR;  in gaining advantage
in business.
</P>
<P>
   In the lexicon of trickery, a correct gamesman uses a  &UR; gambit &LR; 
while an engaging rogue employs a  &UR; ploy &LR; , and the mildest deceiver
trots out a  &UR; gimmick &LR; . When Bill Bradley's spokesman, Eric Hauser,
followed up his candidate's  &UR; ploy &LR;  characterization by castigating
Gore for ``resorting to contrived  &UR; gimmicks &LR; ,'' his use of
 &UR; contrived &LR;  was redundant.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, as we see, a  &UR; ploy &LR;  is double-edged; accusations of
trickiness can get tricky. In dealing with nationalities, Winston
Churchill observed in 1906: ``Nothing is more fatal than a  &UR; dodge &LR; .
Wrongs will be forgiven, sufferings and losses will be forgiven or
forgotten, battles will be remembered only as they recall the
martial virtues of the combatants; but anything like a  &UR; trick &LR;  will
always rankle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1603EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-ROMANO-BOS &LR;      01-03 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-ROMANO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN ROMANO, 45; GLOBE ASST. SPORTS EDITOR BATTLED CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robin Romano, an assistant sports editor at the Boston
Globe known for inspiring colleagues and friends with her passion
for sports, her flair for journalism and her penchant for off-key
crooning, died of cancer Monday at her home in Marblehead. She was
45.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Romano was born in Marblehead and graduated in 1972 from
Marblehead High, where she served as captain of the softball,
basketball and soccer squads, was top player on the golf team, and
developed a life-long love of athletics. She attended Northeastern
University on a scholarship, playing on the softball and basketball
teams and graduating in 1977 with a degree in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first newspaperwomen to cover major sporting events,
Miss Romano held writing and editing jobs on most of America's best
newspaper sports sections. She was drawn to sports journalism by
her late father, Anthony, who for 50 years worked as a reporter,
writer and sports editor at the Salem Evening News until he retired
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Romano began her journalism career in 1973 as a co-op
student at the Quincy Patriot Ledger, for which she would cover the
1975 World Series and the '76 NBA playoffs. ``She was just one of
those people you could see instantly would be great. You know the
kind,'' said Fred Turner, who hired Miss Romano in Quincy and now
is the sports editor at the Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel. ``She
walked in and started interviewing for the co-op spot, and I said
to myself, `This one's going to make it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her next job was in 1977 at the Lawrence Eagle-Tribune, where
she covered the Celtics for four years and the Patriots for two,
along with writing a weekly column. In 1981, she moved to the old
Washington Star, where she was a copy editor and wrote part-time.
After the Star folded, she worked as a senior copy editor at the
Atlanta Constitution, then moved to the Dallas Morning News to
supervise layout and oversee a weekly, in-season special section on
the Cowboys, working for one of the most respected names in sports
journalism, Dave Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin Romano's loss is a personal tragedy for me, but also a
major tragedy for the journalism profession,'' Smith said. ``Robin
was a special journalist . . . talented with a solid work ethic and
a love of the profession. Robin had a great sense of values. She
always put God and family first. And she loved people.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Romano was hired as Sunday sports editor at the Orange
County Register in 1984 and a year later was promoted to assistant
sports editor. She was in charge of the paper's special sports
sections, was instrumental in its award-winning coverage of the
1984 Olympics in Los Angeles, and assigned writers to stories. As
much as they remain impressed by her organizational and layout
skills, her California colleagues remember her even more as a
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just very warm and cared about everybody,'' said Mark
Whicker, a sports columnist at the Register since 1987. ``She'd
tease people about things and would like to be teased by others _
especially about the Celtics and golf. Everybody could talk to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing Robin liked most about southern California was its
almost year-round sunshine, which meant more time for golf. ``I
played with and against her a few times,'' Whicker said. ``She'd
swing easy, and it'd go a long way. I do remember she wouldn't
always give you the putt you wanted her to give you.''
</P>
<P>
   That competitive spirit, and the skill to back it up,
characterized Miss Romano's golf game anewsroom performance
when she returned to Massachusetts in November 1989 to take an
assistant sports editor's job at the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the process of hiring her, she would always
mention how much she loved trying to beat the larger paper in
southern California, the LA Times,'' said Globe sports editor Don
Skwar. ``But I knew about her competitive nature a few years
earlier when I'd met her for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Dallas at a wedding of a friend who worked at the
Dallas Morning News, and Robin was working there at the time. We
were at a pre-wedding party, and Robin and I started talking about
golf. She mentioned that she golfed, and we talked about getting a
game going the next day. I asked her what her handicap was, and in
the space of about 40 seconds, it grew from a 7 to a 17. She knew
she might be playing against me, so she was greasing the skids. I
knew right then and there that some day, she should be working for
us at the Globe.''
</P>
<P>
   Her editing duties at the Globe included overseeing special
sections on topics ranging from baseball and football to the Boston
Marathon, the Olympics, and the closing of the Garden, and helping
put out the daily and Sunday papers. She was a critical factor in
the more than two dozen national awards the Globe won during her 10
years there and helped make it what sports editors across the
country agree year after year is among America's premier sports
sections.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, however, don't capture the depth of her
contribution. She was a master at bringing together photographers
and designers, writers, editors and layout artists to produce
special sections, series and daily papers. She had an exceptional
eye for laying out a compelling page, an ear for distinguishing
good story ideas, and a sense of how to draw in fans, those who
were avid like her as well as rainy day ones. And she had a special
way with office interns, some of whom composed poems to her in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was her ability to come up with compelling story
ideas the way she did in creating a section commemorating the 100th
Boston Marathon. Recognizing that it was the course itself that
helped distinguish the race, she took readers to each key spot,
from the start in Hopkinton to Heartbreak Hill, letting them see
and feel the route through the words of marathon legends and
seasoned journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Romano also helped report, write, edit and lay out three special
series, all of which grew in part out of her personal experiences
and two of which won national awards. The first was on the way
greyhounds are sometimes mistreated during and after their racing
careers, which she knew about as the owner of a greyhound named
Poppy. The second, called ``Kids and Sports,'' looked at what can
be an excessively competitive world of youth sports that she knew
about through her long sports career and the experiences of her
niece and nephews. The most recent involved medical errors, a topic
she approached even as she was fighting her own colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin was a gifted journalist, but more importantly her
friendliness, her thoughfulness and her smile lifted the spirits of
all of us who worked with her,'' said Globe Editor Matthew V.
Storin. ``The Globe family has sustained an irreparable loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The last story Miss Romano wrote for the Globe was a review last
April of the book, ``Born to Play,'' by baseball player Eric Davis.
Like Miss Romano, Davis was battling colon cancer; and like him,
she inspired friends with the lessons the disease taught her. Miss
Romano wrote that Davis ``chooses not to tell a tale of suffering
and heartbreak but of how _ out of adversity _ one can learn to
appreciate life and set an example for others to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the Globe, Miss Romano collected two women's
championships at Thorny Lea Country Club in Brockton and was a
fixture in the winner's circle at events of the Women's Golf
Association of Massachusetts. While she loved most sports, her
favorites were baseball and basketball, while her passions were the
Red Sox and watching the horses run at Suffolk Downs.
</P>
<P>
   As her sickness limited her stamina, Miss Romano took up walking
and cycling. She also spent even more time with her family. But she
almost never complained, not to her brother, Anthony, and sister,
Ruth of Salem, or to her mother, Myrtle. And especially not to her
doctors and nurses, who became her friends. She liked to sing
publicly, particularly Barbara Streisand tunes, but she never let
on whether she accepted the widely-held view that she could not
hold a note. And when Globe colleagues recently presented her with
their tape of Streisand's ``People,'' she said, ``They were worse
than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last April, when she was undergoing treatment at the Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute, she took 100 sick children from there to a
Celtics game and got Patriots kicker Adam Vinatieri to come along.
And last month, when she was so weak she could barely stand, she
worried about how her family was handling her illness and what she
could do to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed at some of the darkest moments,'' says friend and
colleague Marcia Dick. ``One Friday afternoon after the cancer came
back, her oncologist and her surgeon were battling over whether she
should have more surgery or go back on chemo. Her mother and I were
ashen, but she bolted down a sandwich from Boston Chicken while
discussing the options.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved junk food, but she learned to love broccoli.''
</P>
<P>
   A funeral Mass will be held Saturday at Star of the Sea Parish
in Marblehead, followed by burial at Waterside Cemetery. In lieu of
flowers, expressions of sympathy may be made in her memory to the
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, 1309 Beacon St., Brookline, MA 02115;
Hospice of the North Shore, 10 Elm St., Danvers, MA 01923; and
Greyhound Friends, 167 Saddle Hill Rd., Hopkinton, MA 01748.
</P>
</TEXT>
