<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-JFK-JOURNALIST04-COX     01-03 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFK-JOURNALIST04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DID CIA RANSACK GREEK JOURNALIST'S OFFICE?
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A reporter's interview of a potential political
adversary of the president of the United States touches a sensitive
nerve at the very highest level of the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the FBI gets a call from one of the president's
closest aides and immediately opens an investigation of the
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Intelligence Agency is called to the White House and
ordered to investigate the reporter and his story.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the reporter's office is ransacked _ at the
very moment he is having dinner at the invitation of a high-ranking
U.S. government official.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate?
</P>
<P>
   Try Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Greek journalist Elias P. Demetracopoulos says he
believes his 1961 interview with Adm. Arleigh Burke, then chief of
naval operations, caused the Kennedy White House to resort to
extraordinary and illegal measures against him.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he accuses Kennedy press secretary Pierre Salinger
of initiating investigations of him by the CIA and the FBI. He also
suggests that the CIA ransacked his Athens office while he was
dining with the U.S. ambassador to Greece``I just don't remember anything about that,'' Salinger said in
a telephone interview from Paris. ``I'm sorry, but it's just not
something that's in my brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Demetracopoulos says documents he has obtained from the FBI and
the Central Intelligence Agency support his conclusions.
   In an article in the January issue of ``Proceedings,'' a
magazine of the U.S. Naval Institute at Annapolis, Md., he says his
experience illustrated ``a kind of paranoia'' in the Kennedy White
House, ``... almost the sort of paranoia that was to grip, then
consume, and finally overwhelm the Nixon administration a decade
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Demetracopoulos, now 71, is retired and lives in Washington. In
early 1961, he was political editor of three Greek dailies,
Macedonia, Ethnos and The Athens Daily Post. He also was Athens
correspondent for the North American Newspaper Alliance (NANA). He
came to Washington in January 1961 to cover the inauguration of
President-elect John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Before the inauguration, the Greek journalist interviewed
several U.S. officials, including Burke. Like Kennedy, Burke was a
War War II naval hero.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes called ``Thirty-one-Knot Burke'' because of the high
speed he ran the ships under his command in the Pacific, the
admiral was known for his hard-line views of the Soviet Union. He
died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1961, amid speculation that he had presidential
aspirations, some Republican leaders already were urging him to run
against Kennedy in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   His comments during the Demetracopoulos interview included a
response to threats by Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev to shoot
down any U.S. Sixth Fleet aircraft flying over the Black Sea and to
deny the Navy surface ships access to the the sea. The subject was
important to Greek readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Admiral replied in his usual no-nonsense manner, warning
the Soviet Union that it would come out second best in a nuclear
confrontation with the United States,'' Demetracopoulos writes.
``He asserted the right of U.S. warships to sail in the Black Sea,
despite Soviet objections.''
</P>
<P>
   Demetracopoulos said the interview, in which Burke expressed
other, similar views on the Russians and nuclear war, was taped and
transcribed by the Navy. Pursuant to ground rules for the
interview, the transcript was reviewed by the Navy and a copy
delivered to him, stamped, ``No objection to publication on grounds
of national security.'' The stamp was dated ``JAN 16 1961.''
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, Kennedy was inaugurated, amid concern in some
military circles that his administration would fail to maintain
former President Dwight Eisenhower's vigilance against Soviet
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful of this sentiment, the new president on Feb. 9,
1961, issued an order that top military officers clear all public
statements with the White House and the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Demetracopoulos was back in Athens, transcribing his
interview notes, translating them into Greek and writing stories.
On Feb. 14, his story based on the Burke interview was released
simultaneously to the three Greek dailies and North American papers
subscribing to the NANA news wire. It was widely published the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   In light of what was being called a Kennedy White House ``gag
policy,'' the story carried an editor's note, declaring that the
interview had been conducted and cleared before the policy was
announced, indeed before Kennedy became president.
</P>
<P>
   The story generated a stir, although the president noted during
another press conference _ on the day the story was published _
that the interview had taken place prior to his taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy got a laugh from White House correspondents when he
declared, ``I would say that this makes me happier than ever that
such a directive has gone out.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Demetracopoulos said records he has obtained from the
CIA and FBI show the administration did not drop the matter. The
day after the second press conference, Demetracopoulos writes,
Kennedy's press secretary, Pierre Salinger, summoned CIA officials
to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several lines describing the meeting have been expunged from
the copy of the memo the CIA provided me,'' Demetracopoulos writes.
``Then, at the bottom of the page, the text resumes with this
comment: 'It has not as yet been established definitely whether the
cited interview was a personal one with Admiral Burke or based on
questions submitted to him in writing by (Demetracopoulos). In
addition, there is some doubt as to the exact date of the
interview, which is the crux of the
</P>
<P>
   entire investigation, inasmuch as the establishing of an
interview date prior to or after January 20, 1961, is of prime
importance to President Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Proceedings article refers only to contacts between
the White House and the CIA, Demetracopoulos said in an interview
last month that documents he has obtained from the FBI show that on
Feb. 17, Salinger telephoned J. Edgar Hoover, then director of the
FBI, and initiated an investigation by that agency as well.
</P>
<P>
   Demetracopoulos said that because he was aware that his story
was creating a stir in the United States, he published a follow-up
on Feb. 19, along with a photograph of the Navy stamp at the top of
the interview, showing his conversation with Burke took place on
Jan. 12, too early to have been subject to the Kennedy directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CIA file does not show when or what the CIA reported back
to Salinger,'' he writes. ``The redacted file gives no hint of what
actions the CIA took to try to answer the questions Salinger posed
on behalf of the President. But I believe that the file is related
directly to an experience I had back in Athens.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that shortly after the second article was published, he
was telephoned by the late Ellis O. Briggs, then the U.S.
ambassador to Greece, inviting him to dine privately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Briggs asked that I bring along my stamped copy of the
interview,'' he writes. Instead, Demetracopoulos said he placed the
original copy of the interview in a bank deposit box and brought a
copy to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was having dinner with the ambassador, and the
original copy of the interview reposed safely in a central Athens
bank safety deposit box, my office was burglarized,'' he said. ``No
valuables were removed, but my files were rifled. Could this be
what the CIA was doing for Salinger? The agency certainly knew that
I was at the U.S. Embassy that evening and would not be working at
my office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over decades, my office was never burglarized, except that one
night. A mere coincidence? Possibly. But I think not.''
</P>
<P>
   In a footnote to the article, Demetracopoulos quotes a passage
from the book ``The Dark Side of Camelot,'' by journalist Seymour
Hirsch: ``Demetracopoulos suffered for publishing his interview
with Burke: a State Department notice eventually was sent to all
American embassies in NATO countries cautioning senior officials
against the granting of any interviews to him. He also was
investigated for years by the CIA, at the request of Pierre
Salinger, the White House press secretary.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Naval Institute is a private research and publishing
organization with offices on the campus of the U.S. Naval Academy.
The full text of Demetracopoulos's article can be found at the
institute's Internet site, www.usni.org.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e-mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
