A5467 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-03 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Harnessing Bacteria &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that if World War III were to occur, perhaps
the only thing left alive on the planet would be swarms of
radiation-resistant bacteria. But before those bugs get the run of
the place, at least one team of scientists would like to put them
to work.
</P>
<P>
   A researcher from the Uniformed Services University of the
Health Sciences, with colleagues, has re-engineered the most
radiation-resistant form of bacteria known, with the goal of using
it to clean up the toxic mess left behind at radioactive waste
sites associated with the production of nuclear weapons. Their work
is reported in the journal Nature Biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to containing radioactive elements like uranium,
these sites, of which there are about 1,000 in the United States
alone, are often also contaminated by heavy metals like mercury and
by toluene and other organic solvents. The bacterium, D.
radiodurans, has already been shown to be effective in breaking
down some organic contaminants. The trick was getting it to deal
with heavy metals as well.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers accomplished this by inserting genes from a
strain of E. coli bacteria that can change mercury from an ion (the
form it is most often found in at waste sites) to its elemental
form, which is less toxic. While the scientists acknowledge that
they still have much research to do, they hope that D. radiodurans
can someday play a major role in reducing the costs of nuclear
waste cleanup, now estimated worldwide at $265 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An Icy Finding &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pluto's moon, Charon, orbits the planet so closely that the two
are very difficult to observe separately using Earth-based
telescopes. Even with a large and precise instrument like the Keck
telescope in Hawaii, atmospheric blurring makes it practically
impossible to distinguish planet from moon.
</P>
<P>
   But on one exceptional night in May 1998, astronomers using the
Keck were able to obtain distinct images and spectra of Pluto and
Charon. And Charon's spectrum held some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   While it had previously been known that Charon has water ice,
the spectrum revealed that the ice was in crystalline, not
amorphous, form (meaning the molecules were neatly ordered, not
jumbled together). Crystalline ice is found in the relatively warm
conditions found on moons of Jupiter, Saturn and Uranus. Out around
Pluto, which is far colder because of its distance from the Sun,
the ice would be expected to be amorphous.
</P>
<P>
   The astronomers, who described their findings in the journal
Science, suggest that the ice on Charon probably recondenses in
crystalline form as it is vaporized by the constant bombardment of
tiny meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Versatile Parasite &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One way many species adapt to changing environmental conditions
is by adjusting the sex ratio of their offspring. British and
French researchers have discovered that this holds true even when
the species is the tiny malaria parasite Plasmodium and the
environment is blood.
</P>
<P>
   During their reproductive cycle, Plasmodium parasites produce
both male and female gametocytes, or sex cells. It is these cells
that are picked up along with blood when a mosquito bites an
infected animal or person. The gametocytes then produce male and
female gametes, and fertilization occurs, eventually producing new
parasites that are passed on when the insect bites again.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who studied Plasmodium in birds and mice, found
that in response to the infection, the animals' immune systems
produce more of a hormone that promotes the production of blood
cells. More blood cells make conditions more crowded for the male
gametes _ it's harder for them to get around and fertilize females.
The parasite's response is simple: it produces more male
gametocytes so that there will be more male gametes around in the
harsher conditions, thus increasing the chances for fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who reported on their studies in Science, note
that the anti-malaria drug chloroquine inhibits the production of
the hormone, so it may be influencing the gametocyte sex ratio and
how efficiently the disease is transmitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
