<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5476 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DAS-VADANYA-YELTSIN-7     01-03 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAS-VADANYA-YELTSIN-750&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOUT TIME, BORIS: YELTSIN GOES _ AND NONE TOO SOON  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This pithy 900-word (trimmed) ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO EDITOR-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 450 WORDS _ AT
750 (150 WORDS) AND 975 (300 WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,350 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PHIL REEVES  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end it was a merciful relief. Every extra day that Boris
Yeltsin's courtiers dusted him off, dosed him up and sent him
tottering into the public eye had become a personal humiliation and
a national embarrassment. It was amazing he lasted so long.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years in office, the Russian president leaves the
Kremlin but a husk of the man who did more than any other to bring
about the collapse of the Soviet Union and, with it, the threat of
a return to a new arms race, Cold War, repression, suspicion and
fear.
</P>
<P>
   The sparkling figure who leapt onto the turret of a tank during
the farcical 1991 coup attempt against President Mikhail Gorbachev
was long ago displaced by a fitful and muddled invalid who seemed
in permanent danger of making a fool of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Autocratic though he remained to the end, it became hard to
imagine that this was the same man who, faced with a rebellious
legislature that had appointed someone else in his place, ordered
tanks to shell parliament in 1993, brutally reasserting his own and
the Kremlin's authority, at the cost of several hundred lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the robust contours of Yeltsin the Democrat and
Yeltsin the Autocrat collapsed into the blurred and wobbly lines of
a bewildered and erratic old man.
</P>
<P>
   In his later years satirists portrayed him as King Lear.
</P>
<P>
   You could see their point. He had become a remote and unloved
figure, shielded from the outside world by a tight group of aides,
and his family _ notably his younger daughter and adviser, Tatyana,
and his wife, Naina.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the so-called ``family'' became no less plausible
than Yeltsin himself, their public standing became corroded by
allegations of corruption and rumors that they had stashed away
personal fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Russians became increasingly uncomfortable with their leader,
and seemed pathetically happy to attach their affections to almost
anyone else who took control of the nation's helm as premier _
Sergei Kiriyenko, Yevgeny Primakov, Sergei Stepashin, and finally
the Yeltsin protege Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the president set foot abroad, the public winced with
embarrassment. They will long recall his tipsy attempts to conduct
an orchestra in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did they enjoy the sight of him stumbling in public, or
taking 25 seconds just to sign his name.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he was not to blame. His most famous foreign gaffe _
his non-appearance from the presidential aircraft at Shannon
airport in 1994 was probably the result of illness.
</P>
<P>
   And no one will ever know whether the night, in 1987, when he
ended up getting drenched in the Moscow River was _ as Alexander
Korzhakov, his former bodyguard, alleges _ an attempt at suicide,
or the result of drunkenness, or (as Yeltsin has hinted) the work
of the KGB.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as history assesses the career of this contradictory
and capricious Siberian, he will be granted real credit, and
deservedly so. Russians of the late twentieth century can speak,
worship and travel more or less freely.
</P>
<P>
   With the shameful exception of the Chechen war, cynically
reignited anew by his protege Vladimir Putin, their leader never
resorted to the repressive and dictatorial solutions _ the prison
camps, purges, tireless snooping and daily harassment _ of his
Soviet predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kremlits wealthy allies increasingly
controlled access to the media _ particularly at election time _
his enemies were usually allowed to carp, and many have done so
loudly.
</P>
<P>
   History will surely also relate that Yeltsin should have done
more to contain human-rights abuses, which are rampant, especially
within the vastly corrupt police and courts. And yet it is doubtful
whether any Russian president, in the post-Soviet maelstrom, could
have exerted control over a country so vast.
</P>
<P>
   To do so certainly required a longer concentration span than he
could ever muster. Yeltsin's spells of intense work _ he rose at 5
a.m. daily during the 1996 election campaign _ combined fatally
with periods of detachment, exhaustion and boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Illness did not help. Even before his second term began _
between the two rounds of the July election _ he was stricken by a
heart attack. A quintuple coronary bypass was not enough to put him
back on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Double pneumonia, laryngitis, bronchitis, and colds ensured that
he was, at best, a part-time president.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition to him remain muted because the majority of
Russians were divided over the alternatives, or driven to apathy,
overwhelmed by the struggle to survive. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Communists could never muster the necessary political
consensus to challenge him. It often seemed that their leaders did
not, at heart, even want to. Their demise will be seen by history
as one of Yeltsin's biggest achievements.
</P>
<P>
   The West will also praise Boris Yeltsin for securing the rise of
the centrist parties in the State Duma, which is no longer under
Communist control. This is, in western thinking, a good thing as it
means parliament should work with the Kremlin, which is supposedly
good for ``reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a country as crony-riddled and corrupt as Russia, where
the rot reaches into the Kremlin itself, this comfortable
arrangement is scarcely cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The centrists are, in fact, mostly the same old apparatchiks
that have hovered around the corridors of power for last eight
years. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   None of this diminishes the fact that Friday saw one of the
world's great politicians bowing out of the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   He was, in his own way, a maestro, an impoverished laborer's son
turned builder from Sverdlovsk who became Russia's first elected
post-Soviet leader. He was a maverick and natural leader from the
outset. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 300 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 975) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world may never know for certain whether the young Yeltsin
really did blow off two fingers of his left hand with a grenade, or
_ typhoid stricken _ rescued his school friends after an expedition
into the taiga, or gambled on his life with criminals on train
tops, or was nearly drowned in his baptismal font by a drunk
priest.
</P>
<P>
   These sound like inventions; he was always prone to boastfulness
and exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   There was times when he had good cause to brag. By 45, he was
the region's first secretary of the Communist Party, the most
powerful man in Sverdlovsk, the third most important industrial
province in the entire USSR.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985 _ at 54 _ he was running Moscow, brought to the capital
by his future enemy and rival, Gorbachev. But discomfort with
Gorbachev developed into full-blown conflict which nearly cost
Yeltsin his political career.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1987, at a plenum of the Central Committee, he
attacked the Soviet leader for the ``culture of adulation,''
announced that ``perestroika'' was going nowhere, and asked to be
allowed to resign from the Politburo. Instead, he was
unceremoniously sacked.
</P>
<P>
   His humiliation won him vital public support, and was a major
turning point for himself and the country.
</P>
<P>
   By June 1991, he was elected president of Russia, a newly
created job under the Soviet umbrella. Six months later, in the
aftermath of the failed August coup, the USSR finally ceased to
exist, and (though it rose again) the Communist Party was banned.
And he was left in charge of its largest component part.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge was clearly sweet. His nemesis, Gorbachev, claims
Yeltsin threw him out of his Kremlin office three days earlier than
agreed, and held a breakfast-time whisky-drinking party in it with
his aides. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,350) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He remained spectacularly capable of surprising his critics to
the end.
</P>
<P>
   No one could have guessed that he would return to fight in
Chechnya, having called the first war his greatest mistake. But, in
hindsight, his arrogance, his determination always to prove the
world wrong, overrode judgment and decency.
</P>
<P>
   Had his political opponents been tougher and less cozy with the
ruling elite, and had ordinary Russians been less world-weary and
more willing to rise up and challenge their masters, he would
probably have left the Kremlin years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at last, he has given his power away. A new era can begin. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
