<P>
   There was times when he had good cause to brag. By 45, he was
the region's first secretary of the Communist Party, the most
powerful man in Sverdlovsk, the third most important industrial
province in the entire USSR.
</P>
<P>
   By 1985 _ at 54 _ he was running Moscow, brought to the capital
by his future enemy and rival, Gorbachev. But discomfort with
Gorbachev developed into full-blown conflict which nearly cost
Yeltsin his political career.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1987, at a plenum of the Central Committee, he
attacked the Soviet leader for the ``culture of adulation,''
announced that ``perestroika'' was going nowhere, and asked to be
allowed to resign from the Politburo. Instead, he was
unceremoniously sacked.
</P>
<P>
   His humiliation won him vblic support, and was a major
turning point for himself and the country.
</P>
<P>
   By June 1991, he was elected president of Russia, a newly
created job under the Soviet umbrella. Six months later, in the
aftermath of the failed August coup, the USSR finally ceased to
exist, and (though it rose again) the Communist Party was banned.
And he was left in charge of its largest component part.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge was clearly sweet. His nemesis, Gorbachev, claims
Yeltsin threw him out of his Kremlin office three days earlier than
agreed, and held a breakfast-time whisky-drinking party in it with
his aides. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,350) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He remained spectacularly capable of surprising his critics to
the end.
</P>
<P>
   No one could have guessed that he would return to fight in
Chechnya, having called the first war his greatest mistake. But, in
hindsight, his arrogance, his determination always to prove the
world wrong, overrode judgment and decency.
</P>
<P>
   Had his political opponents been tougher and less cozy with the
ruling elite, and had ordinary Russians been less world-weary and
more willing to rise up and challenge their masters, he would
probably have left the Kremlin years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at last, he has given his power away. A new era can begin. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
