<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Damascus) _ President Clinton today launched a
fresh round of negotiations between Israel and Syria, seizing on a
``historic opportunity'' to reach a land-for-peace deal and end 50
years of enmity between the two Miountries. Clinton held a
separate meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and
planned a similar one with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa, before a three-way session anticipated later in the day.
(Summary from wires) By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Acting Russian President Vladimir
Putin began on Monday to put his own imprint on the Kremlin
administration, moving aside several veteran staff members loyal to
retired President Boris Yeltsin and showing the door to his former
boss's daughter, Tatyana Dyachenko. But as one television
commentator said Monday night, the changes amount to a ``freshening
up'' of the presidential administration, and hardly a revolution
inside the Kremlin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ Facing sharp criticism of his
government's decision to negotiate with the hijackers of an Indian
commercial jetliner, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee on Monday
accused Pakistan of being behind the incident and called on major
nations, including the United States, to declare Pakistan a
terrorist state. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FAMILIES (Washington) _ A current Supreme Court case on
whether grandparents, other relatives, and even non-relatives
should be able to gain a court-ordered right to visit with children
over the parents' objection has opened the door not only to an
examination of the stresses besetting the generations, but to a
profound debate over the very definition of family. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum, Iowa) _ Al Gore told 1,000 students in
Iowa that the nation needs a tried-and-true leader, capable of
addressing more than a few national problems. His reference is
clearly to his opponent, Bill Bradley. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY (Dateline to kum, N.H.) _ Playing the anti-Washington
themes that have won New Hampshire primaries for Jimmy Carter,
Ronald Reagan and Pat Buchanan, Bill Bradley on Monday portrayed
Vice President Al Gore as timid and out of touch with the American
people, who, he said, are tired of partisan politics and think that
Washington has nothing to do with their lives. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
