   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-RDP (Undated) _ Year 2000 computer glitches began
multiplying as much of the world headed back to work Monday
following the New Year's holiday, but they remained scattered and,
for the most part, trivial. Nearly all of the reported problems
were fixed within hours of their discovery. The relatively smooth
sailing, especially in foreign nations that had spent far less
money on Year 2000 repairs, led to renewed questions about whether
governments and businesses had squandered money and management
resources after overestimating the scope of the Year 2000
challenge. By Barbaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   DIVMARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Dividends, corporate America
appears to be concluding, are an unnecessary cost of doing
business. Investors do not appear to be interested in getting
dividend payments, so why bother paying them? For the first time in
recent history _ and probably the first time since the Depression _
a quarter of the value of the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks
now comes from companies that do not pay dividends. Two decades
ago, only 2 percent of the value of the index came from such
companies. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTERO-DONATE (Medellin, Colombia) _ Just the mention of this
city immediately conjures up images of drug cartels, guerrillas and
gangs of kidnappers and hired killers. But Medellin is also the
hometown of Fernando Botero, 68, Latin America's most celebrated
living artist, and he is now putting the full weight of his renown
behind a wide-ranging effort to overhaul the city's reputation and
skyline. Over the next few months the painter and sculptor intends
to install 79 of his paintings, drawings and sculptures that he has
just donated to the Museo de Antioquia here. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
