<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 4, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exceptionally mild air will cover the East Coast states again
Tuesday as gusty winds from the southwest precede an approaching
cold front. Some sunshine will occur near the coast in the morning,
but clouds will thicken by afternoon. Farther west, a band of rain
with a few imbedded thunderstorms will accompany the front as it
moves slowly east across the Appalachians. The rain will reach the
Atlantic Seaboard on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the front, colder air will surge from the
northern Plains to the Middle West on strong winds from the
northwest. Scattered rain showers in the eastern part of Great
Lakes and Ohio Valley will change to snow showers late Tuesday. As
the chilly winds blow over the relatively mild water, snow showers
will develop near the southern and eastern shores of the lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will linger in most of the Plains states. Sunshine
will be plentiful in the central and southern sections, but patchy
clouds will mix with the sun across the north. Afternoon
temperatures will remain several degrees below the seasonal average
in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of Pacific fronts will bringwinds,
coastal rain and mountain snow to the Pacific Northwest. Locally
heavy snow will fall in the Cascades and Bitterroots. Some of the
interior valleys will have rain showers early Tuesday that will
change to snow showers as a cold front sweeps across the region.
Farther south, after a cold dawn, the sunshine will boost
temperatures to near seasonal values in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Perihelion
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Earth came within 91,400,005 miles of the sun as it
reached perihelion, the Earth's closest approach to the sun during
the year. In the current era, perihelion occurs during the northern
hemisphere winter, favoring a modest reduction in temperature
extremes. Aphelion, the point where the sun and earth are farthest
apart, occurs in summer, slightly limiting the warming powers of
the sun. However, the earth's orbital parameters are slowly
changing. In 11,000 years, perihelion will occur in summer and
aphelion in winter, accentuating the seasonal temperatures
differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
