<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      01-03 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``TWILIGHT'' &QL; 
By Henry Grunwald (Knopf, $20) &QL; 
Grunwald was vacationing in Italy in 1992 when he went to pour a
glass of later and missed the glass. When he returned to the United
States, his doctor gave him ominous news: He was in the early
stages of macular degeneration, a mysterious condition that affects
some older people and for which there is no cure. ``Macular''
refers to a spot on the retina of the eye. ``As for `degeneration,'
'' he writes, ``the term was extremely depressing, with its
overtones of moral decay.'' His journalistic curiosity outweighed
his apprehension, and Grunwald, former editor of ``Time,'' set out
to learn about the disease that was destroying his sight. He also
became ``a visual glutton, devouring the images around me in order
somehow to hold on to them before they grew even dimmer. The faces
of the people I loved . . . the chance glimpses of youngsters at
play in Central Park, old men in peaceful combat playing chess in
Washington Square.'' He coped through humor (``I joke about all the
ugly things I don't have to see anymore'') and by writing this book
about one of the most poignant episodes in a long and interesting
life. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``RAY GUN'' &QL; 
By Eugene W. Metcalf and Frank Maresca (Fotofolio, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We mention this one on behalf of two boys with whom New &AMP;
Notable has more than a passing acquaintance (one is 45, the other
is 7), who perused it together and announced that it was one of the
greatest books of all time. The weaponry, of course, went to their
heads. We flattered ourselves to think we'd be immune to it, but
after only a few pages _ specifically, it was when we saw the Buck
Rogers Liquid Helium Water Pistol, which we knew at once was too
cool for words _ we became ray-gun zealots and prepared to nominate
Metcalf and Maresca for the Pulitzer Prize. Their book is little
more than pictures of old toy ray guns that will make you smile and
remember a time when little boys provided the sound effects for
their guns and didn't really try to kill anyone. These are grand to
look at and whimsically friendly (witness the Smoke Ring Gun or the
Automatic Repeating Bubble Shooting Gun). The only disappointment
is that you don't get to hold them and fire a few bubbles. Metcalf
has a Web site: www.toyraygun.com. &QL; 
``AMERICAN HOLLOW'' &QL; 
By Rory Kennedy (Bulfinch, $35) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Appalachia to be a place of in breeds and
six-fingered children, of hillbillies and moonshine, an America
more backwards than backwoods,'' Kennedy writes. ``But in my year
with the Bowlings, I discovered that the truth is not so simple.''
The Bowling family lives in one of the poorest and most isolated
regions of eastern Kentucky. Kennedy spent a year living with the
family while she produced an acclaimed documentary for HBO. This is
its companion volume. Rich with photographs and long passages in
the Bowlings' own words, it is a portrait of disparate things:
family love and physical abuse, poverty and generosity, tradition
and despair, hard work and joblessness. Tying it together is the
Bowlings' deep family loyalty and regard for the land. ``Me and
Bascum might have worked hard, but now that didn't hurt us,'' says
matriarch Iree Bowling, married 50 years. ``I'm 68, he's 69, and
we're still working. And I plan on working as long as my hands will
move and my legs will go. No, I don't consider myself poor _ never
did. I feel like I'm rich, rich as the Lord wants me to be.'' &QL; 
``THE GREATEST GENERATION SPEAKS''  &QL; 
By Tom Brokaw &QL; 
(Random House, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you ever want to tell your life's story, do get Tom Brokaw to
write it for you. He was a lean, mean promotional machine on behalf
of his last book, ``The Greatest Generation.'' Now, he's back with
more. This volume offers memories and letters (many written in
response to ``The Greatest Generation'') from men and women who
weathered the Depression years, fought in World War II, and
returned home to create what Brokaw calls a ``world of broader
horizons'' for their children and grandchildren. Most of it is
presented as an oral history, with people telling their own
experiences and Brokaw providing chapter lead-ins and transitional
paragraphs. As with those in the previous book, these stories of
courage, hard work, tragedy and perseverance are told quietly, with
little fanfare or self-pity. There's plenty to get weepy over.
According to Brokaw, it shows the effect that ``The Greatest
Generation'' had onpeople who lived through those difficult decades
but never told their stories. ``I wrote a book about America,'' he
says, ``and a lot of America is writing back.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Stephenson is a freelance writer. You can reach her at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
