<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ATOMIC-CLOCK-2TAK     01-03 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ATOMIC-CLOCK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CLOCK IS GOOD FOR 20 MILLION YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most people, it is enough to know that one second is the
sixtieth part of a minute, which is one-sixtieth of an hour, which
is one twenty-fourth of the time it takes the Earth to make one
complete revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But nature is not nearly so tidy. All kinds of factors
constantly distort the standards by which ordinary people measure
time, and something far more accurate than the Earth's rotation
rate is needed to time such split-second events as course
corrections for interplanetary space probes.
</P>
<P>
   The world's pre-eminent timekeepers, in the United States and
France, have now invented a clock so accurate that it will neither
gain nor lose so much as a second in nearly 20 million years of
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Builders of one of these new ``fountain clocks'' said at a news
conference in Boulder, Colo., last week that practical uses for
these costly gadgets, which keep time by counting the vibrations of
cesium atoms, might not be found for a decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, our task is to create the most accurate and
reproducible fundamental standards we can,'' said Thomas Parker,
chief of the Atomic Standards Group at the Boulder laboratory of
the National Institute of Standards and Technology, or NIST.
``Users catch up later by adapting our research to specific
applications.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Jefferts and Dawn Meekhof of the institute built and
tested their fountain clock over four years. A clock based on
similar principles recently began operating in Sevres, France, at
the International Bureau of Weights and Measures.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1967, an international agreement has defined a second as
the period in which a cesium atom vibrates 9,192,631,770 times. The
vibration rates at which atoms absorb energy are as stable as the
clock pendulums (and far more accurate), and atoms make excellent
gauges of the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   Atomic clocks that measure time in terms of the natural resonant
frequencies of various atoms and molecules have been in use since
1949. All of them evolved from techniques suggested in the 1930s by
Dr. Isidor I. Rabi, a physicist at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Today, atomic clocks are widely used to synchronize the time
signals essential to many forms of telecommunication and to the
satellite-based Global Positioning System, which permits extremely
accurate navigation.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of ultraprecise timing in scientific research was
underscored by a discovery for which Dr. Joseph H. Taylor and Dr.
Russell A. Hulse were awarded the 1993 Nobel Prize in Physics.
</P>
<P>
   With the huge radio telescope at Arecibo, P.R., the scientists
discovered a great rarity: a pair of neutron stars orbiting each
other and emitting a radio pulse every six one-hundredths of a
second. By making ultraprecise measurements of the pulse rate of
these emissions over years, they determined the rate was very
slightly increasing, a sign that the neutron stars were spiraling
toward each other and losing energy.
</P>
<P>
   The energy lost, they calculated, was exactly the amount
predicted from Einstein's general theory of relativity as energy
shed by the double pulsar in the form of gravity waves. This was
the first proof, indirect though it was, of the existence of
gravity waves.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists in the United States, Europe and Japan are now
searching for direct detection of these subtle ripples in the
cosmic web of space-time.
</P>
<P>
   But a new technical wrinkle in atomic timing is incorporated in
the latest descendant of Rabi's atomic clock idea _ a laser system
for cooling cesium atoms. The result, a clock the institute calls
NIST F-1, is some three times as accurate as the NIST-7, a cesium
clock invented in 1993 by the standards agency.
</P>
<P>
   Laser cooling of atoms, the main innovation in the NIST F-1
clock, is a technique developed by Dr. Steven Chu of Stanford, Dr.
Claude Cohen-Tannoudji of the Ecole Normale Superieure in France
and Dr. William D. Phillips of the standards institute. The three
shared the 1997 Nobel Prize in Physics for their achievement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At room temperature an atom flies around at speeds up to 2,500
miles an hour, and is hard to measure. But if six laser beams are
directed at it from opposite directions, the atom must lose energy
in any direction it turns and is soon brought almost to a stop. The
temperature of an atom in such a trap is very close to absolute
zero.
</P>
<P>
   In the fountain clock, six lasers squeeze a cluster of cooled
cesium atoms into a little ball. Levitated by the lasers, the
cluster is then gently tossed upward as if it were the stream of a
fountain, and after the cluster has reached its maximum height
(about one yard) the lasers are turned off.
</P>
<P>
   As gravity tugs the cluster downward, it passes through a
chamber filled with precisely tuned microwaves, which excite those
atoms whose resonant frequencies match the microwave frequency. The
excited atoms then fluoresce, and light detectors measure the
brightness of the fluorescing cluster, which is a measure of the
proportion of atoms excited by the microwaves.
</P>
<P>
   By trial and error, the entire procedure of squirting cooled
atom clusters upward and passing them through a microwave cavity is
repeated many times, each time with a slight change in frequency of
the microwaves until a frequency is found that produces the most
intense fluorescence.
</P>
<P>
   This frequency is closest to the natural frequency of the cesium
atoms. From this information it is comparatively simple to mark off
a precisely measured second, which can then be used for setting
y clocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of each cesium atom as something like a little clock
that ticks more than nine billion times a second,'' Ms. Meekhof
said. ``You count the ticks and then you can use the result to set
the world's other clocks.''
</P>
<P>
   An important use of atomic clocks is correcting the errors in
clock time that result from the wobbling of the Earth's orbital
motions through space.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of timekeeping has been a continuous process of
correction and refinement over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient calendars based on a lunar cycle of 29 or 30 days
resulted in a year 11 days too short, so many governments added a
leap month whenever farmers deemed it necessary. Later, Julius
Caesar decreed a year with 365 days, with the added condition that
every fourth year, starting in 45 B.C., should be a leap year with
an extra day.
</P>
<P>
   But this created three leap years too many every 385 years, so
Pope Gregory XIII (with help from an astronomer) introduced a new
calendar in 1582 that called for a leap day in every year that is
exactly divisible by four; to make things work out correctly, the
pope decreed an exception to this rule: leap years ending in 00
(including 2000) must be evenly divisible by 400 to qualify for the
extra day.
</P>
<P>
   The Gregorian calendar has remained universal in Western
countries and in Japan, Egypt and China. But it is not perfect.
Atomic clocks have shown that unless a leap second is added every
18 months of so, the sun in New York would rise at noon 10,000
years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the forces acting on the Earth's rate of spin are
somewhat unpredictable, so it is impossible to schedule leap
seconds in any systematic way. Like the most ancient calendars
based on lunar cycles, leap seconds (the most recent of which was
delivered to the world's clocks on New Year's Eve, 1998) must be
decided by observations rather than timetables.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no end to the quest for improved time-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``About once every decade science turns up a new refinement, and
I'm sure our fountain clock is not the end of the line,'' Jefferts
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
