<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REZ-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      01-03 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REZ-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REZ': LOOKING FOR A `BIG SKY' AND FINDING DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ian Frazier's 1989 book, ``Great Plains,'' was one of those
enchanting books that thoroughly captured the peculiar mood and
magic of a place: not just the mythic dimensions of its history and
not just the mundane facts relating to its highways and byways and
towns, but the shimmering, miragelike overlap of the two. The Great
Plains in Frazier's dreams were ``enormous, bountiful, unfenced,''
and in that book he filled in some of those blanks with names and
stories, peopling that vast Western prairie with individuals he met
in the course of his 25,000-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas that earlier book had an air of exuberance about it _
``Once happiness gets rolling in this open place,'' Frazier wrote,
``not much stops it'' _ ``On the Rez,'' a sequel of sorts to
``Great Plains,'' is a sadder, darker and in many ways less
satisfying book. It continues the story of Frazier's fascination
with the Indians of the Great Plains, taking the author to the Pine
Ridge Reservation in southwestern South Dakota, where his friend Le
War Lance (whom readers first met in ``Great Plains'') now makes
his home.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier comes to Pine Ridge eager to achieve ``that
self-possessed sense of freedom'' he believes the Indians uniquely
understand, and when he first sets foot on the reservation, he
thinks: ``I feel as if I am in actual America, the original version
that was here before and will still be here after we're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it,'' he writes, ``this is the American
bedrock upon which the society outside its borders is only a later
addition. It's the surviving piece of country where `the program'
has not yet completely taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   On the reservation, Frazier finds people of remarkable courage
and resilience, but he also finds terrible alcoholism, poverty and
factional infighting. He tells us that the Census Bureau lists Pine
Ridge as the ``poorest place per capita'' year after year and that
``the alcoholism rate among adults on Pine Ridge is above 65
percent,'' though ``there is as yet no alcohol treatment center on
the reservation.'' Indeed, drunk driving is a leading cause of
death on Pine Ridge: In 1996 alone, he reports, 12 people died as a
result of alcohol-related car accidents on its roads.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this book is that Frazier never really comes to
terms with the disparity between his romanticized dream of Indian
life (based largely on historical readings and a genuine love of
Sioux culture) and the often discouraging facts of day-to-day life
``on the rez.'' He writes that ``the hopeful, big-sky feeling with
which we often invest Western landscapes is at odds with the
reality of life on Pine Ridge,'' but wistfully adds that the
reservation ``still looks grand to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also complains about other writers' describing reservation
life as ``bleak'' but then gives us pages of sad statistics showing
that ``Indians are about twice as likely as non-Indians to be
murdered,'' that ``their death rate from alcoholism is four times
the national average'' and that ``one in five Indian girls and one
in eight boys attempts suicide by the end of high school.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frazier leaves broad generalizations, the results are
decidedly better. He creates a moving portrait of a young high
school basketball star named SuAnne Marie Big Crow, who led her
reservation team to the state championship in 1989 and died three
years later in a car wreck. He makes an eloquent and impassioned
argument for the U.S. government's giving back the Black Hills to
the Sioux. And he provides some artful digressions on Sioux ideals
of heroism, on the Lakota language, and on Indian superstitions and
lore. (``Rainbow-hued sun dogs _ bright spots on either side of the
sun _ mean an enemy is approaching.'' ``The smoke from anemone
flowers burned on hot coals can cure headaches.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for Frazier's accounts of his own travels, they are enlivened
by a keen eye for detail, and the same delightful sense of the
absurd that animated his humor collections, ``Dating Your Mom'' and
``Coyote vs. Acme.'' Ing us about his own hero worship of
the great Sioux warrior Crazy Horse, Frazier notes that he often
referred ``to his example when wondering how I should act in
certain situations'': so when it came to talking to his wife about
renovating their house, he asked himself, ``Would Crazy Horse have
spent this much to remodel a kitchen?''
</P>
<P>
   All too aware that he is a ``middle-class white guy'' with
Walter Mitty-ish dreams of being an Indian, Frazier chronicles his
friendship with Le War Lance in a wry voice that mixes
self-deprecation with skepticism and wishful thinking. He points
out that Le is constantly asking him for money _ for one emergency
or another, one car part or another _ and he feels both put upon
and grateful that he has a chance to ingratiate himself with his
friend. At times, he grows impatient with Le's habit of getting
drunk and telling far-fetched tales; at other moments, he berates
himself for being judgmental and chintzy and for taking a
``journalistic interest in Le.''
</P>
<P>
   Engaging as the evolving relationship between the two men proves
to be, it enlivens ``On the Rez'' without quite making up for the
book's longueurs and contradictions. In the end, the difference
between this volume and its predecessor may be best summed up by
the two historic figures who act as the presiding spirits of the
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great Plains'' featured a moving portrait of the heroic Crazy
Horse, whom Frazier says he loves ``because he remained himself
from the moment of his birth to the moment he died''; because ``his
dislike of the oncoming civilization was prophetic''; because ``he
is not the Indian on the nickel, the tobacco pouch or the apple
crate.'' ``On the Rez,'' in contrast, features an ambivalent
portrait of Red Cloud, who made an early peace with the whites, and
who, under pressure from the U.S. government, reluctantly signed a
treaty agreeing to the sale of the gold-rich Black Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crazy Horse, who died in his 30s, is a good hero for someone
young,'' Frazier writes. ``As you age and see more of life's
complication, you may find sympathy, if not admiration, for Red
Cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ON THE REZ'
</P>
<P>
   By Ian Frazier
</P>
<P>
   311 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1715EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
