<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5522 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      01-03 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH TOUTS HIS RECORD IN TEXAS TO BOLSTER CREDENTIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Gov. George W. Bush hits the road this week
with key early political contests looming, he is packing his Texas
resume as proof that he has what it takes to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a big step going from governor to president of the
United States, but I've had some pretty good training,`` the
Republican candidate said in Bedford, N.H., the state with the
nation's first primaries on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   After months of honing his political arsenal on the campaign
trail and a holiday break to recharge his batteries, Bush is
heading into an intense monthlong stretch leading to a political
reckoning for would-be presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our state was a nation, it would be the 11th-largest
economy in the world,'' said Bush, who was elected to a second term
as Texas governor in 1998. ``I think if you were to check with the
people down there, they would pay me the high compliment of saying,
`He's done in office what he said he would do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his business experience also helped prepare him for
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But he highlights his five years as an elected official in the
government's executive branch to distinguish himself from the other
Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Executives are decision-makers. A good executive builds teams.
A good executive knows how to lead,`` said Bush, 53, who is running
for president as a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters said his 1998 re-election with 69 percent of the
vote shows most Texans are satisfied with his leadership on issues
ranging from education to criminal justice to cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said Bush takes credit for some initiatives that were in
the works before he took office, exaggerates the positive effect of
tax-cut measures and has a poor record in areas such as
nvironmental protection _ a record he defends.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Bruce Buchanan of the University of Texas at
Austin said that overall, Bush's record gives him modest bragging
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got what I call a moderately successful record compiled
in favorable times, rather than in crisis or trying times,``
Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does show a few characteristics we want in a president,``
including the ability to set and achieve goals, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Texas political scientist, Jerry Polinard of UT-Pan
American in Edinburg, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``His claims for success are valid, and one recognizes it's been
a modest success,`` Polinard said. ``He has not been able to get
everything he wants, but neither has he been shut out of the
process.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush's drive for the presidency comes after five years in the
``bully pulpit`` of the governorship. The Texas governorship is
considered a constitutionally weak post in which the power of
persuasion is critical.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has forged a reputation for one-on-one magic that he
demonstrates while campaigning, charming potential voters as he
shakes hands, makes small talk and signs autographs.
</P>
<P>
   And he is credited for being able to work with Democrats, who
controlled the House and Senate when he first was elected in 1994.
The Republican governor particularly forged a bond with former Lt.
Gov. Bob Bullock, a Democrat who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any other statewide Republican that involves
themselves in crowds like he does,`` said Democratic House Speaker
Pete Laney, wondering ``whether that'll be able to continue when he
gets his Secret Service.``
</P>
<P>
   George Christian, a consultant who was a press secretary to
President Lyndon Johnson, said Bush ``came in as governor not
knowing a lot about state government, and he's done very well by
utilizing his natural traits, which are friendliness, cooperation
and a calm approach to what he's trying to do.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not just been someone legislative leaders can work
with, he was ``agreeable to work with,'' Laney said. ``There's a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's gubernatorial record began in 1995, when lawmakers
approved measures addressing four goals he campaigned on: reforms
in education, welfare, juvenile justice and the civil lawsuit
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some said Bush simply latched on to four issues already at the
forefront of the state agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in effect piggybacking on trains that were already
moving,`` Buchanan said. ``There's nothing immoral about that, but
it's not quite the same as being an entrepreneur with bold and
daring vision, either.``
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who heads Bush's Texas campaign for
president, said Bush talked to lawmakers about the issues as his
1994 gubernatorial campaign unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they being talked about before? Yes. Was he intuitive
enough to understand these are important issues the people of the
state of Texas need and want? Yes,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He articulated where he wanted to take Texas, and then he
followed through. That second part is the most important part,`` he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm dismissed
such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only really positive thing George W. Bush has done is to
stay out of the way when the leaders of the House and Senate were
trying to get things done,`` she said.
</P>
<P>
   The House speaker wasn't so harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of what made it happen,`` Laney said. While
agreeing with Buchanan that Bush jumped on a moving train in his
first session, Laney called the move ``pretty smart politics.``
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's second legislative session, in 1997, he proposed a tax
overhaul with an eye to relieving local property taxes that heavily
support Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush left himself open to criticism by suggesting that property
tax relief be financed partly by increases in some state taxes,
along with a budget surplus. In the end, he did not get the
overhaul he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But the $1 billion property tax reduction for which Bush settled
is a key campaign selling point, coupled with another $1.85 billion
in property and other tax cuts from the 1999 legislative session.
Again, the total was less than he sought.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legislation, a taxpayer group said hoped-for
property tax relief appeared to vanish into a ``black hole`` as a
number of local school districts raised rates. But an official with
the group said that, without state action, taxes would have been
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Bush secured the right to say he had signed large
tax-cut measures into law, which he does with alacrity.
</P>
<P>
   As he travels the country, Bush also touts his record on
education, especially a plan meant to ensure youngsters can read
and are not promoted until academically ready. He wasn't, however,
able to win Texas lawmakers' approval for a pilot program of
publicly paid vouchers for private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, Bush says welfare rolls are down, that he has
made a priority of ``putting people in jail who cannot figure out
how to peacefully coexist with their neighbors`` and that tort
reform has made Texas ``entrepreneurial heaven.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATIERAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics see his record as something less than angelic.
</P>
<P>
   They said he has not supported some important measures,
including a bill to strengthen the state's law against hate crimes
after a black man was dragged to his death behind a truck.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contended the bill's inclusion of gays prompted concern
from advisers as Bush eyed his presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush stopped that bill. ... I think he only did that
because his advisers didn't want him to sign a bill that protected
gays,`` said Dianne Hardy-Garcia of the Lesbian and Gay Rights
Lobby of Texas. ``That was heartbreaking for us.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied defeating the bill and said existing law should be
enforced. In the dragging-death case, which resulted in three
murder convictions, he noted that the death penalty was handed down
in two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record on the environment also has come under fire, with
environmental groups contending it was filled with industry
influence and missed opportunities. Bush said Texas has made
progress while he has been governor.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also said Bush has not done what he should to help the
poor, including those who suffer from hunger, or prevent gun
violence. Bush says the crime rate has decreased and that he has
worked to rally religious groups to help the poor while moving
people from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recently took issue with a federal report saying Texas had
the nation's second-largest percentage of households that
experienced hunger between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some people in my state who are hungry. I
don't believe 5 percent are hungry,`` he said in New Hampshire,
drawing concern from advocates for the poor who said there are many
hungry Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and others compare criticism he receives to that in his
first gubernatorial race, when Democratic incumbent Ann Richards
and others suggested he was unprepared to lead the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They underestimated me,`` Bush has said of that contest. ``I
love to be underestimated.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
