<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MOUTH-BACTERIA-AR     01-03 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOUTH-BACTERIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPECIES IN KINGDOM OF THE MOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 4 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People may believe that their mouths are pristine after a good
brushing and flossing. But the truth is that the human mouth is
home to so many microbes that some researchers compare it to a rain
forest for the diversity of life and vast territory yet to be
explored.
</P>
<P>
   A study last month in The Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences supports this analogy by identifying 37 new kinds of
b thriving between teeth and gum. The research brings the
total known species of oral wildlife to about 500, some of which
are permanent residents while others may just be passing through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mouth is a plush ecosystem unto itself, and we are just
beginning to see what is really there,'' said Dr. David A. Relman,
the study's team leader and an assistant professor of medicine and
microbiology at Stanford University. ``People like to go to Africa
to stare at animals, but micro-organisms are far more diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers extracted plaque from the crevice between a
subject's tooth and gum. They then used two techniques to identify
what kinds of bacteria the plaque contained.
</P>
<P>
   One was the traditional method of growing bacteria from the
sample and examining the results with a microscope. The other was
to identify bacteria by examining DNA.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the researchers found 31 new species of bacteria
with the DNA technique and just six from laboratory cultivation.
The difference was that most bacteria have trouble growing outside
their natural environment, Relman said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the organisms appear to be related to others normally
found outside the human body. One was similar to a bacterium that
lives in lake bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Floyd E. Dewhirst, a molecular geneticist and dentist at the
Forsyth Institute, a dental research center in Boston, said that
people need not be concerned about most bacteria living in their
 While some bacteria cause diseases like pneumonia if they
get into the bloodstream, others are harmless hitchikers profiting
from a warm, protected environment in which there is plenty to eat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1724EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-VOTING-AZR &LR;      01-03 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S VOTES OPEN TO MISCHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ This year, Arizonans will be able to vote for
president about as often as they get an oil change _ and it will
all be legal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current presidential primary arrangement, voters could
legally cast ballots in the primary elections of the two major
political parties, election and party officials concede.
</P>
<P>
   Voters could then go on to vote for a candidate in the Reform
Party in the summer and cap off all of this multipartisan mischief
with a vote in November for one of the three people they helped
nominate.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could vote for somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to world-class political chaos, Arizona-style.
</P>
<P>
   County and state election officials acknowledge that two-fisted
voting could be the result of the scheduling of Republican and
Democratic primaries on separate days 18 days apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it would be possible,'' conceded Maricopa County
Recorder Helen Purcell.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Purcell doubts that voters, many of whom have
proven themselves to be less than excited about voting at all in
recent years, will be inspired to take advantage of the loophole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get 'em to go to the polls once, much less twice,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The snarl begins on Feb. 22, the day Arizona Republicans will
vote in a taxpayer-supported presidential preference primary.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the thread leads to March 11, when Arizona
Democrats, constrained by their national rules, hold a separate and
privately financed election.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for mischief arises because the Democrats allow
their members to register to vote up to and including the day of
the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   That means there is nothing to prevent Arizona residents who
register as Republicans by that party's deadline of Monday, Jan.
24, to re-register as Democrats on or before March 11 to cast a
second ballot.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage this type of double-dipping at the polls,
Democratic officials say they plan to require voters to sign a form
swearing that they did not vote in any other primary contest.
</P>
<P>
   But the form isn't worth a jot legally, officials admit, because
there are no consequences for signing it with your fingers crossed
behind your back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, it's probably not something we could enforce
legally,'' conceded Mark Fleisher, chairman of the Arizona
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will have a third crack at the ballot box next summer,
when the Reform Party intends to hold a national primary election
by mail. The party will allow any registered voter, including
Democrats and Republicans, to participate in an effort to encourage
more interest in the party.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party will then hold a national convention at which
only Reform Party members will be permitted to ratify the party's
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Reform Party Chairman Eugene Kerkman said he does not
believe Democrats and Republicans will face ``wholesale'' voter
shenanigans, but he is aware of some people who intend to vote, as
the saying goes, early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are people who do exactly that,'' Kerkman said,
adding that such unauthorized attempts to interfere with another
party's election are ``kind of malicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happens, we've completely lost our sense of
ethics,'' Kerkman said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the Natural Law Party, with only 70 registered voters,
has already qualified for the ballot, while Kerkman's Reform Party,
which can boast at least one candidate (Pat Buchanan) who got
93,000 votes for president in Arizona in 1996, has not. But the
Reformers, who have 800 registered voters, are working on that.
They have until May.
</P>
<P>
   In another wrinkle that could have important implications for
the Democratic presidential candidates, members of the state
Democratic Party will vote Jan. 22 on whether to allow Independent
voters to participate in their primary.
</P>
<P>
   If the party approves the participation of Independent voters,
it is widely believed that Bill Bradley, who has spent a lot of
time appealing to Independents, will benefit.
</P>
<P>
   State election officials have been aware of the opportunities
for mischief for some time. Last year they tried to get the
Democrats to change their plans and participate in the presidential
preference primary on the same day as Republicans. They even
offered to try to get a joint primary date moved back to March and
proposed an all-mail ballot election to accommodate the Democrats'
national rules, which prevent them from holding their election in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, rebuffed by the Democratic National Committee, state
officials gave up their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pursued different ways to have more uniformity in how this
was going to happen, but we just couldn't get any traction,'' said
Jessica Funkhouser, state elections director.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Democrats are running their own show, state
officials are powerless to monitor their election, meaning that the
only safeguard in place is the Democratic Party's sign-up sheet
requiring that voters affirm that they haven't already voted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep trying to emphasize that the Democrats are not
participating in a state election,'' Funkhouser said. ``We don't
have any jurisdiction over who they allow to participate in their
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Under rio in which Democrats register as Republicans and
then re-register as Democrats, it would be the Republicans who
could end up hurt, as conceivably Democrats would wish to vote for
the presidential candidate with the least chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said state GOP Chairman Mike Minnaugh, who laughingly
dismissed any concerns about a Democratic raid on his party's
primary. The Democrats, he suggested, have a hard enough time
getting their own members to the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are so concerned about a particular (Republican)
candidate that they are going to get their two people together and
go and re-register,'' Minnaugh joked.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher said Democrats are not encouraging such a scheme.
</P>
<P>
   And, pointing out that Democrats went through much the same
routine in 1996, asking voters to promise they weren't voting
twice, Fleisher said he is confident there will be no organized
attempt to subvert the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would interpret it as voter fraud,'' Fleisher
said, adding that ``most people will act responsibly if they think
they're supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Fleisher said he worries about the potential for such
contretemps to backfire. For instance, Democrats could
inadvertently help elect a candidate who is anathema to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems to backfire when you try to do something like
that,'' Fleisher said. ``I think the Republicans should put forth
their best candidate, and the Democrats should put forth their best
candidate.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
