u f BC-Y2K04-COX     01-03 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K BUG STILL MISSING AS WORKERS RETURN FROM HOLIDAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Americans returned to their offices and
factories Monday, they found the lights on, the phones working and
their fears about Y2K bugs dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   On the first regular business day o the nation
experienced only ``minor glitches'' that had no chance of
snowballing into big trouble, said John Koskinen, President
Clinton's top Y2K adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can safely say that what has been referred to as the Y2K
bug has been squashed,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example the kinds of problems that turned up, he noted
that a customer returning a movie to a rental shop in suburban
Albany, N.Y., was hit with a $91,250 late fee after computers
showed the tape was overdue by 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said such incidents, while mostly causing chuckles,
help confirm the existence of the Y2K bug, a software flaw that
could have caused older computers to misinterpret the year ``00,''
misreading it as 1900 rather than 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw had the potential to cause massive failures of
computerized equipment, but because of a $100-billion effort by
business owners to eradicate it, the problem will be confined to
``some glitches around the edges,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   The $8.5 billion in spending by the federal government also
appears to have paid off. All 1,300 Social Security Administration
field offices opened Monday and reported no difficulties with their
50 million lines of computer code. The Postal Service did turn up
two minor problems, one involving old retail terminals that showed
the wrong date and the other in a system that reports mail volume.
Both glitches were quickly fixed.
</P>
<P>
   One bug affected a computer at the Y-12 nuclear weapons plant in
Oak Ridge, Tenn., but had no impact on operations or workers, the
Energy Department reported. Because computer controls are a
classified function, the exact nature of the problem was not
explained, but the Energy Department said the bug was fixed in
about three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, banks started making plans for shipping back the
extra $50 billion in cash that the Federal Reserve Board had
ordered up to avert possible runs on automated teller machines. The
fresh bills will not be destroyed, but rather will be stored and
eventually used to replace worn-out currency.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said his operation, called the President's Council on
Y2K Conversion, will begin this week to scale back its efforts to
monitor the Y2K bug. However, some staff will continue to watch
computers through Feb. 29. Years ending in 00 include a leap day
only every fourth century _ including this year _ and some
computers are not be prepared for that date quirk.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said he is pleased that software fixes went so well
that they have given rise to skepticism about Y2K, saying he'd
rather respond to those comments than to questions about why things
went so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We geared up for a major potential set of problems and I think
all of us view it as a great victory that we can sit here and talk
about, `Was it money well spent? Did we have to do it?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is mgeewax(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
