<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN04-COX     01-03 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTENTION, BORED VOTERS: PRESIDENTIAL RACES ENTERING KEY PHASE
 &HT;    With CAMPAIGN-TIMELINE. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four debates in four days this week signals a new
phase of the 2000 presidential campaign _ one that is likely to be
more ferocious and more unpredictable as voters take control of the
process from the candidates, their advisers and the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats square off Wednesday in New Hampshire and again
Saturday in Iowa, while the Republicans debate Thursday in New
Hampshire and Friday in South Carolina _ the beginning of a 10-week
campaign sprint in which a majority of delegates will be chosen for
the parties' nominating conventions.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign begins to take root in the American
consciousness, it does so with serious contests being waged in both
parties. That situation was anticipated by few in the political
class last summer, least of all the two front-runners: Vice
President Al Gore on the Democratic side and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas among the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   However, for all the rhetorical flourid unprecedented
fund raising that has taken place over the past 12 months, experts
say the campaign has failed to come into focus for most voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a serious horse race in both parties, but it's hard
to put your finger on what they're about,'' said Linda Fowler, a
Dartmouth College professor who directs the presidential primary
polling in New Hampshire for Dartmouth and The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Fowler said, that both Gore and Bush have tried to
wage a general election campaign since last summer, tailoring their
appeals to moderate centrist voters rather than the more activist
partisans that largely dominate primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Another, she said, is the complacency growing out of years of
uninterrupted economic growth and staggering declines in crime and
welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center for The People and The Press
last month, for example, found that the rhetoric and events of the
presidential campaign had had ``impact'' on the attitudes of
voters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that ``relatively few people are able to
associate candidates with their main policy proposals.'' For
example, only 15 percent of the 1,073 adults polled by Pew
researchers could identify Bush with ``compassionate
conservatism,'' the Texas governor's main campaign slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public doesn't seem to care very much about this election
so far, because there doesn't seem to be a salient issue,'' Fowler
said. ``And that has made it easier for insurgent candidates.
People are willing to take a chance on lesser known quantities.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples are former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, who only
six months ago was considered a long shot against Gore, and Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, widely regarded as an even longer shot
against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown Bradley and McCain running slightly ahead of
their chief opponents in New Hampshire, which holds the nation's
first presidential primary Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's strength in New Hampshire has allowed him more time to
pick at Gore's lead in Iowa, where both parties will conduct
presidential nominating caucuses on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is skipping the GOP caucus in Iowa, concentrating instead
on winning the South Carolina primary on Feb. 19. A win there,
combined with a victory in the Feb. 22 primary in his home state of
Arizona, could sustain him into a March 7 showdown involving 11
states, including the huge prizes of California, New York and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's poll momentum and his crusade against the
campaign-finance system may be no match for the awesome
fund-raising talents of Bush. The Texas governor has raised more
than $67 million for his White House bid and still has $31.4
million in the bank. McCain, on the other hand, has raised $15.6
million but has only $7.7 million left.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the GOP, the Democratic Party has not altered its rules
prohibiting primaries between New Hampshire and March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Gore and Bradley will be waging an expensive
coast-to-coast campaign after Feb. 1, perhaps until six Southern
and Western states, including Texas and Florida, vote March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley will both have about $20 million to finance
their campaigns, but Gore, like Bush in the GOP contest, has the
advantage of being supported by the party establishment. Gore also
has the backing of President Clinton, an advantage in the
Democratic primaries, if not in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley anticipated Gore's advantages from the start and has
waged his campaign accordingly, seeking new and independent voters
with promises of a few ``big things'': providing health care to all
children and most adults, reforming campaign finance, tightening
gun controls and increasing the number of teachers in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in a speech billed by his campaign as a ``vision for
America in the new millennium,'' told a New Hampshire audience
Monday that as president he would open ``a world of new
possibilities guided by goodness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, countering Bradley with a speech in Iowa, offered himself
as a tried-and-true national leader capable of tackling more than a
few national problems. ``We cannot afford to say that meeting one
of these challenges is enough,'' he said. ``All of them are well
within our reach ... if we make good decisions with good
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley will meet for their fourth debate Wednesday
night at the University of New Hampshire in Durham. ABC's Peter
Jennings will moderate the debate, which begins at 7 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Tim Russert will moderate the GOP debate Thursday night at
the University of New Hampshire. All six GOP candidates are
expected: Bush, McCain, publisher Steve Forbes, activist Gary
Bauer, Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah and former ambassador Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
