<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CENSUS04-COX     01-03 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CENSUS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Census posing problem for Bush
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three months before U.S. census workers begin
counting Americans, the seemingly arcane question of whether they
should give states numbers based on a strict head count or
estimates derived from statistical sampling has become a political
quandary for Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans are wary of sampling because it will boost the
number of perennially undercounted blacks and Hispanics, who tend
tDemocratic. They also argue that the Constitution forbids
it. But Bush is hoping to bring many minority voters into the GOP
fold, and he risks alienating them if he suggests that he favors an
undercount of their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The census is all about politics: Federal officials use the
final tally to determine how many of the 435 U.S. representatives
will be allotted to each state. State legislatures use the numbers
to draw congressional and state legislative districts. People who
aren't counted lose political power, and nearly every census since
the first one in 1790 has been politically charged.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Scott McClellan says Bush generally supports
actual counting as opposed to sampling, but the governor hasn't
said publicly whether he would give the estimates to the states,
which is the crux of the issue. Bush is the only presidential
candidate who hasn't taken a position on that question. All the
other Republicans, with the exception of U.S. Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, say they would withhold the estimates from the states.
McCain and Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley say they would send
them out.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan also couldn't say whether Bush would allow federal
agencies to use estimates in calculating how much education and
welfare money to send to each state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's reticence on the issue troubles some conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're trying to do is not upset minority voters who
believethat government should exercise their rights. This is a
crass political move,'' said Matthew Glavin of the Atlanta-based
Southeastern Legal Foundation, a conservative group that
successfully sued to force the use of the actual numbers to
determine how many U.S. representatives each state will get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day that Governor Bush doesn't answer the question makes
it appear as if he supports the use of sampled numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The census bureau estimates that 60 percent of the roughly 120
million American households will return their census forms in the
mail. To reach the rest, the bureau will hire about 860,000
temporary workers, most of whom will fan out across the country to
knock on doors.
</P>
<P>
   But even that effort won't result in a complete count. Many
people, distrustful of government, will avoid being counted or will
give the workers inaccurate infor Americans are increasingly
mobile, and some will fall through the cracks. Language barriers
and illiteracy also complicate the process.
</P>
<P>
   Counting in minority communities in inner cities and in rural
areas is particularly difficult. The Census Bureau says it missed
more than 500,000 Texans, many of them Hispanics, in the 1990
census. The state sued unsuccessfully to get the numbers adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a highly disproportionate undercount of racial
minorities, children and the poor, both urban and rural,'' said
Terri Ann Lowenthal of the Census 2000 Initiative, a 4-year-old
group that tracks census-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan says Bush ``will work to do whatever it takes to
locate and count each and every person in America.'' But the census
will be over by the time the next president takes office. And
Lowenthal says counting everybody, even with more money or workers,
is impossible. Census researchers from the National Academy of
Sciences agree.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about the accuracy of the census count are nothing new:
George Washington and Thomas Jefferson both expressed concerns that
the 1790 census missed many Americans, historians say.
</P>
<P>
   Sampling supporters say the estimates, derived from 300,000
randomly selected households, will produce the most accurate count.
Dozens of prominent minority groups, including the NAACP, the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund, the National
Council of La Raza and the National Urban League, support the
release of the estimates to the states.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are eager to highlight Bush's dilemma. Earlier this
month, the Democratic leaders of the major congressional minority
caucuses wrote a letter to Bush asking him to end his silence on
the sampling issue. ``Do you stand with those who would deny
minorities, children, and the poor fair representation and economic
benefits for purely partisan political reasons?'' the letter
states.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress members say Bush's home state lost about $1 billion
in federal aid during the 1990s as a result of the undercount and
the subsequent decision, made by President Bush's administration,
not to adjust the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said the vice president often
mentions the issue during his interviews with Hispanic media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It literally translates into whether you count or don't count.
Al Gore wants to do everything possible to make sure that Hispanics
are accurately represented,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   The census has a rich history as a political football. Unhappy
with the results of the 1920 census, which showed that for the
first time most Americans lived in cities, rural members of
Congress blocked attempts to adjust political power. As a result,
legislative lines weren't redrawn until after the 1930 census. Most
Republicans acknowledge that the use of sampling to draw districts
would hurt them politically. But some insist that the issue is
constitutional, not political.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would argue that every person in America has a
constitutionally guaranteed right to be counted. But like any other
right that's guaranteed by the Constitution, in order to enjoy the
benefits of that right, individuals must exercise it, `` said
Glavin, who says the Constitution requires a head count.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you choose not to vote, Bill Clinton and the government
can't come in, guess how you would have voted and then adjust the
election results.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody agrees with that analysis. Margo Anderson, a
professor at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee and one of the
nation's foremost census historians, says the Constitution's census
clause is open to interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Glavin and the Republican-controlled U.S. House of
Representatives sued the Clinton administration to force the use of
the actual numbers for the 2000 census. Last January, the Supreme
Court ruled, based on an interpretation of census law rather than
the Constitution, that sampling could not be used to determin-- how
many representatives each state will get. Clinton administration
officials interpreted the decision to mean that sampling could be
used for drawing legislative districts and for handing out federal
aid.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be the next White House occupant who decides whether
to give the estimates to the states _ which is why many are waiting
to find out where George W. Bush stands on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. E-mail: sgreenberger(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
