<HEADLINE>
`ALL MY CHILDREN' TURNS 30 WITH BIRTHDAY SHOW
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service cients) 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to realize it was 30 years ago when a teen-age Erica
Kane descended upon Pine Valley _ and the world _ on the ABC soap
opera, ``All My Children.'' But the venerable daytime drama _ with
Erica's drama-queen antics still going strong _ will celebrate
three decades on the air on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Erica (Susan Lucci, winner of the 1999 daytime Emmy
for best actress _ finally! _ after 19 tries) the remaining three
original cast members will be featured: Mary Fickett (Ruth Martin),
winner of the first daytime Emmy for acting in 1973; Ray MacDonnell
(Dr. Joe Martin); and Ruth Warrick (Phoebe Tyler), who played the
wife opposite Orson Welles in ``Citizen Kane''.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hourlong show, which begins at noon, will be a
clipfest as well as a window to the future as characters recall 30
years of groundbreaking stories, including those focusing on AIDS,
abortion, date rape, teen-age alcoholism, racial bias, spousal
abuse, homosexuality, eating disorders and opposition to the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Agnes Nixon, who is still head writer, ``All My
Children'' debuted Jan. 5, 1970, as a half-hour show; seven years
later, it expanded to an hour. It launched many careers, including
those of Dana Delaney, Lauren Holly, Sarah Michelle Gellar,
Christine Baranski, Dorothy Lyman, Amanda Bearse, Kathy Bates,
Robert Downey Jr., Christian Slater, Wesley Snipes and Robert
Urich. &QL;
</P>
