<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PATIENT-RIGHTS-2T     01-03 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PATIENT-RIGHTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASES: WHEN DECISIONS MEAN LIFE OR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SANDEEP JAUHAR, M.D.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One night recently, when I was on call in the emergency room at
my hospital, paramedics wheeled in an elderly woman on a stretcher
at 2 a.m. She was having severe chest pain, which an EKG
immediately confirmed was a serious heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The ER sprung into action. Doctors whisked her into a treatment
room, put her on a monitor, placed an oxygen mask over her face,
and began an IV drip of nitroglycerin. (The paramedics had already
given her an aspirin.)
</P>
<P>
   Though in pain, she was alert, clear-headed and quiet. The only
indication of an emergency was in the buzz of the many doctors and
nurses around her.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, including the cardiology fellow who had been summoned
on an emergency beeper, began preparing her for angioplasty, in
which a catheter would be threaded through an artery in her groin
to open the blockage that was cutting off blood flow to her heart.
</P>
<P>
   The cardiology fellow, a bright, energetic man, stepped outside
the room to talk with the woman's daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother was in critical condition, he told them, and if
nothing was done she might die. Angioplasty probably offered her
the best shot of surviving this crisis, but it was risky,
particularly in an emergency. Their mother, age 90, could die on
the table or suffer brain damage or end up on a ventilator. No one
could predict with any certainty what would happen.
</P>
<P>
   She could also be treated, with a simple injection, with a
thrombolytic drug to dissolve blood clots. But it would probably
not be as effective as angioplasty in this situation, and it
carried a risk of bleeding, especially at her age, into her head.
</P>
<P>
   So what did they want to do?
</P>
<P>
   The children thought for a few minutes, but couldn't decide.
Perhaps, they suggested, they should ask their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now ordinarily, in an emergency, doctors are not supposed to
waste precious time discussing risks and benefits, certainly not
with patients who probably cannot understand the choices before
them anyway. Doctors are taught to treat first and ask questions
later, on the assumption that rational people would prefer
treatment to prolong their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But this emergency was different. The patient was awake and
seemingly competent. We could decide how to keep her alive, but
only she could decide whether the effort would be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The cardiology fellow went through her options, and the woman
listened.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was not clear how much of the complicated situation
she understood, she did not like any of her options, including
doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted assurances we could not give. We wanted a decision
she could not make. She finally looked out at the room of white
coats, slowly shook her head, and said she didn't know. She was
taken to the cardiac care unit for observation.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this was not a surprise. With little medical
knowledge, and often burdened by fear, depression or pain,
hospitalized patients can have a hard time properly weighing their
options. Some doctors even argue that obtaining informed consent
from them is a meaningless exercise promoted by ethicists who don't
understand the realities of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   There are data to support this view. Most studies show that
patients recall less than half of what doctors tell them. In one
study on informed consent before cataract surgery, for example,
only 4 percent of patients recalled more than two out of five risks
disclosed to them by their doctors (only a third remembered later
that blindness was a potential risk). And studies show that
patients often don't take an interest in the informed consent
process.
</P>
<P>
   But the very fact that patients are often helpless or feel
intimidated is precisely why ethicists have argued that informed
consent is so essential.
</P>
<P>
   So what if patients don't know what is right for them or make
wrong decisions. As Stephen Wear, an ethicist at the State
University of New York at Buffalo, wrote in his book, ``Informed
Consent'': ``Elsewhere, we recognize and accept that harm and
tragedy may result from the free exercise of one's will. But this
is simply the price we must sometimes pay for the freedom to which
we give such a fundamental value and status.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on the cardiology service, I had a patient who
suffered from a dangerous cardiac rhythm called ventricular
tachycardia.
</P>
<P>
   Many studies have shown that these patients live longer when
they have automatic defibrillators implanted in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   My patient was young and seemed an ideal candidate for this
device.
</P>
<P>
   But when I brought it up with him, he flatly refused. His
kidneys had failed years earlier and he had been in and out of
hospitals undergoing dialysis treatment. He had suffered a lot of
pain and did not trust doctors to keep him well.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to matter to him that he could die suddenly
while walking down the street. He wanted out of the hospital, and
so we had to let him go.
</P>
<P>
   But though I believed he was wrong, it was his decision. If
autonomy means anything, it means patients have the right to make
bad decisions, too.
</P>
<P>
   But many situations are far less clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   In their book, ``Assessing Competence to Consent to Treatment,''
Dr. Thomas Grisso and Dr. Paul Appelbaum, two ethicists at the
University of Massachusetts, wrote that when patients were unable
to reach a treatment decision or convey it to their doctors, courts
and ethicists have considered them to be incompetent to make
treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But when does irresolution become incompetence? And how can
patients and doctors properly weigh competing values in
emergencies?
</P>
<P>
   I recently took care of an 80-year-old man with prostate cancer.
He had been admitted to the hospital with severe back pain, and an
MRI had revealed a metastasis that was compressing his spinal cord.
After treatment with high-dose steroids and radiation, he felt
better. But one morning, a day before he was to be discharged, his
heart went into an abnormal rhythm that impaired its ability to
pump. His blood pressure dropped, fluid accumulated in his lungs
and he grew short of breath. The best option was to apply an
electrical shock to his heart to jolt it into a normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   But he disagreed, scowling at me through his oxygen mask. ``I
want to give up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I did not think he was competent to make that decision, so I
continued preparations for the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 50 years had been sitting quietly beside his bed.
But suddenly she got up and left the room. Minutes later, her
husband's attending physician appeared in the room. He said the
patient's wife would not consent to any more treatment. ``We can
get him through this,'' I protested. But his wife had made a value
judgment that superseded my medical one.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the value judgments that complicate emergencies
fall upon doctors.
</P>
<P>
   I admitted a middle-aged man to the hospital a few months ago
who had been diagnosed with salivary gland cancer in 1998. Despite
aggressive treatment, including experimental chemotherapy, the
cancer had spread to his lungs. When I saw him the first night in
the ER, a chocolate cake sat on a small table by his bed. It was
his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   At home he had been getting progressively shorter of breath. But
he was terminally ill and I knew his condition could deteriorate.
So after my exam I broached with him and his wife the subject of
special efforts to keep him alive: whether to resuscitate him if
his heart stopped or if he stopped breathing. His wife said they
wanted everything possible to be done to keep him alive.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, about 2 a.m., he became acutely short of breath.
His blood oxygen saturation was very low and steadily dropping.
</P>
<P>
   He was awake and able to talk, but lack of oxygen was making him
more and more lethargic. I had no idea of his mental state, but he
said he wanted everything done for him, including intubation if
necessary. ``Then we have to intubate you now,'' one of the other
doctors told him.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the immediate prospect of a breathing tube, he
suddenly lost his nerve. Could we wait a little longer, he asked,
to see if he might get better on his own.
</P>
<P>
   But his condition was deteriorating rapidly. Without mechanical
ventilation, he could suddenly develop cardiac arrest. He and his
wife needed to make a decision immediately, either to accept a
breathing tube, or sign a ``do not resuscitate'' form. A 4 a.m.
conversation with the attending physician resolved nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue had begun to set in. Some minutes later, in the dim dawn
light, they asked me what to do, and I told them. He died the next
day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
