A5545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CARE-GUNMEN-COX     01-03 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE-GUNMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elation turns to sorrow as CARE worker killed overseas
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday was a day of deeply mixed emotions for
employees of CARE USA, the Atlanta-based relief and development
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they prepared a party to celebrate the release of a
colleague after eight months in a Yugoslav prison, they received
word that one co-worker in Somalia had been shot to death and
another was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Shuab Mohamed Hussein, a Somali employee of CARE USA, was killed
Sunday when his CARE vehicle was ambushed north of Mogadishu.
Hussein had been with CARE for two months, and worked to ensure
food security and to build bridges and culverts, said Peter Bell,
president of CARE USA.
</P>
<P>
   An employee who was with Hussein is missing, Bell said, and CARE
officials are concerned about his fate. Bell declined to name the
second employee, but noted he was also a native Somali and had been
with CARE forars.
</P>
<P>
   News of Hussein's death came as workers at CARE's headquarters
in Atlanta prepared to celebrate the release of Branko Jelen, a
Yugoslav citizen who worked for CARE Australia. CARE USA and CARE
Australia are both are members of CARE International.
</P>
<P>
   Jelen was arrested April 8, shortly after NATO started bombing
Yugoslavia in March. Two Australian CARE employees had been
arrested a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The three were convicted of passing secret information out of
the country, but the Australians were granted clemency in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that CARE had lobbied hard for Jelen's release,
working with the United Nations, civil rights leader Jesse Jackson,
former South African President Nelson Mandela, former President
Jimmy Carter and former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, Jelen had become ``quite depressed,'' Bell
said. He is receiving counseling, and plans to move to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   CARE USA had been reluctant to work in Yugoslavia while Jelen _
whom CARE officials said had done nothing wrong _ remained in
prison. In light of his release, Bell said his organization may
increase its involvement in Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic,
where CARE Australia helps refugees from Bosnia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``While saddened by the news from Somalia, we are absolutely
elated by Branko's release,'' Bell said. The party would go on.
</P>
<P>
   The news, both the good and the bad, emphasized the dangers
faced by relief workers. Over the last 20 years, 120 CARE employees
have died on the job _ many in accidents, but some from gunfire and
land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who recently returned from a trip to Cambodia, India and
Nepal, said the sense of purpose of the staff members impressed him
_ not only in those countries, but in other dangerous venues such
as Somalia, Sudan, Sierra Leone and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their dedication is humbling,'' he said. ``It really is
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
