<SLUG> BC-FITNESSVIDEOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME EX 101: FINDING THE BEST OF THE NEW FITNESS VIDEOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New fitness videos pop up on store shelves like mushrooms _ a
new crop can appear overnight. It's hard to keep up with the
trends, and it's even harder to figure out what is worth buying.
</P>
<P>
   But it's that new-start time of year, and I had a goal: Find the
newest workout videos, check out the latest trends, and figure out
what's worth the money and the wear on my VCR.
</P>
<P>
   This study is highly unscientific _ I couldn't try every video
on the market, and I didn't use them for an extended period to
gauge their long-term effectiveness. I simply scooted back the
comfy couch, popped in the videos in random order, and worked out
like it was 1999. Which it was.
</P>
<P>
   What I learned: Not all fitness videos are created equal _ there
are plenty of losers on the shelves. I was most unimpressed by
``Tai Funk Aerobics,'' the latest in MTV's popular Grind Workout
series. ``Tai Funk'' features boy-group C Note, and, being older
than 14, I was not impressed when they burst into song at the end
of the workout. Next, I tried a new video from the Living Yoga
series. The box clearly says ``for beginners'' _ but when the
instructor neatly tucked her leg behind her ear and serenely
smiled, this beginner gave up and just plopped down on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Below, a sampling of the videos that seem worth the effort _ and
why:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Crunch Boot Camp Training''
</P>
<P>
   Instructor: Susan L. Hitzman, an exercise physiologist,
certified instructor and trainer.
</P>
<P>
   What it is: One of the latest additions to the series developed
by Crunch gyms. Four 71/2-minute segments are designed to condition
muscles and provide a cardio workout; but even though the video is
in segments, it's a nonstop 30-minute workout. Muscle-toning
exercises require light weights.
</P>
<P>
   Why it's worth your time: ``Boot Camp'' is like going to a class
at the gym; it's mostly low-impact and fun. Hitzman is easy to
follow, and she introduces some push-up variations that are
frustrating but effective.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance factor: The video box says Hitzman's favorite binge
food is vanilla yogurt and cottage cheese, but she's not as
obnoxious as she sounds. A warning, though: if you find the idea of
fitness boot camp a little cheesy, the ``now we're soldiers'' theme
may get to you after a few workouts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna Richardson 3-Day Rotation 2000''
</P>
<P>
   Instructor: Donna Richardson, a fitness guru who is also a
national aerobic champion and the spokeswoman for the American
Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   What it is: The three 20-minute segments are designed to be
rotated each day, but you might prefer to do all three in one
session. ``Kick and Jab'' focuses on kickboxing and ``Circuit
Toning'' targets muscle groups throughout the body (some light
weights are needed for this one). The last segment, ``Dance
Aerobics,'' is a cardio workout _ but mostly, it's a dance party
with flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Why it's worth your time: Although most of the moves aren't any
more challenging than a beginning aerobics class, Richardson's
workout is solid and smart. Each segment has a warmup and
cool-down, and the moves are safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance factor: Slight. For the most part, Richardson's
enthusiasm is infectious, not forced and tiresome. Go through the
tape a few times, though, and you might criny time
Richardson flashes a sugary smile and says, ``I've got your back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Crunch Workout's Tae Boxing''
</P>
<P>
   Instructor: Billy Blanks, martial arts champion and inventor of
still-trendy Tae-Bo.
</P>
<P>
   What it is: The first segment, ``Kickology,'' covers kicking and
boxing moves for beginners. Once you've got that down, you move on
to the second part, ``Tae Boxing Jam,'' which moves faster and uses
many of the moves from Tae-Bo.
</P>
<P>
   Why it's worth your time: As with Tae-Bo, this workout makes you
feel strong. ``Tae Boxing Jam'' tones all major areas of the body,
burning calories and fat. There's lots of kicking involved, which
feels great. But be ready to concentrate: Blanks isn't as easy to
follow here as he is in his own line of videos.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance factor: Very little to complain about here. Blanks is
clearly a fitness professional, not a cheerleader _ he's serious.
If you're mostly just interested in learning Tae-Bo, though, you're
better off buying the official videos instead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Method: Cardio Boot Camp''
</P>
<P>
   Instructor: Tracey Mallett, a cable fitness show instructor and
a Pilates instructor in California.
</P>
<P>
   What it is: Three 15-minute workouts that combine moves from
martial arts, dance and military-style conditioning. ``Cardio Boot
Camp'' is the latest in The Method series.
</P>
<P>
   Why it's worth your time: The workout is high-energy throughout.
It's complicated enough to keep your attention, but it's simple
enough that you can do it the first time. And it feels so good to
throw those punches.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance factor: If super-charged enthusiasm turns you off,
avoid this video. However, Mallett's accent is charming; push-ups
seem so much more exotic when she drawls out, ``Make sure the
ellllbow is in line with the shooooulder.'' Furthermore, this is
the only video I tried in which the backup group isn't constantly
yelling out, ``Woohoo!'' and ``I can feel it!'' There's something
to be said for that.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
