<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5553 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-KIOWAS-BOOK-TEX     01-03 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIOWAS-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZE A PATH TO `RAINY MOUNTAIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way to Rainy Mountain''
</P>
<P>
   by N. Scott Momaday
</P>
<P>
   American Indian Mythology
</P>
<P>
   University of New Mexico Press, $8.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hillerman knows a lot about how to make American Indian
culture and mythology interesting to an eclectic audience; his
dozen bestselling mystery novels featuring Navajo policemen Joe
Leaphorn and Jim Chee are ample testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillerman also recognizes these same themes come across in
their most pristine form when presented as close to the source as
possible. That's why he recommends N. Scott Momaday's ``The Way to
Rainy Mountain'' to every reader who has enjoyed Hillerman's tales
of Leaphorn and Chee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momaday's ability to use plain, elegant language sets him
apart,'' Hillerman says. ``He's (Kiowa) himself, and his respect
for the tribe's old customs and religion comes through in every
word. Because he cares, he makes the reader care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way to Rainy Mountain'' is far from Momaday's best-known
work. That distinction belongs to his novel ``House Made of Dawn,''
which won the Pulitzer Prize in 1969. But ``Rainy Mountain,'' based
on his tribe's history, may be the work closest to the author's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtaposing tribal legend with real-life travel, Momaday begins
with remembrances of Aho, his late grandmother, who ``belonged to
the last culture to evolve in North America.'' Aho followed the old
ways, and encouraged her grandson to do the same. Ten years old in
1890, when U.S. soldiers would not allow reservation Kiowas to
enact their beloved Sun Dance ceremony, Aho prayed to tribal god
Tai-me all her life, and when she died was buried at the foot of
what her people call ``Rainy Mountain'' in Oklahoma's Wichita
Range.
</P>
<P>
   In Momaday's skillful hands, Kiowa legends about tribal origins
blend smoothly with history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything had to begin,'' the old tale goes, and the Kiowa
tribe entered the world through a hollow log in what is now called
the American Northwest. After a few people had come through the
log, a woman got stuck and no one else could squeeze past her. That
is why the Kiowas ``are a tribe small in number.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the better part of two centuries, beginning in the 1600s,
the tribe gradually moved south and east. Its people evolved from
survivors of mountain life to worshippers of the sun they found
beating down on the Great Plains. Although their animal companions
included only dogs, they took quickly to horses and horseback
riding, becoming proud of their ability to raid other Plains tribes
for mounts.
</P>
<P>
   Their folklore reflected this, and also the lands in which they
traveled before eventually winding up mostly in Kansas, Nebraska
and Oklahoma. Devil's Tower, the square-topped mountain in the
Black Hills that later would figure prominently in Steven
Spielberg's ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' is especially
key.
</P>
<P>
   But Rainy Mountain is most important, as elemental to Kiowa
beliefs as the stable in Bethlehem is to Christianity. It is the
place the tribe was led to by Tai-me, a bird/man who came to the
Kiowas just when it seemed their migration would stall amid despair
and starvation. In addition to its physical manifestation in
Oklahoma, Momaday writes, Rainy Mountain and the path leading there
``is pre-eminently the history of an idea, man's idea of himself
... and of course the idea itself, as crucial and complete as it
ever was. That is the miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, amid tales of ``grandmother spider'' and ``the
storm spirit'' and ``a buffalo with horns of steel,'' a grand human
epic emerges. As Momaday notes, interspersing his own comments
between short tribal fables, the Kiowas remade themselves and their
culture, adapting to new places and circumstances and surviving
nicely until the encroachment of white settlers into the Southern
Plains. Even then, he notes, the tribe wouldn't have minded had the
newcomers considered war a sport rather than a means to completely
eradicate their enemies. When soldiers forbade the defeated Kiowas
from enacting the Sun Dance ceremony in 1890, it marked the end of
the tribe's ability to control its own culture, and, therefore, its
future.
</P>
<P>
   With an inexplicably low price of $8.95, ``The Way to Rainy
Mountain'' is a great purchase for readers who either love American
Indian history or simply enjoy perusing words set down by a fine
writer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Check out www.star-telegram.com/bookclub for more Celebrity Book
Club information.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
