<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox says not to Fox transmissions
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications last weekend stopped carrying the
signal of several big-market Fox TV stations as part of a larger
dispute between the two media giants.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, nearly 90,000 Cox Communications cable TV
subscribers in Dallas, Texas, could not see Fox's telecast of a
National Football League game between their hometown team and the
New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Cox Communications also stopped carrying the
signal of Fox stations in suburban Washington, D.C. and Cleveland.
In total, some 425,000 Cox Communications subscribers have lost
access to Fox television stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, the dispute remained unresolved. ``We're working
on trying to come to an agreement,'' said Cox Communications
spokeswoman Amy Cohen. ``But there are no active negotiations at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two seemed far apart as of Sunday. Fox took out ads
in the Washington Post that blamed Cox Communications for the lost
of its signal in the D.C. suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the dispute is how Cox Communications should
compensate Fox for the right to carry the signal of its 22 owned
and operated stations. Under federal law, Cox Communications is
required every three years to seek renewed consent from
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   The company has reached agreements with 99 percent of the
broadcasters in its systems, which serve some six million
subscribers nationwide. But Cox Communications has been unable to
strike an agreement with Fox, one of the world's largest TV
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is Fox won't give its consent unless Cox
Communications agrees to carry two new cable TV channels. The
channels are FXM, a moive channel, and Fox World Sports.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially tough right now to establish a new cable TV
channel, and Fox is infamous within the television industry for
such hardball tactics.
</P>
<P>
   While cable operators criticize Fox's negotiating tactics, they
also carry most of the programmers shows and channels, which
include Fox Family and FX.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has steadfastly refused Fox's terms for
renewing its retransmission agreement. The company wants to retain
control when and where it introduces any new channels.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Cox Communications announced Monday that it had
registered with the Securities &AMP; Exchange Commission to sell five
million of its 19.1 million shares of Sprint PCS. the registration
doesn't indicate when, if ever, the sale will take place.
</P>
<P>
   The company would not reveal its plans for the proceeds other
than to say it would be used for general corporate purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
