A5559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-Y2K-CZAR-HNS &LR;      01-03 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CZAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE HOUSE Y2K CHIEF DECLARES VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House Y2K chief John Koskinen declared
victory Monday after millions of Americans experienced few computer
problems as they returned to work and school for the first time in
the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view thisas a great accomplishment in meeting what I view
as the most significant management challenge the world has met in
the last 50 years,'' Koskinen said.
</P>
<P>
   He also defended himself against criticism that the federal
government overstated the significance of the Y2K computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt about the magnitude of the problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the world rolled over into the year 2000 this past
weekend, officials here and abroad have reported only a smattering
of Y2K computer failures. Some experts had feared the so-called Y2K
computer bug would cause widespread disruption in financial markets
and electric power-grids, especially in places like China and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   When Jan. 1 came and went without problems, officials then
warned that Y2K computer problems could crop up Monday when world
financial markets opened and millions of businesses transactions
were conducted for the first time since the holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But as of the end of the first business day of the year,
financial markets operated without a hitch, as did most other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A few minor problems, however, did pop up that are believed to
be Y2K related.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen reported that a Godiva chocolate store in New York City
opened for business without problems on Jan. 1. But when it opened
on Jan. 2 _ the start of its first work week in the new year _ a
Y2K glitch caused the cash registers to stop working. The registers
were fixed after a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's Bureau of Tobacco, Alcohol and
Firearms also has experienced computer problems since Jan. 1 when
the electronic link between gun dealers and the ATF went down. This
link allows gun dealers to electronically register guns with ATF.
The agency has since switched to a manual system. Koskinen stressed
that the ATF's computer problems do not affect background-check
systems.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Housing and Urban Development computer system
that handled Federal Housing Administration mortgages temporarily
went down, but it has since been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the glitches as evidence that the Y2K problem, indeed,
was real.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will show,'' Koskinen said, ``that the glitches that
continue to come out will continue to remind people that those are
glitches today that would have made major system failures'' if
government and private industry hadn't spent billions fixing their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department estimates that some $100 billion was
spent in the United States over the past five years to fix the Y2K
problem. The potential problem was posed by out-of-date computers
that could incorrectly interpret the digits 00 as 1900 rather than
2000, causing the computers to crash.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, is it estimated that governments and private industry
spent close to $400 billion fixing their computers. Koskinen put
the federal government's Y2K tab at $8.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We geared up for a major potential set of problems and I think
all of us view it as a great victory that we can sit here and talk
about, `Was it money well spent (and) did we have to do it?''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While declaring victory, Koskinen cautioned that Y2K glitches
would likely keep surfacing over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think a number of small retailers and small businesseswill
find some glitches but we don't think any of that is going to
accumulate in any way to have a noticeable economic effect on the
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's Y2K center _ which has been operating on a
24-hour basis since last Wednesday _ will scale back its operations
from about 400 people to a core staff of 30 next week. The center
will gear up again in February to monitor whether there are any
computers glitches on Feb. 29 _ a date that occurs only every four
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
