<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOTOX-YOUTH-TEX     01-03 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTOX-YOUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOT AT YOUTH: IT'S POISON, YES, BUT IT SMOOTHS THE WRINKLES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BOTOX-SIDE EFFECTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They can't frown effectively or reflect anger, surprise or
disapproval, but some celebrities are smiling over theibiological warfare weapon against wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you see her in concert, get out your binoculars
and focus in on Celine Dion's forehead. Insiders say the reason
it's frozen as smooth as vanilla ice cream is because she gets it
treated with Botox every six weeks or so.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted as the safest, least invasive and least expensive
treatment in anti-aging medicine, Botox is a weakened and purified
form of botulinum toxin, a bacteria that thrives in rotten meat and
causes food poisoning. Injections of the poison in the upper face
temporarily paralyze the muscles responsible for lines and
wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Botox injections are the latest extreme in how far women _ and
men _ will go to fight the aging effects of time and gravity.
Although doctors are currently using Botox to treat everything from
crossed eyes and sweaty armpits to twitchy vocal cords and migraine
headaches, it's the purely cosmetic use by dermatologists and
plastic surgeons _ a use still not approved by the FDA _ that has
skyrocketed in popularity, more than doubling from 1997 to 1998,
according to a survey conducted by the American Society of
Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, where the superficial is essential, rumors have it
that Cher, Madonna and Sylvester Stallone are all fighting
crow's-feet, forehead wrinkles and frown lines with Botox.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Rivers offers glowing testimonials to the deadly poison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had it done, and it's great,'' Rivers quips in last
summer's edition of Women's Quarterly magazine. ``True, it's a
voluntary muscle paralysis from a poisoned Fountain of Youth. If
the needle hits the wrong muscle, I can't close my eyes. Oh, well.
I'd only be awake for six months because then the treatment wears
off, and beauty demands fresh paralysis.''
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, the treatment is becoming increasingly popular
and is often used in conjunction with facial resurfacing or in
addition to collagen injections, which smooth out lines and
wrinkles around the mouth without immobilizing the lower face. Most
doctors won't inject Botox too far below the eyes because it can
limit the ability to smile, eat and talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has taken off. We have a lot of people who come in
for repeat treatments,'' says Molly registered nurse who
gives Botox injections at Southwest Cosmetic Dermatology
Associates. ``When we started, we did Botox injections one day each
month. Now we have a Botox day once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Two to six appointments are clustered together on Botox days
because the expensive poison is highly perishable and each vial
contains enough to treat up to six patients, depending on how many
sites (creases between the eyes, wrinkles across the forehead or
crow's feet at the outer corners of each eye) each wants treated.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is between $300 and $900, depending on how many areas
are treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people come in at lunch for Botox and go right back
to work. There's no down time,'' says Dr. James McCarty, a cosmetic
dermatologist who began offering his patients Botox about 2 1/2
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Patients leave the office with what looks like a tiny mosquito
bite at the site of injection and instructions to keep their heads
upright for four hours and make a few faces, stretching the muscles
to insure quick and even distribution of the paralyzing toxin. It
usually takes four to five days for the injected facial muscles to
relax completely and the crinkles they control to smooth out.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, a patient will get a droopy eyelid for a couple of
weeks, but the treatment is considered safe and without adverse
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Ophthalmologists and neurologists have used Botox for about 15
years to treat conditions characterized by uncontrolled twitching
or spastic muscles, including some complications of cerebral palsy
and stroke. It was first approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for marketing in this country for the treatment of
strabismus (crossed eyes) and blepharospasms (eye spasms) in 1989.
(Botox is still not FDA approved for the treatment of anything but
crossed eyes and muscle spasms.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a Canadian ophthalmologist who was using Botox to treat
eye spasms when one of her patients commented on how it smoothed
out her crow's feet. The ophthalmologist told her husband, a
dermatologist, and he began testing it on wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   In the same serendipitous way, Dr. William Binder, a facial
plastic and reconstructive surgeon, was using Botox injections on
wrinkles back in 1992, when several of his patients reported that
they were not bothered by migraine headaches in the months
following their Botox treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use a lot of Botox because I was the first one offering it
out here. Now everyone is using it,'' says Binder, clinical
professor of cosmetic surgery at UCLA and attending physician at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a huge patient population of starlets,'' Binder said in
a recent telephone visit. ``A lot of people in the soaps have been
doing Botox for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of Botox _ including those who admittedly can gain
financially through its use for cosmetic purposes _ say its ease
and effectiveness make it popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for things that work _ that are easy, safe
and have no down time. Botox fits right in with all of that,''
McCarty says.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty had his own forehead treated wix, and he loves
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've had it done, you will certainly want it again.
It's very addictive,'' he says. ``I think it surprised even me.
Most of us in dermatology grew up thinking all wrinkles are sun
damage, but these muscles get used to tightening into wrinkles and
sometimes result in a perpetual frown. If you keep up the Botox,
and the muscles get used to being relaxed instead of being
contracted, the effect can last a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Lavine, a Fort Worth plastic surgeon who offers Botox
injections, says the treatment is especially good for forehead
wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps improve the forehead wrinkles much better than
getting collagen injections, and it's really a less invasive
deal,'' Lavine says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everyone is a fan.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Potts, popular co-star of the Lifetime channel's ``Any Day
Now,'' says she tried Botox treatments. The former Designing
Womencast member didn't like it, though, because she couldn't lift
an eyebrow on demand during a photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's something to frown about.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: wwtelegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
