<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5566 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-BOTOX-SIDEEFFECTS-TEX     01-03 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTOX-SIDEEFFECTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTOX SIDE EFFECT A PLEASANT SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BOTOX-YOUTH) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When his patients first started telling Dr. William Binder that
the Botox injections he was giving them to remove lines and
wrinkles in their foreheads was relieving their migraine headaches,
he was incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a neurologist. I'm a facial plastic surgeon. I
specialize in rhinoplasty,'' says Binder, who first offered Botox
treatment for wrinkles in 1990 and began a study on volume
relationships for cosmetic purposes in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was injecting a lot of foreheads, and patients began coming
back with no headaches,'' he said in a telephone visit. ``My
patients first told me about their headaches going away before I
began looking into it. It took a two-year study for me to prove it
to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   A clinical professor of cosmetic surgery at the University of
California at Los Angeles and attending physician at Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center, Binder enlisted the help of three other physicians
to study his serendipitous finding further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contacted a professor of neurology at Columbia and several
other top doctors who were already using Botox for other
indications, and I said I have a cure for migraine, and they
laughed. I said, you try it and let me know what you find. If you
can't replicate my results, I'll go away. The studies took two
years, but their results were the same as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Botox shows ``significant usefulness in relieving
migraine headaches'' were first presented in April at the American
Academy of Neurology's annual meeting in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Binder then presented his initial study results in September at
the annual meeting of the American Academy of Otolaryngology/Head
and Neck Surgery in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   In his studies, involving 106 people, 60 percent of the patients
who were getting Botox injections for forehead wrinkles and who had
migraines experienced total relief of symptoms for an average of
three to five months, the same amount of time they experienced
wrinkle relief. Thirty percent had partial relief of at least 50
percent _ their migraines were cut in half both in number and
severity, Binder says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reasonable to suspect an effect on tension headaches
because we mistakenly think they are related to muscle contractions
or tension, but that's not true, anyway,'' Binder says. ``We don't
know why Botox works on migraines.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies are now under way in about a dozen large headache
clinics nationwide to identify which patients will benefit most
from Botox and determine whether the product should have Food and
Drug Administration approval for marketing as a migraine treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Botox cannot be promoted as a treatment for wrinkles
or headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, Botox was only known to be a muscle-relaxing
agent. Now we know it works through the parasympathetic nervous
system, and is related to sweating, smooth muscles and even some
skin conditions,'' Binder says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it definitely works differently on headaches than it
does on wrinkles,'' Binder says. ``It works even better on acute
migraine attacks. For patients experiencing a migraine crisis, I
can almost guarantee relief within an hour and 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
