u f BC-BIZMAGS04-COX     01-03 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forecasts for 2000 optimistic
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last big batch of economic and investment
forecasts for 2000 is showing up on the newsstands, and the message
is upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. economy, just off a spectacular 1999, is poised to
confound the pessimists again in 2000,'' says Business Week (Jan.
10) in its annual industry outlook edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth has averaged more than 4 percent for the past three
years, yet inflation has been dormant. ... Expect more good news in
2000, as companies find new ways to produce more with less,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy also means the bull market in stocks will
continue, say the editors of Barron's (Jan. 3).
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, the long-running party in U.S. equities will end, but
it may not be any time soon,'' the weekly says. ``As the new
millennium dawns, Wall Street seers predict another record-breaking
year for stocks. A robust economy will boost earnings, they say,
while restrained inflation keeps interest rates in check.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the question gnawing at investors today is how
long this crazy stock boom can last, says Money (January), in its
forecast 2000 edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, there's only one thing you need to know about the
market: Over a decade or longer, stock prices inevitably follow
corporate profit growth,'' says Money. ``And investors can expect
companies to keep boosting earnings, even if not at quite the same
rate they have achieved during the past five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Business Week: Two Atlanta executives are among the
magazine's ``top 25 managers of the year'': Arthur M. Blank,
president and chief executive of Home Depot, the Atlanta-based
retailer of home improvement products, and James P. Kelly, chief
executive officer of Atlanta-based United Parcel Service. Among
``managers to watch in 2000'' is Douglas Daft, tapped by Coca-Cola
to succeed M. Douglas Ivester at the helm of the world's biggest
soft drink firm.
</P>
<P>
   A century on Peachtree
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the Great Crash of 1929 may have devastated Wall
Street immediately, but its impact came more slowly to Peachtree
Street. The day after Black Tuesday, the monthly report of the
Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta noted ``a significant improvement
in business conditions.'' A day later the financial crisis competed
for front-page coverage with legendary golfer Bobby Jones,
participating in a convention.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few of the fascinating facts about Atlanta's
business, economic and political history in the 20th century, the
topic of Business-to-Business (January), an Atlanta business
magazine. The Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. is on the cover of the
magazine's ``millennium issue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   Inc. (January) offers readers a clue to what it's like to start
a business, with five stories of ``entrepreneurs in the trenches''
and what they had to go through to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Worth (Winter), a personal finance magazine, is out with a bonus
issue on ``Chic Tech,'' devoted to articles on a wide range of
technology products and to the stocks of companies that make them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
