<HEADER>
A5570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWDEN-COX     01-03 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWDEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowden in search of perfection
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Tucked away in his office, Florida State coach
Bobby Bowden keeps an empty picture frame that few people have
seen. Only a handful of friends and players know what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told some of us that he's saving that frame for a picture
of his first undefeated team,'' quarterback Chris Weinke said.
``Before the year, he asked us if we would be the one. I think it
was his way of challenging us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, 70, has accomplished almost everything in his 34 years
as a head coach. He is one of only five coaches in Division I
history to win 300 games. He won a national championship in 1993.
Only Penn State's Joe Paterno with 19 has won more bowl games than
Bowden's 16. Each of his last 13 teams has won 10 games or more, an
NCAA record.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Bowden has not done in his illustrious career is
go through an entire season undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say that's the one missing piece to my
career,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden could find that missing piece and in the process fill
that empty picture frame tonight when his No. 1-ranked Seminoles
(11-0) meet No. 2 Virginia Tech (11-0) in the Nokia Sugar Bowl in
the Louisiana Super Dome (8 p.m., ABC).
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in seven seasons, Bowden goes into a bowl
game for the national title. Bowden won in the 1993 season at the
Orange Bowl but lost the past two tries, in the 1996 season to
Florida State in the Sugar Bowl and to Tennessee in last season's
Fiesta Bowl. Bowden's family and friends, who have gathered here in
New Orleans, desperately want him win another title before the end
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy will joke about it, but I do feel a sense of urgency
from him about this game,'' said son Terry, the former head coach
at Auburn now an analyst for ABC. ``At this point in his life, he
doesn't know how many more chances he's going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden made light of his situation Monday during the final press
briefing before tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, people are going to say, `He's so old. When is he going to
win another one? Is it going to be before he dies?' '' Bowden said,
chuckling. ``I won't feel all that bad if we lose, but I know you
all will feel bad for me.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it has been a good week for the father of six and
the grandfather of 21. Both Terry and Tommy, the head coach at
Clemson, have been here to lend support. They remind him, not so
gently, that they both have undefeated seasons on their resumes.
Terry was 11-0 at Auburn in 1993. Tommy was 12-0 at Tulane in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, there's a lot of pressure on him,'' said Tommy Bowden,ame to New Orleans on Friday after his team lost to
Mississippi State in Atlanta in the Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl. ``We've
set a pretty high standard for him to live up to.''
</P>
<P>
   In 24 years at Florida State, eight of Bowden's teams have
finished with one loss. In 1996, the Seminoles went 11-0 during the
regular season but then lost to Florida in the Sugar Bowl 52-20 for
the national title. That's the closest Bowden has come to
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you realize how dadgum hard it is to go undefeated,''
he said. ``You've got to be good, but you also have to be lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's players and coaches have spoken very openly this
week about their desire to give Bowden the one gem missing from his
coaching crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can you think of that deserves this more than coach
Bowden?'' offensive coordinator Mark Richt asked. ``He has won so
much, but something has always kept him from being perfect. Now,
we've got a chance to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we want to win the national championship for
ourselves,'' defensive tackle Corey Simon said. ``But we would also
like to be remembered as the team that gave coach Bowden his first
undefeated season. That would be something that people would never
forget. That's really important to this group of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has 303 career wins and is on track to catch Alabama's
Bear Bryant, who leads the list with 323. Depending on longevity,
either he or Penn State's Joe Paterno (316 wins) will end their
careers as the top coach in the history of Division I.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get up there with coach Bryant, but if I can't get
Joe to retire, I'm probably going to finish behind him,'' Bowden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is another reason why Bowden wants to add an undefeated
season and the national championship that goes with it. A lot of
good coaches have won one national title. The list of those who
have won two or more is significantly shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy doesn't have to be in a class all by himself, but he
deserves to be in one where it doesn't take long to call the
roll,'' Terry Bowden said. ``Winning that second national
championship would put him in a very elite group. A lot of us think
he really belongs there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
