<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, Jan. 4. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
JEROME (Jerome, Ariz.) - Jerome, that old mining town atop a hill
in northern arizona, has long been a haven for hippies, who
resurrected it from a ghost town in the '60s. The flower children
effectively have run the town since. Now, bikers are claiming
Jerome as their own, occupying restaurants and shops and, in some
cases, moving into the town. The two groups are locked in a clash
of cultures, among others. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TCE (Phoenix) - A $24.5 million settlement is proposed in a civil
action involving TCE in the Phoenix area's groundwater. Dealing
with the same subject as the 1999 movie, ``A Civil Action,'' this
is one of the most important civil cases of the decade in the
Valley. Story will show how the lives of key people involved have
been affected by the groundwater pollutions and the suit. Three
major defendants including the city of Phoenix and Motorola are not
part of the settlement and remain in the lawsuits. By CHRIS FISCUS.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
