<HEADER>
A5574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-MATCHUPS-CO     01-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-MATCHUPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUGAR BOWL: FLORIDA STATE VS. VIRGINIA TECH
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When, where: 8 p.m. today, Superdome, New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ABC, with Brent Musburger, Gary Danielson, Jack Arute.
</P>
<P>
   Records, rankings: Florida State (11-0), the ACC champion, is
ranked No. 1 in both major polls; Virginia Tech (11-0), the Big
East champions, is ranked No. 2 in both polls.
</P>
<P>
   What's at stake: The winner of the game automatically will be
declared national champions by the ESPN/USA Today coaches poll. The
winner probably, but not automatically, will be declared national
champion in the Associated Press media poll.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Bobby Bowden is 303-85-4 overall, 230-53-4 in 24 years
at Florida State; Frank Beamer is 130-82-4 overall, 88-59-2 in 13
years at Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   GAME ANALYSIS
</P>
<P>
   RUSHING OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Florida State running back Travis Minor had 815 yards rushing
this season but usually plays well against ranked opponents. In 13
career games against Top 25 teams, Minor has averaged 97.2 yards.
Florida State averaged 112.8 rushing yards a game, 83rd in Division
I. Virginia Tech was eighth nationally in rushing offense,
averaging 253.9 yards per game. Running back Shyrone Stith ran for
1,119 yards and 13 touchdowns behind a solid offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: VIRGINIA TECH.
</P>
<P>
   PASSING OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Florida State's Chris Weinke (232/377, 3,103 yards, 25 TD) was
seventh in the nation in passing efficiency. Wide receiver Peter
Warrick (71 catches, 934 yards, 8 TD) was eighth nationally in
receiving yards per game (103.8). The Seminoles averaged 302.9
yards passing per game. Virginia Tech quarterback Michael Vick was
the nation's most efficient passer, with a rating of 180.4. Vick
finished third in the Heisman Trophy voting after gaining 2,425
yards in total offense and scoring 20 touchdowns. Wide receiver
Andrew Davis averaged 87.4 yards receiving per game.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA STATE.
</P>
<P>
   RUSHING DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Led by defensive tackle Corey Simon, Florida State was 12th
nationally in rushing defense, giving up 98.8 yards per game. The
Seminoles, not as strong against the run as in years past, have
been giving up about 3.4 yards per rushing attempt. Virginia Tech
was third nationally in rushing defense, giving up only 75.4 yards
per game and 2.2 yards per rush. Opponents converted only 25
percent of their third down attempts (41 of 167) against the
Virginia Tech defense, which led the Big East in every major
category.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: VIRGINIA TECH.
</P>
<P>
   PASSING DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Florida State led the nation with 22 interceptions. The
Seminoles allowed 205.8 yards passing per game but allowed only 13
touchdown passes all season. Virginia Tech ranked seventh
nationally in passing-efficiency defense, giving up 171.4 yards per
game and only 10 touchdown passes. The Hokies intercepted 10
passes. Defensive end Corey Moore, who had 17 sacks, is a major
factor in the pass defense.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: NONE.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has one of the top weapons in college football in
placekicker Sebastian Janikowski. Almost 70 percent of his kickoffs
were not returned. Janikowski made 23 of 30 field goals. Florida
State blocked six kicks this season. All-America wide receive Peter
Warrick might be used on some kick returns. Virginia Tech's special
teams suffered a major loss when punt returner Ricky Hall suffered
a broken bone in his foot during practice. Hall, who averaged 12.8
yards on 40 punt returns, is not expected to play. Placekicker
Shayne Graham, the Big East special-teams player of the year, has
converted a conference-record 97 consecutive extra points. He made
17 of 22 field goals during the regular season, including a
44-yarder as time expired to beat West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA STATE.
</P>
<P>
   COACHING
</P>
<P>
   This national championship game is the fourth this decade for
Florida State coach Bobby Bowden. Bowden wants what be his only
undefeated season. His staff has worked hard to get this team ready
after a 45-day layoff. Virginia Tech coach Frank Beamer has proved
to be one of the most solid coaches in college football. Offensive
coordinator Ricky Bustle is one of the rising stars in the game,
and defensive coordinator Bud Foster has turned down several
opportunities to leave Virginia Tech. The only thing missing is
big-game experience. ADVANTAGE: FLORIDA STATE.
</P>
<P>
   FINAL ANALYSIS
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech is a very talented and confident football team,
but the Hokies have not seen the kind of overall team speed,
especially on defense, of Florida State. Virginia Tech's Vick is
especially dangerous when he gets flushed out of the pocket and
outruns defenses, but he will not be able to do it as effectively
against Florida State. Florida State coaches have been saying
privately that this team is the most focused they have taken to a
bowl game in a long time and seems determined to deliver Bobby
Bowden's first undefeated season. The Seminoles will make one more
big play _ a punt return, a big pass or a long field goal _ and
that will be the difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   PREDICTION: FLORIDA STATE 28, VIRGINIA TECH 24.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
