<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OFF TO AN ODD START 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new century is off to a provocative start with
that sinful lame duck, President Clinton, seizing the initiative by
trumpeting a legislative agenda for his last year in power that
warns congressional Republicans he does not intend to go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   There are contradictory ways of looking at this.
</P>
<P>
   _ He is so blind to his own weaknesses he will end his
presidency as an aggressive but irrelevant nuisance who fatally
undercut the candidacies of his two political heirs, his wife
Hillary and his vice president, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   _ He is smarter than the clueless Republican conservatives who
threw away their majority advantage with an unpopular impeachment
drive and an extravagant tax cut that hardly anybody wanted. Now he
is continuing the ideological confrontation in hopes of making
Democrats look good and the GOP look bad in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   _ He can't help himself. He has spent his entire adult life
campaigning and he doesn't know how to do anything else. The
political focus may be on the presidential primaries, but he's
still the fat lady and his song isn't over yet. The winners of the
2000 presidential competition may represent the future, but Clinton
and his Republican opponents are the present. There is still a
leftover year to kill inside Washington's power circles. And
ambitious folks abhor a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Wasting no time, the president's agents rushed out to spread his
message during the first days of the new year. Among other
initiatives, he will propose targeted tax breaks to help people
without health insurance, more aid for education and poor families
and ways to prop up Social Security and Medicare. The Republicans,
missing an opportunity to regain the offensive, were still on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, not much is likely to be achieved in the nation's
capital. Partisan divisions perpetually hobble common sense and
compromise. The angry voters that produced the 1994 right-wing
revolution led by House Speaker Newt Gingrich are gone, as is that
hypocrite Gingrich himself. But widespread disdain for the act of
governing remains.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can be personally maddening, but the Republicans take
the trophy for professionally messing up. Although they narrowly
control both houses, they have not produced a popular agenda since
the balanced budget demolished their favorite message of pinching
fpennies. The country has moved on, but Republican
congressional leaders are mired in the old rhetoric and the notion
that their only duty is to block whatever Clinton wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of measurable legislative progress, however,
noise matters. And a president, speaking with one voice, can
dominate the debate with opposition leaders babbling in many
voices. As Senate Minority Leader Trent Lott says, unifying his
partisan troops is often like herding cats.
</P>
<P>
   His problem helps explain why the Democrats are on the verge of
taking back control of the House, if not the Senate. A shift of
only five seats will enable Minority Leader Richard Gephardt to
become speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are scrambling. But the Democrats have been more
successful in persuading incumbents to stay on, adding the campaign
advantage of constituent familiarity and the implication of victory
in the air.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the Pew Research Center reported that 49
percent surveyed said they would vote for their district's
Democratic candidate while 43 percent would vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   A voter's identification with a party can be changed later by
the pull of presidential nominees or the strength of individual
congressional candidates or last-minute issues. But the survey
provides a good clue.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew poll also showed that Republican Party approval ratings
stand at 53 percent favorable and 43 percent unfavorable, compared
with Democratic standings of 59 percent favorable and 37 percent
unfavorable. In 1994, the year the GOP took over Congress, that
party's favorable rating was 67 percent, its unfavorable rating,
only 27 percent. The Democrats, by contrast, had only a 50 percent
favorable rating and a 44 percent unfavorable ranking. There's a
substantial trend at work here.
</P>
<P>
   At this early point, the surface congresssiional campaigns are
being carried out on a separate track from the presidential
primaries. (Helping hands behind the scenes are a different
matter.)
</P>
<P>
   All the presidential candidates, in fact, behave as though they
never heard of Congress. They are going to save the world all by
themselves once they're in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The interests of presidential and congressional candidates have
yet to converge. After the bulk of the presidential contests are
over in late March, when the nominee choices will be obvious, the
dynamics will change. It will be pretty much all for one and one
for all within each party _ so long as the local constituents can
swallow the party's choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Clinton still has a voice and a platform. The
Constitution doesn't say a disgraced president who has no shame
can't use both.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
