<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-PLAYOFF-ANALYSIS-     01-03 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLAYOFF-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road to Atlanta bumpier for Jacksonville
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The march to Super Bowl XXXIV in the Georgia Dome
still goes through Jacksonville, Fla., but the Jaguars are facing a
few more obstacles than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville on Monday lost Pro Bowl offensive tackle Tony
Boselli, who tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee
in Sunday's 24-7 victory over the Bengals. Boselli will miss the
playoffs and faces seven months of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our share of injuries, and this is another,''
Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin said. ``Obviously, it's a huge blow to
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars (14-2) can certainly use the bye week they secured
by finishing with the NFL's best record. Jacksonville won't play
until hosting an AFC divisional playoff game on Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Mark Brunell missed the Cincinnati game
with a sprained left knee, but he hopes to practice Wednesday.
Right offensive tackle Leon Searcy (high ankle sprain), another Pro
Bowler, and rookie cornerback Fernando Bryant (hamstring) also were
hurt against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Searcy said. ``It's a little disturbing.
All our hard work will go in vain if we don't make the most of it.
This bye week will give a lot of guys an opportunity to get
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars also seemed to lack the killer instinct late in the
season. They struggled in a 24-14 victory at lowly Cleveland on
Dec. 19, were blown out by the Titans the next week and squandered
several opportunities against the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cincinnati game, the Jaguars made six trips inside the
Bengals' 20-yard line but scored only three touchdowns, with two
missed field goals and a lost fumble in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year long, people have been questioning whether we're this
or that or whether we have the right chemistry,'' Jacksonville
linebacker Lonnie Marts said. ``I could (not) care less about that.
That's naysayers. It takes a lot of courage and scrap to win 14
games in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   It might take even more grit for the Jaguars to play in the
Super Bowl. They probably will face a long, tough road, despite
being the AFC's top seed and having home-field advantage throughout
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If the Titans beat the Bills and the Seahawks beat the Dolphins
in AFC wild-card games this weekend, Jacksonville hosts Tennessee
in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   And Tennessee could be a daunting assignment. BoJacksonville's losses this season came against the Titans _ 20-19
on Sept. 26 and 41-14 in Nashville on Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans have won four games in a row and seem to be peaking.
With Sunday's 47-36 victory at Pittsburgh, Tennessee scored 40
points in consecutive games for the first time since 1961, a span
of 552 games.
</P>
<P>
   Titans quarterback Steve McNair, who missed five games in
midseason after undergoing back surgery, has thrown six touchdowns
while playing just more than five quarters the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big-time,'' Titans strong safety Blaine Bishop said.
``We're going in with momentum, and we've got to continue to win.
It's the playoffs now, and we know that once you lose it's over.
Every play is crucial, and this gives us more confidence going in
that we can't be beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Colts will be a sizable favorite over the
Dolphins-Seahawks winner in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills have won three games in a row, including a 31-6
blowout of Indianapolis on Sunday. But Buffalo would probably have
to win three games on the road to advance to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC, the Cowboys-Vikings winner must slay St. Louis, the
NFC's top seed, in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (11-5), which won eight of its last nine games, might
have an easier route to Atlanta. The Bucs face the Lions-Redskins
winner in a second-round game on Jan. 15. Detroit has lost four
games in a row, and Washington surrendered 41 more points than any
other playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers are 13-3 in games at Raymond James Stadium the
past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bucs defensive tackle Warren Sapp said, ``I pity the fool who
has to come to Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
