<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOTERO-DONATE-ART-2TA     01-03 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOTERO-DONATE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDELLIN HOPES GIFT FROM FAMOUS SON WILL CHANGE ITS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 13 and 14 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDELLIN, Colombia _ Just the mention of this city conjures up
images of drug cartels, guerrillas and gangs of kidnappers and
hired killers.
</P>
<P>
   But Medellin is also the hometown of Fernando Botero, 67, Latin
America's most celebrated living artist, and he is now putting the
full force of his renown behind a wide-ranging effort to overhaul
the city's reputation and skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months the painter and sculptor intends to
install 79 of his paintings, drawings and sculptures that he has
just donated to the Museo de Antioquia here. The gift by Botero,
who spends most of his time in Italy, will make the collection the
largest of his work anywhere, and the local authorities hope it
will be a new calling card for this metropolis of 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Botero's gesture is very important to us,'' said Juan Gomez
Martinez, the mayor, ``because it makes it possible for us to
undertake a process of physical and spiritual recovery, and so we
are grateful to him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a city known around the world for all the wrong
reasons, stigmatized for all the problems we have had, but now we
have an opportunity to be known culturally, to have people think of
us as the city of Botero,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Museo de Antioquia, which takes its name from the province
of which Medellin is the capital, already had an impressive
assemblage of pieces by Botero, whose work is instantly
recognizable for the extravagant corpulence of his subjects. Since
the late 1970s, two galleries have housed 16 of his sculptures and
16 paintings, including ``Miss Rubens,'' a sly satire on his
penchant for fleshy figures, and a chilling 1977 portrait called
``Minister of War.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist donated those works in memory of his young son Pedro,
who was killed in an automobile accident in 1974 and whose name has
been given to the section of the museum in which the works are
exhibited. Museum staff members had always hoped that he would make
the institution the permanent repository for the bulk of his other
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Botero is a very important part of our cultural identity, so
of course we have always wanted him here,'' said Pilar Velilla
Moreno, the director. ``He may live in Italy, but he has never
stopped being from Antioquia for a single day of his life, so that
his work has always portrayed us and who we are: our customs,
architecture, food, landscapes, flowers, leading personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the larger Botero bequest, Medellin had to fend off
Bogota, the nation's capital, which had been even more aggressively
pursuing the artist.
</P>
<P>
   After officials here were slow to come up with a site, Botero in
fact donated 61 pieces from his collection, including works by
Picasso, Miro, Braque, Chagall, Degas, Matisse, Calder and
Giacometti and several of his own paintings, to the National Museum
in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medellin felt a bit let down when they lost that, but I
couldn't wait all my life,'' Botero said in a telephone interview
from his New York City studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things kept dragging out, and I wanted to do it right away. I
don't blame anybody, it wasn't ill will on anyone's part. It is
just that it is difficult and costly to find a piece of prime real
estate in a city of 2 million people, and I wasn't willing to wait
another 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Gomez and a senator from the province visited Botero in
Paris in an effort to persuade him not to leave his hometown
empty-handed. Anecture student in Medellin led a petition
drive that collected more than 150,000 signatures, which may have
been even more decisive in persuading the artist to collaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tremendously moved by that, because I love my native
region and want to do as much as I can for it,'' he said. ``I left
many years ago, long before all the problems started, and have
lived in New York, Paris, Monte Carlo and Italy. But I still feel a
great spiritual connection to Colombia and want, after all the
terrible things that have happened, to provide a bit of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Botero agreed, there were formidable bureaucratic
barriers to be overcome. Because the museum is a private, not a
public, institution, said Ms. Velilla, it is subject to a 16
percent tax and 20 percent tariff on imported ``cultural
material.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter that Botero was donating his own property and was
willing to make an additional grant of $1 million to help renovate
the museum. For insurance purposes, the value of his gift, 65
paintings and drawings and 14 large sculptures, had been declared
as $60 million, and government tax collectors wouldn't budge: They
wanted their share before the paintings and sculptures could be
sent to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, however, there was a change of government, with
both the new minister of culture and minister of finance being
natives of Antioquia. With their support, an accord was negotiated
that exempted Botero's donation from the tax levy, opening the way
for the first shipment of 15 pieces to arrive in January.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an absurd situation to have to pay an entry tax for
something that is going to benefit the people, but they assure me
that the problem has now been solved,'' Botero said. ``So I am
sending the biggest and most costly of my works as a showdown, and
we will see if that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Botero has also donated several large sculptures
to his hometown, and they are prominently displayed in downtown
plazas and have become local landmarks. ``If you have to arrange to
meet someone, you suggest getting together at `La Gorda' and
everyone knows exactly what you mean,'' said Marcela Restrepo, a
university student, referring to a statue of a fat woman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 one of the pieces, ``The Bird,'' was destroyed in a bomb
attack that killed 27 people and injured more than 200. None of
Colombia's leftist guerrilla groups, right-wing paramilitary death
squads or drug cartels took responsibility. But because Botero's
son Fernando Botero Zea was defense minister at the time and the
bird was the dove of peace, it has always been assumed that the
bombing was political.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the gift he is offering now, Botero made a
replacement for the bird, asking that it be placed next to the
pedestal where the blasted remains of his original sculpture still
sit. The result, installed in early December, is even more
powerful, Gomez argues, because ``we have a symbol of peace and a
symbol of war and barbarism side by side.''
</P>
<P>
   Botero said he planned to spend 10 to 15 days in Medellin to
welcome the arrival of the initial shipment and supervise the
installation of those works. He plans to return for the dedication
and opening of the complete Botero collection, which is tentatively
scheduled for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very enthusiastic about this project and think that we
can put together something extraordinary,'' he said. ``I have been
given full control to do what I want. I want the rooms to be
simple, to be minimalist, so that the focus will be on the art and
not on the room.'' To assure that, he said, he has been in contact
with architects and light technicians in both Medellin and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Botero's grant is part of a larger plan to revive a run-down
section of downtown Medellin and transform it into what he calls
``an open space that will change the skyline and allow the city to
breathe.'' The project, called Medellin Cultura Viva, envisions
turning the former city hall, built in Art Deco style, into an
extension of the museum and converting a nearby area frequented by
alcoholics, glue-sniffers and prostitutes into a sculpture park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a cultural complex with bookstores,
theaters, antique dealers, cinemas,'' Ms. Velilla said, ``and
Botero's contribution is the cornerstone of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the political situation in Colombia remains so unsettled and
violent that security, both for Botero and his works, continues to
be a major concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm going to have to go around with bodyguards and in an
armored car,'' he acknowledged. ``It's dangerous and not the kind
of life I want, but I still believe in Colombia. Eventually this
country will be civilized and have peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
