<HEADLINE>
ACTRESS' HEART-TO-HEART WITH HER DIRECTOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   C &UR; ourtney Love &LR;  ``interviews''  &UR; Milos Forman &LR; , her director in
``Man on the Moon,'' in the latest issue of Interview magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's so interesting,'' she says, ``that some of the
best men in my life ever _ you and  &UR; Michael &LR;  ( &UR; Stipe &LR; ) _ are
fascinated with  &UR; Andy Kaufman &LR; . And I'll admit it, I wasn't. My
late husband, Kurt, was also very fascinated with Andy; his
favorite R.E.M. song was `Man on the Moon.' I just think it's so
crazy and karmic. I mean here's this man I loved who died, and this
other man _ Michael _ who saved me from such misery, and this man,
you, who saved me from another misery, and it all sort of circles
around Andy. I don't know if that makes sense to anybt it is
so intense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make much sense to me,'' says Forman, who was
supposed to be the subject of the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't?'' asks Love.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important,'' says Forman, ``is that it makes sense to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the psychic network of life and the karmic
wheel,'' says Love, ``and I think you do, too.'' Says Forman, ``You
have a right to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending the interview after a soliloquy on whether she is vain or
not, Love offers, ``I just want to say that I think the new movie
is stunning and incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you are part of this film!'' says the director. ``Let
other people say these words! This is one thing that I am
idiosyncratic about. Because when I was living in a Communist
country, there were huge posters saying `Long Live the Communist
Party!' on every corner. And I thought, it's wonderful if somebody
else is telling you this, but if you are posting this yourself,
well, then it stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Elsewhere in the wide world of interviews,  &UR; James Woods &LR; 
shares his view of  &UR; President Clinton &LR;  with readers of Gear
magazine:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loathe, f_ loathe with every fiber my being, liars. ...
My second ex-wife was a liar. And Nixon was a liar. And this f_
Clinton is a liar. I have no respect for him no matter what in the
f_ world he ever does.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, when the interviewer asks Woods about his
intelligence, he says that in tests he took  &LR; in third grade, ``I
had the highest score in the history of my school system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD WORKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Recent Spirit of Freedom Awards ceremonies in Aspen honored
 &UR; Goldie Hawn &LR; , raised money for the Tibet Fund and were emceed by
 &UR; Ivana Trump &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post says the jewelry company that sponsored the
event is planning to sue a Miami-based firm that promised that
 &UR; Richard Gere &LR;  and  &UR; Ricky Martin &LR;  would be there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PROSE OF ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A press release for a group show opening at the Haines Gallery
on January 11 includes the following information:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a duality to the work in this show in that there is a
tension that resonates from active surfaces and an intensity of
vision, while at the same time there is a quieter, meditative
element that stems from the process of creation. ... These are
luscious, sophisticated works which resonate with each artist's
distinctive approach to the process of creating art. The works in
this exhibition resonate within each viewer, and are examples of
serious works by artists that are not likely to remain
under-exhibited on the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, here's the show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREAT GRAPE IDEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Glue, a magazine about ``style and action in L.A.,'' reports on
Osseus Labyrint, a team of performance artists whose work consists
of ``movement and sound with no words,'' performed totally nude,
totally shaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of humor in what we do,'' says  &UR; Hannah Sim &LR; ,
``but because we are naked and vulnerable people are afraid to
laugh.'' The artists tried to break that barrier at a recent
performance ``when Sim punctuated the end of their performance by
popping a grape from'' an unusual place. The magazine calls that
trick ``unbridled self-expression.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in time. After all, we invented the calendar.
Nature's looking down saying, `Millennium what? What are you
talking about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rod Steiger in Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
