A5585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-COACHING-CHANGES-     01-03 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHING-CHANGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rhodes, Carroll among NFL departees
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It didn't take long for the NFL's firing season to
begin. Two coaches were fired and one retired Monday, the same day
the league's regular season officially ended.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise was the firing of Packers coach Ray Rhodes,
who led his team to an 8-8 record in his first season in Green Bay.
The Packers crushed the Cardinals 49-24 on Sunday, but they missed
the playoffs when Dallas beat the Giants for the final NFC
wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired him to succeed,'' Packers general manager Ron Wolf
said of Rhodes, who had three years remaining on a $4 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he a different coach than I thought he was?,'' Wolf said.
``Yes. The answer to that is yes. But what we need to have is a
well-disciplined, tough, hard-nosed football team. That's how you
win in this league. We have to get that here. We don't have that
here.''
</P>
<P>
   New England coach Pete Carroll was dismissed after the Patriots
finished 8-8 by losing six of their final eight games. Carroll, who
had two years left on his contract, had a 27-21 record in three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a business of accountability, and two years ago we won
the division,'' Patriots owner Robert Kraft said. ``Last year, we
barely made the playoffs, and this year we're 8-8. We need a
momentum change.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft can't hire Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick, once
considered the favorite to replace Carroll. Belichick was named the
Jets' head coach after Bill Parcells retired. Parcells, 58, will
remain with the team as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were a popular pick to contend for a spot in the Super
Bowl this season, but injuries crippled the defending AFC East
champions. Quarterback Vinny Testaverde was lost in the opener when
he ruptured his Achilles' tendon, and the Jets started a woeful
1-6. But New York rallied to win seven of its last nine games to
finish 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who won two Super Bowls with the Giants and got to
another with the Patriots, had hedged about returning next season.
But he told the Jets his decision in a late-morning meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells read a poem titled ``The Man in the Glass,'' dropped a
microphone and left the silent room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stunned,'' Jets running back Curtis Martin said. ``A
lot of people didn't know what to think. I would imagine it was
emotional after being a head coach all those years and giving a
speech about leaving footr leaving after being a head coach
all your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Saints coach Mike Ditka canceled a news conference
Monday and won't address the media until after a meeting with owner
Tom Benson on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
