<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-INTERNET-MOVIES-ART-2     01-03 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MOVIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIE FILMS AND SHORTS FIND THE WEB A GOOD ALLY
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Okla. Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT15 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Gary Zeidenstein and Amine Bitar made
``Triangles and Tribulations,'' they encountered the usual brick
walls met by first-time independent filmmakers. They tried in vain
for a year to interest Hollywood studios in the 84-minute film,
about a man who sacrifices career and family in pursuit of his
dream to play the triangle in an orchestra. They tried entering it
in film festivals, but there was so much competition that they were
often rejected.
</P>
<P>
   So Zeidenstein and Bitar set up a Web site to publicize their
film and show it online. They also opened the site to other
filmmakers and were besieged with submissions. ``It just started to
snowball,'' said Zeidenstein, 34.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Always Independent Films (www.alwaysif.com) offers over
375 movies and trailers. It is one of at least two dozen sites
showing films as filmmakers flock to what could be a new means of
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Some independent filmmakers hope the Web will let them bypass
Hollywood and reach viewers directly. Or they hope to use the Web
to drum up huge publicity, as seen with ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' a low-budget amateur film that became a blockbuster in
movie theaters after generating a buzz with a clever and alluring
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Most independent filmmakers will never duplicate the success of
``Blair Witch,'' and there are drawbacks to distributing movies on
the Web, like particularly poor image quality and long transmission
times.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some experts predict the Internet will have a profound
effect on the movie business, especially when combined with new
digital video technology in which movies are shot on digital tape
instead of film and edited on personal computers. Together, digital
production and Internet distribution promise a sharp reduction in
the cost of making and distributing their product, allowing for an
explosion in filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you lower the bar, more voices can be heard and be
profitable,'' said Ray Price, president of American Zoetrope, the
studio owned by Francis Ford Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   Such a popularization has already happened in music, with garage
bands now distributing their music directly over the Web by using
the MP3 protocol. ``The whole indie film world is the next MP3
opportunity,'' said Joseph A. Cantwell, executive vice president
for new media at Bravo Networks, which runs the Independent Film
Channel on cable television and is developing a Web site to show
and sell films online.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet could also provide a market for short films, which
now have few outlets. Short films are more suitable for the Web
than full-length features because it take hours to download a long
film using a conventional personal computer modem. And many people
won't want to watch a full two-hour movie at a desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't know what to do with short films,'' said
William Azaroff, 29, whose first short film can be seen at
Atomfilms.com, which specializes in short films. ``Hopefully, the
Web will bring them back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is not yet a good place to see a movie. In addition
to long download times, the picture is often blurry and appears in
a little box on the computer screen. And the movie sometimes
pauses, waiting for more of the signal to arrive. Such problems,
however, should diminish as more people get high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   There is also little or no money to be made by showing movies on
the Internet. Most Web sites do not pay filmmakers for their movies
because many are happy just to get the exposure. And most sites do
not charge viewers to see the movies, hoping instead to support
themselves with advertising. Some of the sites plan pay-per-view
services or offer videocassettes for sale. But it is far from
certain that any of the movie sites will be self-supporting.
</P>
<P>
   One site that does charge viewers, Sightsound.com, allows people
to view a film for a day or a few days for a price similar to those
at a video store. Its most popular title, ``The Perfect 10 Model of
the Year'' video, is rented about 60 times a month, fewer than a
hit movie at a single Blockbuster outlet. In April the site offered
the movie ``Pi,'' which had been in theaters, and fewer than 200
people viewed it.
</P>
<P>
   One way around the technical limits of the Internet is to use it
to sell videocassettes. Sam Sokolow and Rob Lobl, fledgling
filmmakers in New York, have sold more than 800 copies of their
first film, ``The Definite Maybe'' on Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   It cost them about $2,000 to have the cassettes and cover art
made and to set up a Web site for their film with a link to Amazon.
The tape sells for $14.95, and they keep about $5 after expenses,
or a total so far of over $4,000. This has not gone very far toward
recovering the $100,000 it cost to make the movie. But Sokolow said
the exposure helped them land another job directing a sitcom for a
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sidestepping the whole movie business,'' Sokolow said.
``I don't need Hollywood anymore to have 35 million people take a
look.''
</P>
<P>
   For most budding filmmakers, having the film appear on the Web
is not an end in itself, merely a stepping stone to the more
established entertainment world.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day they'd like to be seen on a TV screen or
even better in a theater,'' said Mika Salmi, president of
AtomFilms, which is based in Seattle and receives 50 to 100 films a
week.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Todd Lincoln, a 23-year-old from Tulsa, Okla., parlayed his
exposure on the Web into a job making music videos. ``There's just
a lot of people watching the progress of films on there,'' he said.
``It's just a real kind of digital democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln made two films, ``Honeypot'' and ``Xavier,'' that are
among the most widely watched on Ifilm.com, a site in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   While most of its films can be viewed by the public, Ifilm also
set up a separate site, Ifilmpro.com, that can be seen only by
movie industry professionals and is a conduit for filmmakers who
are trying to shop their films around.
</P>
<P>
   The first film put on that site, ``Sunday's Game,'' is a
nine-minute dark comedy about elderly women who gather on a Sunday
and play Russian roulette. David Garrett, a writer and producer of
the film, said he and his partner, Jason Ward, had received many
inquiries since the film appeared and had closed a deal to produce
a pilot for Fox TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the Internet exposure definitely increased our
visibility and got people talking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the odds are very long. Ifilm can point to only a handful
of success stories among the 1,000 films it shows. Always
Independent Films says that three films on its site have attracted
distributors, including Zeidenstein's ``Triangles and
Tribulations.'' It was licensed by a company that will try to place
it in video stores.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the very advantage of the Web _ its low
barrier to entry _ is also a disadvantage because so many films are
being shown there that it is hard for one to rise above the crowd.
And having a film freely available on the Web can discourage a
profit-minded distributor from picking it up. Then there is the
image quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people's first exposure to it, if we think we
can make a sale, to be on the Web,'' said Azaroff, commenting on
the picture quality. He said he put ``Checkmating,'' his short film
from 1996 about a woman who sizes up potential boyfriends while
playing chess with them, on the Web because it was made mainly as a
calling card and had little chance of commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   Meher Gourjian said that it is mainly children who contact him
after seeing previews of his short film ``Plug'' on the Web. The
inquiries he has received from movie industry executives resulted
from festival screenings or his videocassette mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Making oneself heard on the Web can require aggressive
marketing. Two first-time filmmakers, Terry Keefe and Michael
Wechsler of Los Angeles, not only put trailers of their ``Slaves of
Hollywood'' on some movie Web sites but they also sent out hundreds
of e-mail messages with links to those sites.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe also used the Web site of the Chicago Sun Times to send an
e-mail to the critic Roger Ebert, who told him to send along the
film. ``I would never have gotten Roger Ebert any other way, and he
answered my e-mail in an hour,'' Keefe, 29, said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ebert has not reviewed the film, which is about the
abuses endured by Hollywood production assistants. And it was a
conventional test screening that got Filmopolis, a small
distributor, to agree to try to place the movie in theaters. It ran
for a week this fall in a single theater in Santa Monica, Calif.,
and might run for a weekend at a theater in New York in January.
</P>
<P>
   To get people to the theater, Keefe and Wechsler relied not on
the Net but on a more old-fashioned medium: flyers they posted
around town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
