<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5592 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BKN-ACC-SEC-COX     01-03 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ACC-SEC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC, ACC finally get down to business By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Florida State kicks off the 2000 ACC season, or,
rather, tips it off tonight against Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball Seminoles will have no television conflict with
their football brethren, however. To avoid the national
championship Sugar Bowl, the basketball team starts at 6 p.m.,
while the football 'Noles play at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC office swears that the game time was in place as early
as October, in order for the basketball game to avoid the Sugar
Bowl, no matter who would be playing.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, all nine ACC basketball teams and all 12 in the
SEC will have started league play, with all roads leading to
Indianapolis in March for the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Both leagues have been through a steady diet of Woffords, Elons,
Tennessee Techs, Mercers, High Points and Belmonts before the games
begin to count. Some teams have been warriors and have taken on top
programs. For instance, Kentucky has played Utah, Maryland,
Arizona, Indiana, Louisville, Michigan State and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Tubby Smith says it helps to find out early who you are and
strengthen your team.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, LSU has played _ and defeated _Grambling State,
Southeastern Louisiana, Oakland, Alcorn State, Tennessee-Martin,
Sam Houston State, Centenary, Nicholls State and Howard.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kentucky is 8-4 record, and Louisiana State has a
12-0 mark. But guess who will get the better NCAA seed, if both are
invited?
</P>
<P>
   Florida, ranked No. 6, has played and beaten New Hampshire,
Florida A&AMP;M, Bethune-Cookman, High Point, Rutgers, UNC-Wilmington
and VMI.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Donovan says some upper-echelon programs hesitate to play
the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has played 146 non-league games, but only 12 against
teams ranked in the Top 25, and Kentucky faced six of those in
compiling a 3-3 record. Georgia and LSU each had one win against a
Top 25 opponent: The Bulldogs beat then-ranked Wake Forest, and the
Tigers stopped Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC has played 104 non-conference games and went 7-10
against Top 25 teams.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina faced four teams in the Top 25; Duke, Maryland
and Florida State played three each; and Wake and N.C. State had
one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of competitive schedules even forced the ACC and Big 10
to come up with the ACC/Big 10 Challenge, a made-for-TV event that
pitted nine Big 10 teams against nine Big 10 teams. The ACC
squeaked out a 5-4 composite win.
</P>
<P>
   The polls, however, aren't reflecting the caliber of opposition.
In the AP poll, Auburn, for example, is ranked No. 4, yet the
Tigers lost to the only ranked team they played, Stanford. Auburn's
12-1 record is inflated by wins over UAB, Belmont, Coppin State,
Arkansas-Pine Bluff and Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   But now the games not only get tougher, they count more. Too
many losses in league play could cost a big NCAA pay check. Those
unskilled and unlucky programs could be relegated to making an NIT
appearance or, even worse, staying home.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
