<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-DOLE-HNS &LR;      01-03 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DOLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP HOPING DOLE ENDORSEMENT PROVIDES SPARK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a tougher-than-expected race in the early
primaries, the Bush campaign is hoping that an endorsement by
Elizabeth Dole will boost the Texas governor's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former Red Cross chief who dropped out of the
presidential race last fall, will announce her support of Bush on
Tuesday at an event in Bedford, N.H., his campaign confirmed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is honored to have her support,'' said Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan. ``Governor Bush looks forward to the announcement
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   After the New Hampshire event, Bush and Dole will fly to Iowa
and appear together at events in Des Moines, Davenport and Cedar
Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bush campaign had been negotiating with Dole for about
a month, the governors' aides said that no promises had been made
to secure her backing, including the prospect that she would be his
vice-presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, who quit the Dole campaign last summer and now is
a spokesman for Bush, said it would be premature for the governor
to talk about naming Dole as a running mate before the primaries
are over.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign believes that Dole's support will help with
women and independent voters who had been drawn to her campaign.
The Texas governor may need that additional support to overcome a
strong challenge by Sen. John McCain, R-Arizona, who polls show is
now beating Bush in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign dismissed the expected Dole announcement,
saying the Bush campaign specialized in collecting high-profile
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is another endorsement for the endorsement campaign. Our
campaign is about Senator McCain's reform message, not about our
bank account or list of endorsements,'' said McCain spokesman
Howard Opinsky, who noted that McCain's support rose when Dole
dropped out of the race in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't spend a lot of time courting Mrs. Dole. We would
have been happy to have her support. But we spent more time on
trying to win the support of her backers, and we have done that
successfully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has drawn the backing of most in the Republican
establishment, including a majority of GOP governors. But one
prominent Republican he has yet to snare is Elizabeth Dole's
husband, Bob Dole, the former Senate majority leader and
unsuccessful Republican presidential candidate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not prepared to endorse anyone just yet,'' said Bob
Dole's spokesman Doug MacKinnon.``The only thing the senator has
been saying is he is proud of the Republican field.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bob Dole stunned political observers and embarrassed
his wife by remarking that he would consider contributing to
McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elizabeth Dole enjoyed high voter interest when she
launched her presidential effort last winter, her campaign quickly
fizzled because of rocky management, a muddled message and an
inability to raise money. By the time she dropped out in October
she was registering in the single digits in New Hampshire polls.
</P>
<P>
   Since Dole dropped out, McCain has surged in New Hampshire. He
is making strong efforts there and in South Carolina, where his
campaign announced Monday it will air new radio and television
spots that feature the state's popular GOP congressman, Lindsey
Graham, touting the candidate's military credentials, Senate record
and character. Opinsky said McCain will soon start airing ads in
Michigan, where polls show he has cut into Bush's lead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
