<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-ART-TR     01-03 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S PRESIDENT UNDER PRESSURE TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Ezer Weizman, a crotchety outspoken
political veteran, faces pressure to resign over his endorsement of
an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights and revelations that
he has accepted substantial undisclosed financial gifts from a
French executive.
</P>
<P>
   A blunt opinionated man who has ignored the constraints of his
supposedly nonpartisan post, Weizman outraged the right wing last
week when he announced that he would ``go home'' in disappointment
if the public voted down an eventual Israeli-Syrian peace deal.
Several legislators demanded that he immediately resign instead.
</P>
<P>
   He came under fire again when an investigative journalist
revealed last Thursday that Weizman had received some $450,000 in
the form of monthly cash allowances between 1988 and 1993 from the
executive, Edouard Zaroussi.
</P>
<P>
   In those years, Weizman, who has been a public figure since the
state was born, was a legislator and Cabinet minister. The
journalist, Yoav Yitzhak, did not publish a story but called a news
conference to release his findings. He contended that Weizman had
broken the law by failing to report the money to the Parliament and
to the tax authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Weizman acknowledged receiving the money but
rejected the idea that he should have disclosed it. The statement
said the money was a personal gift from a friend who has no ties to
Israel, and that it was not considered taxable income by law.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zaroussi does not have known business ties here, he
does own a house here and has been linked with political and
business ventures here, according to Israeli news reports. He tried
to found an English-language newspaper here about 10 years ago, the
reports said. He could not be located for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The president's associates told Israeli newspapers that Zaroussi
gave Weizman the money partly to help finance medical care for
Weizman's son Shaul. As a soldier in 1970, Shaul Weizman suffered a
serious head wound from a sniper's bullet in the Suez Canal. He
died in 1991 in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein asked Weizman,
who is serving his second five-year term as Israel's seventh
president, to turn over all related financial documents. Weizman
said he welcomed the investigation, Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial Monday, Haaretz, a liberal newspaper, urged
Weizman to resign, saying that it didn't matter whether the gift
was legal or illegal and that politicians had faced trial for
receiving less substantial presents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public expects its representatives to make do with their
monthly salaries and not to be tempted by gifts,'' the newspaper
said. ``Nor was this a reasonable one-time gift that one friend
gives another: It was in fact a second, and very hefty, monthly
salary that was given to Weizman while he held a highly influential
public position.
</P>
<P>
   ``With high-ranking public positions,'' the editorial continued,
``it is impossible to come to consensus as to the distinction
between private gifts and those that are given for purposes of
bribery. Weizman must step down as president now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the political spectrum, Hatzofe, the
National Religious Party paper, also called Monday for his
resignation because of his unequivocal support for the peace
efforts being made by Prime Minister Ehud Barak. ``So Weizman is
threatening to resign?'' the editorial's long headline said.
``Another reason to vote against the withdrawal!''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a rich career, Weizman, a former air force
commander and hard-line defense minister, evolved from hawk to dove
and switched from the Likud Party to Labor. His blunt assessments
have skewered political figures across the board.
</P>
<P>
   But he is firmly entrenched in the political establishment. And
he has become almost beloved by some for his colorful irascibility.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition Likud Party leaders have been loath to exploit the
revelations, which is unusual here. Reuven Rivlin, a Likud
legislator, described the financial allegations as a ``private,
human story that should not be exploited for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's lawyer, Yaakov Weinroth, said that the president had a
``deep personal relationship with Mr. Zeroussi that does not have
to be publicized to the whole world.'' Weinroth said that Weizman
does not want to use his late son as a defense in discussions about
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not use the Shaul case, which is a very tragic case,
if it is true, or if it is not true'' that the money was intended
for his care, Weinroth said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Then Weizman's lawyer, who has represented prominent right-wing
politicians including Ariel Sharon and former prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, offered a qualified endorsement of his client,
the president. A radio reporter asked him if he would counsel
Weizman to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this specific issue, I would not advise him to resign,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some here speculate that there is a connection between the
timing of the 6-year-old financial revelations and Weizman's
partisan campaign for the Israeli-Syrian peace.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's outspokenness has been the hallmark of his six years
in the presidency, which was established as a position supposedly
above the political fray. It is hardly out of character for him to
have taken a clear public position on the Israeli-Syrian peace
talks. He has never been adverse to using the power of his platform
to sway public opinion. He purposefully butted heads with Netanyahu
and openly worked to elect Barak. He is considered by the right
wing, which used to count him as a member, as a leftist possessing
the extra ardor of a convert.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Weizman played a vital role in the
Israeli-Egyptian peace negotiations at Camp David as Israel's
defense minister. Today he has said that he feels Israel has
reached a similar critical juncture with Syria, and he has placed
the office of the presidency behind the emerging campaign in
support of Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights. Last week, he
actively lobbied Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, the spiritual leader of the
Shas political party, whose support is considered crucial.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's partisanship has brought calls not only for his
resignation but the dissolution of the office of the presidency.
Jewish settler leaders said he had stabbed them ``in the heart.''
They met him and demanded, echoing Barak's campaign promise, that
Weizman be the president of ``ev-er-y-body.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to be president of all the nation,'' Weizman
quipped. But he was serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1849EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
