<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL MATCHUP? NOT ACCORDING TO THE COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NENS _ So we're here for _ what? _ oh, yeah, the faux
National Championship Game, even though we can't actually call it
that since there really is no such official thing.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, no one has ever come up with any good reasons
why there isn't a more efficient system (the operative word back
there being ``good'') to determine a proper champion of Division 1A
football. The pooh-bahs have offered phony reasons, ludicrous
reasons, bogus reasons, and absolutely hypocritical reasons
(Academics? Puh-leeze), but never a good reason, not one.
</P>
<P>
   The National Championship Game in college football should pair
teams that have fought their way to this juncture on the field, be
it Astroturf or God's green grass. What we have now is a Florida
State-Virginia Tech game, courtesy of something called the Bowl
Championship Series computer! Now these may very well have been the
two best teams in college football this year, but that is not the
point. The system is the point. And the system smells.
</P>
<P>
   Would appointing an eight-team postseason field, selected in
very much the same way the at-large teams for the two Division 1
basketball tournaments are now chosen, be all that difficult? You
already know the answer to that. Wouldn't you rather have the field
selected by human beings with the aid of computers, if they can be
deemed useful, than have a computer actually spit out the identity
of the two finalists? Does a computer know from a key injury? Does
a computer know from weather? Does a computer know from a killer
bad call? No. All a computer knows is the final score, plus
whatever statistics you choose to feed into it.
</P>
<P>
   That all being said, a legitimate 1A football tournament is not
even on the proverbial radar screen, so we are stuck with this
cockeyed Bowl Championship Series format for years to come. They
may even have lucked out. The first Sugar Bowl of the mill _ Whoa!
May we agree to ditch the dreaded M-word? Make that century _ could
be pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   But you must understand something. This is no David-Goliath
deal. Florida State may be the reigning program of the '90s, with
the unbroken succession of Top 4 finishes and the relentless run of
10-win seasons, but this is hardly the greatest of all Florida
State teams. Circumstance dictates an awful lot in sports, and the
circumstances were very good for the Seminoles to enter the Sugar
Bowl as an unbeaten team. It's generally a given that they will run
the table in the ACC, and this year the Florida State nonleague
biggies weren't all that big. Specifically, Miami is good, but
hardly great, and Florida is basically in the same category.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Virginia Tech must be respected, if for no
other reason than the presence of a dangerous and explosive force
in freshman quarterback Michael Vick. Had I more guts I would have
emulated colleague Mark Blaudschun and done the right thing by
following my instincts and voting for this kid as the Heisman
Trophy winner. Sadly, I wimped out, giving him a third-place vote,
which, frankly, I thought was rather daring. It turned out that 24
other people were as sagacious as Mr. Blaudschun, making the rest
of us look pretty gutless. That wasn't a good way to conclude the
mill, er, century.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vick is a terror, and there is no reason to believe this
superb running and passing talent will freeze up in the spotlight
game.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech has much more to offer than Michael Vick. The
Hokies have every base covered, from offense to defense to special
teams, where they nright legendary. The only reason for
concern is an unfortunate practice injury sustained by standout
return man Ricky Hall, who broke a bone in his left foot Friday.
Hall is also a reliable receiver. At this level, true depth is a
must, so we will see about the Hokies in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't been paying attention, Virginia Tech is not
the Indiana State of football. Coach Frank Beamer has been there
long enough to construct a major program. You cannot get this far
unless you are very, very, shall we say, aggressive in pursuit of
your goal. In other words, you push envelopes, you cut those
corners closely, you take in some, um, borderline people if need
be. In Virginia Tech's case, you ride out very bad headlines when
some of your players are accused of rape, assault, and the like.
You don't kid anybody by pretendbe Oberlin. If you want to
play in the Bowl Championship Series title game, you must do what
the big boys do. If you're still playing college football on Jan.
4, you're no virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech has been hanging on the fringe of collegiate
football greatness for a few years now. The Hokies have even been
here before, having dusted off Texas in the 1995 Sugar Bowl. Of
course, that wasn't The Game, the way this one is. But this is no
one-shot program. These guys are big, quick, and nasty.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure is on Florida State, which, with all those Ws this
past decade, has but one cheesy and highly debatable national
championship and no undefeated teams in the entire Bobby Bowden
era. They may increase each of those totals Tuesday night, but they
will surely have to earn it in what will have to suffice as a
National Championship Game until common sense pravails and we get a
real one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
