<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUSSIA-MUSEUM-2TAKES(     01-03 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MUSEUM-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SIBERIA, THE WORLD MOVES IN WITH LENIN'S LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SOPHIA KISHKOVSKY 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRASNOYARSK, Russia _ Not that long ago it was one of Russia's
largest Lenin museums, five stories devoted solely to the first
Soviet leader and his Communist state. It is now one of Russia's
most unconventional, multifaceted museums, serving not Moscow or
St. Petersburg but a swath of Siberia better known for
concentration camps than culture.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was completed in 1987 to commemorate Lenin's exile in
this region by Czar Nicholas II. When the curtain went down on
communism, officials considered turning the building into a
commodities exchange or a Siberian nature museum. Today, thanks to
its director, a philosophy professor, and a staff of young
architects and intellectuals, it is the Krasnoyarsk Museum and
Historical Center and the region's cultural heart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the Council of Europe designated it the best museum in
Europe _ all of Russia being considered Europe _ although
geographically Krasnoyarsk is in Asia. The museum topped 60 other
candidates, including Moscow's Tretyakov Gallery, one of seven
Russian entries.
</P>
<P>
   The staff, by all accounts, achieved something of a miracle in
turning the Lenin Museum into a contemporary museum, said Patrick
Greene, director of the Museum of Science and Industry in
Manchester, England, who was one of the judges. ``In Krasnoyarsk we
saw an exhibition of quality we would be proud to show here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Shoubsky was teaching Marxism-Leninism in 1991 when he
was appointed director of the white elephant. It was the spring
before the collapse of the Soviet Union, and attendance was down to
a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want this job. No one wanted this job,'' said
Shoubsky, who with his bald pate and goatee looks a bit like Lenin.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the deal, he was promised the apartment his family
desperately needed. With Lenin and his ideology losing favor,
Shoubsky counted on plenty of time to complete a dissertation on
his true love, Russian religious philosophy. He got his apartment
ae his dissertation but found hardly any time to spend at
home. He had to master a new specialty: modern museum management in
a fledgling capitalist economy.
</P>
<P>
   As director, he oversees up to 100 new exhibitions a year on
subjects as diverse as Siberian history, the war in Chechnya and
modern art. Many are interactive multimedia displays.
</P>
<P>
   To help finance the museum's operations, he rents out space for
everything from cat shows to political meetings. The Communist
Party leader, Gennadi A. Zyuganov, for example, pays for space when
he comes to Krasnoyarsk and holds a news conference there. In 1999
the museum raised more than $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   While money remains a problem, Krasnoyarsk has managed to start
up a successful biennial exhibition. The third, held in September,
included exhibits from nearly 80 museums from across Russia and
several from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our idea was that the museum is not a preserver of the ancient
but is something that must develop,'' Shoubsky said. ``It must
attract cultures, subcultures and youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Of major Lenin museums (it retains its Lenin collection),
Krasnoyarsk's is the only one to draw crowds in post-Communist
Russia. In 1999 nearly 500,000 people visited the museum, though
Krasnoyarsk has a population of just 1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are scrambling to keep pace. Last year Krasnoyarsk's
governor, Gen. Alexander Lebed, not a fan of modern art, sponsored
a biennial prize for loyalty to traditional museum values.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from the stereotype of Russian provincial museums,
which are generally viewed as musty, dusty guardians of an ossified
past controlled by a stodgy culture ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The region's bumpy history offers some creative advantages,
Shoubsky said. The region is a melting pot of Poles, Lithuanians
and ethnic groups from the Caucasus deported by various regimes,
and Siberia has hundreds of indigenous ethnicities. The Jewish
Agency for Israel keeps its local offices in the museum. The mix is
reflected in the museum's exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The biennial drew attention to other provincial museums that
could not compete with those in Moscow and St. Petersburg but are
showing creativity and resourcefulness. An exhibit from Togliatti,
an auto industry city on the Volga River, took visitors through a
maze of aggressive words and images depicting the horrors of drug
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Many art critics complained that it was not so much an art
exhibit as an attempt at social outreach, but the young came in
droves. Young people are also drawn to clubs and concerts in the
museum, and to a new department at a local university that trains
museum workers.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lenin has been erased or evicted. A 65-ton statue of
``Lenin and His Brothers-in-Arms,'' too heavy to move, stands in
the cathedral-ceilinged foyer. So the museum designers work around
Lenin and with him. Turn any corner in the mazelike split-level
building and Lenin is there, his image rendered on carpets,
paintings and statues, his words carved into the marble walls.
Shoubsky says that's the way it should be.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't destroy the past,'' he said. ``We're not trying to
turn it into something political. We don't say that Lenin is bad.
Lenin is a subject with which we often hold a dialogue in artistic
language.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last fall Lenin and his comrades were surrounded by children's
paintings and whimsical paper-and-tape sculptures of that other
national symbol, the 19th-century poet Alexander Pushkin. A
graceful wooden footbridge led up from the statue, alluding to the
``bright future'' Lenin promised.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The museum also organized an exhibition of Moscow
conceptualists, with works ranging from stylized reproductions of
Russian Orthodox icons with blank spots where the faces of saints
should be to mangled teddy bears to stark photographs depicting
what might be bearded terrorists beating a child, or might just be
roughhousing.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many were angered by the exhibition, but iconoclasm is not the
museum's main emphasis. One of the most successful exhibits last
year, said Shoubsky, featured traditional Orthodox iconography.
</P>
<P>
   As the museum has evolved, some staff members have left. But
encouraged by Shoubsky's philosophical, tolerant bent, many of the
original members stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The museum has some typical Soviet drawbacks, like a leaky roof.
The impenetrable walls were not suitable for hanging works and
museum equipment was unavailable in Russia, so Sergei Kovalevsky,
the museum's deputy director and a professor of architecture, and
other designers created portable aluminum structures. The solution
was practical and cheap, as aluminum is the local industry.
Recently they have designed interlocking wooden pieces like the
bridge in the foyer, and they are taking orders from other Russian
museums at their new wood shop on the site.
</P>
<P>
   So Kovalevsky possibilities in hardship. ``Frank Gehry is now
rich, but he became famous on the aesthetic of poverty,'' he said.
``He made art from garbage _ that's why he is attractive to us. The
role of the museum is to take simple objects and show their
essence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
