<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-BOS     01-03 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETIC PARCELLS TURNS JETS OVER TO BELICHICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Bill Parcells read a poem.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning that Parcells gathered his New York Jets players
at Weeb Ewbank Hall on the campus of Hofstra University to tell
them of his retirement fromng, he recited, ``The Man in The
Glass,'' to explain the ever-present ``Why?'' that has defined
these moments with the Giants, the Patriots, and now the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells time and again returned to the theme that a man can
fool many people, but never himself.
</P>
<P>
   The poem, an anonymous composition, begins, ``When you get what
you want in your struggle for self/and the world makes you king for
a day/Just go to a mirror and look at yourself/and see what that
man has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after addressing the players, Parcells was relaxed
and loose, far from maudlin or sentimental, as he explained to the
media why he was leaving the sidelines once and for all _ ``Write
it on your chalkboards; I'm not coaching any more games'' _ and
turning the Jets over to longtime assistant Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   The news was shocking to many. When running back Curtis Martin
gave linebacker Bryan Cox the word early in the morning, Cox said
he didn't believe Martin. Linebacker James Farrior said, ``I think
everybody was pretty much shocked with what happened. This has been
our coach for three years and we all came in together. I like him a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani weighed in, suggesting
Parcells as a possible candidate for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Because I'm so long on patience?'' replied Parcells.
``I'm flattered, but I'm not a political animal.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the shock in New York was immense, Parcells's reasons for
leaving were personal. The Jets may be as close to next year's
Super Bowl as any team, and, said Parcells, ``We do have a credible
franchise here now,'' but he said he looked in that mirror and no
longer could give his all to the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I could probably do it for 16 games or 32 or 48,'' said
Parcells, who coached the Jets for three years, ``but you have to
have the committed energy to do it at the level I want to do it. I
demand commitment from the players and they have the right to
demand the same commitment from me. At this point in time, I don't
feel I can give it the way it has to be given.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time. In fact, I know it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he had told late Jets owner Leon Hess a year ago
that the 1999 season might be his last, and he was ``99 percent
sure on Saturday,'' the day before t game against Seattle.
And the poem, he said, explained why:
</P>
<P>
   ``For it isn't your father, mother or wife/whose judgment you
must pass;/The fellow whose verdict counts most in your life/is the
one staring back from the glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells felt he no longer could look in that mirror and see a
truly dedicated NFL coach. So he told Belichick Sunday night of his
decision, then told his wife and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You . . . you've just got to pull the trigger,'' said
Parcells. ``I knew it was time to go. And I know that I'm not
coaching football again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some close to the Jets feel the delay in selling the team after
the death of Hess last May was an irritant to Parcells and may
explain why he chose to move so quickly. Others felt it was one
last chance for Parcells to deal a setback to Patriots owner Bob
Kraft, who was hoping to court Belichick to replace Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Under NFL rules, Kraft could not contact the Jets for permission
to talk to Belichick until there was a vacancy in New England. It
was learned Monday that the Patriots faxed the Jets Monday morning
seeking such permission.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells left no time for Kraft to move because Parcells
left his job an hour or so after Kraft fired Carroll. Under terms
of his contract, Belichick automatically moved up as the Jets'
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if New England's interest in Belichick hastened his
announcement, Parcells said, ``No, not really. I felt I owed it to
the organization to move quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Patriots had sought permission to talk, Parcells
said, ``It's a moot point now.'' His more direct answer had come
Sunday evening when asked the same question. ``Know the rules,'' he
had said then.
</P>
<P>
   The public comments notwithstanding, Parcells's one last chance
to trump Kraft clearly seemed to be a factor in the rapid
transition of power. Parcells and Kraft are still fierce foes after
their messy divorce four years ago, when the Patriots reached the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job, Mr. Hess said I could coach the team one
year, two years, three years, or whatever I wanted to do,'' said
Parcells. ``And that at any point in that time I could move into
the operations end of the organization. At the end of last season,
I had a conversation where I informed Mr. Hess that _ win, lose, or
draw _ there was a good chance this was my last year in coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was how the Jets recovered from losing
quarterback Vinny Testaverde in the first game _ while losing to
the Patriots _ that led to Parcells's decision. Hne of his
best coaching jobs in bringing the Jets back to 8-8 after a
horrendous start, and that comeback, said Parcells, made it easier
for him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact,'' said Parcells, ``if we hadn't finished
the way we had, I think I probably would have considered even more
strongly staying on. I think one of the things that I've always
prided myself is that where I've gone, when I left there, there was
a better operation.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was one uncertain area in Parcells's announcement, it
was his new role with the team. He will now go upstairs in the Jets
organization and do . . . well, little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill (Belichick) will be making the football decisions,'' said
Parcells, who will have the title of head of football operations.
``I will be available to him, to consult with him in any manner
that he deems necessary. But Bill will be making all football
decisions.'' That includes the draft.
</P>
<P>
   As he did with the Giants and Patriots, Parcells brought out
fierce loyalty in many of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a list of 10 former guys who I've coached who've
called this morning,'' said Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there is some sadness. But there's no `poor me'
syndrome. I'm not looking back.''
</P>
<P>
   And his legacy?
</P>
<P>
   He wants it to be that he brought out the best in players, that
all his players ``knew I would do anything to win a game,'' that
``you see something in somebody, you're not sure what it is but you
become infatuated with somebody,'' and that ``something'' in
somebody, nourished by Parcells, results in an NFL player.
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned former Patriots Sam Gash and Ray Lucas and current
Patriot Troy Brown as examples of such players. Just as he
mentioned the ``development of Drew (Bledsoe) as a quarterback.''
It was clear that Parcells retains fondness for the players he had
in New England.
</P>
<P>
   The final verse of the anonymous poem Parcells read to his
players explained all: ``You may fool the whole world down thway of life/And get pats on your back as you pass./But your
final reward will be heartache and tears/If you've cheated the man
in the glass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
