<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, Jan. 4 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Shepherdstown, W.Va.) _ President Clinton on
Monday began a fresh round of negotiations between Israel and
Syria, seizing on a ``historic opportunity'' to reach a
land-for-peace deal and end 50 years of enmity between the two
Mideast countries. Clinton held a separate meeting with Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and planned a similar one with Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, before a three-way session
anticipated later in the day. (Summary from wires) By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WEALTH (Tokyo) _ The gap between rich and poor Japanese is
widening, spurred by changes in the economy and in society. By
Stephanie Strom. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Undated) _ Playing the anti-Washington themes that
have won New Hampshire primaries for Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan
and Pat Buchanan, Bill Bradley today portrayed Vice President Al
Gore as timid and out of touch with the American people, who he
said are tired of partisan politics and think that Washington has
nothing to do with their lives. Gore, meanwhile, tells 1000
students in Iowa that the nation needs a tried-and-true leader,
capable of addressing more than a few national problems. His
reference is clearly to his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, this story supercedes the separate GORE and BRADLEY
stories scheduled earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-FAMILIES (Washington) _ A current Supreme Court case on
whether grandparents, other relatives, and even non-relatives
should be able to gain a court-ordered right to visit with children
over the parents' objection has opened the door not only to an
examination of the stresses besetting the generations, but to a
profound debate over the very definition of family. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-SUITS (Undated) _ HMO companies _ like cigarette,
lead paint and gun manufacturers _ are under a growing legal
bombardment. The assault includes at least 16 recent class-action
lawsuits, most filed by some of the same lawyers who won huge
settlements from the tobacco industry. Several new state laws and
measures in Congress could open the industry to still more
lawsuits. And the federal law that has long protected many managed
care companies is being whittled away in a series of court
decisions in various malpractice cases. That is why the industry is
looking to guidance from the Supreme Court, which will hear an
important test case in February. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDENDS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Dividends, corporate America
appears to be concluding, are an unnecessary cost of doing
business. Investors do not appear to be interested in getting
dividend payments, so why bother paying them? For the first time in
recent history _ and probably the first time since the Depression _
a quarter of the value of the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks
now comes from companies that do not pay dividends. Two decades
ago, only 2 percent of the value of the index came from such
companies. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: FBN-JETS-PARCELS (Hempstead, N.Y.) _ Bill Parcells
announces he not coach the Jets next season. His decision comes in
the wake of a rousing finish by his team, which started the season
1-6 but then swept their final four games from teams headed to the
playoffs. Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
