<HEADER>
A5605 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOS &LR;      01-03 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, SCORE WILL BE SETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Finally.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of hype and hoopla, after six weeks of idleness,
after a season filled with debate, controversy, and, most
signficantly, games, college football will crown its national
champion in the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the event Tuesday night will be called the Bowl
Championship Series Sugar Bowl game _ winner take all.
</P>
<P>
   For No. 1 Florida State it is just another piece of a puzzle
that has virtually remained unchanged over the past decade. This
game will be the Seminoles' third appearance in the title game in
the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   For No. 2 Virginia Tech, it is more of a coming-out party. Even
with an 11-0 record, the Big East champion Hokies still hear the
familiar refrain that they don't belong here.
</P>
<P>
   easy a league, too soft a schedule, it's said. ``I know
people are used to seeing Florida State for sure,'' said Virginia
Tech coach Frank Beamer, ``and they're not used to seeing Virginia
Tech. But hopefully they will get to see what we're all about.
We're not the new kids on the block, but we're going to try to
uphold our end of the championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Hokies have paid their dues. They have been to an
Orange Bowl and a Sugar Bowl in non-championship game situations.
Since 1993 they have the eighth-best record in Division 1A (54-19).
</P>
<P>
   They also have the ingredients necessary for a championship
team. An outstanding defense and a diverse offense, with arguably
the best quarterback in college football in redshirt freshman
Michael Vick, who finished third in the Heisman Trophy balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's beautiful that the Sugar Bowl has matched up a
Cinderella team like Virginia Tech and kind of an old-timer like
Florida State,'' said Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden, who turned 70
during the season and shows no signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida State is also on a mission. Although they are not
chasing respect the way Virginia Tech is, the Seminoles are going
after their first unbeaten season under Bowden, as well as their
second national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one would definitely mean more,'' said Bowden, who won
his first crown in 1993, but saw his team lose title opportunities
to Florida in 1996 and Tennessee last season. ``In '93 we had gone
seven years in a row being close, but never getting it. So when we
won it, it was a bigger relief than anything. Now it's been six or
seven years and everybody is saying, ``He's only got one . . . but
he's so old. I've made everybody else a national champion. I made
(Tennessee coach Phil) Fulmer one, I made (Flordida coach Steve)
Spurrier one. It's time I got another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden understands how the Seminoles have changed their image
over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to Florida State (in 1976) we were the
homecoming queen to everybody,'' said Bowden. ``I prefer the
underdog role. You can tell the team, `Look what they're saying
about you.' If you're the favorite, you talk about defending your
ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Florida State has had to defend more than that. The
Seminoles have been plagued by a series of off-the-field problems,
lowlighted by the now infamous PeterWarrick discounted shopping
spree at a Tallahassee department store that led the wide receiver
to a plea bargain arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems, despite a couple of New Year's Eve curfew
violations, seem to be behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids do things,'' Bowden said with a shrug and then a laugh as
he stepped through the minefields of talking about incidents such
as Warrick's. ``Idon't condone the things that they do, but I don't
kill them. Some of these kids, we're the closest thing they have to
a father. If a kid commits murder, I have to let him go. If he gets
a discount, I'd want to know how he got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles have seem more focused this week than a year ago.
They are used to the hoopla of championship game week, in which
questions are repeated over and over again while the players are
going stir crazy waiting for game time.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the teams are a mirror image. Both play
aggressive, push-the-envelope defense, with outspoken players; both
have quarterbacks who are regarded as the key to success; both are
opportunists that turn the other team's mistakes into points
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come down to fundamentals,'' said Florida State
running back Travis Minor. ``When a play is there, we need to take
advantage because it might not be there again. We can't miss
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have had opportunities to lose. Virginia Tech narrowly beat
West Virginia and Florida State had to go-all out to beat Georgia
Tech and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   If Florida State wins, fewuestion the Seminoles' claim on
No. 1. If Virginia Tech wins, there no doubt still will be a few
critics who question the Hokies' credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But with no playoff system in place, or being planned, this is
the best the BCS has to offer. And the winner will indeed be a
fitting champion for the final season of the 20th century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
