<P>
   Y2K-RETURN (Los Angeles) -- The Y2K bug came and went for Los
Angeles with no reports of widespread glitches, but people who
stocked up for the millennium meltdown now wonder what they will do
with the stuff. Government officials say the preparation was worth
the investment, $115 million in Los Angeles. And people who took
out money are making deposits in banks. Daily News staff. (Will
move on the ``n'' California news wire and ``f'' financial news
wire.)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-WEATHER (Los Angeles) -- What's a gardner to do?
Unusually dry, temperate weather has played havoc with San Fernando
Valley gardens, as lawns, roses, and other plants are blooming out
of season. Mulch to keep in moisture and to protect against cold,
wind and heat. But the key is: water, water, water. By Robert
Monroe. (Will move on the ``n'' California news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW-STUDIO (Los Angeles) -- Matthews Studio Group announced
Monday it's facing surprisingly large deficit for its
just-concluded fiscal year. The entertainment equipment supply
company blamed costs associated with its recently launched website
for the loss. By Chris Sieroty. (Will move on the ``f'' fianncial
news wire.)
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) -- Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in
organizational behavior _ is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News. His column moves Mondays in the ``f'' financial news file.
</P>
</TEXT>
