<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: NAZI SUSPECT DEPORTED
</P>
<P>
   Britain ordered the deportation to Australia of Konrad Kalejs,
86, suspected of being a Nazi death squad officer responsible for
the murder of up to 30,000 Jews, Communists and Gypsies in Latvia
in World War II. Kalejs, an Australian citizen of Latvian descent,
was found living in a retirement home in England. The police said
they had no grounds for arresting Kalejs and Australia said it had
already decided not to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: OUSTED PRESIDENT ARRIVES
</P>
<P>
   The former president of the Ivory Coast, Henri Konan Bedie, who
was ousted in a military coup on Christmas Eve, arrived in Paris.
He had been staying in Togo since the coup and flew into Orly
airport aboard the Togolese presidential jet. Togolese officials
said Bedie, who has an apartment in Paris, is expected to take up
residence there.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: 3 HELD IN BASQUE REGION
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested three suspected members of the Basque group
ETA after a car chase in the northern town of Basauri. Authorities
said the three were planning a car-bomb attack against the Civil
Guard. Two men were armed when they surrendered and the third was
arrested in a raid on an apartment in Bilbao, where explosives and
guns were found.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: RULING PARTY'S SLIM LEAD
</P>
<P>
   The governing ruling center-right Popular Party led the main
opposition Socialists by 4.4 percentage points in an opinion poll
of voters published by the Madrid daily El Pais. According to the
survey, just over two months before general elections are to take
place, Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar's party would win 40.9
percent of the vote, against 36.5 for the Socialists. Pollsters
questioned 1,500 adults for the survey, which has a 2.6 percent
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: KOHL INQUIRY OPENS
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors formally opened a criminal investigation into
whether former Chancellor Helmut Kohl broke the law by accepting
more than $1 million in secret cash donations he has admitted
taking for the Christian Democratic Union during his 16 years in
office. Investigators said they would seek to establish whether
Kohl, 69, committed a criminal breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: OPEC TALKS PUT OFF
</P>
<P>
   The government has asked that a rare summit meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries be postponed in order
to give Venezuela more time to rebuild after floods and landslides
that killed thousands of people. The meeting, to which all 11 OPEC
heads of state were invited, was scheduled to begin in Caracas on
March 27, but will now probably be shifted to Vienna and downgraded
to a conference of oil ministers.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: SQUATTERS REMOVED
</P>
<P>
   Citing the danger posed by weather forecasts of up to a month of
additional rains, security and civil defense authorities have begun
forcibly evacuating residents of hillside squatter settlements in
Caracas who survived last month's floods and landslides. Officials
warn that up to a million Caracas residents live in unsafe areas.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: MUSLIM'S GRAVE DEFACED
</P>
<P>
   The grave of a Muslim cleric who led a group that attacked Jews
in British-ruled Palestine in the 1930s was defaced with red paint
near Haifa. Swastikas and the name of Baruch Goldstein, a Jewish
settler who killed 29 Muslims in Hebron in 1994, were daubed on the
grave. A group calling itself ``Friends of Baruch Goldstein'' took
responsibility, protesting the Israeli army's demolition of a
shrine at his grave last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
