<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBC-SUGAR-VATECH-BOS &LR;      01-03 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-VATECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOKIES GETTING USED TO THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Maybe if they win they will get respect,
recognition for what they have accomplished. Maybe the jokes about
their schedule will go away.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if they lose, the critics will call them frauds,
saying they didn't deserve to be here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Tech Hokies and their fans have heard all of this
before, of course. But the perception is beginning to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The perception) is best explained by my wife,'' said Virginia
Tech coach Frank Beamer at Monday's final news conference before
Tuesday night's Bowl Championship Series title game against Florida
State in the Sugar Bowl. ``She said it's like reading about
somebody new every day. We get two and three stores a day in USA
Today. There were years when we didn't have our scores in USA
Today.''
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Virginia Tech has come under Beamer's watch. In the
past seven seasons, the Hokies have a 64-19 record, which includes
two trips to the Sugar Bowl, an Orange Bowl appearance, and seven
straight bowl appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The school's climb in stature also has helped the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of a sudden all the doomsday-ers have gone away,''
said Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese. ``We had a period where
we struggled a little, and all of sudden we feel better. Tech's
success put a new face on it.'' But not even Tranghese could
project the speed of the Hokies' climb. ``I've seen it happen in
basketball,'' Tranghese said. ``But I didn't know if it was
possible in football this quickly. I don't think anyone could have
predicted this.''
</P>
<P>
   Beamer says the goal has been a simple one from the time he came
back to his alma mater 13 years ago. ``It's not so much where
you're from, but where you're going,'' he said. ``There's a thin
line from being OK in this business to not being OK in this
business. We hope to stay among the best in college football.
That's hard to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long ago we were ahead of seven teams in the fourth
quarter and went 2-8-1 (in 1992). Now we've been to seven straight
bowl games. We've got some good players. Then we got some
confidence and we won games in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden knows how Beamer feels. ``I've
been here 24 years,'' Bowden said. ``Frank's pretty much at the
same place at Virginia Tech as I was at Florida State after 10
years. We went to the Orange Bowl in 1979-80. We lost a couple of
those games during those years by 1 point. Then we hit a lull. In
1987, we began to hit that string (of success).''
</P>
<P>
   Beamer says he has used Florida State as a role model. ``No
question about it,'' he said. ``Florida State is exactly in the
position we are trying to get to. We worked to get in on the
national level for a long time and I am proud of the fact that we
are one of only eight programs to get to seven straight bowl games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think consistency is the key element in trying to get to
where Florida State is. I think we have everything we need at
Virginia Tech to play at a high level year in and year out. We've
got a great academic school to sell. We are in a good state for
football. We've got great facilities. We are in a great conference.
Our athletic director (Jim Weaver) has plans to enlarge our stadium
in a consistent fashion, to add boxes and so forth. That needs to
happen. As long as we continue to grow in that direction, I don't
see why Virginia Tech shouldn't be able to play at the top level.
That's our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies have gotten much of the talent from Virginia _ 65
players on the roster are from the state. ``We recruit as hard as
we can in Virginia,'' said offensive coordinator Ricky Bustle.
``Then we recruit to replace certain areas. We have four coaches in
Florida _ 16 players come from Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Beamer says the Virginia-first philosophy will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see me going somewhere other than Virginia to
recruit first,'' he said. ``It's tough to get in somewhere and
learn about the players. If you're going all around the country,
you're dealing with unknowns. I want to deal with knowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a people guy. A player has to have a certain talent level,
but I'm just as interested in what he's all about. I want to go
back to the same high schools where the coaches know us and we know
the coaches. We know the coaches will be truthful about their
players. If we do the best job of getting players out of our state,
this won't be the last time we'll be playing for the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   With exposure like that provided by the Sugar Bowl, Virginia
Tech has become more of a national program, despite the remoteness
of its Blacksburg campus in the western part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is as close-knit a community as you will find, from
Beamer, a Tech alum; to the university president, who has worked at
Tech for 33 years; to the mayor, a Tech grad; to the thousands of
Hokie fans who have come to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   And the turnaround has been as quick. In Beamer's early years,
few people cared about or knew of Tech football. They had a home
game scheduled against Florida State in 1991, but switched it to
Orlando for the cash guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Their nickname, the Hokies, which came from a student-written
cheer in 1896, seemed to fit the school.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with All-American and Heisman Trophy vote-getters such
as defensive end Corey Moore and redshirt freshman quarterback
Michael Vick, the Hokies' roster still has a blue-collar feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said Florida State has like 13 guys who were Parade
All-Americans,'' said Beamer. ``I said we had two guys that have
been in a parade.''
</P>
<P>
   More players should be coming to Blacksburg now, which will
mean, among other things, more scrutiny. Virginia Tech had a
problem during a 13-month period in 1995-96 when 19 football
players were arrested 22 times on a series of charges from drunk
driving to rape.
</P>
<P>
   It was not headline news outside of Blacksburg because the
Hokies were not national championship contenders. As Bowden, who
has had to deal with a series of off-field incidents this season,
noted, ``If you don't want other people to know, don't be No. 1. Be
No. 50. I learned that.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech's response to its problems was to institute a
program that issued harsher penalties for transgressions and also
to set up more restrictive character requirements in recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Beamer, like Bowden, says some mistakes have been made. ``When
you deal with 115 guys,'' he said, ``not everyone is going to do
exactly what you want them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies have done what Beamer has asked of them. Moore had an
outburst last week that caused a stir, but for the most part,
Virginia Tech has played its role as a newcomer in the national
spotlight fairly well.
</P>
<P>
   What happens will either enhance that role or diminish it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
