<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-STAFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN Interactive plans to double employees within year
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN Interactive says it plans to nearly double its
staff of online writers, editors, Web developers and multimedia
producers in the United States and overseas by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The growth, says General Manager and Editor-in-Chief Scott
Woefel, reflects the increasing depth and breadth of content on
Atlanta-based CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, CNN.com has about 300 employees, including 100 in the
news division and 50 each at CNN's online sports and business
sites. Rivals ABCNews.com and MSNBC.com have similar staffing
levels. Woefel declined to say how many new hires are expected, but
says a major expansion is planned.
</P>
<P>
   Since CNN launched its Web site in 1995, Web news junkies have
come to expect more than text and pictures from online news
sources. RealAudio, multimedia slide shows and streaming video are
all part of the online news experience.
</P>
<P>
   CNN.com already draws much of its news from its well-known
roster of national and international staffers. However, Woefel says
it takes more than just a handful of people to assemble a
content-rich Web news story. CNN has always been a leader in online
breaking news, but Woefel admits there are places where CNN.com
could do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what CNN.com does on a daily basis, there's a
lot there. There are a lot of sections. In some places, we can't
rely on CNN television, so the best way is to hire a good,
competent staff and reliable partners. The other consideration is
to look at our international needs and make sure it matches our TV
interest. That's why we are looking at hiring domestically and
internationally,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every story we do, we have to have background materials
and links and chat,'' he says. ``All this hiring is about catching
up in some of the areas we've neglected in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analyst Preston Dodd says CNN's online
staff expansion is part of an effort to better integrate the Web
brand with its TV counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now breaking news is all about the Internet, and that's a big
challenge they face. When you think of the number of people they
have on the TV side, 300 people (on the Web side) is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Internet is part of their business and part of the
relationship CNN has with its consumers. They have to react and
change accordingly. If they don't, their competitors will get ahead
of them,'' Dodd says.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNews and MSNBC have always worked to integrate TV and Web
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ABCNews, for example, is nearly always ready for any major news
event with an array of charts, graphs, chats, explainer boxes,
glossaries and background materials that give users added depth.
Meanwhile, MSNBC has always made extensive use of personalization
and chat as well as links to other Microsoft and NBC properties
such as Slate and NBC news programs.
</P>
<P>
   While CNN has always been a leader and innovator in online news
coverage, Woefel knows it has to expand its staff to make the best
use of the Web as well as the extensive resources of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are another network of CNN,'' says Woefel. ``The one place
we didn't have a dedicated Internet team was in the field. We don't
need two people the White House or two people in Sarajevo, when we
have such well-known on-air talent as Christianne Amanpour and Wolf
Blitzer.'' What's needed, he says, are Web producers who can
assemble the audio, the video, the story and the related links and
graphics to back up the on-air staff. ``We aren't close to having
interactive producers everywhere,'' he says, ``but we are moving in
that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
