<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-Y2K-COSTS-COX     01-03 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COSTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K: What the millennium cost
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Hallock spent six hours baby-sitting over the Y2K
weekend and took home $500 _ equal to half of his regular weekly
pay at Cablevision Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old contract worker volunteered to work New Year's
Eve, from 9 p.m. to 3 a.m., at one of Cablevision's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked the phone system to make sure they were working. We
had to make sure the connections to the billing systems were still
intact, and we basically had to be sure the computer network stayed
up and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it (the new year) passed through Japan and Europe with
no problems, we had an understanding of what was going to happen,''
said Hallock, who joined Cablevision a month ago as an information
technology manager overseeing the company's local area network
system.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to spend a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   While the impact of increased staffing has yet to be fully
tallied by many companies, Y2K turned out to be a financially
fruitful weekend for many workers. Even if they didn't get overtime
pay, many workers went home from their Y2K watch with extra days to
tack onto vacation time later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Information technology workers _ especially people with computer
and network skills _ earned about $700 for a day's work during the
Y2K weekend, estimates Joe Koscik, chief executive of MDI, a
high-tech outsourcing firm that placed Hallock at Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   MDI said it has temporary tech workers at telecommunications
firms, banks, credit-card and payroll companies. Most of them were
at their desks New Year's Eve and New Year's Day. In the extreme
cases, some workers were on call from last Thursday through today.
</P>
<P>
   For workers who spent the past year on Y2K matters, it is
turning out to be a springboard to other work. MDI said it has
already placed three-fourths of its Y2K staff in other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preparation (cost of Y2K) was astronomical,'' Koscik said.
``The staffing cost is probably about medium. For most of the
companies, this was an unknown. We've never gone through this
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Barnes agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not just a day at the office,'' said Barnes,
an Atlanta-based consultant in performance and reward at the human
resources consulting firm William M. Mercer Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the New Year's weekend, most
companies used a combination of measures to make sure there were
enough people on hand, according to a Mercer study of 250
organizations' plans nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies built a contingency workforce using in-house
employees. ``You can assume the compensation will be in overtime
pay or extra time off,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 20 percent of the companies were bringing
in extra help. Another 20 percent had people to focus solely on Y2K
matters. ``It ranged from having people working for a few days to
several months,'' Barnes said. ``Basically, they're people brought
in from other departments within the company, not outside help.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta, most of the people
working over the weekend were salaried _ management and
professionals _ and some people who would have been working anyway.
About 125 people worked over the weekend, spokeswoman Jean Tate
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of elusive,'' Tate said of trying to pin down the
cost of staffing at the Fed. ``What probably will happen is many
workers will receive comp time for their hours, but it's not
something that's actually been written out as a policy.''
</P>
<P>
   AGL Resources has no idea what it cost to have extra staff
Friday night at the natural gas utility. Many of the workers in the
command center were exempt from union requirements for
compensation, said Y2K project director Michael Hutchins.
</P>
<P>
   A BellSouth spokesman said the company had not broken out its
Y2K weekend staffing costs.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Hallock plan to do with the extra $500?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay off Christmas bills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
