<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0104-CO     01-03 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-0104-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAEL, SYRIA OPEN NEW ROUND OF PEACE TALKS WITH CAUTIOUS
OPTIMISM
 &HT;    With TALKS-TOWN-0104.
 &HT;    EDs: This story expected to update following 9 p.m. EST briefing
by Clinton.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPERDSTOWN, West Va. _ President Clinton met into the night
Monday with Israeli and Syrian negotiators, opening a critical new
phase in his efforts to broker an end to a half-century of
bloodshed and enmity in the fractious Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on talks he began in Washington last month, Clinton
hosted Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa in a day of meetings at a secluded
conference center in this rural village on the banks of the Potomac
River.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met separately with Barak, then Sharaa, in the
afternoon, and came out encouraged that both men had come prepared
for brass-tacks talks over issues centered on territory and
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president came out of his two meetings believing that ...
both sides are serious about being here,'' said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``He believes the talks are off to a good
start.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief break for dinner, Clinton was expected to convene
a trilateral meeting with Barak and Sharaa at the semi-secluded
Clarion Hotel and Conference Center just outside Shepherdstown,
before returning to Washington late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were expected to continue, under the auspices of U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, at least through the week.
Barak, Sharaa and the battery of issue experts each man brought
along were expected to assess the talks' progress at week's end and
determine whether to continue or to head back to their respective
capitals to consider each other's positions.
</P>
<P>
   As promised when the talks were announced last month, Lockhart
declined to discuss the substance of Monday's talks. The
negotiations are being held under a news blackout _ Syrian and
Israeli delegates were stripped of their cell phones to deter
clandestine chats with reporters _ in an effort to avert public
controversy at each juncture of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin cautioned reporters,
though, against expecting the Shepherdstown talks to resolve all
the differences between Israel and its giant Arab neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not expect to achieve a core agreement with one round of
talks,'' Rubin said. ``We're at a time for decisions, but those
decisions don't get made in an instant.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton regards this round as ``an important next
step,'' in a negotiating process analysts expect will take months
to complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was easy,'' Lockhart said, ``it would have been done a
long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   There's much riding on the talks for Clinton. He sees the
Israeli-Syrian negotiations as a key part to the larger quest for
Mideast peace, one of the top foreign policy priorities for his
final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges to that goal were apparent even as the talks got
under way, however. In Syria, about 50 protesters, mostly
university students, staged a sit-in at the offices of the
International Committee for the Red Cross, denouncing Israel and
demanding the release of Syrian prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no peace as long as Israel keeps our men
imprisoned,'' Maymouna al-Maqet, whose two brothers have been
jailed in Israel since 1985, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high, also, for the United States, which counts
Israel as its closest strategic ally in the oil-rich Mideast
region.
</P>
<P>
   Americans would certainly be called upon to provide billions of
dollars in military, economic and humanitarian aid to help cement
any peace deal between Israel and Syria. U.S. troops might also be
deployed to help police a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin stressed that no such arrangements have been agreed upon,
but he suggested that Americans should be ready to accept a
peacekeeping role should an Israeli-Syrian accord be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big, big deal,'' Rubin told reporters at a news
briefing, ``and a deal this big is going to carry a price tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived at this two-century-old town at the edge of the
Appalachian Mountain range shortly before noon, putting down in the
presidential helicopter, Marine One, in a muddy baseball diamond at
Shepherd College after a half-hour flight from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded immediately into separate meetings with Barak and
Sharaa at a conference center in a secluded, wooded retreat
operated by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton, who has cleared his weekly schedule to
monitor the talks, would be available throughout the week to return
to Shepherdstown whenever Albright decides his presence would help
move the talks forward.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate track, Barak is pursuing a peace agreement with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. The two men have pledged to
hammer out a framework for so-called ``final status'' talks by
mid-February and to nail down a comprehensive agreement _ to
include such contentious issues as the future of Jerusalem and the
question of Palestinian statehood _ by October.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's talks with Syria are centered on a plan under which
Israel would return to Syria the Golan Heights in return for
security guarantees, and normalized diplomatic and economic
relations between the two Mideast neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are such matters as how to structure security
guarantees _ possibly using United Nations and U.S. peacekeeping
troops _ for Israel; a timetable for Israeli withdrawal from the
strategic Golan Heights; how to allocate precious fresh water
supplies from the Sea of Galilee, in the Golan; and how to set up
the first-ever commercial and diplomatic ties between Israel and a
country that has been its avowed foe since the birth of the Jewish
state in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli troops seized the strategic Golan territories from Syria
during the 1967 war, after Syria joined Egypt and Jordan in
attacking Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from the talks here was Syria's aging President Hafez
al-Assad, who is reported to be in uncertain health.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said U.S. officials are confident that Sharaa is
negotiating with Assad's full confidence and authority, however,
Assad's personal attention is likely to be required to seal any
comprehensive accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do expect him to be involved,'' Rubin said, though it was
too soon to say whether Assad would make an appearance in
Shepherdstown.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
