<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN CANDIDATE URGES PARTY TO GIVE UP CONTROL OF BUSINESSES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In a proposal that could foreshadow new rules for
Taiwan's politics, the faltering presidential candidate of the
long-ruling Nationalist Party has proposed that the party's vast
business holdings be placed in a trust and that it end its direct
role in managing hundreds of companies in which it owns shares.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes could reduce the widely resented advantages enjoyed
by the Nationalist Party as it pulls in hundreds of millions of
dollars in profits each year and, according to critics, wields its
shares in everything from banks to oil companies to secure the
allegiance of key groups and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Lien Chan made the surprise proposal on Sunday as
he inaugurated his Taipei campaign headquarters for the
presidential elections scheduled for March. Lien has fared poorly
in what is shaping up as a close three-way race for the presidency,
and his proposal was widely interpreted as a gesture to win back
disillusioned voters.
</P>
<P>
   As Taiwan has moved over the last decade toward a full-fledged
democracy with a probing press, the Nationalist Party's
multibillion-dollar business holdings and evidence of pervasive
cronyism have become sore points with much of the electorate. The
assets of its main competitor, the Democratic Progressive Party,
are meager by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let all of our parties cease any further profit-making
activities, and let it begin with the Nationalist Party,'' Lien
told his supporters. ``Political competition should be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics said that a major transformation of the party's role in
business could take years, and that abuses could continue as long
as the party owns many assets bringing in profits that can be used
in campaigns. But Lien's statement implicitly suggested how strong
the pressures for change have become. In the same speech, he also
proposed new rules to fight election-related corruption and the
political involvement of organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Lien is the hand-picked successor of President Lee Teng-hui, 76,
who is the country's first directly elected president and enjoys
popularity for his assertive stance toward mainland China. Lee
asserts that Taiwan has sovereign status, but he has not risked a
Chinese military attack by formally declaring independence.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has repeatedly declared its goal of reunification, by
military force if necessary, with Taiwan, the seat of Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalist forces since their defeat in the Chinese
civil war in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Progressives' standard bearer is Chen Shui-bian,
the former mayor of Taipei. Chen was scornful of Lien's proposals,
saying they would only mean cosmetic change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pour fresh water into a cesspool, the cesspool still
stinks,'' he said at a rally on Sunday night, arguing that only a
wholesale change in the government could clean up Taiwan's
politics. Chen and his Democratic Progressives originally called
for Taiwan's formal independence from China, but he has moderated
the position to avoid losing the many voters who are afraid of
dangerously provoking the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The third major candidate, until recently the front-runner in
polls, is James Soong, formerly a popular Nationalist Party leader
who feuded with Lee and recently broke away for an independent run.
</P>
<P>
   Soong has been hurt by accusations that he controlled a large
personal slush fund, in part derived from his party's corporate
profits. Soong has denied any wrongdoing but has suffered in public
polls. He has not yet commented publicly on Lien's new proposals,
but his spokesman questioned Lien's credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
