<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COX     01-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oddsmakers none too keen on Cowboys chancesBy Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys have a better chance of
winning the Texas lottery than beating Minnesota in the playoffs.
Or so they've been told.
</P>
<P>
   History has an unkind reminder for the Cowboys. In the previous
century, no NFL team won a playoff game with an 8-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   But Instead of waving a white flag and staying in 70-degree
Dallas, the Cowboys have confidence their mediocre season will not
end Sunday under a dome in 20-degree Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team is told it has no chance to win, it just adds
incentive to do so,'' safety George Teague said Monday. ``When I
played at Alabama, no one gave us a chance in history of beating
Miami in the (1992) Sugar Bowl, and we went out and kicked their
butt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are seven-point underdogs against the 10-6 Vikings,
but Dallas' players and coaches are convinced they have a chance to
write a unique story. It no longer matters that Dallas barely
reached the playoffs, owns a combined 24-24 record the last three
years, lost to Minnesota 27-17 two months ago and finished the
season with a 1-7 road mark.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Cowboys tried to convince critics that a victory
in Minnesota is not as far-fetched as many think it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the playoffs as a stage, a tremendous platform,''
cornerback Deion Sanders said, ``and everyone is watching. I get
excited just thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys watched film Monday of their Nov. 8 loss to the
Vikings. Emmitt Smith rushed for 140 yards and two touchdowns,
helping the Cowboys take a 17-0 lead, before breaking his hand in
the second quarter. Smith missed the entire second half,
quarterback Troy Aikman suffered his second concussion is
successive weeks in the third quarter and the big-play Vikings
scored the game's final 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tale of two halves, and the Cowboys think they would
have won had Smith and Aikman not gotten hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play both halves (Sunday) like we did the first
half (on Nov. 8),'' Coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   That might be easier said than done, but a healthy Smith gives
the Cowboys an obvious lift. The 10-year veteran finished the
season with 1,397 yards, ranking fourth in the league. That is a
nice accomplishment, considering that Smith missed a game after
breaking the bone beneath his right ring finger.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is not the only Cowboy who will be healthier in the
rematch. Sanders no longer has the groin and hamstring problems
that hurt him last time in Minnesota. Gailey said Monday that two
cornerbacks who have been dogged by injuries, Kevin Smith and Kevin
Mathis, should return for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has spent much of his time trying to explain the Cowboys'
roller-coaster season. They have had a knack of blowing
fourth-quarter leads, and most of their games were close. Dallas
has not lost a game by more than 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very emotional season,'' he said. ``Every game
has been a gut-wrencher all the way to the fourth quarter. That
takes a lot out of you emotionally. From now on, anything you
accomplish now must be proven.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to beating the Vikings, Gailey said, is preventing them
from making big offensive plays. Randy Moss and Cris Carter might
be the best tandem of receivers in the league. They have combined
for 170 receptions, 2,654 yards and 24 touchdowns. Against Dallas
last time, they combined for 15 catches, 207 yards and three
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   So, which receiver does Gailey worry about most?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like asking which kid you love most,'' Gailey said.
``You can't pick one. Both are real talented guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: rcantu(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
