<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT     01-03 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS FREE KIDNAP VICTIMS IN ASSAULT ON CHECHEN CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-POLITICS) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ Fighting is raging in the streets of Chechnya's
capital, but some stories have a happy ending. Viktor Dolgalyov
ought to know. He was a kidnap victim in Chechnya, and the
ferocious Russian assault on Grozny led to his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kidnapped in September and locked away in a cellar in
the city until last week,'' he said Monday, still seemingly a bit
stunned by the abrupt turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   As international criticism of Russia's military tactics in
Chechnya has increased, Russians have responded by citing the
problem of kidnappin insisting it is doing battle against
``bandits'' and ``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Dolgalyov was Exhibit A in the Russian public relations
campaign. He was made available by officials of the Russian
government to a small group of reporters at the Russian air base
here, a sprawling compound northwest of Chechnya where Russian
warplanes and helicopters take off on their missions.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappings have indeed been a major hazard in southern Russia _
and a major business for many of the lawless gangs that have roamehnya and the region. More than 800 people have been kidnapped
in the last few years, often by armed bands that left Chechnya in
search of captives and then hauled their victims back to the
breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   Many journalists had stopped going to the region before the
latest war broke out, for fear of becoming another kidnap victim.
And a group of British communications workers were beheaded by one
gang after efforts to free them failed.
</P>
<P>
   The captives also include Maj. Gen. Gennady Shpigun, the Russian
Interior Ministry's senior representative to Chechnya, who was
abducted in March. Sergei Stepashin, Russia's prime minister at the
time, vowed to track down the culprits and free the officer, but it
is believed that he is still being held at an undisclosed location
in C.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappings were not the only sign of the lawlessness that
infected Chechnya. Gangs seized oil wells or tapped into the oil
pipeline and stole fuel. Russian authorities estimate that
thousands of cars have been stolen from regions throughout Russia
and taken to Chechnya. The authorities are mounting a campaign to
track down the missing vehicles in the Russian-controlled regions
of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Dolgalyov, however, was more fortunate than most kidnap victims,
probably because he did not have a high-ranking position and maybe
because he was plain lucky.
</P>
<P>
   While he was locked away in a dark cement basement, his captors
sometimes amused themselves by playing a came they called the
``wheel of fortune.'' They fired their automatic weapons into the
basement to see which of their captives managed to find a safe
corner and survive.
</P>
<P>
   Dolgalyov, 44, was born in Mozdok, just over the Chechen border
that is the home to a major Russian air base located amid acres of
farm land. Dolgalyov had worked as the director of a local
agricultural trading company, and had a good connection in Chechnya
who was close to the local government. In September, he negotiated
an agreement to export scrap metal from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Dolgalyov drove from Mozdok into Chechnya on September 3 _ just
several weeks before the Russians began their military campaign
against the Chechen militants _ to sign the contract. But he had
barely entered the republic when his car was surrounded by a gang
of armed men and he was taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I later found out that they knew I was coming and were waiting
for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dolgalyov said his abductors were a gang from the neighboring
republic of Ingushetia that had fought on the Chechen side in the
1994-1996 war and later went into the kidnapping business. The gang
called Dolgalyov's wife and two sons and demanded a $2-million
ransom. When Dolgalyov's family did not pay, the kidnappers reduced
their demand to $200,000, still a princely sum for most Russians.
</P>
<P>
   To elude detection, the kidnappers moved Dolgalyov to
Achkhoi-Martan, a city in western Chechnya and then to several
locations in Grozny, the capital city, eventually ending up in a
cellar near the city center.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely had enough to eat and lost so much weight that his
clothes do not fit.
</P>
<P>
   The psychological pressure, however, was worse. After the
Russian military campaign started, Dolgalyov said that his captors
tried to exchange him for Chechen prisoners. And if the Russians
refused, they hinted, they would kill him and sell his kidneys to
patients who needed an organ transplant.
</P>
<P>
   As his ordeal continued, the Russians mounted their military
campaign against Islamic rebels. The Russian bombardment of Grozny
has jeopardized thousands of civilians. The rebels have yet to be
destroyed, though both sides have suffered serious losses.
</P>
<P>
   As a thick fog settled on Chechnya Monday night, a group of 30
militants tried to break out of the encircled city, sparking a
firefight in the small settlement of Krasnopartizansky, a few miles
southwest of Grozny, according to Col. Vasily Chirman, the deputy
chief of operations of the Russian troops in the Caucasus. Each
side claims to have come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   The brutal fighting, however, has sometimes led to the release
of some of the kidnap victims as kidnapers have abandoned their
captives. Others have come up against Russian troops and police,
who have been moving house to house within the city, searching for
militants, caches of arms and kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run across hostages practically every day,'' said Maj. Gen.
Vladimir Pronin, the senior commander of the Russian Interior
Ministry troops fighting in Chechnya. ``They are not only Russians.
We have freed Armenians and Ukrainians. We found them as we were
mopping up the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolgalyov does not exactly knoaved him, but he believes
his rescuers were from a Russian Interior Ministry unit set up to
fight organized crime that had been tipped off to his whereabouts.
He was sitting in his basement prison when the door suddenly opened
and he was told to go outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was December 26,'' he said Monday. ``I heard a voice say,
`Viktor. It's time to go.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
