<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-QA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book addresses women's needs according to age group
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At age 16, Judith Reichman first experienced the
medical lie, ``Relax, this won't hurt,'' during her first pelvic
exam from a male family internist. Now, 38 years later, and, after
having spent half her lifetime as a gynecologist examining,
listening to and advising women, Dr. Reichman named her third book,
``Relax, This Won't Hurt: Painless Answers to Women's Most Pressing
Health Needs'' (William Morrow, $24).
</P>
<P>
   It reviews women's health and changing bodies through each
decade from the teens to 70 and beyond. Reichman terms it a
``user-friendly guide'' complete with tips for staying healthy and
a list of recommended screening tests for each decade. She's also
the author of ``I'm Not in the Mood: What Every Woman Should Know
About Improving Her Libido,'' and ``I'm Too Young To Get Old:
Health Care for Women After Forty.''
</P>
<P>
   Reichman frequently appears on NBC's ``Today'' reporting on
women's health issues, and she'll be off on a book tour this month.
However, Reichman insists her practice at Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center in Los Angeles remains her top career priority. Married with
two adult daughters, Reichman, 54, knows firsthand the traumatic
decisions women face regarding their health; she recently had both
breasts removed and reconstructed because of abnormal overgrowth in
breast duct cells that turned out to be noncancerous. Reichman
spoke by telephone for this interview.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your new book, you call the age of the 40s a woman's
``most negotiable decade.'' What do you mean by that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 40s are a time when we need to really sit up and pay
attention to our health. It's the time of wake-up calls with
perimenopause since the average age of menopause is 51. The changes
in the reproductive system are fairly significant. And weight
becomes a bigger issue because we can't get by with eating what we
used to eat and not gain weight. Women also tend to diminish
exercise in this age group.
</P>
<P>
   The woes in our 60s and 70s often start in our 40s, such as
weight gain leading to Type 2 diabetes, coronary vascular disease
and osteoarthritis. Twenty percent of women in their 40s also
develop gallstones or gallbladder inflammation, whereas only 8
percent of men do in the same age group. The decade of their 40s is
when women need to become aware and negotiate change in their
health patterns. It's not too late by then and new habits can
really make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A slow, steady gain of weight seems to be inevitable with
women in menopause or following surgical removal of the ovaries.
Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: As we lose estrogen, changes occur in our weight gain
pattern. The gain becomes more like male-patterned obesity _ with a
pot belly. However, women on estrogen replacement often say, `I got
fat because I took estrogen.' But it's not the ERT, (estrogen
replacement therapy) it's the menopause. There is an average 3-to-5
pound increase in the first few years of estrogen deprivation,
regardless of whether or not you take ERT.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You stirred up some controversy with your ``I'm Not in the
Mood'' book because of your solution _ giving women with low libido
the male hormone, testosterone, particularly in ointment form.
</P>
<P>
   A: A woman's libido can be affected at any age and with
different estrogen fluctuations. For some women, the change can
create a real calamity. They just don't have any libido. It's
affecting them and their marriage and the sense of who they are.
Adding a very small amount of testosterone to their system can
dramatically help. But it's not a hormone I throw at anyone. Their
testosterone levels need to be checked before I consider
supplementing. There's only a pill, Estratest, made by a
pharmaceutical company, but I prefer other forms of testosterone
available in lower doses, such as lozenges, cream, ointments. But
these have to mixed up by compounding pharmacies with a doctor's
prescription. (Call the International Association of Compounding
Pharmacies at 1-800-927-4227 for Atlanta area locations.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your book ends with a genetics lesson, and the importance of
women knowing their family health history. Also, for the first
time, you disclose how your own family history fed into your
decision to undergo a prophylactic mastectomy. Did you undergo
genetic testing for the breast cancer genes, BRCA1 and BRCA2?
</P>
<P>
   A: The genetic tests were negative. However, my mother developed
breast cancer at age 47 and underwent a mastectomy. She's doing
just fine now at age 75. As a physician, I always take a very
complete family history with my patients. Nowhere can I get a
better sense of their fhan from taking a look at their
first-degree relatives, who share with us 50 percent of our genes.
It's a wonderful mirror and it allows me to be a brilliant
fortune-teller. My own decision was based on that and the results
of a Mammotome biopsy. (No early cancer was subsequently found in
either breast, Reichman writes in her book. She estimates removing
her breasts reduced a 35 percent to 40 percent risk of developing
invasive cancer in the next five to 10 years to a ``negligible
one.'')
</P>
<P>
   Q: No doubt, it was one of the hardest personal decisions you've
ever made?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but we all make tough decisions about our health
everyday. If you think about it, living is making a health
decision. But this book is not a personal book or breast-health
book. I've tried to address the most frequently-asked questions
I've heard over the years and the ones patients are too embarrassed
to ask about _ aging, skin, sex.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
