<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET SITE OF THE WEEK
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of cyber-innovations, and you're likely to imagine junk
food-fueled 20-somethings writing code in garage-based startup
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. Sometimes the Internet can surprise you; sometimes
innovative presentation and trustworthy content come from the old
reliables.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, www.healthfinder.gov. A project of the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services, the 2-year-old
consumer-health gateway provides both consumer-friendly health
information and access to additional sources of data such as
medical journals and databases. The site is both reliable and
popular: In each of its years of operation, it has registered an
average 2 million visits.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the site expanded its accessibility, in a way that is
sorely needed on the Net. It has translated the majority of its
content into Spanish, making it accessible to the millions of
Americans for whom English is not a first language.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the basics, Healthfinder En Espanol
(www.healthfinder.com/justforyou/espanol
</P>
<P>
   /default.htm) addresses important concerns for Latino readers
who may be economically disadvantaged and thus lack access to
complete health care. Articles about cancer, diabetes and infant
mortality top the list.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
