<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Setting off fireworks for the nonevent of Y2K
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time ($3.95) and Newsweek ($3.95) each published commemorative
issues for the new century this week with reports on the
noneventful Y2K issue along with colorful photo spreads of
worldwide New Year's celebrations. Time's pictures are more
spectacular, with a dramatic three-page foldout of Russell Goomes
and his granddaughter Shontelle holding hands and watching the
year's first dawn in New Zealand's Chatham Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek, however, has a compelling article on self-help gurus
such as Anthony Robbins, Steven Covey and John Gray and Americans'
obsession with improving themselves. More than $563 million worth
of self-help books are sold each year, and millions more are spent
on seminars. According to Newsweek reporter Daniel McGinn, the
biggest consumers are female baby boomers who feel something is
missing in their lives. People who used to go to their priests or
pastors for guidance, McGinn says, are now reading ``Chicken Soup
for the Soul'' or signing up for Robbins' $6,995, weeklong ``Life
Mastery'' course.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mixed bag: This week's New Yorker ($3) is an eclectic
collection of finely crafted articles, including author Bobbie Ann
Mason's report on the safety problems at a nuclear plant in
Paducah, Ky., Pete Hamill's profile of pulp fiction master Ed
McBain and Malcolm Gladwell's analysis of several books on early
childhood. In a thought-provoking essay, Gladwell questions the new
theory supported by Hillary Rodham Clinton and a number of experts
that the first three years of a child's life determine how he or
she will turn out. Comparing the new theory to the genetic
determinism espoused in ``The Bell Curve,'' Gladwell asserts that
``an ideology that holds that your future is largely decided at
birth by your parents' genes is no more dispiriting than one that
holds that your future might be decided at three by your parents'
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   _ High-tech: Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) talks with Bill Gates
about the future of Microsoft and the convergence of technology and
entertainment. Gates foresees a future with digital music instead
of CDs, customized TV access and expanded online shopping where you
can simply share your Christmas list with all your friends. That
way, Gates says, ``if somebody's going to take something off your
list, other people know and you don't get three or four of the same
things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ More than smoke: Cigar sales are down, according to the latest
figures, but Cigar Aficionado ($4.95) doesn't seem to be hurting.
The 226-page February issue is packed with ads. In addition to a
profile of cigar-puffing actor Laurence Fishburne, the magazine
offers provocative columns by political guru Dick Morris on the
upcoming presidential primaries and futurist Faith Popcorn on
changes in the 21st century. Actually, Popcorn says, people are
becoming so afraid of the future they yearn for the security of the
past. That's why, she writes, they secretly wished for a Y2K
disaster that would have made everything stop. Many of Popcorn's
predictions, of course, should be taken with a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
