<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHNQUIST-JUDGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE FEDERAL JUDGES NEEDED IN BORDER REGIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress must add federal judges to the Houston and
El Paso areas because courts there cannot handle the large and
increasing number of criminal cases brought in those border
regions, Texas' top federal appellate judge said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just in serious need of help,'' said Carolyn Dineen
King, chief judge of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans. ``I think when our senators and congressmen look at the
numbers they will support our efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures that concern King include a 145 percent rise in the
number of criminal cases filed in the U.S. District Court for
Southern Texas between 1995 and 1999. During that span the number
of judges assigned to the Houston-area court remained constant at
18, she added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the number of criminal cases in the U.S. District
Court for Western Texas rose 181.5 percent between 1995 and 1999.
The number of assigned judges in the El Paso-area court remained
steady at 10, according to the Administrative Office of the U.S.
Courts.
</P>
<P>
   King's comments followed Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist's
New Year's Day call for Congress to add two judges to the federal
court in Southern Texas. Rehnquist said that court faces an
``unmanageable'' trial schedule due to illegal immigration and drug
crimes in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual report on the state of the U.S. judiciary,
Rehnquist said federal courts in Arizona, Southern California and
New Mexico face similarly large criminal dockets and should also be
assigned more judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal courts in U.S. border areas face a crisis in workload
created by an unmanageable number of immigration and drug-related
cases,'' Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice specifically mentioned the U.S. District Court
for Southern Texas as needing additional jurists. The court, which
has 18 judges, sits in Brownsville, Corpus Christi, Galveston,
Houston, Laredo, McAllen and Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 3,387 criminal cases were filed in that court, an 8.1
percent increase from 3,134 in 1998, from the previous year, the
administrative office reported.
</P>
<P>
   King, while praising Rehnquist's call for more federal judges in
the Houston-area, said the federal court in Western Texas also
needs at least two more jurists.
</P>
<P>
   That court, which has 10 judges, sits in Austin, El Paso,
Midland, San Antonio and Waco. Last year, 4,301 cases were filed in
the court, a 14.6 percent increase from 3,753 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   King, who keeps her office in Houston, said Congress has
exacerbated the judicial workload at the Texas-Mexico border.
Lawmakers have beefed up law enforcement in the region to catch
more criminals but have failed to increase the number of judges to
preside over the additional trials, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the top Democrat on the Senate
Judiciary Committee, has proposed legislation that would add the
sought-after two judges each to the courts in Southern and Western
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure faces opposition from Committee Chairman Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, who stated in the panel's end-of-year report on the
U.S. judicial system that ``the federal judiciary is once again
sufficiently staffed and funded to perform its function under ...
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the Judicial Conference of the United States, which
Rehnquist heads, is urging Congress to add 58 district court judges
to the current roll of 645 authorized positions. Of those
authorized slots, 42 are vacant.
</P>
<P>
   In his year-end message, Rehnquist also reiterated his call for
Congress to refrain from turning local crimes, such as murder, into
federal offenses. The needless expansion of the U.S. criminal code
further burdens already overworked judges, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist and several fellow justices, including Anthony M.
Kennedy and David H. Souter in past years, have urged Congress not
to expand the criminal code to include local offenses. But recent,
highly publicized and especially brutal killings have created
public support for congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the brutal 1998 slayings of James Byrd Jr., a black
man in Jasper, Texas, and Matthew Shepard, a gay University of
Wyoming student, spurred congressional proposals to expand federal
laws that already outlaw attacks based on the victim's race. A
Democratic proposal, which Congress rejected last year, would have
expanded the federal prohibition on ``hate crimes'' to attacks
rooted in hatred toward women, homosexuals and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the spurned congressional legislation, such as
Sens. Charles Schumer, D-New York, and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., say
such national laws reflect the public's disdain for brutal displays
of prejudice. But opponents of federal intervention, such as
Rehnquist, counter that Byrd's and Shepard's attackers were
successfully prosecuted under state law.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 59,923 criminal cases were brought in federal court,
a 4 percent increase from 57,691 in 1998. That increase was
relatively small compared to the 15 percent climb in criminal cases
brought between 1997 and 1998, Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal judiciary were at full strength each district
judge would have on average presided over 93 criminal trials in
1999, compared to 89 the previous year, the chief justice added.
</P>
<P>
   But the average number of cases each judge actually presided
over was significantly higher due to the 42 vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
