<SLUG> BC-BELL-10CENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL TO OFFER NEW YORK LONG-DISTANCE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phone giant Bell Atlantic is expected to roll out a flat-rate
calling plan in New York state Tuesday, one with no monthly minimum
fee.
</P>
<P>
   The New York plan appears to reflect a consensus view among Baby
Bells that as they begin to return to the long-distance business,
they can profitably target low-volume long-distance customers who
have been irritated by the $6 and $7 monthly fees AT&AMP;T, MCI, and
Sprint charge as a condition of getting flat-rate calls as cheap as
5 or 7 cents a minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that Bell Atlantic's
plan will offer New Yorkers long-distance calls for 10 cents a
minute. Bell Atlantic officials would not confirm that, and they
stressed the ``surprise-free'' flat-rate plan is only one of
several they will unveil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to very aggressively offer plans in all market
segments,'' said Bell Atlantic Massachusetts spokesman Jack Hoey.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's World Wide Web site indicated Monday it will
also offer in New York a long-distance calling plan charging 9
cents a minute, and 5 cents on weekends, to people who sign up over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts were disappointed that the first foray by a Baby
Bell into the long-distance market since the 1984 AT&AMP;T breakup
could be, as Atlanta telecommunications analyst Jeffrey Kagan put
it, ``a yawner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten cents per minute might be a bit disappointing if consumers
were expecting a long-distance price war,'' Kagan said, adding that
he sees Bell Atlantic wanting to compete to retain customers with a
bundle of services rather than waging a margin-shaving price war.
</P>
<P>
   But others noted that no one is in a better position than Bell
Atlantic to make money going after people who make few toll calls.
The company is already carrying the biggest expense _ maintaining
accounts and sending bills _ and because actual call completion is
now so cheap, getting another $3 or $4 a month from millions of
low-volume customers can be mostly gravy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've already got the billing relationship, and that's where
all the cost is,'' said telecommunications analyst Fred Voit of
Yankee Group in Boston. ``AT&AMP;T and MCI are going to be delighted to
lose customers who spend $3 or $4 a month. If they could send a
list of those customers to Bell Atlantic and say `Take them,' they
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Voit also said he thinks ``all Bell Atlantic has to do is come
out and say `We've got long distance,' and their phones are going
to be ringing off the hook. I don't think they have to come out
with killer prices. Ten cents is a very good price, especially
without a fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoey said Bell Atlantic thinks it can hope to get 25 to 30
percent of Massachusetts' long-distance market within five years.
``We think that's realistic given that we have a strong existing
relationship with the customer that will allow us to go after what
some people call the lower end of the long-distance market,'' Hoey
said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, which is fighting in court to block Bell Atlantic from the
New York long-distance market, already offers a 10-cents-per-minute
plan with no monthly fee to people who sign up over the Internet
and pay by credit card.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, AT&AMP;T has drawn more than 60,000 customers already
with a ``Local One Rate New York'' plan that charges $24.90 a month
for 75 hours of local calling, 7 cents per minute interstate long
distance and 5 cents for in-state toll calls, spokesman Gary
Morgenstern said.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Corp., the Texas-based Baby Bell that plans to offer local
service in Eastern Massachusetts as soon as this fall, has
indicated its offerings will include a similar no-monthly-fee
long-distance calling plan and perhaps a fixed-fee ``all you can
eat'' calling plan for residential customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
