<HEADER>
A5660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FBI-AGENT-BOS &LR;      01-03 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-AGENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI-AGENT, MOB FIGURE APPEAR AS CODEFENDANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For decades they appeared to be on opposite sides, one
a notorious gangster, the other a decorated FBI agent. One an FBI
informant, the other his longtime handler.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi and retired FBI
Special Agent John J. Connolly Jr. came together in US District
Court in Boston as codefendants in a federal racketeering case.
</P>
<P>
   As federal marshals removed handcuffs from Flemmi's wrists,
Connolly jumped to his feet and walked to the other end of the
defense table to shake Flemmi's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, 65, dressed in a navy and white jogging suit, and
Connolly, 59, wearing a dark suit, crisp white shirt and tie,
chatted briefly, then Connolly returned to his seat alongside his
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Missing was the third defendant in the case, South Boston crime
boss James ``Whitey'' Bulger, also one of Connolly's prized
informants, who has been a fugitive since a warrant was issued for
his arrest five years ago today (Jan. 4) in another racketeering
case.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, Flemmi and Bulger were charged three days before
Christmas in a federal racketeering indictment that alleges that
Connolly protected them from prosecution and tipped them to the
earlier indictment five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation should have been dubbed, if it wasn't
already, Operation Scapegoat,'' said Boston attorney R. Robert
Popeo, who represents Connolly. ``They have rewritten history.''
</P>
<P>
   Popeo insists Connolly's handling of Bulger and Flemmi was
overseen and authorized by his FBI superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing before US Magistrate Judge Robert Collings lasted
less than 30 minutes. Connolly had pleaded not guilty to
racketeering and obstruction of justice charges at his arraignment
Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Collings postponed Flemmi's scheduled arraignment after his
longtime lawyer, Kenneth Fishman, announced he wouldn't be
available to represent him in the new racketeering case. Collings
said he'll allow Flemmi, who is indigent, time to find a
court-appointed lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Fishman told reporters that he can't take on the new case
involving Flemmi because of the ``tremendous time commitment''
required by the five-year-old racketeering case involving Flemmi
that has yet to go to trial before US District Judge Mark L. Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   And Fishman wasn't the only one claiming that he doesn't have
enough time to handle the new case.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf, who was randomly assigned to preside over the
Connolly-Bulger-Flemmi case, recused himself, citing a heavy
caseload, including the 1995 racketeering case.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had been poised to seek the removal of Wolf, who
had concluded in a 661-page decision last September that Connolly
had committed numerous crimes to protect Bulger and Flemmi --
including tipping the pair on the eve of the 1995 indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's order followed hearings throughout 1998 that exposed the
FBI's cozy relationship between Bulger and Flemmi from 1975 through
1995. Wolf refused to dismiss the indictment against Flemmi, who
claimed the FBI promised him immunity from prosecution in exhange
for providing information about local Mafia leaders. But Wolf has
ordered more hearings in that case.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-page order, Wolf insisted he could remain impartial
but chose to remove himself from the case because of concerns about
his workload.
</P>
<P>
   Citing how exceptionally time-consuming the earlier Flemmi case
has been, Wolf wrote, ``I expect that if I retain the new case, it
will seriously disrupt my plans for previously pending cases on my
docket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connolly-Flemmi-Bulger case was assigned to US District
Judge Joseph L. Tauro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
