u a BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-COX     01-03 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-WINNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia residents in the money, win Big Game jackpot
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A ``good life'' got richer for Katheryn and Paul Lowry
of Norcross, Ga., on Monday. The couple walked out of the Georgia
Lottery offices in downtown Atlanta with a $14.8 million check.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowrys won a $46 million Big Game jackpot just after 11 p.m.
on New Year's Eve, two days after their 10th wedding anniversary.
The jackpot was the fifth largest in Georgia Lottery history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to retire a year early and start making some plans
for us and the kids,'' said Katheryn Lowry, a 61-year-old loan
processor who bought the winning ticket from a Racetrac gas station
in Gwinnett County. ``I'd like to buy a lot in Michigan on a lake _
put up a summer home some place that we can go to fish and just
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lowrys, who won on a ``quik pic'' ticket, chose to be paid
all at once instead of over 30 years, whittling their win to more
than $22.4 million. They paid $7.6 million in state and local
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Katheryn Lowry plans to quit work, she and Paul, 71,
won't give up the three-bedroom, two-bathroom home that they bought
new more than three years ago for $154,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during an afternoon press conference how the money would
change their lives, 71-year-old retiree Paul Lowry leaned on his
cane and choked back tears: ``We already have a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lowry, who was forced into retirement from General Motors
10 years ago after a stroke, said the money will provide
higher-priced physical therapy to continue his recovery. He also
wants a pontoon boat for the Michigan log cabin the Lowry's will
build. Parents of six children between them, they intend to set up
college funds for their 16 grandchildren and several
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowry's watched the television drawing Friday night as their
winning numbers _ 4, 17, 32, 38, 46 and Big Game ball 26 _ were
chosen. They passed the ticket back and forth in disbelief. After a
fruit and toast breakfast Monday at home and a chat later with a
banker, the couple made it downtown to claim their prize after
lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Said Katheryn: ``We've been kind of relaxed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Duane D. Stanford writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
