<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-(TRIM     01-03 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN MOVES TO FRESHEN UP KREMLIN REGIME
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Acting President Vladimir Putin began to put his own
imprint on the Kremlin administration Monday, showing the door to
Tatyana Dyachenko, who wielded considerable influence in the
administration of her father, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also moved aside several other staff members who had been
loyal to Yeltsin. But as one television commentator said Monday
night, the changes amount to a ``freshening up'' of the
administration rather than a revolution inside the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Long vilified by anti-Yeltsin forces as a palace intriguer, Mrs.
Dyachenko, 39, had served as Yeltsin's official image maker since
his re-election campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment effectively ended when Yeltsin resigned on
Friday. On Monday, even before Putin issued a decree removing her,
she was already packing her papers, said Dmitri Yakushkin, who
served as Yeltsin's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Gorbachev, the previous Soviet president, said in an
interview published Monday that Mrs. Dyachenko and other members of
the ``family'' _ as Yeltsin's inner circle was dubbed _ were
responsible for persuading Yeltsin to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to,'' Gorbachev said in an interview published
in the Italian newspaper La Stampa. ``He resisted with all his
might. Essentially they pushed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev was quoted as saying Yeltsin had finally been
convinced that he should quit by doctors who told him that to stay
on as the Russian leader could prove ``fatal.'' Yeltsin had
frequent health problems throughout his years in office, including
multiple bypass heart surgery in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dyachenko, the younger of Yeltsin's two daughters, used her
influence in the Kremlin to control access to her father. She was
an essential figure in a circle that also included Boris
Berezovsky, a financier and media magnate, and Anatoly Chubais,
designer of Russia's privatization program. The two men played
important roles last fall in helping Putin's campaign for this
year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dyachenko's name was mentioned in several financial
scandals that enveloped the Kremlin last summer. She allegedly made
tens of thousands of dollars of purchases on a credit card supplied
to her by a Swiss company that held lucrative Kremlin contracts.
And her husband, Leonid, an oil trader connected to Kremlin-favored
oil companies, was reportedly linked to foreign bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with La Stampa, Gorbachev said that the
architects of Yeltsin's resignation were Mrs. Dyachenko,
Berezovsky, and the Kremlin chief of staff, Alexander Voloshin.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's press secretary, Yakushkin, said in an interview
Monday on a Moscow radio station that Yeltsin made up his own mind
to leave office early and to give Putin, Yeltsin's recently
appointed prime minister and heir apparent, a head-start in the
upcoming presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the president listens to opinions, but makes
decisions himself,'' said Yakushkin. ``And this decision was not
discussed in the family circle. Of course, he considers Putin an
ideal choice for Russia's further development. To an extent he felt
that he had become a factor curbing Putin's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Yakushkin said that Yeltsin would be given office space in one
of the buildings in the Kremlin and was expected to take trips
abroad and within Russia as the country's president emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 5, Yeltsin is to visit Bethlehem, a which had already
been planned. He will celebrate a Russian Orthodox Christmas Eve
service there with Aleksy II, patriarch of the Russian church.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as Yeltsin eases into retirement, spending his ``happiest''
New Year's holiday ever, Yakushkin said, Putin had a full schedule
of official meetings Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He met with the Central Bank chairman, Viktor Gerashchenko, and
with Nikolai Koshman, Moscow's envoy to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also met Monday with Marat Baglai, chairman of the
Constitutional Court. Baglai indicated in remarks afterward that
presidential elections might take place earlier than anticipated,
as the constitution stipulates only that they be held ``within''
three months of the president's resignation. A final date will be
set later this week by Parliament's upper house, Baglai said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a senior aide to Putin said his chances in that
election had been enhanced by Yeltsin's signing of a new law
raising the barrier for challengers in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before he resigned on Friday, Yeltsin signed the extensive
rewrite of election laws, one clause of which requires presidential
candidates to amass 1 million signatures on petitions to gain spots
on an election ballot. The law previously had lowered that barrier
by half, to only 500,000 signatures, in the case of an early
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's first deputy chief of staff, Igor Shabdurasulov,
said the restoration of the 1-million-signature requirement would
make it extremely difficult for Putin's challengers to land a space
on the ballot by the closing of the registration period for the
election, probably in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his first decrees, Putin reappointed Voloshin as chief
of staff. But Monday Putin relieved several top aides from their
official positions.
</P>
<P>
   They include Vladimir Makarov, a deputy chief of staff; Vladimir
Shevchenko, director of the Kremlin protocol office, and Valery
Semenchenko, director of the president's chancellery. The last two
have been retained as informal advisers to Putin, said Alexei
Gromov, director of the presidential press service.
</P>
<P>
   A top Kremlin official, quoted tonight by the Interfax news
agency, said that both Shevchenko and Semenchenko would be
transferred to Yeltsin's personal staff, where they would provide
the services ``essential for the first Russian president to keep on
with his active political work and maintain his government role.''
</P>
<P>
   Yakushkin, who is expected to take a job as Yeltsin's personal
spokesman, was relieved Monday of his position as presidential
press secretary, and given another job as assistant to Voloshin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
