</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS SAYS DECISION MADE WITHOUT PATRIOTS IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Parcells laughed at the thought that he would give up his
coaching career just so the Patriots would not get Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Patriots wanted to do had nothing to do with my
decision to leave coaching _ nothing whatsoever,'' said Parcells.
``I had known pretty much for the last month that I was going to
give up coaching at the end of this season, and Saturday I spoke
with Belichick about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been talking with Belichick all the way along throughout
the season. Saturday morning I met with him and asked him if he
wanted to be the next head coach of the New York Jets. He told me,
`I've been planning on it,' and he said this is the job he wanted.
If he was upset about not having the chance to go to New England,
he's never said anything to me about it. I don't think that's the
case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, the Patriots sent a fax to Steve Gutman,
president of the Jets, asking permission to speak with Belichick
about becoming head coach and general manager in New England. But
it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had resigned Sunday night, informing Gutman, and under
the terms of a contract that had been signed three years ago,
Belichick automatically went into place as head coach of the Jets.
That preempted the Patriots' attempted strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the question (of permission) was moot,'' said
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the situation, a league official said, ``This
time, the Jets had the contracts on their side. The last time, they
didn't. The contracts were in New England's favor.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Patriots and Jets got into a major fight over
Parcells. He wanted to leave New England for the Jets after the
Patriots' Super Bowl season. NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue
intervened, settling the matter by awarding the Patriots four draft
choices in return for giving up their coaching rights to Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported Monday that Belichick was upset because he did not
have the chance to entertain the Patriots' offer.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was not available for comment. However, it seems
highly unlikely that he was upset. First, since the Patriots had no
way of talking to him without violating league rules, Belichick
would have no way of knowing what the New England offer was in
terms of money. Second, he is the general manager of the Jets,
without the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is going to be in complete control of the football side
of the business,'' said Parcells. ``I'm giving him everything that
I had here as a coach. He'll call all the shots. I'm stepping
completely away from the coaching end. I have coached my last game.
I will never coach another football game in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is a Machiavellian conspiracy theory afloat that
Parcells set up the Patriots _ that he arranged it so that the
Patriots would have to give the Jets compensation (i.e. draft
picks) if they want to hire their top candidate, Belichick. And
then, if this transpired, Parcells would return to coaching the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said today that I have coached my last game,'' said
Parcells. ``I will never coach another. That is it. I don't know
where some of you guys come up with some of this stuff, although I
will say it is creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who now has the title of head of football operations,
says he intends to stay on the perimeter of the Jets' front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Bill (Belichick) if he wants me to help in any way I'll
be here,'' said Parcells. ``I'm not running into his office and
offering any advice. When the new owner shows up here, I'll help
him any way I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``My future is going to be month to month. Each month I'll
evaluate my life and see if I am happy with what I am doing. But
let me say it again: I'll never coach another football game, so
people can start all the rumors they want, and it just isn't going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
