<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-HANCOCK-BASEBALL-     01-03 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HANCOCK-BASEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK TO SPONSOR MAJOR LEAGUALL FOR FIVE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. signed a
five-year sponsorship agreement with Major League Baseball Monday
that sources said is worth at least $10 million and probably much
more.
</P>
<P>
   The move extends a one-year contract that Hancock had in
connection with the 1999 MLB All-Star Game at Fenway Park and puts
the Boston-based insurance giant in the company of Adidas,
FleetBoston Financial Group, Gillette, Gulden's mustard,
MasterCard, Pepsi-Cola, and Ritz crackers, also Major League
Baseball sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   One source familiar with the Hancock-MLB negotiations said the
deal could be worth $35 million, but Hancock spokesman Steve Burgay
disputed that. ``In terms of what we are paying Major League
Baseball, that is wildly, wildly inaccurate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual number, the contract was seen within the
close-knit world of sports marketing as record-setting for a Major
League Baseball sponsorship, both in the dollar amount and in its
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Fleet Financial Group was reported to have paid
between $4 million and $6 million last April in a Major League
Baseball deal that extends into 2001, with an option to renew for
one additional year.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, which also sponsors the Boston Marathon, the Olympics,
and college sports events, said it's sure it will get its money's
worth during the 162-game season, played out in 30 venues from
coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we continue to expand our product and distribution lines in
the financial services business, Major League Baseball will be a
partner, a differentiator, and a way for us to sell,'' Hancock's
president, David F. D'Alessandro, said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's ability to capitalize on such deals is respected in
the sports industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are among the companies that know how to make
sponsorships work well,'' said Sean Brenner, an editor at IEG
Sponsorship Report in Chicago. ``D'Allesandro and Hancock have a
lot of experience at this.''
</P>
<P>
   And the John Hancock brand is expected to help Major League
Baseball further regain stature lost during a 1994 labor dispute
between players and team owners that led to an abbreviated season
and cancellation of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``By their partnering with us they are telling their customers
something about the importance of our property,'' said Timothy J.
Brosnan, senior vice president for Major League Baseball
Properties.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, signed last week, makes Hancock Major League
Baseball's 18th ``official sponsor,'' a number that some say
approaches the limit of what fans can tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All professional sports have suffered somewhat in what
consumers see as overcommrcialism,'' said Jed Pearsall, of
Performance Research Inc. in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's long-term affiliation with professional baseball comes
as the company converts from mutual ownership by its policyholders
and races toward an initial public stock offering that could raise
$2.6 billion to finance further marketing efforts and growth. That
offering is scheduled for Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Major League Baseball agreement certifies Hancock as an
exclusive sponsor in a broad ``financial services'' category that
ranges from pension management to long-term care insurance,
investments, and a portfolio of stock and bond mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Effectively, this blocks others in similar fields _ for example,
Fidelity Investments, Merrill Lynch, or Prudential Life Insurance _
from also winning sponsorship agreements with Major League
Baseball. Such competitors remain free, however, to bid for local
sponsor rights, as Coca-Cola has done in Atlanta in spite of a
nationwide agreement between MLB and Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock may seek team-by-team local agreements to augment its
MLB sponsorship pact, Burgay said, pointing out that John Hancock
is already an official sponsor of the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   About the only subcategories not included in the Hancock-MLB
sponsorship agreement are retail banking, held by Fleet, and credit
cards, shared by MBNA Financial and MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the ability to display its name prominently in
connection with games, playoffs, the All-Star Game, and the World
Series, Hancock also gains priority in obtaining tickets for its
employees and clients and in recruiting ballplayers to endorse
insurance plans, mutual funds, and other investment instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific marketing platform for us,'' Burgay said.
``Baseball demographics tend to cut fairly broadly, but as you get
closer to the playoffs it gets to be more upscale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
