<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW AND S&AMP;P 500 LOSE, NASDAQ GAIN AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks began the new year with a topsy-turvy
performance Monday, as technology and Internet shares bolted to new
records even as broad swaths of the market slumped in the wake of a
sharp rise in long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Observers who note only the closing quotes for major market
averages would probably comment that the Nasdaq composite index
continued to perform as it did throughout much of December, when it
rose in what seemed like a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which ended 1999 with a record, did so again Monday.
Led by companies like JDS Uniphase, Yahoo and CMGI, the index
gained 61.84 points, or 1.52 percent, to 4,131.15.
</P>
<P>
   But the road to the close was bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the opening, the Nasdaq was up more than 122,
to as high as 4,192.19. The index then reversed and fell as low as
3,989.71 _ a swing of 202.48.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the performance of the Dow Jones industrial average
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was more consistent: Both
measures moved lower shortly after the opening bell, and stayed
down throughout the session.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market's bad day hit financial service stocks
particularly hard as investors feared that the Federal Reserve
might raise interest rates now that year 2000 computer glitches
have not materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at 11,357.51, down 139.61 points, or 1.21
percent. American Express, General Electric and J.P. Morgan were
the Dow's biggest losers. Cyclical stocks like Minnesota Mining &AMP;
Manufacturing and Alcoa _ companies whose businesses are also
sensitive to rising rates _ also registered declines. Weakness in
bank and brokerage stocks, as well as oil and big retailers, helped
to drag down the S&AMP;P 500 index by 14.03 points, or 0.95 percent, to
1,455.22.
</P>
<P>
   And the Russell 2000 index of smaller cap stocks was also
hammered. The index fell 8.33 points, or 1.65 percent, to 496.42.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to back out an investment thesis from
today's session, even though the backup in bond yields was
dramatic,'' said Satya Pradhuman, director of small cap research at
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this might be an unwinding of the fast run-up we saw
last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while many spent much of December worrying that the
Federal Reserve would move to raise short-term interest rates at
its February meeting, nearly as many said they expected to see
investors take advantage of the strong move in December stock
prices and take some profits n the new year, thereby
delaying capital gains taxes until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of people have expected tremendous tax selling,''
said Fred Kobrick, president and chief executive of Kobrick Funds,
a Boston-based mutual fund company. ``This was one pie in the face
of the market that was welltelegraphed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the big swings in prices, traders said the market was
fairly quiet.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, more than 931.8 million shares
changed hands. Volume on the Nasdaq stock market was 1.48 billion
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volatility would connote there was more activity than was
actually going on,'' said Bill Allyn, head of listed trading at
Jefferies &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase led the rise in the Nasdaq, climbing 26 11/16, to
188. The stock jumped after the manufacturer of parts used in
fiber-optic equipment announced plans for its third 2-for-1 stock
split since July.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI gained 49 9/16, to 326 7/16. America Online was up 7 5/16,
to 82 3/4. And Yahoo jumped 42 5/16, to 475.
</P>
<P>
   Strength in technology was not limited to companies whose
corporate history did not begin at some point in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   IBM gained 7 9/16, to 115 9/16. Hewlett-Packard was up 3 1/2, to
117 7/16. And Intel rose 4 11/16, to 87. All three companies are
components of the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Among financial stocks, American Express slid 9, to 157 1/4.
J.P. Morgan fell 5 3/16, to 121 7/16. Citigroup fell 2 13/16, to 52
7/8. And General Electric, whose GE Capital subsidiary is the
largest nonbank finance company, shed 4 3/4, to 150.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks also fell. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter tumbled 7
3/4, to 135. Merrill Lynch fell 2 11/16, to 80 5/8. And Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette lost 1 7/16, to 46 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good day for biotechnology stocks. Amgen rose 2 7/8, to
62 15/16, on expectations that it will beat fourth-quarter earnings
estimates and is on track to win approval of two new drugs.
Genentech rose 1 1/2, to 136. Biogen was up 3 1/2, to 88. And
Millennium Pharmaceuticals jumped 17 15/16, to 139 15/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
