u f BC-Y2K-EXCHANGES-BOS &LR;      01-03 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-EXCHANGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCHANGES, OTHERS UNFAZED BY Y2K BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American businesses and workplaces cleared a major test of the
technological era Monday, as the first business day of the new
century passed with little significant fallout from the once-feared
Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   As Americans returned to work after the New Year's holiday, the
nation's stock markets, financial institutions, manufacturers and
other major organization reported few computer problems caused by
the calendar rollover to 2000. The results suggested that years of
preparation and billions of dollars spent by large corporations to
head off the potential disruptions had paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Even small businesses, which had been seen as the least
prepared, seemed to have exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of scattered glitches emerged, however. At South End
Video in Boston, a database struck by the Y2K bug incorrectly
determined 400 customers didn't meet age restrictions for PG-13
movies like ``The Waterboy.'' ``I made a lot of people feel young
again,'' said Alex Pinck, the video store's owner, who quickly
found a way to override the problem.
</P>
<P>
   So went reports from around the country as officials including
John Koskinen, President Clinton's chief Y2K adviser, called the
most worrisome aspects of Y2K beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we continue to find that the extensive
time, effort and work devoted to this problem . . . have resulted
in the fact that while there are glitches around the edges, the
systems are running well and we have made a successful
transition,'' Koskinen told reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a UN-sponsored monitoring center cancelled briefings for
lack of new data.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's financial institutions, including stock markets and
banks, said they averted major problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, institutions including FleetBoston Financial, Thomson
Financial, the Massachusetts Bankers Association and the Federal
Reserve Bank of Boston reported no troubles. The Boston Stock
Exchange said it handled a record number of trades, about 100,000,
which it attributed to confidence that most computers had survived
Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   In Lexington, Mass., defense contractor Raytheon Co. reported
only a few problems with security-card readers that were resolved
early Saturday morning, within an hour after the glitches surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   State utility officials and regulators called systems normal.
</P>
<P>
   The overall prospects of small businesses, the most difficult
area of the economy to measure, may not be known for weeks. For
most ``mom-and-pop'' businesses, ``the jury's still out,'' said
FleetBoston spokesman Jim Schepker.
</P>
<P>
   But early returns were cheering. In Gaithersberg, Md., a hotline
set up by the Small Business Administration to assist in
last-minute fixes had received just 200 calls nationwide since
Thursday, said Scott McIntyre, a manager for the service. ``I think
everybody's done their homework,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K problem stemmed from the habit of many older computers
to use just two digits to represent the year; left unfixed,
``2000'' could have been misread and caused many systems to shut
down or malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The problem turned out to be more complicated than originally
estimated; in many cases companies doubled their initial estimate
of the cost to fix bugs. The federal government once estimated it
would spend $2.7 billion and wound up spending about $8.5 billion
on Y2K work.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen estimated that global spending on Y2K totalled around
$200 billion, although other estimates vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, it seemed the massive worldwide spending campaign
had succeeded in minimizing the bug's impact. A random telephone
survey by the Boston Globe of about 20 businesses around New
England found four that reported problems, though none seemed
serious.
</P>
<P>
   At Architect's Studio Inc. i Easton, Mass., designers
Monday mornnd they couldn't ship drawings over the Internet
because computers made by Gateway Inc. were running old software.
</P>
<P>
   Bookkeeper Mary Dixon said several customers granted extensions
and, by the end of the day, Gateway had promised to send floppy
disks with new code by overnight mail. ``People have been very
gracious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, Mass., attorney Jim Rafferty grumbled after
discovering he couldn't log on to legal databases, despite spending
about $12,500 last year on Y2K software upgrades and consulting
fees. ``In terms of productivity, we're not affected,'' Rafferty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other firms had nothing to report. ``Things are
fine,'' said Liz Kay of South End Realty in Boston, who updated
software on 10 computers last month.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after thousands of merchants in England reported
problems with credit-card machines, US Petroleum gas stations in
Massachusetts put up notices they would only accept cash. But
Monday George Artin, manager of one such station in Cambridge, said
the chain would resume accepting cards on Thursday, the first day
possible under the terms of the company's network contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing, but it was better to be safe than sorry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The limited fallout has led to defensive comments from some
experts and officials, worried they would be accused of overblowing
the problem. Deustche Bank economist Ed Yardeni, once one of the
most pessimistic observers, wrote on his Web site that some risk
remains but added that ``if no significant problems occur by the
end of January, then I will concede I was wrong about a Y2K global
downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   At Raytheon Co., computer-systems director Saul Fisher said he
didn't regret the $121 million Raytheon spent over two years in the
name of preventing damage related to Y2K. The company spends
roughly $700 million on technology annually, and Fisher said the
Y2K program helped ``rationalize'' what had been a hodgepodge of
computer systems and accounts around the company.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company discovered it was doing business with
Compaq Computer Corp. using 30 different accounts, and consolidated
them into one to gain more negotiating leverage. ``There were a lot
of other benefits'' aside from preventing obvious Y2K shutdowns,
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff reporters Lynnley Browning and Aaron Zitner
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2035EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
