u a BC-PEACE-TALKS-HNS &LR;      01-03 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND ROUND OF ISRAELI-SYRIAN PEACE TALKS OPEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim, optional ending) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ Israel and Syria opened a second round of
peace talks Monday in hopes of ending more than 50 years of
hostilities and setting a course toward a final comprehensive
settlement of Arab-Israeli disputes.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was on hand to kick off negotiations between
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa, who held their first historic meeting last month
at the White House. They agreed in that meeting _ the first ever
high-level Syrian-Israeli discussions _ to enter intense
negotiations aimed at producing a peace agreement by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Israel on Sunday night, Barak told reporters he
still feels a ``burden of responsibility'' to reach an agreement
this year. Syrian officials said they had come to this rural
college town with ``open minds'' and a ``true desire'' to settle
their differences with Israel over the Golan Heights, which Israel
captured during the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   But State Department spokesman James Rubin sought to play down
speculation about a quick settlement of the long-standing problems
that have kept the two countries in a state of war since Israel was
established in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our view that progress can be made ... But we have no
reason to expect that a core agreement can be reached in a couple
of days,'' Rubin told reporters. He added that the Shepherdstown
talks could run a week or more and may, in the end, produce only a
promise to meet again later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement of the Syrian-Israeli dispute would finally close
``the circle of peace in the Middle East,'' as Rubin put it, that
began with the Camp David Accords between Egypt and Israel in 1978
and has since led to Israeli agreements with Jordan and, most
recently, the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would like to see a comprehensive settlement between
Israel and all its Arab neighbors before he leaves office next
January. He set to work on that task by meeting separately with
Barak and al-Sharaa early in the afternoon. He later presided over
a face-to-face session between the two men held in the secluded
confines of the National Conservation Training Center here run by
the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the quiet community of Shepherdstown, located about
70 miles northwest of Washington, was chosen as the site for the
talks so the participants would be somewhat isolated and better
able to ``focus on narrowing the differences that divide them.''
Both the Israeli and Syrian delegations are being housed in the
nearby Clarion Hotel and Conference Center, many of them in rooms
on the same floor. Rubin said the arrangements, including communal
dining, are designed to keep the two sides together and talking as
much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to create a ``climate'' conducive to success,
Rubin said both sides are also being encouraged to show restraint
during the talks. He said the Syrians were asked specifically to
use their influence in Lebanon with the militant Arab group known
as Hezbollah to curb terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique and historic opportunity and the kind of
opportunity that may never come again,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and al-Sharaa, who is representing Syrian President Hafez
Assad at the talks, began their discussions by joining Clinton in a
short stroll around the grounds of the training center, which sits
along the Potomac River. The three looked to be deep in
conversation at one point. They refused to answer questions shouted
at them by a handful of reporters. Clinton waved and smiled for the
cameras, and then herded Barak and al-Sharaa back into the
conference center.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton hopes to act
``as a facilitator'' and ``honest broker'' in the talks as they
proceed over the next week or so and, quite likely, into the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
He also cautioned against speculation of an immediate breakthrough
in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take it day-by-day. At the end of the week
we'll take stock of where we are,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to shuttle back and forth by helicopter
between Shepherdstown and Washington ``as needed.'' But Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright and special Middle East envoy Dennis
Ross planned to remain behind to help keep the talks on track.
</P>
<P>
   Albright called the Shepherdstown talks ``the beginning of a
process'' that could lead to a land-for-peace deal giving Syria the
Golan Heights in return for security guarantees to Israel. Those
issues are the most difficult, but other issues, including water
rights and normalization of relations, could prove to be equally
hard to resolve for the two long-time enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, seem determined to make the effort work.
Evidence of that could be seen in the size of their respective
delegations. Barak, for example, brought along his government's top
legal, national security and military officials, as well as
representatives from Israel's tourism and cultural agencies.
Syria's delegation was large as well. Altogether, the influx of the
U.S., Syrian and Israeli delegations _ not to mention several dozen
reporters _ nearly doubled the Shepherdstown population of 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said talks would be taking
place ``at various levels'' between the two countries even as Barak
and al-Sharaa are meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barak seemed to stress the urgency of moving the peace talks
along on a number of tracks before arriving in Sstown. ``We
don't need to wait for another millennium, another century or even
another 10 years to find a way to make peace with our neighbors,''
he told Israeli journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Although al-Sharaa is Assad's most trusted aide and has been
authorized to speak for him in the talks, Israeli Foreign Minister
David Devy said Israel would insist on the Syrian leader joining
the talks at some point before anything is finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who makes only rare public appearances and travels
infrequently, has never participated in any peace talks with
Israel. Al-Sharaa led the Syrian delegation in 1996 when it held
low-level talks with Israeli officials. Those talks broke down in
1996 after a series of terrorist bombings in Israel. They were
revived last month at the White House after Clinton spent months
talking to Assad and Barak by telephone urging them to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, who has reportedly been ill, would like to oversee the
return of the Golan Heights to Syria before he dies or turns over
power to his son. Barak has indicated that he is ready to give up
much of the disputed territory bordering Lebanon and the Sea of
Galilee, but has refused to say whether he will return all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants assurances that Israel will still have access to the
Galilee, an important fresh water source for the Jewish state. He
also wants assurances that the Syrian army will be withdrawn from
the immediate area of the Golan Heights and that ``listening
posts'' will be established on Mt. Hermon to monitor any movement
of Syrian forces toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is expected to play an important role in any
final agreement, both financially and, possibly, militarily.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said, however, that it would be
``premature'' to discuss the amount of funding Clinton might ask
Congress for to help implement any agreement or whether U.S. troops
would have to be committed to the region to help keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Damascus, Syrians staged a sit-in denouncing the
Jewish state and demanding the immediate release of Syrian
prisoners in Israeli jails, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   The government-sanctioned protest, held annually for three years
but this year timed to coincide with the negotiations, was a
reminder of the numerous thorny issues facing negotiators and the
need for both sides to take steps to build each other's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
