<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      01-03 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Cowboys' season is now just as good as last year's.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the Cowboys' record is just as good as any of the teams
still playing.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Cowboys slid into the playoffs at 8-8. But they woke
up Monday morning with a fresh start and a 0-0 record to match
those of the other 11 playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   The .500 record means the Cowboys won't get a bye and, barring a
Dallas-Detroit NFC Championship Game, won't be playing again at
Texas Stadium this season. But that's all it means. From here on
out, it doesn't matter that the Cowboys lost to the Jets and the
Saints. It doesn't matter that Dallas won only once on the road
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, the slate was wiped clean, and the Cowboys have
as good a chance as anybody to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the Cowboys see it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've had as good a season as we had a year ago,''
quarterback Troy Aikman said, referring to the fact that Dallas
made the playoffs but went no further after a first-round loss to
Arizona. ``That's it. That's the reality. All that matters now is
what happens in the playoffs. It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out and play like we're capable of playing, I think
we've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's believable if you buy into that theory that each team
starts fresh in the playoffs, or that the regular season is solely
a means of positioning for the playoffs. The problem with that line
of thinking is that a 16-game schedule, whether the Cowboys choose
to admit it or not, generally is indicative of a team's talent
level.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Dallas went 10-6 with an easy schedule but fooled no
one, losing at home to the Cardinals in their playoff opener. And
the postseason road, which begins at 11:35 a.m. Sunday at
Minnesota, would appear even more difficult this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different feeling, going to the playoffs at 8-8,''
safety Darren Woodson said. ``Back in '92 and '93, we pretty much
dominated teams and always had the bye week. So this is different,
going to Minnesota to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Had they slipped in with another mediocre victory, perhaps the
Cowboys would be less positive. But after Sunday's 26-18 win over
the Giants, they had several reasons to be optimistic:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense, which had struggled against seemingly
lesser opponents this season, put up 437 yards against New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is as healthy as it has been all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have big-game experience.
</P>
<P>
   And they scored 17 unanswered points in the first half against
Minnesota before losing Emmitt Smith (broken hand), Aikman
(concussion) and eventually the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you like to do when you're David fighting
Goliath is make sure you have a good sling and good rocks,''
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. ``I feel like we have that.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there's nobody in the NFC who looks untouchable.
The St. Louis Rams have been the only team to set itself apart from
the pack in the NFC, but the Rams proved beatable Sunday as they
fell to the Philadelphia Eagles. Tampa Bay (11-5) won has won eight
of its last nine games but was blown out 45-0 by Oakland two weeks
ago. The Vikings (10-6) seem to be improving each week but have
been far from dominating all season. And Washington (10-6) and
Detroit (8-8) have been hot and cold, much like the Cowboys, this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of super teams, but most of them are in the AFC,''
Dallas offensive tackle Erik Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason experience factor could even the playing field.
The top-seeded Rams haven't been to the playoffs since 1989, and
the second-seeded Buccaneers have been once previously since 1979,
losing in the first round two years ago. Washington's last
appearance came in 1992, and although Detroit is playoff-bound for
the sixth time in nine seasons, the Lions haven't won a postseason
game since 1991. Minnesota owns the NFC's longest streak of playoff
seasons at four, but the Vikings failed to turn last year's 15-1
regular season into anything more than a loss to the Falcons in the
NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not easy to go to the Super Bowl, and this team has been
there more than any other team,'' Aikman said. ``I think anyone can
win this thing. It is more trueear than any other year that
I have been here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys are still convinced they're far better than an
8-8 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a miscarriage of something if we would have
had what we've got here, as far as our talent, and not have gotten
to the playoffs,'' Dallas owner Jerry Jones said. ``It would have
been a sad sight with all of the talent on this Cowboys team to
have them sitting at home watching the playoffs on TV. I don't know
if we can shove this much talent on the table again with the salary
cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the last intangible is the Cowboys' ``mystique.'' It's
not enough to pull them through if they play a bad game. But all
else being equal, it could help tip the scales in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of talent,'' Woodson said. ``Teams see that we
have Emmitt, Deion (Sanders) and Troy, and they don't want to see
us. We've got players who have been to the show. Teams that play us
know they're going to have a tough game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
