<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5705 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-REDLINE-SETTLE-KAN &LR;      01-03 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDLINE-SETTLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRUDENTIAL SETTLES INSURANCE DISCRIMINATION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL WENSKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Prudential Property and Casualty Insurance
Co. has agreed to pay a total of $200,000 to 16 Missouri residents
who say the company discriminated against minority homeowners in
its underwriting practices.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential last week settled its portion of federal and state
lawsuits filed in February 1996 against 10 homeowners insurance
groups. Fifteen of the plaintiffs live in Kansas City; one lives in
St. Louis. Attorney fees will be paid out of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sprenger, a Kansas City lawyer whose firm represented the
16 plaintiffs, all of whom are black, said the settlement was ``a
positive for minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   While settling the case, Prudential officials defended the
firm's practices in urban communities. Company officials said
Prudential had demonstrated ``a commitment to fair access.'' They
say the number of customers Prudential serves in urban, minority
areas is proportionately more than its share of the residential
insurance market across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Laurita Warner also said Prudential _ which has
about 1 percent of the Missouri residential property insurance
market _ agreed to seek state authorization to offer discounts to
homeowners in certain urban areas who meet safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Sprenger said lawsuits were still pending against nine other
insurance groups accused of either denying homeowners insurance to
minorities or charging higher-than-normal premiums.
</P>
<P>
   All of the insurance companies have denied liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complaints in all the lawsuits say that because of a
variety of underwriting rules and marketing techniques, and other
sales practices, homeowners insurance has not been available at
all, or not in the terms available in white areas,'' Sprenger said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprenger said discrimination tactics included the denial of
insurance based on the age of a home or its market value.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Department of Insurance studies released in 1993 and
1995 showed that homeowners in predominantly minority neighborhoods
paid larger insurance premiums than white homeowners, and received
less in claims.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent 1998 state insurance study found that residents in
high-minority areas had less access to insurance agents, more
restricted policies and higher complaint rates than residents in
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Insurance Department spokesman Randy McConnell noted a
national trend of cases being settled against homeowners insurance
firms.
</P>
<P>
   He said insurers were required to sign anti-discrimination
pledges to do business in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have tried in various ways to ensure coverage for
minorities. But McConnell said developing language that guarantees
results had proved difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, citizens and consumer groups have also pressed
regulators in various states to release more information about how
insurers decide whom and where to insure.
</P>
<P>
   Sprenger acknowledged that insurers had begun marketing more in
urban neighborhoods, but he said homeowners insurance remained
``widely unavailable'' in minority areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sprenger said litigation was continuing against nine insurers
that collectively make up about 75 percent of the Missouri market
for homeowners insurance coverage. The companies and their percent
of the market:
</P>
<P>
   Allstate, 4; American Family, 17; Chubb, 1.5; Farm Bureau, 2.5;
Farmers, 8.5; Liberty Mutual, 1; Safeco//American States, 6.5;
Shelter, 6.5; and State Farm, 27.5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
