EDLIFE-BLACKBOARD-2 -- A drawing of Patrick Henry College. On 44
acres of secluded land in Virginia, about an hour west of
Washington, the foundation is being laid for an experiment in
higher education. Patrick Henry College will be both the nation's
first post-secondary institution designed for home-schooled
students and a training ground for Christian political advocates.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
EDLIFE-BLACKBOARD-1 -- When Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx
opens a children's hospital next year, every child's bedside will
be equipped with a computer that has Internet access. Similar plans
are under way for new children's facilities at the Westchester
Medical Center in Valhalla, N.Y., and the Columbia-Presbyterian
Center in Manhattan. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 9 --
EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-4 -- Liz Land, 72, who sings in the Smith
glee club, top, spends fours day a week in Northampton, Mass., and
three in Westport, Conn., with her husband, Gay. Mrs. Land was a
16-year-old freshman when she first arrived in Northampton from
Manhattan in 1943. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-3 -- Alyssa Mahoney reviewing
animal physiology with her 4-year-old son. Ms. Mahoney, 36, a
former hospice caregiver, is juggling her studies at Smith as a
premed student with her responsibilities as a single parent. ``In
your heart, you think, 'I'm here under false pretenses,' `` says
Ms. Mahoney. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-2 -- Sandy Colvard, 43, left,
and Laurel Mutti, 19, take a study break in Ms. Colvard's dorm
room. Ms. Colvard did not simply go back to college. She did
something far more daring: she quit her job as a logistician with
the United States Navy, packed up a U-Haul and moved into a
dormitory with 84 other undergraduates. ``When I got the letter
that I had been accepted, I sat on the floor of my living room and
I cried,'' she says. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NORTHAMPTON, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 9 -- EDLIFE-COLLEGE-RETURNEES-1 -- In 1932, Anne C.
Martindell's college career was sidetracked by a stern father's
restrictive dreams. ``He wanted me to get married, and he thought
it was a complete waste of time for me to be here,'' Mrs.
Martindell says. ``He thought I'd scare men off by being
overeducated.'' Now 85, she's back at Smith College, working toward
her bachelor's degree in a special program for nontraditional-age
students. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LAKELAND, Fla. -- Jan. 3, 2000 -- OBIT-ADDERLY -- Jazz
muscian Nat Adderley during his jazz improvisation class at Florida
Southern College in November, 1997. Adderley, the younger brother
of late bebop saxophonist Julian ``Cannonball'' Adderley, died
Sunday of complications from diabetes at age 68, a spokesman said
Monday. Inducted into the Jazz Hall of Fame in 1997, Adderley
played cornet and occasional trumpet on nearly 100 albums, many of
them with his better-known older sibling in the legendary
Cannonball Adderley Quintet. (Rick Runion/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- WOMAN-JUGGLER-2 -- Natalia
Sarygina performing with her juggling troupe at the Big Apple
Circus. At 28, she is among a handful of women worldwide at the top
of the juggling profession. Even rarer, she juggles clubs, which
are heftier than the batons, rings or soft balls that other female
jugglers favor. ``You can train and train, but if you miss one
thing, juggling becomes an ungrateful profession,'' she says.
(Ozier Muhammad/The New Yos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- WOMAN-JUGGLER-1 --
Five-foot-four and 110 pounds, Natalia Sarygina appears to have
more grace than intensity. At 28, she is among a handful of women
worldwide at the top of her profession: juggling. It is a field in
which men outnumber women 9 to 1, according to the International
Juggling Association. ``I think man is a man, he's more strong,''
she shrugs, speaking in Russian-laced English. ``A woman? It's a
woman.'' (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- WASHINGTON-FLOATER-B&AMP;W --
Workers dismantle on Monday the stage and lighting towers used for
New Year celebrations. From Main Street to Wall Street, Americans
returned to work Monday after spending the weekend celebrating the
arrival of the year 2000. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) HOLLYWOOD -- Jan. 03, 2000 --INTERNET-MOVIES -- Gary
Zeidenstein, left, and Amine Bitar set up a Web site to show their
film, ``Triangles and Tribulations,'' and have been besieged by
other filmmakers. ``It just started to snowball,'' says
Zeidenstein, 34. Today, Always Independent Films (www.alwaysif.com)
offers over 375 movies and trailers. (Mark Lyons/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MEDELLIN, Colombia -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- BOTERO-DONATE-3
-- Pilar Velilla Moreno is the director of the Museo de Antioquia
in Medellin, which will be hosting an installation of works by
Fernando Botero. ``Botero is a very important part of our cultural
identity, so of course we have always wanted him here,'' says Ms.
Moreno. ``He may live in Italy, but he has never stopped being from
Antioquia for a single day of his life, so that his work has always
portrayed us and who we are.'' (Larry Rohter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MEDELLIN, Colombia -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- BOTERO-DONATE-2
-- A child sits atop a sculpture by Fernando Botero in Medellin.
Over the next few months, the painter and sculptor intends to
install 79 of his paintings, drawings and sculptures that he has
just donated to the Museo de Antioquia here. (Larry Rohter/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MEDELLIN, Colombia -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- BOTERO-DONATE-1
-- Paintings by Fernando Botero in the Museo de Antioquia. Just the
mention of this city immediately conjures up images of drug
cartels, guerrillas and gangs of kidnappers and hired killers. But
Medellin is also hometown to Fernando Botero, 67, Latin America's
most celebrated living artist, and he is now putting the full
weight of his renown behind a wide-ranging effort to overhaul the
city's reputation and skyline. (Larry Rohter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Jan. 03, 2000 --
FBN-JETS-PARCELS-4 -- Bill Belichick, right, defensive coordinator
for the New York Jets, discusses strategy with the Victor Green
(21) and James Farrior during their game against the Buffalo Bills
in November, 1999. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) JERUSALEM -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- ISRAEL-WEITZMAN -- Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, left, speaks with Israeli President
Ezer Weizman during a memorial service for slain Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin in October, 1999. Weizman, an outspoken political
veteran, faces pressure to resign following his endorsement of an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights and revelations that he
accepted substantial, undisclosed financial gifts from a French
businessman. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SHREWSBURY, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- VIET-MIAS-BOS
---Eleanor Gregory, whose brother, Russell Peter Bott, was a Green
Beret last seen in Laos on Dec. 2, 1966, when he was 30 years old
and the father of a baby he never had the chance to hold. She
believes her brother may have been a prisoner of war, and that he
may still be one. ``It's been 33 years, and it's just like this all
happened yesterday,'' says Ms. Gregory, 66. (Frank O'Brien/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- DIVORCED-POET-BOS --
Meg Campbell, author of a poetry book about divorce, poses near her
office in Cambridge. Last October, Ms. Campbell was the featured
poet on www.PoetryCentral.com - a New York-based Web site promoting
poets and poetry events - and it resulted in ``this incredible
word-of-mouth networking,'' says Campbell, still dazzled. ``It's
really feeding on itself.'' (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BALTIMORE -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- SCI-CARSON-BRAIN-SURGERY --
Dr. Benjamin Solomon Carson viewing films of a patient on his way
to the operating room at Johns Hopkins Hospital. Carson, who
performs three to five operations daily, has an international
reputation as the man to call for tough pediatric neurosurgical
problems. (Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- SCI-FITNESS-KIDS -- Haley
Moran-Wollens, 13, working out with her personal trainer, Rodica
Vranceanu at Radu Gym in Manhattan. Even children now are turning
to personal trainers, and at least some exercise experts don't
think it's such a great idea. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- SCI-FOSSIL-EROSION-2 --
The stegosaur displayed at the National Museum of Natural History
in Washington, savaged for years by the hot breath of museum
visitors, is now, like some of its fossil neighbors, threatened
with destruction. The museum, part of the Smithsonian Institution,
hopes to save its most endangered fossils by removing them from
display and exhibiting only their plastic casts. (Marty Katz/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- SCI-FOSSIL-EROSION-1 --
This triceratops at the Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural
History will be replaced by a cast, but the skull will stay. The
biggest factor in the deterioration pf such prized fossils is
pyrite disease, a condition hastened by moisture, in which sulfur
and iron combine as pyrite (fool's gold), which replaces and
greatly weakens the mineralized bone in fossils. (Marty Katz/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- SCI-MOUTH-BACTERIA -- A
study last month in The Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences identified 37 new kinds of bacteria thriving between teeth
and gum. The research brings the total known species of oral
wildlife to about 500, some of which are permanent residents while
others may just be passing through. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- FBN-JETS-PARCELS-3 --
Bill Parcells announces his resignation as head coach of the New
York Jets on Monday. Parcells resigned after three seasons as coach
of the New York Jets, but will remain with the team as its chief
operating officer. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Jan. 03, 2000 --
FBN-JETS-PARCELS-2 -- Bill Parcells, head coach of the New York
Jets, during his team's game against the Seattle Seahawks on Sunday
at Giants Stadium. The Jets won 19-9. Parcells resigned on Monday
after three seasons as coach of the New York Jets, but will remain
with the team as chief operating officer. (Ozier Muhammad/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) TAMPA, Fla. -- Jan. 03, 2000 -- FBN-JETS-PARCELS -- Bill
Parcells, then coach of the New York Giants, is carried of the
field by his team after he led them to a 20-19 victory over the
Buffalo Bills in Super Bowl XXV in 1991. Parcells resigned on
Monday after three seasons as coach of the New York Jets, but will
remain with the team as chief operating officer. Parcells turned
around three franchises in his history as a coach. He won two Super
Bowls with the Giants and got to one with the Patriots. He was 9-7,
12-4 and 8-8 as Jets coach. (Vic DeLucia/The New York Times)
</P>
