<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5711 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-LOTTO-LIMIT-KAN &LR;      01-03 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTO-LIMIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY GAME HITS $2 MILLION LIABILITY LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Too many Missouri Lottery players wanted 2-0-0-0 and
1-9-9-9 in Friday's Y2K Eve Pick 4 game _ leaving plenty of others
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers were selling like hotcakes all day long, and the
game hit its $2 million liability limit shortly before the 6:59
p.m. televised drawing, said lottery spokeswoman Susan Goedde.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only happens a couple of times a year,'' said Goedde, when
the potential payout for a particular combination of numbers
reaches the $2 million mark _ and sales of that combination
automatically are halted by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Goedde said 9-9-9-9 sold out Sept. 9 last year and 0-6-2 hit the
Pick 3 game's limit and was declared sold out one day in the summer
of 1998 during Mark McGwire's chase for the season home run record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every lottery has liability limits on their fixed-prize daily
games, just like casinos have limits on how much you can bet,'' she
said. ``It's to protect the organization from going broke.''
</P>
<P>
   In parimutuel games, such as the multistate Powerball, multiple
winners split the jackpot, which is determined by the total amount
bet.
</P>
<P>
   The Pick 4 game, with a $5,000 daily jackpot, has sold $5.6
million worth of tickets since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 2-0-0-0 and 1-9-9-9 weren't very good plays
for the final Pick 4 game of 1999. The winning numbers were
4-1-3-9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
