<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5715 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-930(2TAK     01-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE RENEW BATTLE IN WARM-UP FOR DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President
Al Gore, 1,125 miles apart, argued about the virtues of experience
and accused the other of having a vision too limited to deal with
problems that concern most Americans.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Only those who have never left Washington have missed the
lessons of the last decade,'' Bradley told an audience of 400 in
Manchester. The audience first giggled and then applauded at the
obvious reference to Gore, who has held office in Washington since
1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only those who have embodied the ways of Washington have
failed to notice that Americans see Washington as a place that has
nothing to do with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Gore told 1,000 students and supporters in
Davenport, Iowa, that Democrats should be proud of the
accomplishments of the last seven years. ``We balanced the budget
for the first time in a generation _ and turned record deficits
into record surpluses,'' he said. ``We reformed welfare, and cut
the welfare rolls in half.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic presidential hopefuls will debate in person
twice this week, on Wednesday in Manchester and on Saturday in Des
Moines, Iowa. On Monday they warmed up, in speeches their staffs
advertised as important, with the ideas they think will play best
in Iowa's Jan. 24 caucuses and New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley approach reflected some of the anti-Washington
themes that won primaries here for Jimmy Carter in 1976, Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and Pat Buchanan in 1996. In a line that recalled
Carter's promise to provide a government as ``full of love as the
American people,'' Bradley said, ``I'm not prepared to settle for
anything less than America realizing the potential embodied in our
ideals, in the creativity of our minds and the goodness of our
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Without directly naming his rival, Bradley called the vice
president no more than a tinkerer. He referred briefly to his own
major campaign proposals _ providing universal access to health
insurance, ending child poverty, putting 600,000 new teachers in
public schools, registering all handguns and reforming the campaign
finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a comment the audience took to be aimed at Gore, he
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those voices that say we cannot do big things any
more, that we must tinker around the edges offering small solutions
to big problems. But I say now is not the time to be timid. Above
all, now is not the time to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took on his rival much more bluntly, scoffing at his
emphasis on health care. He said, ``Senator Bradley seems to
believe America can address only one thing at a time, or only a
very small number, and that health care is the only challenge we
can handle.'' He added, ``The promise of America means more than a
single proposal, done in the wrong way, at a price that leaves us
helpless to take on other great national priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Bradley's approach was, if not un-American, at
least un-Democratic: ''Can you imagine John Kennedy saying, `We
have to fight the Cold War; we can't explore the heavens or put a
man on the moon?' He knew we would do more. Can you imagine Lyndon
Johnson saying, `We can wage war on poverty, but we'll have to
postpone the creation of Medicare and Medicaid. He knew we could do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bradley's vision was too small, warning that ``the
presidency is not an academic exercise'' or ``a seminar where you
get to entertain a single grand theory.'' For his part, Gore cited
a much longer list of goals, helping farmers, expanding health
insurance coverage, revolutionizing public education, making
preschool available to everyone, raising the minimum wage, easing
the ability of workers to unionize, and protecting affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, cultivating the rocky New Hampshire soil of
anti-Washington feeling requires a bit of juggling, since he served
in the Senate for 18 years and boasts of his experience there as
evidence he can get things done. So he emphasizes the years since
he retired in 1995 as a time when he got reacquainted with a nation
that has ``an abiding sense that Washington doesn't have a clue as
to where people really live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a state where he may be ahead because independents
can vote in the Democratic primary, Bradley attacked Washington,
and, by implication, Gore, for excessive partisanship. ``Only those
who have been mired in the battles of partisanship have failed to
realize that Americans are tired of partisanship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he has before, Gore suggested on Monday that Bradley made a
cowardly retreat, not an intellectual exploration, when he retired
from the Senate. Speaking of the seven-year Clinton-Gore economic
record, he said, ''There were many good individuals _ even in high
places in our own party _ who thought it couldn't be done. When
Senator Bradley retired from the Senate during President Clinton's
first term, he spoke of a `budget stalemate,' of a political
process that was paralyzed on creating jobs, on reforming welfare,
a continual deadlock. And he said that part of the problem was that
Democrats `cling to old programs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also criticized Republicans as he sought to rally
Democratic loyalists in Iowa, where polls suggest he is stronger
than Bradley. He said, ``When the Gingrich Congress tried to cut
education and slash Medicare and we stopped them, it didn't just
happen _ it happened because we took on Republicans, we fought
long, we fought hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And he criticized all Republican presidential candidates for
``endorsing tax cuts for the wealthy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's other main topic on Monday, raised perhaps as a
counter to Gore's experience in the area, was the contradictions of
technology, which ``brings us closer and makes us distant at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With cell phones and pagers and e-mail, we're never out of
touch, but we're not face-to-face, either,'' he said. ``We're both
more connected and more isolated. Now we have so many different
avenues of communication that about the only thing Americans do at
the same time any more is watch the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said this did not worry him because ``every new form of
information and knowledge creates more liberty, not less. Democracy
always benefits from more information, more transparency, more
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate closed with an effort at inspiration, though
Gore's was more programmatic. The vice president said, ``Imagine
what this country will be like when every child has health
coverage, when we save Medicare and Social Security, when we invest
in world-class public schools, when we make bold new strides for
opportunity and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's raise our sights and broaden our vision. Let's reach for
the America that is in our dreams _ and also within our grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley concluded by saying: ``What does it profit us to expand
the boundaries of knowledge if we don't expand the circle of
justice. For though we're expanding the frontiers of knowledge, the
coordinates of the human heart remain the same, and that is the
ultimate challenge of politics, to touch the goodness that is in
all our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in an age of new possibilities,'' he said.
``Some people say we can never achieve our special destiny, but I
say, in a world of new possibilities, guided by goodness, we can
and we will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
