<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BP-ARCO-ART-1000(2TAK     01-03 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BP-ARCO-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PROPOSED BP AMOCO-ARCO DEAL, PROBLEMS ARE MANY, LOBBYING
INTENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Ore.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators and governors from the West Coast and
Alaska, as well as oil executives and lawyers, have been flocking
to the Federal Trade Commission in recent weeks in what has quickly
turned into one of the most contentious political and regulatory
campaigns of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the FTC approved the largest industrial merger in
history a few weeks ago _ Exxon's $81 billion acquisition of Mobil
_ the agency's staff recommended that a second large oil merger be
blocked. Negotiations ensued between government officials and the
two companies involved, BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield. But the
gap over the proposed $29 billion deal remains wide, with the
companies and government officials unable to agree on what impact
the merger would have on gasoline prices on the West Coast, the
primary recipient of crude oil from Alaska's North Slope.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are preparing for what would be the biggest courtroom
challenge to a corporate merger in American history. Yet even as
they do so, the companies and their allies in Congress, in state
capitals and from their Alaskan oil operations are waging an
intensive lobbying effort to try to force a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Pitofsky, the FTC chairman, ponders whether to try to
block the deal, he has been besieged by hundreds of e-mail
messages, telephone calls and visits from lawmakers, as well as
from an array of corporate executives and consumer groups. He has
heard conflicting views about the deal from senators, governors and
state officials from Alaska, California and Oregon, some lawmakers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a full-court congressional press to get this deal
approved quickly from BP and ARCO and their supporters, folks who
carry a tremendous amount of influence,'' said Sen. Ron Wyden,
D-Ore. Wyden met recently with Pitofsky to present what he said was
clear evidence of antitrust problems and to urge him to reject the
merger on any terms.
</P>
<P>
   The central issue is whether Alaska and the West Coast are such
closely related markets that production in Alaska affects prices in
California and neighboring states. BP Amoco and ARCO together
control about 70 percent of the Alaska oil production. FTC
officials have concluded that Alaska production and California
prices are indeed closely related, while the companies and a number
of private analysts maintain that prices on the West Coast are,
instead, set by the world market.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles, a Democrat, joined by the state's two
Republican senators, Frank H. Murkowski and Ted Stevens, has told
FTC officials that any delay in completing the merger could have a
devastating effect on the state's economy. The state's oil
production has sharply declined over the last decade, to 1.1
million barrels a day from more than 2 million, as prices have
plummeted. New investment in exploration by BP Amoco holds the
promise of sharply increasing supply and heading off thousands of
layoffs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that the FTC has a different responsibility than
we do,'' Knowles said in a recent interview. ``We also have a
strong antitrust act. But I also have other concerns, such as the
long-term health of the industry, and the economy of the state, and
none of those are the responsibility of the FTC. They have just a
narrow antitrust issue. Their focus is solely on the downstream, on
the California gas pump.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the deal say the commission's staff has
fundamentally misunderstood the realities of the market, and that
there is no legitimate reason to fear that the domination of the
oil fields on Alaska's North Slope by BP Amoco, if it acquires
ARCO, would affect prices at gas stations on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is talking ideology and theory, not reality,''
said Roger Diwan, managing director of Petroleum Finance Co., an
industry consultant in Washington. ``There is no evidence of a
connection between production in Alaska and the price in
California.'' Diwan said gasoline prices were higher in California
largely because of higher taxes and a state requirement that
consumers buy cleaner, more expensive gas.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the deal reply that the ties between Alaska
production and West Coast prices are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that there is no connection between the North Slope
and Oregon is absolutely preposterous,'' Wyden said. ``It's
laughable.'' He said Oregon was a good laboratory of how prices at
the pump are dictated by North Slope crude. Oregon has neither
California's high local taxes nor its requirements for cleaner gas,
but prices are still among the nation's highest, by some
calculations as much as 31 cents above the national average last
year.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy the states, the two oil companies have offered a
variety of benefits _ what one lawyer has called ``grease'' _ that
have nothing to do with antitrust issues. They have pledged to
spend at least $15 million to clean up ``orphan'' environmental
sites caused by other companies. They have agreed to give $2
million annually, in perpetuity, to the University of Alaska. And
they have vowed to raise their charitable contributions in
California by more than 25 percent, to at least $100 million over
the next decade. Sir John Browne, BP Amoco's chief executive, has
also pledged to California's governor that he will continue ARCO's
program of providing gasoline at lower prices than competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The merger's critics, meanwhile, have been seeking to embolden
the FTC to take on the oil companies and undo the deals struck by
state officials in Alaska and California. They say the deal would
give the newly merged company a stranglehold on Alaskan production,
leading inevitably to price gouging on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, though, needs little to lift its confidence. It
is coming off its strongest year in decades, exemplified in recent
weeks by a stream of multibillion-dollar deals that cratered after
running into skepticism from antitrust officials. BP Amoco and ARCO
executives insist they will not cave in, as the other companies
did, and are so confident of their legal arguments and their view
of the marketplace that it makes little sense to propose huge
divestitures when the odds are strongly in favor of a court
victory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the FTC and BP Amoco and ARCO are still negotiating,
as government officials and the companies' executives try to reach
an accommodation and close a deal that would greatly realign power
over Alaska's vast reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is clearly in the hands of Pitofsky, a former
antitrust law professor whose grip on his agency is perhaps best
illustrated by his voting record. In his nearly five years on the
job, he has not cast a single dissenting vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and others who follow his agency closely say it is
inconceivable that his staff would recommend barring the deal
without coming to believe that such an action had the support of
Pitofsky, who has taken an active role in negotiations with the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Pitofsky declined to answer questions about the
merger. In general comments about the industry, though, he has
hinted at his skepticism about the merger unless there are more
significant divestitures. He noted in particular that the spate of
oil mergers in recent years was reaching the point that requires
particularly careful scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people understand how de-concentrated oil was
just five years ago,'' he said. ``It used to be that the top eight
companies barely controlled even 40 or 50 percent of the market.
Then Texaco and Shell did a joint marketing venture. BP merged with
Amoco. Exxon bought Mobil to become Exxon Mobil. Now the top four
firms have 40 to 50 percent of the market in the United States.
We're approaching the zone of moderate to high concentration under
the antitrust guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior executives at BP Amoco and ARCO were reluctant to talk on
the record while the deal is pending. Privately, however, some
executives expressed deep frustration and anger with Washington,
saying they are the victims of a particular hostility toward big
oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of anger and frustration, and a strong
conviction that we have a strong legal case,'' one executive said.
``There is a limit to how much this procrastination can go on. We
have made it clear that we won't roll over and die.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies have also made it clear that since North Slope
production is a crown jewel of the merger, they will not make any
huge concessions beyond those already made to the state of Alaska.
The largest concession is the divestiture of 175,000 barrels a day
of the 800,000 they produce. That divestiture would leave the
merged company _ which some in Washington refer to as BP ARCO, even
though no official name has been settled on _ with about a 60
percent share of production, which is still too much for the FTC.
The companies also say they haveameliorated any potential problems
through long-term contracts with independent West Coast refiners
for an additional 100,000 barrels or so a day.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the deal say Alaska's interests as the owner of the
oil fields are different from those of West Coast states that
consume the refined oil.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's staff has apparently rejected the argument that
Alaska and the West Coast have not been a single market for a long
time. In making that argument, the companies have noted that the
decline in North Slope production forced West Coast refiners to
look to other sources for crude oil and that the government ended
the ban on exports of Alaska crude to foreign countries three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the companies say, they have no power over West
Coast prices because the market is competitive enough and refiners
would look to other sources. In addition, ARCO has employed a
highly successful strategy of marketing gasoline at a discount by
using higher volumes and lower margins and has no interest in
abandoning that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics of the deal, like Wyden, Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., and a group of consumer organizations in Alaska and
California, say the divestiture still leaves BP Amoco with too much
control over North Slope crude, and would inevitably result in
still higher prices on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Wyden said he had told Pitofsky the deal was fatally flawed,
would do great harm to consumers in Oregon and adjoining states and
could not be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pitofsky is asked to approve it in some other form, they
will have to attach so many conditions and riders that the FTC
would not have the resources to monitor it,'' he said. ``The
companies would run circles around everybody. It may be bad news
now, but it would be even worse. We would need a new federal
department of BP ARCO to supervise it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
