<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-KCPL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KCP&AMP;L calls off merger with Western Resources  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER and STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. has called off
its $2.1 billion merger with Western Resources Inc., saying
Western's falling stock price left them with no good reason to do
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to his counterpart at Western Resources, KCP&AMP;L Chief
Executive Drue Jennings said shareholders in increasing numbers had
been asking that the deal be terminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger agreement is no longer in the best interest of KCPL
and its shareholders,'' said the letter from Jennings to David
Wittig, Western's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L exercised a provision in the agreement that allowed either
side to cancel the merger if it was not completed by Dec. 31, 1999.
The company had a special meeting Sunday in which board members
voted to kill it. Under the agreement, there were no fees to be
paid to or by either side if the deal was not completed.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which was announced in early 1997, dragged through the
regulatory approval process, and Western's shares fell 49 percent
last year as the value of its investments in the Protection One
home security company and Oneok, a natural gas producer, declined.
Ironically, the deal had to be reworked in 1998 because Western's
stock price was so high Western was faced with paying more for
KCP&AMP;L than it had intended.
</P>
<P>
   Western's shares closed the year at $16.94, the lowest price
since the merger was announced. If the deal had closed with
Western's stock being so low, KCP&AMP;L shareholders would have
received a third less than they had been told to expect. Shares in
Western Resources closed Monday at 16.50, down 43 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also was pulling down KCP&AMP;L's stock, which lost 26
percent in value in 1999. The utility's management already had
cashed out most of its stock options when the price was nearly $30
a share. It closed the last trading day of 1999 at $22.06 a share.
KCP&AMP;L's board of directors, which has fiduciary duties to serve the
best interests of its shareholders, was under mounting pressure.
KCP&AMP;L shares closed Monday at 22.43, up 37 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings could not be reached Monday for comment. KCP&AMP;L
spokeswoman Phyllis Tilden said the company was reviewing its
alternatives and would comment in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Wittig said Western was ``disappointed'' the
deal had been canceled. He said the proposed merger made sense
``but it simply took too long to complete the process.''
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L's decision was not unexpected in the financial community,
said Edward Tirello, an analyst with Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown in
New York. The question is what is next for KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have laid out a number of possibilities, but at the end
of the day I think another merger is in order,'' Tirello said.
``That is what I think they will do. They are too small to be
successful on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Tirello said he would not be surprised to see UtiliCorp United
Inc. make another offer for KCP&AMP;L. Kansas City-based UtiliCorp and
KCP&AMP;L announced merger plans four years ago, but they were
disrupted by a hostile bid by Western Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was their merger partner of preference. I am sure they
will be chatting again,'' Tirello said. ``They could do it as a
merger of equals and not have to worry about the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Cosley, a spokesman for UtiliCorp, said the company had no
comment on the dissolution of the deal or whether it would be
interested in a merger with KCP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L's decision to end the Western merger completes a decade of
frustration for the utility's strategy of trying to become a larger
company by merger or acquisition in order to withstand the rigors
of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The first try... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
