<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      01-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More and More Companies Deciding Against Dividends
</P>
<P>
   A growing portion of corporate America appears to be concluding
that dividends are no longer needed to attract investors and are
therefore an unnecessary cost of doing business. Fewer companies
are raising dividends, and more and more large companies do not
bother to pay them at all. Dividends used to be a virtual
requirement to convince investors that a company's stock was worth
buying. Some institutional investors were barred from buying shares
that did not pay dividends. But now, for the first time in recent
history, a quarter of the value of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index comes from companies that pay no dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Humana Plans to Take Big Charge
</P>
<P>
   Humana, the troubled managed-care company, said that it would
take a pretax charge of $400 million to $500 million in the fourth
quarter, the latest in a series of charges and one-time items. The
latest charge will result in a loss for 1999, wiping out operating
profits projected at 63 cents a share. The task of turning around
the company has fallen to David A. Jones, a founder and former
chief executive, who returned as interim chief executive last
August.
</P>
<P>
   Managed Care Comes Under Fire
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care companies are under growing legal attack, including
at least 16 recent class-action suits, most filed by some of the
same lawyers who won huge settlements from the tobacco industry.
Several new state laws and measures in Congress could open the
industry to still more suits. And the federal law that has long
protected many managed-care companies is being whittled away in a
series of judicial decisions in malpractice cases.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing Grew in December
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing expanded for the 11th consecutive month in
December, and more companies reported paying higher prices for
materials. The National Association of Purchasing Management said
that its factory index was 55.5 last month. That means more
businesses reported improved conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel Financial Officer to Retire
</P>
<P>
   Mattel said that Harry Pearce, its chief financial officer,
would retire in March It also named Bernard Stolar, former
president of Sega of America, to be president of its interactive
division, which includes the Learning Co., its children's software
company whose slow sales prompted a third-quarter profit warning.
</P>
<P>
   July 4 Takes Back Seat to New Year
</P>
<P>
   New Year's business was spectacular for Fireworks by Grucci, the
pyrotechnics company in Brookhaven, N.Y. Typically, the Fourth of
July is the big occasion for fireworks, with New Year's Eve a puny
also-ran. But on Friday, Grucci took in more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Cuts Prices in Germany
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores, which acquired two German supermarket chains in
the last two years, began its first big price-cutting campaign on
products. The move sent a chill through German retailers, which
have been battered by price wars and have been terrified about
Wal-Mart since it arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Limits Urged on Banking in Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Some of Brazil's most powerful bankers are urging the government
to limit the power of foreign financial institutions, which have
taken over or made heavy investments in many of the nation's banks.
</P>
<P>
   Programming Blocked for 500,000
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has blocked 500,000 customers from seeing
local programming from News Corp.'s Fox Entertainment Group after
the two companies failed to reach a new distribution agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
