<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5721 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-MERGER-KCPL-2NDTAKE-K     01-03 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-KCPL-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 KCP&AMP;L calls off merger with Western Resources  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER and STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...the rigors of deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The first try was KCP&AMP;L's bid to purchase Kansas Gas and
Electric Co., which was snapped up by Western Resources. The second
attempt, announced in 1996, would have been a friendly merger with
UtiliCorp.
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources foiled KCP&AMP;L's plans by offering more money
and forcing UtiliCorp to withdraw. When Western and KCP&AMP;L came to
terms in early 1997, it was the first successful hostile bid for a
utility in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, KCP&AMP;L's chairman, said the transaction would have
benefits for all, including shareholders, employees and customers.
John Hayes Jr., then Western's chairman, also was optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased to be working together to take advantage of the
tremendous opportunities this merger presents,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   The price for KCP&AMP;L was $2.1 billion. The deal would have
created a company with more than $8 billion in assets and 1 million
electricity customers. Western's utilities, KGE and KPL, and
KCP&AMP;L's electric operations would have been combined in a Kansas
City-based company called Westar Energy.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the remainder of the planned company that especially
dazzled analysts and investors. The unregulated businesses,
including Western's Protection One monitored security company,
would have been separate from Westar but would have been key in
forming a corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to create a consumer services company that would go
beyond operating an electric utility. Indeed, the response to the
KCP&AMP;L and Western deal was so positive that Western's stock
increased so much that in 1998 the deal had to be redone so that
KCP&AMP;L's shareholders would not get more than originally intended.
</P>
<P>
   The only major concerns about the merger were over what
regulators would do. Missouri, Kansas and federal regulators would
have to approve the merger.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the regulatory proceedings did prove contentious.
Western sought to get as much as $1 billion _ the premium it paid
for KCP&AMP;L _ from ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the staff of the Kansas Corporation Commission agreed
to give them part of the premium. But Missouri refused and Kansas
regulators then took the same route. Both states agreed to let the
merged company retain a portion of the merger savings resulting
from the combination of the companies.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1999, Missouri and Kansas had approved the deal. As the
year closed, only the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission was
considering the deal, and its approval was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Wittig, who had succeeded Hayes as chairman and chief executive
of Western Resources, said at the time that there was nothing in
the regulatory conditions that would cause financial harm to the
merged company.
</P>
<P>
   But by then there were greater problems. Wittig, a former
investment banker, had been one of the architects of making Western
into a consumer-services company through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, had begun to lose its luster. Protection One
was losing money, and the Securities and Exchange Commission was
questioning how it accounted for the cost of acquiring new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of all of that, Tirello said he expected Western to do
well. He said that the company had made changes at Protection One
to get it turned around, and that he expected the company to look
for another electric utility with which to merge its energy
operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
