<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANKS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL HAVING SECOND THOUGHTS ABOUT FOREIGN-BANK INROADS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Perhaps no trend has made its mark on Sao
Paulo's changing cityscape more than the proliferation of
foreign-owned banks. After a wave of takeovers and heavy
investments in recent years, many Brazilian banks have been nudged
aside by institutions with un-Portuguese sounding names, like
Santander, HSBC and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   However, the growth of these banks, with their colorful
nameplates, billboard advertisements and increasing clout in this
nation's financial services industry, are coming under criticism.
Fearful of the encroachment of foreign financial institutions, some
of Brazil's most powerful bankers are urging the government to
limit the power of foreign financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The richest countries of the world are wise enough to realize
that national interests coincide with a strong, domestically led
financial system,'' said Fernao Bracher, a former central bank
president who now heads Banco BBA-Creditanstalt, a Sao Paulo bank
with Austrian shareholders, thjority owned by Brazilians.
``Why should Brazil, a developing country, be run roughshod over?''
</P>
<P>
   A reminder of the foreign banking industry's expansion in Brazil
came Monday with news that the government had approved a request by
the Bank of New York, one of the biggest and oldest banks in the
United States, to buy a controlling interest in Credibanco, a Sao
Paulo bank with large corporate lending and asset management
operations. Terms of the transaction were not disclosed, but the
Bank of New York had owned 50 percent of Credibanco for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the simmering debate over limiting foreign banks has to
do with the privatization planned for later this year of Banco do
Estado de Sao Paulo, one of the country's largest banks.
Institutions as diverse as Citigroup's Citibank unit, and Banco
Bradesco, the largest Brazilian bank not owned by the government,
have shown interest in buying Banespa, as the bank is called.
</P>
<P>
   After the central government said last month that it would
authorize foreign institutions to bid for Banespa, domestic
competitors grew nervous. According to local reports, they began a
behind-the-scenes lobbying effort to ensure that foreigners would
be limited in trying to buy Banespa by, for instance, being forced
to bid in a consortium controlled by a Brazilian partner.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasoning is based on what they view as excessive foreign
bank incursions in recent years. There have been
multibillion-dollar acquisitions by Britain's Hongkong and Shanghai
Banking Corp. and ABN-Amro NV, the Dutch giant. Other institutions,
notably Spanish banks like Banco Santander Central Hispano and
Banco Bilbao-Vizcaya, have also made large forays into Brazil's
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreigners have extremely deep pockets,'' said Paul
Bydalek, the president of Atlantic Rating, a Brazilian banking
analysis company. ``They don't necessarily understand the nuances
of Brazil's magnificent chaos.`
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, this means that Brazilian banks tend, in some
instances, to support the stability of the financial system in
times of crisis. For instance, in the tumult that followed the
devaluation of the currency nearly a year ago, some foreign banks
counseled their clients to avoid buying Brazilian government bonds
and other securities, citing the risk of default.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the largest Brazilian banks, such as Bradesco and Banco Itau
S.A., continued to refinance government bonds much as they had done
during the last several decades. In fact, the Brazilian
institutions that buy more than 90 percent of the country's
domestic bonds made out well in 1999 since most of these securities
were linked to the dollar or to interest rates, which remained high
for most of the year.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that the government is acknowledging this type
of argument. ``Foreign banks could cause a problem in not wanting
to roll over our debt so some type of ceiling on their share of the
system might be a good idea,'' Rubens Barbosa, Brazil's ambassador
to the United States, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of opening the banking system to greater foreign
participation say this thinking is misguided and exaggerates the
influence of foreign banks in Brazil's economy. Foreign banks
account for about 30 percent of banking assets in Brazil, but they
account for more than half of assets in neighboring Argentina,
where privatization and deregulation have been carried out to a
larger degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is pure self-interest in avoiding competition,''
said Gustavo Franco, a former president of the central bank who was
responsible for engineering Brazil's opening of the financial
system to foreign investment during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask the consumer if he prefers a foreign or Brazilian bank and
you'll be told his choice is the one which provides the best
service,'' Franco said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The debate surrounding foreign banks is largely limited to the
area of consumer banking, which providess with services like
checking and savings accounts. In the more exclusive world of
investment banking, foreign institutions have made enormous inroads
in Brazil, including the purchase of the country's leading
investment bank, Garantia, by the Credit Suisse Group.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas two or three years ago Brazilian investment banks like
Garantia, or Banco Pactual of Rio de Janeiro, dominated areas like
trading equities on the Sao Paulo stock exchange, or underwriting
stock and bond issues for Brazilian companies, today foreign banks
account for much of these business areas.
</P>
<P>
   This trend shows few signs of letting up, as reflected in the
Bank of New York deal for Credibanco.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal is completed, 53 of the 118 banks in Brazil that
are not controlled by the government, whether in the areas of
consumer or investment banking, will be foreign-owned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
