<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-SUGARBOWL-DEFENSE     01-03 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSES TO FORCE ISSUE IN CHAMPIONSHIP GAME
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-DEFENSE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Virginia Tech playing in its first national
championship game. ``Pressure.'' Redshirt freshman quarterback
Michael Vick, age 19, being expected to make the big play at the
right time for the Hokies. ``Pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Florida State, No. 1 all season, seeking its elusive
second national title. ``Pressure.'' Junior quarterback Chris
Weinke, age 27, operating behind an offensive line that allowed two
sacks a game and will be facing a relentless Virginia Tech defense
that averaged five sacks a game. ``Pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   National championship games, like Tuesday's Sugar Bowl tussle
between Florida State (11-0) and Virginia Tech (11-0), carry their
usual stress-test levels of excitement, nerves, fear and
anticipation. But this game, even with the Hokies a solid underdog,
figures to overload the pressure points.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the players on both sides of the ball on both teams, the
potential for big plays is great,'' Virginia Tech coach Frank
Beamer said Monday. ``Preventing those plays will be a key. It will
be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting. That's a coach talking.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams, but especially Virginia Tech, push the envelope with
their defenses. The Hokies often crowd eight defenders to the line
of scrimmage. Their front four, led by defensive ends Corey Moore
and John Engelberger, usually don't need help harassing the
quarterback. If they do, Tech blitzes. A mistake _ a missed
assignment, a poor tackle, a sack or a fumble _ could result in
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it going to be a shootout? That's a big question,'' said
Weinke, who has thrown for 25 touchdowns this season. ``Both
defenses take a lot of chances. That would tell you there will be
an opportunity for big plays. That's how we're looking at it. It's
going to be a game where they're either going to get to the
quarterback _ me _ or we're going to make some big plays. It's not
going to be a boring college football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with Peter Warrick on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' senior wide receiver/kick returner could be the
deciding factor. In last year's national championship loss to
Tennessee, Warrick was almost a nonfactor, totaling 69 yards on one
reception, one rushing attempt and one punt return. Even if they
have to put him in the shotgun and snap him the ball, the Seminoles
will try to get the ball in his hands at least a dozen times
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warrick's the most dangerous player I've seen with the ball in
his hands,'' Tech coach Frank Beamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said his team will counter
Virginia Tech's pass rush with draw plays. Tailback Travis Minor,
who averaged 74 yards rushing per game this season, has a history
of giving the Seminoles a ground boost in big games. In 13 games
against ranked opponents, he has averaged 97 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia Tech's pass rush is the best I've seen,'' Bowden
said. ``One of the ways to slow that down is with draw plays and
we've worked hard on that. We've got to have some success with that
to slow down their rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech allowed just 75.9 yrds per game and 2.2 yards per
rushing attempt. For the Hokies, stopping Florida State's running
game is Job One.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they start running the ball effectively, mixed in with
their passing game, that's when they start toying with you,''
Virginia Tech defensive coordinator Bud Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles hope they can toy with Vick, who thus far in his
career has shown the poise of a ... well, a 27-year-old
quarterback. He displayed his poise in Virginia Tech's biggest
victory. Trailing West Virginia 20-19, 1:15 remaining and no
timeouts, Vick moved the Hokies from their 15-yard line to the
game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being calm is just the type of person I am,'' he said. ``It's
kind of tough to get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech has allowed just 26 sacks. But Vick's ability to
avoid tackles and make big plays has Bowden concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the ability to take a play that breaks down and beat
you,'' he said. ``He's the whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as the Hokies hope to harass Weinke, the Seminoles want to
confuse and confound Vick with changing coverages and blitzes. The
risk/reward aspect is this: If Vick avoids the first wave, he could
break loose to either throw or run for big yardage. Or, he might be
hurried into a bad decision; the Seminoles led the nation with 22
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an attack defense, we're not a read-and-watch defense,''
said Florida State nose guard Corey Simon, the Seminoles' defensive
leader. ``We go out there to attack the quarterback, attack the
running back and attack the line of scrimmage. We're not gonna sit
back and watch anything. This is not a watching game. This is a
game where you go out and bring your hitting shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   And it figures to be a game, as both coaches have pointed out
all week, where the difference between victory and defeat could be
razor-thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's pretty simple,'' Florida State senior guard Jason
Whitaker said. ``If we keep (quarterback) Chris Weinke vertical, we
win. If we don't, they win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
