<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5727 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-ROSNER-ROBINSON-C     01-03 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROSNER-ROBINSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robinson needed at go-to position again
 &HT;    BMark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ David Robinson is on schedule, and that makes
the San Antonio Spurs worth inspection during the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has become a notoriously slow starter in his old age, a
battered 34. So when he scores 28 points and 19 in consecutive
games, as he did did last week, it is time to monitor his impact on
a team struggling more than its 21-10 record would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics say Robinson's performances were indicative of little
except the caliber of competition _ Golden State and Vancouver,
each so inept that its coaches were recently fired. A more focused
picture of Robinson will develop as the schedule becomes tougher.
The Spurs face Minnesota tonight, Seattle on Wednesday, and
Phoenix, Orlando and Utah after that.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson provides new-age explanations for why it takes him so
long to get going: teammates learning to trust each other; the
elusive rhythm he must find after ceding primary-scorer status to
Tim Duncan last season. Others believe Robinson's chronic back
problems inhibit him more early in the season than later, when
tight muscles become loose. Few people, if any, know Robinson's
condition from one day to the next, because he barely acknowledges
injuries, refusing to use them as an excuse. But he looks stiff
much of the time, ready to shatter like glass from the slightest
shove in the back.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs need him in one reasonably functioning piece to
contend for a second straight NBA championship. Robinson is no
longer the player who has averaged 24.4 points and 11.5 rebounds
during his career. His 14-point average this season is
insufficient; he is shooting 47.3 percent, on pace to hit below 50
percent for the first time. That is why he scores less even while
taking the same amount of shots as last season, 10 a game.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Robinson averaged 15.6 points, and even that might
not be enough in the juiced-up NBA, where scoring per team has
increased by nearly six points a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have allowed the fewest points in the league, but they
rank only 20th in scoring. Point guard Avery Johnson said Robinson
needs to produce about 16 points a game, adding that others should
contribute a little more. But Johnson, like anyone who knows the
Spurs, understands that Robinson is the best candidate to supply
the necessary boost.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs starters Johnson, Mario Elie and Jaren Jackson have each
averaged fewer than 10 points a game during their careers. And
while top reserve Terry Porter has provided kindling for the
offense, he is a 13-point-per-game scorer for his career.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Robinson as the man most likely to lift some of the
responsibility that has fallen on Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is no J.R. Rider. You won't find him whining about
teammates after a defeat or in need of transportation to the next
game, having missed the flight. But Duncan, on his way to an
eight-for-23 night during a six-point loss to the Lakers on
Christmas, looked frustrated by the lack of support. Robinson hit
two of eight shots, spending nearly half the game on the bench in
foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to take the pressure off Tim,'' Robinson said.
``I've got to look for my shot more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' offense runs through Duncan, who takes 18 shots a
game. But there are opportunities for Robinson on fast breaks, as
he runs a pick-and-roll with Johnson when Duncan is double-teamed
and must relinquish the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Against Golden State, Robinson hit 14 of 19. At Vancouver,
Robinson made four of nine, misleading figures because he
frequently was sent to the free-throw line, converting 11 of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has saved the Spurs more than once during his 11-year
career. After he was drafted by the team in 1987 out of the U.S.
Naval Academy, he spent two years in the Navy. When he was
discharged, Robinson had an option to re-enter the 1989 NBA draft.
Instead, he signed with the Spurs, a move that some people believe
allowed a franchise suffering from fans' indifference to remain in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Robinson relinquished to Duncan his role as go-to
guy on offense, agreeing to concentrate on defense. The formula
produced an NBA championship. Now they need Robinson to score. For
all anyone knows, Robinson might again be in a position to save the
franchise from disaster. Duncan becomes a free agent after the
season. When he looks at the Spurs, he will consider several
factors, not the least of which is the man playing next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: mrosner(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
