u a BC-SMUGGLED-ALIENS-SPI &LR;      01-03 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLED-ALIENS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE SMUGGLED ALIENS MAY BE EN ROUTE TO SEATTLE FROM CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A cargo ship scheduled to arrive at the Port of
Seattle Tuesday is suspected of carrying illegal aliens smuggled
aboard in Hong Kong in two containers, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation came as federal agents cracked down on a rash of
smuggling carried out in the crowded, dirty confines of cargo
containers stacked by the hundreds on huge, ocean-going vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, federal prosecutors in Seattle charged three Chinese men
with smuggling 12 of their countrymen in a 40-foot-by-8-foot
container on the OOCL Faith, a cargo ship that had just arrived at
Terminal 18.
</P>
<P>
   To get to America, the stowaways had agreed to pay tens of
thousands of dollars apiece, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time immigration agents have arrested alleged
smugglers for bringing in Chinese immigrants in containers at West
Coast ports, said Virginia Kice, a spokeswoman for the Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   INS agents have linked the Seattle smuggling to the recent
discovery of boxed human cargo at a Southern California port, court
documents say. The same firm, Lap Kei Trading Co. of Hong Kong,
shipped the container carrying Chinese immigrants on the OOCL Faith
and shipped two containers that arrived in Los Angeles on Dec. 28.
</P>
<P>
   INS agents n Los Angeles detained 30 illegal immigrants from
China. They had crossed the Pacific in containers on two different
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Steele, an INS agent, also wrote in court documents that
Lap Kei Trading shipped two containers with Chinese stowaways that
are expected to arrive Tuesday at Seattle's Terminal 18, presumably
aboard the California Jupiter. Steele's affidavit identifies that
ship as being suspected of having stowaways aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the INS nor the U.S. Coast Guard would provide further
information about the California Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   According to computerized tracking information, the California
Jupiter left Hong Kong on Dec. 20, arrived in Vancouver, B.C., on
Sunday, and left Vancouver at noon yesterday bound for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The INS in Seattle learned about the California Jupiter and OOCL
Faith last Thursday, according to court documents. A fax from an
INS office in Hong Kong alerted Seattle agents to possible
stowaways in containers on the California Jupiter and OOCL Faith.
</P>
<P>
   Such smuggling operations have occurred regularly on the West
Coast over the last year. The first known smuggling of illegal
immigrants in a container occurred April 7, 1998, in Tacoma, INS
spokeswoman Kice said.
</P>
<P>
   Two others have since occurred in Tacoma; four in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a troubling trend,'' Kice said. ``Some of
these ships have over 1,000 containers. It is, in a sense, like
looking for a needle in a haystack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Faith, owned by Orient Overseas Container Line, can carry
nearly 1,800 freight containers and intended to unload several
hundred in Seattle before heading for Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, INS agents found the ``needle'' they were looking
for in both California and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When a cargo ship arrived in Long Beach, agents found 18
stowaways _ all Chinese nationals _ in a container.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, INS agents waited as the OOCL Faith arrived at 5:30
a.m. Agents knew the number of the container they wanted to see,
found it and had it loaded off the ship, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   They found 12 Chinese men inside.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions inside the container were filthy, INS officials said.
The ship left Hong Kong around Dec. 19, stopped in Kobe, Japan,
then headed across the Pacific for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an international smuggling operation,'' said Bob
Coleman, acting director of the INS in Seattle. ``There are usually
lights. There's food and water, and there's ventilation. It's not
like they're just put in there. There's some thought that has gone
into sustaining them in the voyage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the canvas-covered container, the Chinese men had food as
well as lights, and a fan operated by car batteries. The men slept
on small mattresses, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   They used buckets for toilets and apparently tried to use
chemicals to break down their waste. Coleman said the container had
a strong order of camphor and that the first agents in the
container wore suits to protect them from possible hazardous
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said he suspects that the 12 men agreed to pay around
$40,000 apiece to get to the United States. The money would be paid
later by their families in China and the men, some of whom could be
subjected to something akin to indentured servitude to pay off
their debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think these are random things,'' Coleman said. ``Alien
smuggling is as sophisticated as drug smuggling. There is a lot of
money to be made. Because of our economy, a lot of people are drawn
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The dozen men, believed to be in good health, likely will face
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the Canadian navy seized four ships trying to
smuggled 600 Chinese immigrants into British Columbia. Almost all
of the immigrants intended to end up in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant smuggling is often associated with Fujian province in
China. Fujian has a long history of smuggling, federal agents say.
It is just across the Strait of Taiwan from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the INS ends up arresting only the smuggled
immigrants, not the smugglers. But not on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour after agents searched the container, a Chevrolet
Astro Van drove on Habor Island toward Terminal 18. Its driver
seemed lost and told a federal agent that he was looking for
Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   The driver and his two passengers were the three Chinese men
charged Monday. One carried a New York driver's license. Another a
map of Seattle with Terminal 18 marked in ink.
</P>
<P>
   At a hotel room the three men shared, agents found a bill of
lading for two containers expected to arrive in Seattle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men are in the United States illegally, according to
federal officials. A third has applied for asylum in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The three have been identified as Sheng Ding, Ju Shu Huang and
Yu Zheng. They are thought to be in their late 20s or early 30s. If
convicted of trying to bring illegal immigrants into the United
States, each faces up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   They are being held in federal custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
