<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK WILL BE SOLE PILOT OF JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Having learned from the master of public
relations, new Jets coach Bill Belichick chose to lie low Monday
and wait for another day to meet the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry I was unavailable to comment on today's events,''
Belichick said in a one-paragraph release. ``My intention was to
allow this to be Coach Parcells's day exclusively and I look
forward to meeting the media in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, whose public personality is the opposite of the
voluble Parcells's, had a rocky relationship with the media during
his five years as Cleveland Browns head coach.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, where he was assistant head coach, Belichick was
barred from talking to the media, as were all of Parcells's
assistants. Days before the Patriots' loss in the Super Bowl in
1997, the NFL required that all assistants be available to the
media, and Belichick's interview seemed little different from his
Cleveland days: cautious and stilted.
</P>
<P>
   But it is whether Belichick wins games in New York _ and not his
media presence _ that will determine his popularity. Belichick was
36-44 with the Browns, perhaps best known for his banishment of a
Cleveland icon, quarterback Bernie Kosar.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's any question whether Belichick, an outstanding
defensive coordinator, can succeed as head coach on his second try,
Parcells went out of his way Monday to assert that Belichick will
be his own man with the Jets, and that Parcells _ elevated to chief
operating officer of the Jets _ will not be a ``shadow'' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will he leave all football matters to Belichick, said
Parcells, but the draft choices also will be made by Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said the majority of Jets assistant coaches are under
contract for next year, and he expects the staff to more or less
remain intact. It is expected that Al Groh, the linebacker coach
and another former New England assistant under Parcells, will
become defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill will be making the football decisions,'' said Parcells.
``I'll be available to consult with him in any manner that is
necessary, but Bill will be making all decisions that are pertinent
to the football operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, Parcells went on, ``may want some different things
than what I want, but that's just the natural evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells's forte, clearly, was his ability to motivate players.
It remains to be seen whether Belichick, a superior X-and-O coach,
can do the same. Even clearer is the record of the last two coaches
who followed Parcells; Ray Handley had two unhappy seasons with the
Giants after Parcells left and Pete Carroll had three mediocre
seasons in New England after Parcells left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
