<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-SUGARBOWL-NOTES-T     01-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNCH PAIL IS SYMBOL OF HOKIES' DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 BOWL-NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Virginia Tech's defense prides itself on its work
ethic. The Hokies consider themselves a blue-collar defense.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise, then, that the defense uses a lunch pail as
its talisman. The black metal box _ think of the type that
construction workers used to lug to work _ is painted with the
school's ``VT'' logo. Each week, the team's defensive player of the
week is in charge of carrying the lunch pail to meetings, practices
and the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents what we're about,'' said Virginia Tech defensive
end Corey Moore, who is in charge of the lunch pail at the Sugar
Bowl. ``It goes everywhere with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hokies defensive coordinator Bud Foster has become a lunch pail
expert. The original lunch pail has been retired and sits in his
office. He continues to search garage sales and antique shops
searching for the perfect pail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to have an identity,'' said Foster, whose
defense leads the nation in scoring defense and is third in total
defense. ``Just because we don't recruit the all-American type
players, that doesn't mean they're not good players. What the lunch
pail signifies is that you're going to put in a full day's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of pride in what they do and in each other.
We demand they give great effort. We've played 750 snaps and every
one of those snaps were critical for us to get here. There's not
one play this year where I can say I wasn't happy with the
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Before every game, the defensive unit writes down a list of
goals and places them in the lunch pail. Then, after a victory away
from home, the defensive players often claim a piece of enemy turf
to carry home in the pail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their turf is our lunch,'' senior linebacker Jamel Thomas
said. ``We're a blue-collar team, hard-working, hard-nosed,
get-after-it-for-60 minutes defense.'' BOWDEN'S BELIEF
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden fielded several questions
Monday on how he handles his players off-field problems. Bowden
readily admitted that he's probably not politically correct and
that his methods of dealing with players aren't always popular.
``We recruit the same types of players we recruited 20 years ago
when we won the Sunday School Award,'' he said. ``If they're bad
characters, we don't sign 'em. It's not the bad guys who are bad
all the time, it's your good guys. Kids getting in trouble has been
going on for 2,000, 3,000 years. It's just now, everybody knows
about it. If you don't want people to know about it, don't be No.
1. Be No. 50.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Bowden said that junior defensive end Roland Seymour
won't start. He was one of three players punished for curfew
violations. The others were backup defensive back Reggie Durden and
kicker Sebastian Janikowski. ``If we kick off to start the game,
Janikowski will be out there,'' Bowden said. ``Unless he has a
heart attack. And we play 20, 25 people on defense in the first
five, 10 minutes, so it really doesn't matter who starts.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hokies coach Frank Beamer is good friends with Rangers manager
Johnny Oates. They attended Virginia Tech at the same time. ``I've
followed Johnny's career really closely,'' Beamer said. ``Every
summer, we try to get down to Texas for some games.''
</P>
<P>
   _ More baseball connections: Seattle Mariners manager Lou
Piniella is expected to be at Tuesday night's game. His son Derek
is a sophomore defensive tackle for the Hokies.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
