<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROATIA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION PARTY IN CROATIA LEADS IN EARLY VOTE RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Preliminary results in Monday's
parliamentary elections in Croatia, released early Tuesday morning,
indicate that a six-party opposition coalition should be able to
form a new government, ousting the party founded by Franjo Tudjman,
the late pt.
</P>
<P>
   With a little more than a quarter of the vote counted, the
election nonetheless appeared to be a serious defeat for Tudjman's
Croatian Democratic Union, the umbrella nationalist party that has
governed Croatia since it became independent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman died last month after a long illness, with his party
deeply unpopular because of economic distress, high unemployment
and widespread allegations of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The new prime minister is likely to be Ivica Racan, 55, the
leader of the Social Democrats, the former Communist Party, who has
promised closer and less abrasive relations with the United States,
the European Union and the international war crimes tribunal in The
Hague. He promises more attention to human rights and press
freedom. In return,is seeking Western help to ease the pain
of economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   While officials of the governing party conceded the loss of the
election, another senior party official, Vladimir Seks, the deputy
speaker of Parliament, warned: ``We all have to wait for the final
results to come first. I suggest that the temporary winners not
rejoice too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Croatia experts have warned about vote-rigging and other
irregularities. Foreign election observers will speak about their
findings Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which sees an opposition victory in
Croatia as a model for squabbling democrats in nearby Serbia, has
made no secret of its support for the Racan-led coalition. It is
expected that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will make an
early visit to Zagreb if the results hold up. That would be a sharp
contrast to the low level of diplomatic representation at Tudjman's
funeral, at which the American ambassador was the only
representative of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition of the Social Democratic Party and Social Liberals
will need support from another allied four-party coalition in order
to have a stable majority in the new Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The state electoral commission, releasing the preliminary
results after midnight, said the opposition alliance was ahead in 9
of Croatia's 10 constituencies. An 11th constituency is made up of
votes by 350,000 expatriates who hold Croatian citizenship, most of
them Bosnian Croats; they tend to favor the governing party, which
has supported them with large subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, the vote for the governing party is down in a
high turnout of more than 70 percent of 4.2 million registered
voters. The party is getting about a quarter of the vote, down from
44 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The main opposition bloc of Social Democrats and Social Liberals
is getting about 40 percent of the early vote, while the second
opposition alliance is getting 16 percent. But the country's
proportional system of representation means that voting percentages
do not translate directly into numbers of seats, and the number of
seats for each party is unlikely to be known until Tuesday night or
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Racan expressed optimism about becoming prime minister, saying,
``Together with the other opposition bloc, I think we will have a
very stable majority.''
</P>
<P>
   In a concession statement, the moderate foreign minister, Mate
Granic, who lost in his own central Zagreb constituency, said that
on the basis of preliminary results, ``It is clear that we have
lost the elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Elections to replace Tudjman as president will be held Jan. 24.
The opposition has pledged to reduce the constitutional powers of
the presidency, but will need the cooperation of the now-governing
party to secure the necessary two-thirds majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Granic is Washington's favorite for the presidency, but he has
had trouble getting his own party's endorsement and is considering
running as an independent in a large field. The main opposition
candidate will be Drazen Budisa, the leader of the Social Liberals
and Racan's coalition partner. The election is likely to require a
runoff, probably on Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The results so far in these parliamentary elections are not
encouraging for the governing party, which some experts think might
break apart in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Nikica Valentic, the governing party's candidate for prime
minister, said: ``Although we are only talking about a small
sample, the results are realistically below our expectations.
Obviously the electorate has been critical of our rule.''
</P>
</TEXT>
