<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HUMANA-CHARGE-NYT &LR;      01-03 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMANA-CHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMANA QUARTERLY CHARGE WILL RESULT IN LOSS IN 1999
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., Minn.)  (af)  
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humana Inc., the troubled managed-care company, said Monday that
it would take a pretax charge of $400 million to $500 million in
the fourth quarter, the latest in a series of charges and one-time
items. The latest charge will result in a loss for 1999, wiping out
operating profits projected at 63 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The write-off reflects disappointing results from Humana's 1997
purchase of the Physicians Corp. of America70 million in
cash and $130 million in debt. Humana indicated that it would lower
the value assigned to good will in the purchase, which suggests
that the price, which was considered low at the time, was still too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians Corp. provided coverage for 1.1 million managed-care
members, but almost half were in state Medicaid programs that
typically have slim profit margins. Humana, based in Louisville,
Ky., is one of the largest managed-care companies, with about six
million members.
</P>
<P>
   Lori M. Price, a health care analyst at CIBC World Markets, said
the company, which has had a string of setbacks that battered its
stock, wanted to clear the decks and improve its balance sheet by
taking as big a charge as could be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Humana fell 62.5 cents, to $7.5625, on the New York
Stock Exchange after the announcement. The price has plummeted 75
percent from $32 in 18 months since the collapse of a proposed $5.5
billion merger in 1998 with the UnitedHealthcare unit of the
UnitedHealth Group, based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Humana's executives spent several months preparing for the
United merger and were distracted further while they explored a
merger with the health care unit of the Prudential Life Insurance
Co., which was sold to Aetna Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Gregory H. Wolfe resigned after one year as chief
executive. David A. Jones, a founder and former chief executive,
returned as interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going through a transition,'' said Kenneth S.
Abramowitz, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein. ``Dave Jones will
do whatever he has to do to fix the company. He is a competent
experienced manager with a good track record for fixing things.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge includes $65 million of booked loss on the sale for
$125 million in cash of the marginally profitable workers'
compensation unit of Physicians Corp. to FolksAmerica Holding Co.
Inc. of New York, a unit of the White Mountains Insurance Group,
which is based in Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Humana said it had also agreed to sell its money-losing Medicare
supplemental coverage to the United Teachers Associates Insurance
Co. of Austin, Texas, for an undisclosed price. Analysts said
Humana would be glad to unload the unit, no matter the price.
</P>
<P>
   Arun Kumar, a health care analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's, said
Humana had not met Wall Street investors' expectations for the last
few years, but ``performance in 2000 should be substantially
better.'' The company ``is repositioning itself in its core market
and raising premium rates,'' he said. ``These are things that
should have been done last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Humana was boxed in by several multiyear contracts that delayed
premium increases. And its substantial Medicare business was also
affected when Washington put a lid on increases for Medicare health
maintenance organizations. Managed-care companies are now reporting
double-digit premium increases from many commercial, non-Medicare
customers this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
