<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CANDIDATES-EDUC-2TAKE     01-03 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-EDUC-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS VARY SUBTLY ON EDUCATION GOALS
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE, BRADLEY, BRADLEY-AD) 
(nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to education, the difference between the
Democratic presidential candidates is not so much what they have to
say as how often they say it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley want to
expand early childhood education. Both would dangle dollars to
entice quality teachers to work in impoverished schools and would
pump money into after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   But while Gore has made education a central issue of his
campaign, Bradley has subtly woven it through the themes of child
poverty and working families, which form two of the four pillars of
his platform.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began the race with an education address and recently
rolled out what he has called a sweeping plan to ``revolutionize
American education'' with an infusion of $115 billion over the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's education proposals add up to $90 billion for 10
years, but he has yet to devote a full speech to the subject or
release a comprehensive education plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley doesn't seem that interested in the topic,'' said
Michael D. Casserly, executive director of the Council of the Great
City Schools, a coalition of the nation's 50 largest school
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seemed more focused on health care, Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a shrewd strategic decision in a primary fight where
there is little substantive disagreement. Gore, endorsed by the
nation's two teachers' unions, wants to mobilize a core Democratic
constituency on one of its favorite issues; Bradley hopes to
capitalize on voters' anger over health care, an issue on which the
vice president might be vulnerable because of the failure of the
Clinton administration's health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Larry J. Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, said both candidates ``have made the correct calculus for
their campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   With education topping the list of public concerns in several
polls, it has been a frequent focus of speeches and debates among
candidates in both parties, even though the Department of Education
represents only 7 percent of the federal budget and the federal
government controls only $1 of every $10 spent on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one is running for any office, from dogcatcher to president
of the United States,'' said Arthur Levine, president of Teachers
College at Columbia University, ``you absolutely have to have an
education platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the attention, several education experts say they
are disappointed with much of what the Democratic candidates have
proposed for recruiting teachers and improving student achievement.
They say many of the ideas are incremental and avoid complex issues
_ from equity in financing to bilingual education _ that are vexing
school superintendents, mayors and governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we invest more money in doing the same stuff, we're likely
to get the same results,'' said Amy T. Wilkins of the Education
Trust, a Washington group that focuses on closing the race- and
class-based achievement gap. ``It's like old wine, new bottles, but
more old wine. So we get a bad hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential headache is developing from the frequent
tangling over the question of taxpayer-financed vouchers for
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, backed by the two teachers' unions, which ardently oppose
vouchers, has hammered Bradley for his votes in the Senate to
support voucher experiments in Cleveland and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has said that, unlike several Republican contenders,
he does not see vouchers as the solution to public education's
problems. In any case, vouchers involve a fraction of the nation's
students and have little to do with who is president.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a distraction,'' said Susan Fuhrman, dean of the
school of education at the University of Pennsylvania. ``It doesn't
get to the core of serious educational problems in public
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   On the more substantive education questions, the two candidates
have similar philosophies but offer slightly different routes to
solving the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   Both are emphatic about the importance of prekindergarten
initiatives, which research has shown are crucial to long-term
success in school. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the front-runner
for the Republican presidential nomination, also wants to expand
preschool programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore promises to give states $50 billion over 10 years to set up
preschool programs _ some operated by private groups _ for every
4-year-old and an unknown number of 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley proposes $2 billion a year for infant and toddler
programs, plus a doubling of money for the Head Start program over
four years so all eligible poor children can enroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore plan would help working-class families, whose children
currently have the lowest preschool attendance rates. But several
states already have aggressive plans in the works for 3- and
4-year-olds, so Bradley's program for birth to age 3 fills another
gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one talks about expansion, one can't escape the need to
improve quality at the same time,'' said Ms. Fuhrman, who also runs
the Center for Policy Research in Education. ``It's not just
prorating out what's currently spent by the numbers of children.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates also echo each other on the need for better
teachers in impoverished urban and rural schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley suggests a loan forgiveness program for 60,000 college
graduates and scholarships for 10,000 high school seniors who
commit to teach in disadvantaged schools for four or five years,
estimating the cost at $1.3 billion annually. Gore would go
further, using federal money to offer $5,000 and $10,000 bonuses to
teachers in impoverished districts, in addition to a loan
forgiveness program and money for training second-career teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But neither candidate deals with the questions of how to recruit
better candidates into the profession, retain quality teachers in
difficult schools or improve teacher-education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need incentives for people to enter high-quality training
programs,'' said Tom Corcoran, co-director of the Center for Policy
Research in Education. ``We need incentives for universities to
treat teacher education seriously and not treat it as a cash cow.''
</P>
<P>
   For after-school programs, Gore vows to ``dramatically
increase'' federal spending, but offers few details. Bradley
suggests spending $1 billion to replicate a New York program at
2,000 sites nationwide, and another $300 million to get older
people to volunteer as mentors. In New York, an after-school
program has been used to reinforce lessons taught during the day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In some areas the two candidates do not cross paths.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley wants to spend $400 million on thn's network of
community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a list of proposals that lack clear price tags:
creating small high schools, charter schools and a Web site
offering advanced placement courses; establishing teacher
certification tests; and establishing a high school exit
examination.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the biggest distinction is a strategic one, concerning
how a president _ or, at least, a presidential candidate _ should
consider education.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sees it as a centerpiece, the key to his broader campaign
theme of extending prosperity throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will do more to help close the gap between rich and
poor than lifting up our worst schools,'' said Bruce Reed, the
White House domestic policy adviser. ``Education is too important
to the county's future foext president to leave it toocal level.''
</P>
<P>
   While talk of school reform fills two of the eight pages of
Gore's stump speech, Bradley rarely discusses the subject directly.
Typical of his approach was the anecdote with which he opened a
recent speech. Recalling a Minnesota fourth-grader who told him
that she had skipped breakfast that morning because it was not her
turn, Bradley focused not on education but on children too hungry
to concentrate and teen-agers who think they must carry guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with education, you are dealing with poverty and
you are dealing with hunger and you are dealing with preparation,''
said Eric Hauser, Bradley's press secretary. ``It's an attempt to
see education as part of a larger picture, because it is part of a
larger picture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
