<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, JAN. 3
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-TB-TESTING-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 2,
about calls by public health officials for tuberculosis screening
programs in cities with large immigrant populations misidentified
the agency that emploPaula Fujiwara as assistant
commissioner for tuberculosis control. It is the New York epartment of Health, not the New York State department.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 2,
referred incorrectly at one point to a consulting firm in
Cambridge, Mass., that issued a report on direct sales by
manufacturers online. It is Mainspring Inc., not Mindspring.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MOVIE-GOING-BINGE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Jan. 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Jan. 2,
about movie box-office totals in 1999 misstated the year's ranking
in term of ticket sales. Exhibitor Relations, the Los Angeles-based
company that monitors box-office performance, estimates that more
tickets were sold last year than in any year since 1959, but higher
sales totals were recorded in the 1920's, 30's and 40's. Last year
was not, therefore, a record-setting year.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MALKOVICH-HYSTERIA-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Dec. 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Dec.
26, about the actor John Malkovich and his direction of
``Hysteria'' at the Steppenwolf Theater misstated the play's
history. It was first produced in the United States at the Mark
Taper Forum in Los Angeles in 1995; the Chicago production is not
its American premiere.
</P>
</TEXT>
