<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCA-COLA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINDFUL OF ITS IMAGE, COKE STRIVES TO RETAIN BLACK EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to repair some of the damage to Coca-Cola's public image,
the company's incoming chairman and chief executive, Douglas N.
Daft, has been negotiating intensely with Carl H. Ware, the
company's lone black senior vice president who in November
announced his intention to leave the company, in hopes of
persuading him to accept a high-profile job.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the situation said Monday that Daft began the
talks soon after he was named to succeed M. Douglas Ivester, who
shocked the company and the business world last month by abruptly
announcing his own resignation. The jobs under discussion for Ware,
who is president of the company's Africa division, include
``expanded responsibilities,'' the person said.
</P>
<P>
   Ware's resignation, at 56, caused consternation within the civil
rights community in Atlanta, where Coke is based, because it
effectively removed the company's highest-ranking black executive
while Coca-Cola is being sued by current and former employees over
racial discrimination. Ware is also one of two executives heading a
diversity council at the company; the council was formed after the
lawsuit was filed last April. Without Ware, the senior management
at Coca-Cola is entirely white and male.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has three black vice presidents out of 24. Two new
vice presidents were named last month, along with two new senior
vice presidents; all of those are white. Coca-Cola Enterprises, the
largest Coca-Cola bottler, last month named its treasurer, Vicki R.
Palmer, special assistant to the chief executive and promoted her
to senior vice president; Ms. Palmer, who will continue as
treasurer, is black.
</P>
<P>
   A Coke spokesman refused Monday to comment on the talks. But two
civil rights leaders in Atlanta praised the effort. Persuading
Ware, a former Atlanta city councilman, to stay on ``would be the
wisest thing they could possibly do,'' said Joe Beasley, the human
resources director at Antioch Baptist Church North, a stone's throw
from Coca-Cola's headquarters. ``They should put him in as the No.
2 man. No question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ware's resignation has also been cited in news reports as one of
several incidents that may have upset key members of Coca-Cola's
board in the weeks before Ivester resigned. Directors have referred
calls for comment on what led to the resignation to Coke's public
relations department, and Coca-Cola spokesmen say they do not know
what happened, apart from what Ivester offered in a statement at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, 52, who spent just 25 months as chairman and chief
executive, said he was leaving ``to move on to the next stage of my
life.'' A brilliant planner who masterminded the interlocking
relationship between Coca-Cola and its bottlers around the world,
Ivester was criticized for what was seen as insensitivity and
arrogance in certain situations. His tenure was clouded by
declining worldwide profits, scuttled acquisition plans and the
biggest product recall in company history last June.
</P>
<P>
   He announced a management reorganization in late October, which
required Ware to report to Daft, then a senior vice president,
instead of Ivester himself. Ware announced plans to step down a few
days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put two and two together, one has to speculate that
it didn't go well with him,'' said the Rev. Joseph Wheeler, who
heads the Clayton County branch of the NAACP, near Atlanta. ``It
was a big shock to the black community after hearing Ivester talk
about putting this diversity council together.''
</P>
<P>
   One industry expert said the move would be positive for
Coca-Cola. ``It makes a lot of sense to try to keep an executive
like Carl Ware on the team,'' said John D. Sicher, editor of
Beverage Digest, an industry newsletter. ``I imagine there will be
more changes in the upper echelons of the company in the months to
come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
