<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FIREWORKS-NYT &LR;      01-03 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOOD YEAR FOR FAMILY FIREWORKS COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)  (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Year's business was very, very good for Fireworks
by Grucci, the pyrotechnics company in Brookhaven, N.Y., that the
Grucci family has run for 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably the most important entertainment date in the
history of the world,'' said M. Philip Butler, who is married to a
Grucci daughter, Donna, and insists his title is chief operating
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was an important date in the history of Grucci.
Typically, the Fourth of July is the big occasion for fireworks,
with New Year's Eve a puny also-ran. Not last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Grucci, the highest-profile and most expensive of the country's
fireworks providers, took in about $2.1 million for July 4, 1999;
its revenue on Friday topped $3 million _ six times the amount the
company pulled in on New Year's Eve in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That year, it ran 12 fireworks shows; on Friday, it set off
fireworks displays at 31 different places, places as disparate as
the harbor in Dublin, private homes in the Hamptons and Jamaica,
the Atlantis Casino on Paradise Island in the Bahamas and the
exclusive Yellowstone ski club in Montana. It even lit up the
Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time clients, like the city of Honolulu, which would
normally order a $30,000 show, paid $50,000 and more. And although
Grucci did not raise its prices for the day, it refused to accept
new clients who wanted to spend less than $100,000. ``People
doubled and tripled their budgets,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   They did get more for their money. Last year, Butler said, most
clients were happy with 4-inch shells that would yield a display of
120 feet or so in diameter. This year, far more wanted 6-inch
shells, which exploded into a 200-foot light show.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering all the glitz was no mean feat. All year, Grucci had
sent out feelers, through its Web site and by word of mouth, to
lure the 100 extra technicians it knew it would need. Perhaps
because Grucci paid them well over the $200 a technician would
normally get for a few hours of holiday-night work, more than
enough people came in for training.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Butler tell it, all the programs went off without a
hitch. There was one ``annoyance,'' though, he said: In Washington,
the schedule called for a short light show at midnight, followed by
a longer one at 12:55 a.m., after another concert. On Saturday,
several newspapers reported that the first show had been truncated
by a computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have one glitch, yet we were perceived as having a
Y2K problem,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks industry had reason to set off celebratory
fireworks of its own. According to Butler, the industry's sales
have been soaring since 1993. Corporations are using fireworks as a
promotional tool, while rich individuals _ and, Butler notes, there
are many more of them today than there were when the decade was
young _ use them to make their parties special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the economy, pure and simple,'' Butler said. In the
1980s, he noted, some 70 percent of the company's revenues came
from local governments putting on a show for the citizenry; today,
80 percent of the money is corporate or private.
</P>
<P>
   Will the fireworks boom end now that the millennium hoopla has
ended? Not if the economy keeps steaming along, Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be the `first Labor Day of the 21st Century,' the
`first birthday of the 21st century,' any number of reasons to
throw a show,'' Butler said. ``As long as there's wealth, there
will be people wanting to add some bang to their parties.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
