<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-MINORITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO MINORITY PROGRAM AIDS FIRM RUN BY WHITE MEN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ An investigation ordered by City Hall has found that a
major beneficiary of a program intended to help entrepreneurs
outside the old-boy network is a company run by a white former
union official and his sons.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other big cities, Chicago reserves 25 percent of its
contracts for businesses run by women or members of racial
minorities. One of the big winners under the set-aside program has
been a janitorial business, Windy City Maintenance, which lists its
chief as Patricia Green. The city awarded the company tens of
millions of dollars in contracts during the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation found that the company is being run by Ms.
Green's husband, John Duff Jr., a former vice president of the
Allied Distillery and Wine Workers International Union, and their
two sons _ scarcely the kind of outsiders the program is designed
to help.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was ordered after The Chicago Tribune repor July that Duff and his sons were running the company. The
newspaper said the Duff family controlled businesses that reaped
$100 million in city contracts in the 1990s. Duff served 17 months
in prison in the early 1980s for embezzling union funds.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at City Hall said on Friday, in announcing the findings
of the investigation, that Windy City Maintenance had been stripped
of its status as a woman-run company and would lose its contract
within 60 days. City officials also said they would monitor
businesses that claimed to be run by women and minorities, to guard
against fraud.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Windy City said Monday that no one would
comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley, who has sought to portray fairness to
minorities as a hallmark of his administration, will speak about
the Duff case at a news conference on Tuesday, aides said. Daley's
support among blacks is considered softer than his rock-solid white
base, so the mayor has been careful to guard against anything that
would stir resentment among minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   The set-aside program has been seen as a potentially dangerous
issue for Daley, especially if it seems that white men are taking
advantage of programs intended to help women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Daley last week announced a program to recruit more companies
owned by women and minorities, especially blacks, to do business
with the city. Some black aldermen have complained that only 9
percent of the $1.3 billion in contractsd by the city
through September 1998 have gone to blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Daley, who said he agreed that the percentage of blacks getting
city business was too low, said ``the pool has to be expanded in
some way.'' The mayor named Barbara Lumpkin, the city treasurer, to
head a task force to determine the best way to find more
minority-run companies.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, city officials have simply accepted the word of
companies that say they are run by women or minorities, said
Jacqueline Heard, a spokeswoman for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to rely on the integrity of the companies we do
business with,'' Ms. Heard said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, to guard against fraud, city officials will conduct
on-site checks at the companies and talk to customers to make sure
that businesses are complying with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Heard said Windy City had been deserving of its status as
women-run until recently. ``It was in fact owned and operated by a
woman,'' she said, adding that company officials still insisted
that Ms. Green was the head of the business.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Heard said it was clear to city officials that Ms. Green
had stepped down from her day-to-day management of Windy City and
largely handed over business responsibilities to her sons.
</P>
<P>
   That transfer of power has made Windy City ineligible to retain
its status as a women-run business, Ms. Heard said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the Daley administration, the problem with the set-aside
program was a rare setback. Less than a year after his latest
landslide election victory, Daley commands overwhelming support
with the 50-member City Council.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the Chicago Tribune said that the Duff family and
enterprises they control had contributed more than $30,000 to
Daley's campaigns. The newspaper said the Duffs had played host to
at least two fund-raisers for the mayor, including a breakfast last
February attended by Daley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
