<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIFE IN LONDON'S FINANCIAL DISTRICT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ No matter how expensive it becomes, how snarled its
traffic or how seedy its public transportation, London just keeps
on pulling in the crowds, especially to the central areas most
beloved of visitors _ the West End, for instance, and the
well-trodden routes that lead from museums to monuments.
</P>
<P>
   For years, though, two key sections of the city have largely
been neglected by restaurateurs, hoteliers and the crowds they need
for their business. Mention doing business in the City of London _
the financial district _ or among the steel-and-glass buildings of
Canary Wharf in the old Docklands area, and the talk has always
been of awkward commutes from the smart hotels farther west to the
banks and offices where the real money is made.
</P>
<P>
   All that is set to change. Over the past few months, a series of
hotel chains have announced plans to renovate or build new
accommodations in the City or Canary Wharf _ decisions that will be
enhanced by the long-delayed completion last month of the
Underground's Jubilee Line leading east toward Greenwich and the
Millennium Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will still be something of a commute to link up
the West End with accommodations in the financial district,
particularly in Canary Wharf. But the region's boosters are
suggesting that areas once viewed as urban equivalents of the
Arabian desert's Empty Quarter are gradually assuming an
after-hours life of their own when offices are closed.
</P>
<P>
   The development is closely linked to the financial-services boom
that has transformed a whole area of east London. In the 1920s, in
``The Waste Land,'' T.S. Eliot painted a spectral picture of
commuters entering the city: ``A crowd flowed over London Bridge,
so many, I had not thought death had undone so many.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bonus-driven 1980s and '90s, though, the imagery of drear
commuters plodding their way to work from suburbia has been
supplanted by a newer vision of snappy 20-somethings moving into
riverside lofts and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Even in east London areas once viewed as irredeemably depressed,
such as Tower Hamlets, modest apartments now sell for upward of
$300,000. Districts that once seemed to labor under Dickensian
connotations of deprivation, such as Clerkenwell, draw publishing
and media types to set up shop.
</P>
<P>
   The City itself has seeflux of retailers and bars that,
while catering mainly to the daytime needs of bankers and other
business people, reflect what Alex Branner, a spokesman for
London's Tourist Board, called a trend to see the City as much more
than arid canyons of banks.
</P>
<P>
   This demographic shift has not been lost on hoteliers who,
Branner said, discovered some four years ago that London's 75,000
available hotel beds were about 10,000 less than the British
capital would need by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, Canary Wharf itself, where the opening
this month of a new 139-room Four Seasons hotel coincides with the
creation of Canary Riverside, where the 322 apartments cost from
$380,000 to $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The development brings an array of health and leisure facilities
and restaurants to an area once associated exclusively with
financial services, newspapers and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly there is a calculation that the Jubilee Line extension,
a 12-minute ride from the new Canary Wharf station to Waterloo
station, and the proximity of London's short-haul City Airport,
three miles east of Canary Wharf, will draw business to the area
because, according to Charlotte Doherty, a spokeswoman for the Four
Seasons, ``the worry that there had been about location is no
longer there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the City of London, closer to the center than Canary Wharf,
there is a similar calculation that businessmen and bankers want
more convenient high-class accommodation. The Eton Town House Group
has announced plans to turn a former bank on Threadneedle Street _
close to the Bank of England itself _ into a 70-room hotel to open
in the spring of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The City's Victorian-era Great Eastern Hotel, built between 1879
and 1901, is being reconstructed as a 267-room hotel set to open in
February. And, close to the City, six 18th-century houses on
Peter's Lane have been converted into The Rookery, an upscale
33-bedroom hotel laden with antiques and mellow lighting that
opened last month.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, midprice chains such as Novotel, Holiday Inn
Express and others have opened new hotels close to the financial
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a general trend that London is looking again at all these
po areas,'' Branner said. ``With quite a few years of
economic growth, there's a growth of confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
