<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVELS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Around the World In 115 Days &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A world cruise with the theme ``Lost Worlds: A Voyage Through
History'' will leave March 26 from Piraeus aboard the 850-passenger
Ocean Explorer I. This 115-night cruise will proceed to Syracuse on
Sicily, where a Greek civilization once thrived, and then continue
to 30 other ports, many of them associated with other ancient
civilizations or existing native cultures, like Casablanca,
Port-of-Spain, Callao, Easter Island, Papeete, Bora-Bora, Honiara,
Madang, Sandakan, Cochin, the Seychelles, Aqaba, Port Said, Ashdod
and Heraklion. Ports of call will be preceded by on-board lectures
by anthropologists and historians.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, the former Emerald Seas, refurbished in 1998, carries
eight 12-passenger Zodiacs for excursions into bays and rivers, and
is operated by the World Cruise Co. of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Fares range from $11,890 a person in double occupancy to
$26,990, and include round-trip air fare from North America as well
as transportation between Athens and Piraeus.
</P>
<P>
   For information and reservations, call (888) 558-0887; the Web
site is www &QL; 
.worldcruiseco.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France Plans a Picnic, And Invites 3 Million &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For sheer magnitude and ecological audacity, few millennium
events can match La Meridienne Verte, the showcase of the Mission
2000 project planned by the French government.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, tens of thousands of schoolchildren planted miles
of saplings along the Paris meridian, the line running 2 degrees 20
minutes 14 seconds east of Greenwich from Dunkirk to Barcelona that
helped 18th-century French mathematicians establish the metric
standard and calculate local time.(Despite the ravages of the
recent storms, the small trees have emerged for the most part
unscathed.)
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of the architect Paul Chemetov, each of the
337 communities on the meridian in France is nurturing indigenous
trees. Fields of red poppies, flax and impatiens to be planted
along 20 meridian sites are expected to blossom by midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   As the 597-mile tree line snakes over freeways and forests, it
brushes past Amiens Cathedral, winds through the Louvre courtyard,
across an Orly runway, and ascends the volcanic peaks of Cantal and
the Medieval ramparts of Carcassonne before crossing the Pyrenees
at Prats-de-Mollo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, the Green Meridian will shade the Incredible Picnic,
the biggest dejeuner sur l'herbe that France has ever witnessed.
Picnic tables up to six-tenths of a mile long, all with identical
tablecloths, will be set up all along the axis. More than three
million people are expected to celebrate Bastille Day with their
own bag lunches or with local specialties on sale at the picnic
sites.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, an air show is scheduled and a relay race
combining horses, Rollerblades, motorcycles and ultralight planes
starting from both ends will meet in the middle. Details at
www.2000enfrance.com.
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Partnerships Benefit Frequent Fliers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those who keep score: recent changes in frequent-flier
programs include new airline partners for Delta Air Lines and
American Airlines and new hotel affiliations for Trans World
Airlines and United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   South African Airways has become a partner in the Skymiles
frequent-flier program of Delta Air Lines. Since Dec. 1, Skymiles
members have been able to earn miles and redeem awards on flights
operated by South African Airways. Double miles will be awarded for
flights taken through the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Members of American Airlines' AAdvantage frequent-flier program
can earn miles on non-trans-Atlantic flights operated by Swissair,
Sabena, Crossair (an affiliate of Swissair) and Turkish Airlines
(except flights within Turkey). AAdvantage members also can earn
credit on trans-Atlantic flights operated by Sabena or Swissair
that are code shares with American.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines has added Wyndham Hotels and Resorts, (800)
822-4200, and Best Western Hotels, (800) 528-1234, to its travel
partners in the Aviators frequent-flier program. Through the end of
February, Aviators members earn double mileage (usually 500 miles)
for stays at any Wyndham hotel in the United States, Canada and the
Caribbean. Stays at Best Western hotels in the United States,
Canada and the Caribbean earn 750 miles (usually 250 miles) until
Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Preferred Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, a consortium of more
than 120 independent luxury hotels, has become a partner in Mileage
Plus, the frequent-flier program of United Airlines. Mileage Plus
members receive 2,000 miles for stays at any Preferred Hotel until
March 31, and then 500 miles. For reservations, call (800)
323-7500. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showcasing a Century of Design &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, the cradle of modern American architecture, is the site
of an ambitious exhibition, ``At the End of the Century: One
Hundred Years of Architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis of the show, which runs through Feb. 27 at the
Museum of Contemporary Art, is on broad themes in architectural and
urban thinking, including the Bauhaus movement, Internationalism,
the evolution of suburbs, and the trend toward themes or
``Disneyfication'' as epitomized by recent Las Vegas casino hotels.
Scale models, photographs, film footage, drawings, furniture and
architectural sketches are among the exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   In a segment on the politics of monumentality in the 1930s,
connections are drawn between the colossal scale of Fascist
architecture such as Hitler's grandiose vision of the Nazi capital
Germania, and projects such as Hoover Dam, which was, according to
the program notes, ``equally intended to demonstrate the strength
and stability of government during a time of economic crises and
social upheaval.''
</P>
<P>
   A companion exhibition focusing on current work in Chicago,
``Material Evidence: Chicago Architecture at 2000,'' deals with
millennial design and fascination with new technologies and
materials: one firm is experimenting with a pneumatic membrane that
has the properties of a soap bubble for constructing bus-stop
shelters, and another has designed a newsstand that doubles as a
digital information display.
</P>
<P>
   The architects Frank Gehry and Zaha Hadid, who recently won the
design competition for a Center of Contemporary Arts in Rome, are
scheduled to speak, and there will be a tour of Chicago's
architectural jewels from the Loop to Hyde Park and the Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, at 220 East Chicago Avenue, (312) 280-2660, is open
Wednesday to Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Tuesdays are free, and open
until 8 p.m. Admission is $7.
</P>
<P>
   Eric P. Nash &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
