<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-ART     01-03 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TURNS THE PAGE ON HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y., Jan. 3 _ Irascible, bellicose and demanding,
Bill Parcells helped transform three losing football franchises
into winners, including both New York teams.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, less than 24 hours after he concluded his third
season with the Jets, the 58-year-old Parcells said he could not
put forth the 365-day effort a year it took to coach in the
National Football League, and stepped down as the head coach of the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to coach any more football games,'' Parcells
said. ``This definitely is the end of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by his top assistant and longtime coaching
colleague, Bill Belichick, who devised the famed defenses that
helped Parcells' teams reach those Super Bowls. Belichick, who had
been the Jets' assistant head coach, will also run the entire
football operation, said Parcells, who said he would function as an
adviser and a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be Bill Belichick's shadow,'' Parcells
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' departure came on a day when two other teams changed
head coaches. The New England Patriots dismissed Pete Carroll, and
the Green Bay Packers did the same with Ray Rhodes. Both teams did
not qualify for the playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' decision follows a season that began with the goal of
reaching the Super Bowl after compiling a 12-4 record last season,
but which quickly deteriorated when the starting quarterback, Vinny
Testaverde, was injured in the first game and lost for the season.
The Jets stumbled to only one victory in their first seven games,
but Parcells guided them to a strong finish and a 8-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   It was a turnaround in keeping with Parcells' track record of
building downtrodden franchises into winners, a feat he
accomplished with the Giants of the 1980s, with whom he won two
Super Bowls; the New England Patriots of the early 1990s, whom he
coached to one Super Bowl, and then the Jets, who had a
franchise-worst 1-15 re 1996, the year before Parcells
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   His 29-19 record with the Jets makes him the only coach in
team's 40 seasons to leave with a winning mark. His career record
over 15 seasons is 149-106-1.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would retain the title of chief of football
operations, but claimed he would not exercise those duties. He has
three years remaining on his contract, which has paid him $2.4
million a year for running the club.
</P>
<P>
   There was some urgency involved in the decision. The team is in
the process of being sold by the estate of the late Leon Hess, with
a decision on the winner expected by the end of the week. Charles
F. Dolan and Robert Wood Johnson IV are the two candidates; each
has bid at least $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he had hoped to know lk who the team's new
owners would be. But practically, he could not wait any longer to
anoint Belichick, who was wanted by other teams and might have
accepted a head coaching position elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was especially coveted by the Patriots. Even as they
were dismissing Carroll Monday morning, a league official said, the
Patriots, through a faxed request, were seeking permission from the
Jets to speak to Belichick. But Parcells had already divulged his
plans to club president Steve Gutman and Belichick, who was
elevated Sunday night to the Jets' head-coaching post.
</P>
<P>
   It was another development in the continuing feud between the
Patriots and Parcells' Jets. Parcells left New England three years
ago because of a deteriorating relationship with the owner, Robert
K. Kraft, moved to the Jets and brought Belichick with him. When
the Patriots protested, Commissioner Paul Tagliabue had to
intervene and work out a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kraft admitted he wanted to ask Belichick to
replace Parcells back then, but said that his split with Parcells
had been so acrimonious that the Patriots were better off hiring
someone not connected with Parcells. They brought in Carroll
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jets were concerned enough about losing Belichick
that they asked the league last Friday to clarify Belichick's
status. The league said that even though Belichick's contract
called for him to succeed Parcells, the Jets could not stand in his
way if he wanted to interview with other teams. But if Belichick
became the Jets' head coach, he would be unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the league issued a formal confirmation of
Belichick's status, saying in a statement: ``The New York Jets
confirmed to our office earlier today that Bill Parcells is the
head of football operations, and that Bill Belichick is the Jets'
head coach. Under these circumstances, we have notified teams the
Jets are not under any obligation to any club to grant an interview
to Coach Belichick.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's previous experience as a head coach was a five-year
run with mixed success with the Cleveland Browns starting in 1991.
He was reunited with Parcells as his defensive coordinator and
assistant head coach at New England in 1996. Then Belichick came
here with Parcells the next year, and had a $750,000-a-year
contract that provided for him to move up when Parcells stepped
down. Al Groh, the current linebackers coach, will take over
Belichick's role as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick issued a two sentence statement explaining that he
would rather not comment on his ascension ``to allow this to be
Coach Parcells' day exclusively.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick replaces one of only three to have led two different
teams to Super Bowl appearances. His head-coaching career began
with the 1983 Giants. They won two Super Bowls before he left
unexpectedly in the spring of 1991, citing health reasons. He
subsequently underwent three heart procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells took a job as a television analyst, but returned to
football by taking on the Patriots in 1993. They had finished 2-14
the year before. But in their fourth season under Parcells, the
Patriots made it to the Super Bowl, only to fall to the Green Bay
Packers.
</P>
<P>
   But when his relationship with Kraft became untenable, and the
Jets fired Rich Kotite following the 1-15 season, Parcells
instantly became the No. 1 candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells contended Monday that after last season, he had told
the late Jets' owner, Leon Hess, as well as Gutman and Belichick
that he would be stepping down after this season. Hess died last
May. Yet, Parcells also said Monday that if the Jets had not turned
around their season after the 1-6 start, he was contemplating
returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't finished the way we had, I think I probably would
have considered even more strongly staying on,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his health was not a factor in the decision. ``My
health's fine, don't worry about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
