<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN ARE HELD IN BOMB PLOT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Mass., Ill.)   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Algerians, one in Brooklyn, N.Y., and the other in Seattle,
have been arrested in the continuing investigation of a terrorist
bomb plot. The new arrests came amid indications that federal
authorities are focusing their efforts on a network of Algerians in
New York, Seattle and Boston, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn man, Abdelwahib Hamdouche, was taken into custody
Saturday night at Kennedy International Airport as he was preparing
to leave for Paris on a KLM flight, officials said. Hamdouche, 34,
a naturalized French citizen, was held as a material witness in the
bomb plot investigation, and it is believed that he was ordered to
remain in custody after a closed hearing Monday in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, the authorities said they had arrested another
Algerian man, Abdel Hakim Tizegha, on charges of entering the
country illegally. He is believed to be an associate of a man
charged last week in the bomb plot, law enforcement officials said,
but he has not been accused of any direct role. The new arrests on
both coasts stem from what the authorities said was a bomb plot
foiled in Seattle last month after the arrest of Ahmed Ressam, an
Algerian who has been linked to a terrorist group. Ressam was
charged with trying to smuggle powerful explosives and
sophisticated timing devices in a car he was driving across the
Canadian border near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   While the scope of the investigation into the plot appeared to
be growing, many details of the case remained murky Monday. It was
not clear why the authorities believed Hamdouche was a witness. It
was also not known why he had been released without being charged
after he was taken into custody last Thursday during a raid in
Brooklyn in which another Algerian, Abdel Ghani, was arrested on
charges of being an accomplice in the bomb plot.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal complaint accused Ghani of having knowledge of ``a
terrorist network of Algerian nationals'' that also included
Ressam, and said that he had planned to travel with Ressam to
Chicago to raise money for the group.
</P>
<P>
   After Monday's closed hearing, neither a federal prosecutor,
David N. Kelley, nor Hamdouche's lawyer, Mitchell A. Golub, would
comment or describe the proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Magistrate Judge Michael H. Dolinger refused a request
by The New York Times to open the session, and afterward, he would
not say why he had conducted it in secret.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Hamdouche, who was a roommate of Ghani, appeared
to be a tactical move by investigators seeking to compel his
presence before a federal grand jury or for questioning by federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities may be hoping to see if Hamdouche can tell them
anything about Ghani, and whether he might cooperate in the
investigation. In order for Dolinger to order Hamdouche's
detention, the government had to show that he was material, or
critical, to the investigation, and that he was a risk to flee or
be unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   No one would say if Hamdouche had been ordered held, but he did
not leave the courtroom with his defense lawyer as the hearing
ended.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrests indicated that law enforcement authorities are
continuing to reel in friends and associates of Ressam and Ghani,
although the high degree of secrecy imposed on the case has made it
difficult to learn precisely what the authorities suspect of each
man.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal complaint filed against Tizegha Monday in federal
district court in Seattle, for example, makes no mention of the
bomb plot, nor did prosecutors discuss any link in a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcemenials who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Tizegha was believed to have been a longtime friend
of Ghani, and may have spent time with him in Seattle when Ghani
went there in mid-December, apparently to await Ressam's arrival
with the bomb-making materials. The plot was interrupted when an
immigration agent questioned Ressam at the border and the
explosives were discovered in his car, the government has charged.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint in Seattle against Tizegha says he entered the
United States illegally as a stowaway on a ship in 1993, and lived
in Boston, where he formally applied for political asylum. The
request was denied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
