<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5773 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-SONICS-HNS &LR;      01-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
And you thought the Rockets had problems.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the poor-little-rich-team files, here come the Seattle
SuperSonics, or, as they should be known, the SuperChronics.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Sonics carry an 18-12 record into Compaq Center
tonight, the same things that seem to chronically plague the Sonics
are again flaring up this season. Players arguing with coaches.
Players arguing with players. Players walking out of practices and
shootarounds.
</P>
<P>
   You know, all those things that supposedly got George Karl, one
of the most successful coaches in Sonics history, canned two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Paul Westphal who has been thrust into the maelstrom.
And while the calendar says 2000, it must seem a lot like last year
to Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   We repeat _ and you thought the Rockets had problems.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, at least the Rockets have won a game in the last two weeks;
the Sonics have lost five straight games after wiping their feet on
league doormat Chicago on Dec. 20. Since then, the Sonics have lost
to Indiana, Minnesota, Philadelphia, Portland and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are rapidly becoming the dead-and-gone-ics, and not
even Superman, it seems, can save them. But Superman, at least in
the Pacific Northwest, does not wear an ``S'' on his chest. He
wears No. 20 _ Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary is still doing a pretty good job of taking over when we
need him,'' said Sonics guard Brent Barry. ``But Superman needs
help every now and then from Lois Lane. So one of us has to step up
and do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton wholeheartedly agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Just like last season, the players are starting to cast a wary
eye _ or is that Gary eye? _ at the effort, production and stamina
of Vin Baker.
</P>
<P>
   After a 94-89 loss to Portland, Baker and small forward Ruben
Patterson walked out of the shootaround before last Wednesday's
game against Sacramento after having disagreements with Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just conversation,'' Baker said. ``It wasn't something that
was a blowup, like everybody thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   What everybody thinks is that Westphal confronted Baker on his
soft play and the 6-11 power forward did not appreciate being
embarrassed in front of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotions got a little raw ,'' said Westphal, who had drawn a
reaction from Patterson by dropping him from the starting lineup.
``It would have been better if it didn't come to that. But I think
everything is for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of Baker's teammates were happy to see _ and hear,
it seems _ the normally reserved Westphal break out of character
and yell at a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys came into the shootaround, and coach was getting on
them,'' Barry said. ``I was kind of glad to see coach stepping up
into that role. We've been struggling, and we need a kick-start.''
</P>
<P>
   From someone other than Payton, who seems to have taken it upon
himself to do everything, which could be a big factor in the
Sonics' problems.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that in the Sonics' first 15 games, Payton led in
scoring six times. Get the idea that the ball was zipping around?
Yes, which is why the Sonics won 11 of those games. In the last 15
games, though, Payton has led the team in scoring 14 times, perhaps
an equally big reason they have gone 7-8 over that span.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider that not only has Payton been heaving the ball up
(100 field-goal attempts in the last four games), but he has been
taking a large number of those shots from behind the 3-point line _
a total of 51. To put that in perspective: In the last four games,
Payton isn't too far away from the combined number of 3-pointers he
attempted in his first three years in the league (70).
</P>
<P>
   While he leads the league in 3-pointers made (82), he is on pace
to hoist up 585 treys, a horrifying number for a point guard. And
he's doing all this while still being expected to check the
opposing team's top guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody should be able to step up, but we don't have anybody
to step up right now,'' Payton said. ``We have to understand that
we're not going to win basketball games just with one person
scoring all the points and doing everything. This is a team. This
is not the Gary Payton show.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland point guard Damon Stoudamire, who along with Payton is
represented by Aaron and Eric Goodwin, understands why Payton is
going to such great lengths (and distances) in his efforts to
squeeze out a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about being a leader on your team: If you don't feel
comfortable with players you have on the floor, you're going to
always try to do a little more than you ought to,'' Stoudamire
said. ``Maybe that's what is happening now. You look at Gary and
how he played in 1996 when they went to the Finals and how he's
playing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different. He's having to expend a lot of energy scoring
30 points and defending the point guard. In this league it's hard
to try to do it on both ends every night.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Sonics are discovering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hang together,'' Westphal said, ``and start
winning some games again.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
