<SLUG> BC-NY-ATTICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT EXPECTED IN ATTICA UPRISING SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly 30 years after the deadliest prison rebellion
in American history, a federal judge in Rochester, N.Y., is
expected to announce a settlement Tuesday giving compensation to
the inmates who were beaten and tortured by law enforcement
officers during the uprising at Attica.
</P>
<P>
   As of late Monday, there was no official word on the amount of
the settlement, the number of inmates who may receive awards or
other details. Lawyers involved in the negotiations said details
would be announced at a hearing Tuesday morning before Judge
Michael A. Telesca of U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   If there is indeed a settlement that sticks, it would end a long
legal struggle over a prison crackdown that quickly entered the
American lexicon as a symbol for excessive government force.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven guards and 32 prisoners died during the four-day siege in
September 1971, when inmates took control of the Attica
Correctional Facility in western New York, then were crushed by
state troopers who stormed the prison, guns blazing. An additional
80 people were wounded in what a disillusioned state prosecutor
later described as a ``turkey shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   But as horrific as the siege was, the inmates contended that
what followed was even more unconscionable: an orgy of reprisals
carried out by prison guards and law enforcement officers.
Prisoners were forced to crawl naked over broken glass, and one
inmate had a screwdriver repeatedly shoved into his rectum.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, lawyers representing the 1,281 inmates who were in
Prison Yard D during the uprising filed a clasn suit against
prison and state officials. Now, 25 years of legal fits and starts
later, it appears that the case may be over, said Elizabeth Fink,
the principal lawyer for the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time coming,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell J. Banas, a Buffalo, N.Y., lawyer representing Karl
Pfeil, Attica's deputy warden during the uprising, said that he,
too, expected a settlement Tuesday. He said it would ``still be
subject to court approval and objections.''
</P>
<P>
   The Attica story began on Sept. 9, 1971, when inmates took
several guards as hostages and seized control of parts of the
prison. After several days of negotiations failed, Gov. Nelson
Rockefeller ordered the retaking of the D Yard, giving state
troopers the go-ahead to storm the prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the troopers did not stop there. According to a recent
federal appeals court ruling, there was ``very substantial evidence
that, following the retaking, some, and perhaps most or even all,
of the D Yard inmates were the victims of brutal acts of
retaliation by prison authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit was originally filed against various New York state
police and correction officials, as well as against Rockefeller. A
judge later ruled that the inmates had no claim against the estate
of Rockefeller, who died in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, a federal jury in Buffalo found only against Pfeil.
Five years later, one of the inmates, Frank Smith, won a $4 million
award stemming from that verdict, becoming the first prisoner to be
awarded compensation for injuries suffered after the uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, now a paralegal in his 60s who lives in New York City,
was forced to lie on a table, naked, while officers assaulted and
burned him. He was forced to hold a football against his throat
with his chin, and threatened with death or castration if the
football slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, a federal appeals court overturned the $4 million
award, saying that the trial judge had mishandled the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The case was then turned over to Telesca. And immediately, the
judge said that he wanted to hammer out a settlement to end the
matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
