<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BRIDE-FASHION-ART-NYT     01-03 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDE-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING `I DO' TO A RADICAL GOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 33, 34 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are hardly two more incompatible words in the
English language than ``bride'' and ``fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The former makes you think of hideous gobs of fattening lace,
while the latter brings to mind minimalist shrouds, eccentric veils
and a mother-in-law weeping softly into her hankie. ``Here Comes
the Bride'' does not go with sheer Helmut Lang bloomers any more
than a Prada nylon slip goes with a full slap of makeup and an
illusion veil. It's bizarre, it's tricky _ it's the sartorial
equivalent of saying, ``I do,'' backward.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the news that Barneys New York will open a bridal
salon at the end of the month. Barneys, which is known for esoteric
window displays, avant-garde expressions of understatement and
svelte-looking customers seemingly nourished by parsley, already
carries Richard Tyler's bridal collection (and Vera Wang's in its
Beverly Hills store). But with the new salon, on the revamped
eighth floor, the inveterate fashion seeker can have a wedding
dress from Christian Lacroix, Olivier Theyskens, Geoffrey Beene,
Akira, Dries van Noten, Jil Sander or perhaps Josephus Thimister,
whose spring ready-to-wear collection was inspired by the German
terrorist couple Andrea Baader and Ulrike Meinhof. Even Rei
Kawakubo of Comme des Garcons has promised to deliver a couple of
dresses. Her spring ready-to-wear colors evoked the hilarity of a
clown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we've been thinking about opening a bridal salon for
a long time _ we just needed the space,'' said Judy Collinson, the
general merchandising manager of Barneys. ``We've always dressed a
lot of brides in our evening and special-order departments. Now we
can have all these designer concepts represented.''
</P>
<P>
   Many designers have dressed women for the altar. Lacroix has a
well-established bridal business in Paris, where a made-to-measure
gown (without too many bells and whistles) starts at around
$100,000. Alexander McQueen, at Givenchy, and Oscar de la Renta
also do wedding ensembles for private clients. On Seventh Avenue,
Carolina Herrera and Badgley Mischka have brought fashion, and good
taste, to bridal clothes. And of course, there is Ms. Wang, who has
done a lot to give gowns more sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when June brides place their dress
orders. A glance at the hefty February/March issue of Bride's
magazine _ ``the blockbuster issue,'' as the cover trumpets _
suggests that fashion strongly influences wedding clothes.
Necklines plunge, the silhouettes are sexier, and everywhere, from
Watteau trains to jeweled embellishments, there is a sense of
let-them-eat-cake opulence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change from, say, five years ago is that girls are looking
for fuller skirts, usually in satin or organza, with strapless or
sleeveless bodices,'' said Erisa Katsura, the design director of
Yumi Katsura, a bridal boutique on Madison Avenue. ``There are
still some girls looking for simple dresses, but the look now is
richer, with distinctive details.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wang, who recently opened a Manhattan boutique just for
bridesmaid regalia and who hopes to open what she calls ``combo
stores'' (``It sounds awful,'' she admitted) for both brides and
attendants, said, ``I like to think we changed the perception.''
She paused and let out a throaty laugh. ``I really hate brides!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. With New York awash in cash, this could be a
bumper year for bridal designers. ``There is a proliferation of
weddings right now,'' said Ms. Wang, who, in addition to her
bread-and-butter bridal styles, offers a limited Luxe line of about
25 looks with custom handwork and an average price of $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   There are alternatives. Jessica McClintock sells strapless
dresses with appliqued hems for as little as $350 at department
stores. And Shalini, a former Isaac Mizrahi assistant, who has her
own business on Seventh Avenue, designs the sort of simple,
well-made sheaths and minimalist coats in silk faille that might
appeal to chic brides and guests alike. Defying conventional
fashion wisdom, she always keeps a few classic styles in her line,
which sells at Saks Fifth Avenue. ``I don't know why you should
take a perfectly good dress out of the collection and say, `We
don't believe in it anymore,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Barneys and the prospects for selling, say, a
teacup Lacroix dress with a removable skirt (for the ``I do''
moment), or a sparkly Akira outfit with a stole and trousers? As it
is, the high-end designer business has been a hard sell for many
stores, despite the strong economy. Ms. Collinson won't venture to
predict the response to the Barneys' salon, where prices will
average around $7,000. ``In a way, it's a little like having the
bridal jitters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she thinks there's a sophisticated customer looking for
something different, who identifies with the stark modernism of
Beene's A-line gown with a green harness or who wants the bravura
of a Theyskens gown with a huge train. ``When we first saw the
dress, which was in black, we thought, What would that look like in
white?'' Ms. Collinson said. ``Olivier said he had done it before.
So for a lot of these designers, doing bride is not such a leap.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Ms. Wang, a veteran of bridal jitters, points out,
there's a huge difference between what a woman will buy to satisfy
her fashion tastes and what she wants for her wedding day. ``I love
modern,'' Ms. Wang said. ``I worship at Jil Sander's temple. But
during the eight years I've been doing this, I've always tried to
include some dresses that I think look really modern, and they've
never been very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Ms. Wang has learned is that she can't make her
business grow without satisfying, as she said, ``the other client,
the one who wants something old, something new.'' Bring on the
satin cream puffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be the first to wish Barneys success,'' Ms. Wang said.
``But this is a very strange business. Inside all of us, whether we
want to admit it or not, we have this thing about the spiritual
quality of marriage. I think marriage is so in style right now that
you want to celebrate it.'' And that means clothes that basically
reflect traditional tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if you're at all familiar with how designers like Ms.
Kawabubo present their ready-to-wear collections _ often with
little makeup and no music _ you must either be a devotee or be
able to conjure up a setting where such a radical style wouldn't
look ridiculous. And that doesn't immediately suggest the ballroom
at the Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wang, who has outfitted same-sex commitment ceremonies and
isn't surprised by anything, is philosophical about the limits of
the modern bride. ``In these clothes, there's a lot of room for
error,'' she said. ``It's hard to see a girl in full makeup and red
lipstick wearing Geoffrey Beene.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
