<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTROW-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A '60s Image Maker Marches On
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the mid-1960s, Roman Polanski tried to set up
David Bailey, the British fashion photographer, with a young French
actress whose looks were not the kind to divide opinion. Her name
was Catherine Deneuve, and at first, Bailey declined his friend's
offer. ``She's not my type,'' he said. ``She's too short.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey eventually met Ms. Deneuve, who starred in Polanski's
``Repulsion,'' and married her. This was between long love affairs
with Jean Shrimpton and Penelope Tree, women his camera turned into
icons. Bailey was the original ``modelizer,'' to borrow a term from
1990s media parlance. He was Austin Powers, a character inspired by
his exploits, with a toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
   So when Bailey, in New York a few weeks ago wrapping up an ad
campaign for Bergdorf Goodman, said he didn't really know the names
of the models he'd just finished working with, it sounded the same
as if Martha Stewart had said she couldn't remember if forks go on
the left or right of a dinner plate.
</P>
<P>
   In an East Village photo studio, Bailey, 62, wearing white
Reeboks and a waist size considerably more imposing than it was
when he brought the sex, grit and verve of Carnaby Street to
magazines, said he avoided fashion work in the 1980s. He hasn't
done it often recently. Bailey, based in London, has done portrait
work and hundreds of television commercials for companies like IBM,
some of them award winners. He has also pursued film. Over the
summer, he finished shooting a thriller, ``The Intruder,'' with
Nastassja Kinski. ``It's not a great film,'' he said. ``It's just
OK I've seen worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking more like a character on a Lifetime cable series than a
man who had Mick Jagger as the best man at one of his weddings (to
Ms. Deneuve), Bailey said he shot the Bergdorf ads because members
of the store's creative team ``seemed like nice people and I have
three kids to put through school.'' For years, Bergdorf's campaigns
have been less than memorable. The Bailey images, which recall some
of his spare studio work, center on new spring lines and will
appear next month.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Rizzo, Bergdorf's president, said, ``We don't normally
have the budget for the world's top photographers.'' The store
sought out Bailey to create a look that would be proprietary, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has long said that he's never been all that interested in
fashion. He doesn't seem to think much of the photographs that
document it today, either. ``Lots of photographers are totally the
same,'' he said. ``You don't know who's done what. To do good
things with photography, you have to do something totally
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the world seems perpetually struck by a
nostalgia for the mod '60s that he helped to give birth to, Bailey
says he is not. ``I never went out with girls in white boots and
funny haircuts,'' he said. ``People get caught up in the
characterization of a period.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, he's never seen ``Austin Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bazaar's Drummer Is Vogue
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Katherine Betts has said that in remaking Harper's
Bazaar she intends to beef up the magazine's lifestyle and
Hollywood coverage, and many have interpreted this to mean a book
like the ad-heavy In Style. But the magazine that the evolving
Bazaar most closely resembles is the one Ms. Betts was recruited
from: Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts' full redesign of Harper's Bazaar will not have its
premiere until the February issue,is month, the similarities
to the magazine edited by Anna Wintour, to whom Ms. Betts once
played the role of protege, are hard to miss. Bazaar features the
model Gisele on its cover in a Gucci python dress. Gisele also
appears on the January cover of Vogue in Gucci python. Both
magazines have stories on the craze for fancy handbags. In Bazaar's
new Fashion Click section, which covers parties, one can find a
picture of Jade Jagger in the same Matthew Williamson dress she
wears in Vogue's similar Talking Fashion section. Both pages sit
across from the same ad for Fashionmall.com.
</P>
<P>
   Vogue has a story on young designers titled ``Generation Next.''
Ms. Betts, who has said she loves writing headlines, has run a
story on some of the same designers also under the title
``Generation Next.'' This suggests that fashion copywriters are not
the most imaginative people and that Ms. Betts, perhaps
subconsciously, is out to recreate the formula she learned at Conde
Nast.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Betts' only comment on the pervasive sameness is that it's a
``total coincidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
