<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INMATE STRIKE THREAT, NO DISRUPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite threats that prison inmates across New York
state would begin a strike on New Year's Day, state officials said
no major disruptions had occurred as of Monday, the first day
inmates were expected to return to jobs after the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had several places that were running slow,'' said James B.
Flateau, a spokesman for the state Department of Correctional
Services. ``But the system is operating normally.'' About half of
the 72,000 inmates in state prisons work in jobs from prison
maintenance to furniture making and earn an average of $1.05 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Fitzpatrick, director of public relations for the New York
State Correctional Officers and Police Benevolent Association, a
union that represents state prison guards, said he was not aware of
any reports of violence in state prisons in the last few days. He
would not say whether some inmates had refused to leave their cells
or go to work. ``We have to monitor this very closely,'' he said.
``Until someone comes up and says there's not going to be any
problem, we'll always consider it a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   All 2,100 inmates at the Sing Sing Correctional Facility in
Ossining, in Westchester County, N.Y., and all 1,800 at the Green
Haven Correctional Facility in Stormville, in Dutchess County,
N.Y., remained under lockdown for the 11th straight day Monday,
forbidden to leave their cells except for visitors, emergency
medical care or food-preparation jobs.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 24, Glenn S. Goord, the state corrections commissioner,
ordered the lockdowns after five rounds of 9mm ammunition were
found in a common area at Sing Sing and after some inmates at Green
Haven were charged with trying to coerce other inmates into joining
the planned strike.
</P>
<P>
   Flateau said he did not know how much longer the lockdown would
continue. He added that it would not end ``until we have finished
frisking inmates at Sing Sing, and at Green Haven until we finish
investigating inmates who were strong-arming other inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 85 inmates who were accused of plotting the strike _
encouraging inmates to stay in their cells and not report for
prison jobs _ were transferred from Green Haven to other state
prisons in recent months. Others who were found with a flier
calling for the work stoppage have been punished or placed in
isolation, prison officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Green, executive director of the Center for Law and
Justice in Albany, N.Y., an inmate advocacy group, said the
protests had probably been quelled by inmate transfers and threats
of disciplinary actions. She added, ``Key problems and issues and
grievances remain, and if policy makers don't do anything to
address that, tensions are going to grow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
