<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-ARREST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALGERIAN HELD IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ An Algerian man swept up in the investigation
surrounding an attempt to smuggle explosives into the United States
was charged Monday in federal court in Seattle with illegally
sneaking across the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors made no link with the Dec. 14 arrest of
Ahmed Ressam, who faces five federal counts related to bomb-making
materials discovered in his car as he entered the country by ferry
from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But law-enforcement officials in Washington, D.C., confirmed
Monday they were looking for a connection.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Hakim Tizegha, 29, was in the custody of immigration
agents before federal authorities _ fearing a terrorist plot to
bomb millennium celebrations _ fanned out around the country last
week to question people possibly linked to Ressam.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 people _ most of them Algerian nationals _ were either
charged with criminal violations or detained.
</P>
<P>
   Tizegha, who sported a goatee and cropped curly hair in court
Monday, listened intently as the proceedings were translated into
Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   He will have a preliminary hearing on Jan. 14, unless he is
indicted before then by a grand jury on additional charges.
</P>
<P>
   Tizegha is charged with illegally re-entering ited States,
a felony; and excluding examination by INS authorities, a
misdemeanor. If convicted, he faces 2-1/2 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine. He is being held at the federal detention center in
SeaTac.
</P>
<P>
   Tizegha was arrested in Bellevue on Christmas Eve after he
attempted to run from an INS agent, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   He entered this county in 1993 as a stowaway on a ship,
according to court documents. He lived for a time in Boston, and
applied there for political asylum. That request was denied in
April 1997, as was his subsequent appeal last June.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 30, Tizegha's Bellevue roommate told FBI agents that he
had known the Algerian for 14 months, and that Tizegha moved to
Seattle in winter 1998. In August, Tizegha went to Vancouver, B.C.,
the roommate said.
</P>
<P>
   Tizegha applied for refugee status in that city on Oct. 18,
according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 15, he mailed the roommate a package of his clothes and
his petition for refugee status, the FBI said. Tizegha then asked
for some money so he could return to Seattle from Vancouver, and
the roommate wired him $40.
</P>
<P>
   When Tizegha arrived a week later, he told his roommate that he
had sneaked across the border on foot through woods to avoid INS
agents, then caught a bus to Seattle in Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed with his roommate until his arrest on Dec. 24.
Afterward, he called his roommate from the INS detention facility
and asked him to go through his possessions, find the bus ticket
from Bellingham and burn it.
</P>
<P>
   The roommate did so, the court documents said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Algerian whom federal authorities have linked to Ressam
was arrested last week in New York City. Abdel Ghani, who allegedly
traveled to Seattle on Dec. 11 to meet Ressam, was charged with
secretly trying to help Ressam violate federal explosives laws, and
with conspiring to use fraudulent credit and bank cards.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, arrested in Port Angeles after he drove off a ferry in a
rental car, has been charged with attempting to smuggle a highly
explosive substance known as RDX into the country from Canada.
Timing devices and other chemicals used in creating bombs were
seized from his car.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, 32, faces up to 40 years in prison if convicted of the
charges. He has pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in Vermont say Ressam and a Montreal woman _
Lucy Garofalo _ have ties to an Algerian terrorist organization.
Garofalo was arrested as she entered that state from Canada a few
days after Ressam was nabbed in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Vermont say Garofalo and Ressam are linked to the
Armed Islamic Group, known by the French acronym GIA.
</P>
<P>
   The GIA is an extremist faction held responsible for some of the
bloodiest attacks in Algeria's nearly eight-year civil war. It has
also been blamed for bombings in France in 1995 and 1996, and an
airplane hijacking in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York case, court papers say Ghani mentioned to a
confidential source _ a reference sometimes used for an intercepted
communication _ that ``the situation was boiling in Algeria and
that the United States and the CIA are running everything over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
