<HEADLINE>
TAVERN WHERE GEORGE WASHINGTON GAVE SPEECH IS FORCED TO CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In its 237 years, Fraunces Tavern has survived the
American Revolution, a devastating fire and a terrorist bombing.
</P>
<P>
   For the most recent half-century or so, the historic tavern
where Gen. George Washington gave his farewell speech to his troops
in 1783 has been run by the Norden family. But the establishment
faces a modern-day Manhattan problem _ high real estate costs _ and
the owner, Robert Norden Jr., says he is being evicted.
</P>
<P>
   Last-minute negotiations Monday with the building's owner _ a
historic society called the Sons of the Revolution _ failed, Norden
said. So he began loading much of his office equipment into moving
vehicles, and when the restaurant's staff reports to work Tuesday,
they will come to move, not to cook.
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, Norden said, he has run the tavern on
a month-to-month lease that came out to about $300,000 each year.
But late last year, he said, the board refused to act on a 10-year
lease he proposed that would have kept the rate steady.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Norden said, the owners rejected his request to
extend the lease for a few more months while both parties try to
reach an agreement on a long-term lease, and they told him he had
to leave. Board members of the Sons of the Revolution could not be
reached Monday by phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think that the real estate is worth more because it's
Wall Street, the economy is good, but it is a tavern,'' Norden
said, adding that because of the location in the financial
district, which is busy only on weekdays, it was not even feasible
to open on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Landmarks and Preservation commissioner has
designated the building, which also includes a museum, a historic
site. City officials say this limits the types of uses and
alterations that can be made to the building, so even if Norden's
family is pushed out, it is likely that it would probably be leased
to someone who would operate some sort of bar or tavern.
</P>
<P>
   The original Fraunces Tavern building was erected in 1719 as a
Georgian-style house for Steven DeLancey. In 1763, the building was
converted into a tavern by Samuel Fraunces, and it was there 20
years later that Washington gave his famous farewell address to the
officers who helped the United States gain its freedom from
Britain. In a second-floor room just above the restaurant, the
general told his troops, ``with a heart full of love and gratitude,
I now take leave of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in 1900, the original building was destroyed in a fire
that tore through Lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, the tavern was rebuilt at the same location.
In 1975, four people were killed and 53 were injured when a bomb
set by the FALN, a group of Puerto Rican terrorists, went off in
the building. More recently the tavern has been a popular tourist
spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
