<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TIMES-SQUARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FESTIVAL IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 4: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever since a vast throng gathered in Lower Manhattan to hail the
ratification of the United States Constitution in 1787, New York
City has served as the premier location for great national
celebrations. The New Year's Eve spectacle last weekend was no
exception. Thanks to exhaustive planning by the police and city
officials under Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Times Square bash was a
glittering triumph. The crowd could be joyous because it knew that
all possible precautions had been taken even in the absence of
specific hints of terrorist threats or other mayhem. Yet the
security measures were installed in a spirit that did not
jeopardize the chance of having an uproariously good time.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to New Year's Eve, the temptation was
widespread in this hardened town to be cynical about the events
surrounding the new millennium. The sealed manhole covers, police
barricades, frozen zones and widespread security presence were
welcome but not exactly an invitation to party. Then came the
breathtaking televised diorama that moved from dancing on the beach
in the South Pacific to the fireworks in Sydney, Tokyo, Rome,
Paris, London and finally New York. Maybe the fireworks at the
Eiffel Tower and the light show at the Washington Monument did make
New York's confetti and balloons seem a little dated.
</P>
<P>
   But New Yorkers could boast that they made do with a budget from
local businesses and national sponsorships rather than from the
government. More important, the unusually benign crowd in Times
Square and the surrounding area, where only 14 people were
arrested, epitomized the worldwide theme of peaceful convocation.
What was being celebrated seemed to evolve with the evening.
Initially, many may have been thinking mainly in terms of averted
disasters. But as the wave of midnights rolled around the world,
most people were glad to cheer the global phenomenon that came
wrapped in those blessed hours of peace: genuine hope for the
future.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, New Yorkers have a penchant for what the
historian Mike Wallace calls the ``festivals of connection'' that
have provided the most memorable celebrations in the city's past.
Usually they are linked to particular historic moments. The crowd
cheering the opening of the Erie Canal in 1824 knew that the city
would forever be transformed, Wallace notes. In similar fashion,
the throng that greeted the laying of the trans-Atlantic cable in
1857, with its initial message from Queen Victoria to President
James Buchanan, knew that communication would never be the same.
The cheering turnouts for Charles Lindbergh, John Glenn and Neil
Armstrong were all testimony to the collapsing of physical
distances.
</P>
<P>
   While the worldwide millennium celebration was of a more diffuse
nature, the Times Square party nonetheless followed in that
tradition of celebrating connection. It was a specific New York
moment, rooted in a Midtown area that is emerging as a center of
the city's media and entertainment business. It also brought the
city into an immediate connection with celebrations around the
world, and in Washington, Chicago, Los Angeles and countless
smaller places around the country. With people watching on
television while communicating with each other by Internet, a
vehicle that was barely known a decade ago, the party summed up
where the city and the country are now. Times Square became a
bejeweled cocoon in which we could hear the echoes of each other's
relief and joy that the world had made it through a dangerous time
and could turn to the future with, at the least, a fresh
familiarity with what peace feels like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
