<HEADER>
A5791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BALLOT-TEXAS-COX     01-03 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOT-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ballot set for Texas' statewide primariesBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The March statewide primaries in Texas will be
highlighted by a potentially pivotal _ or entirely meaningless _
Democratic presidential battle between Al Gore and Bill Bradley,
and a Senate scramble among a late-forming field of five
little-known Democratic contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Senate race faces Kay Bailey Hutchison, an
incumbent with no Republican opponent and more than $6 million in
her campaign account. The Democrats itching for a battle with
Hutchison are former state Rep. Charles Gandy, retired military
lawyer Gene Kelly, Dallas lawyer Bobby Wightman-Cervantes, retired
airline worker H. Gerald Bintliff and former bank executive Don
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly filed several weeks ago. The others filed on Monday, the
deadline for getting on the March 14 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats wound up fielding candidates in three of the nine
statewide races. Under a strategy that has them concentrating on
legislative and congressional battles, the Democrats have no
big-name contenders for statewide posts.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deadline passed with no Democrats filing for Railroad
Commission seats now held by Republicans Charles Matthews and
Michael Williams. Williams faces Andy Draughn of Houston in the GOP
primary. Matthews drew no opponents. In other filing highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas Court of Criminal Appeals Judge Steve Mansfield, a
Republican who pleaded guilty after being caught scalping
University of Texas football tickets, announced he would not seek
another term. Five Republicans filed for Mansfield's seat. There
are no Democratic contenders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Democrats (attorney William Barr and Waco Court of Appeals
Justice Bill Vance) filed for seats on the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals now held by Republicans. The party, however, will have no
candidates for any of the three Texas Supreme Court seats. GOP
Supreme Court Justices Nathan Hecht and Al Gonzales drew primary
foes. Incumbent Republican Priscilla Owen did not.
</P>
<P>
   _ State Sen. Drew Nixon, R-Carthage, announced he would not seek
re-election. Nixon served jail time in Austin after his 1997 arrest
for soliciting an undercover officer posing as a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   The March primaries lead up to a November election that will be
the first since the Republicans, in 1998, completed their sweep of
all 27 statewide offices. Texas Democrats, who formerly dominated
state government, are concentrating are maintaining their edge in
the Texas House, regaining a Texas Senate majority and keeping its
edge in the U.S. House delegation. Democratic Chair Molly Beth
Malcolm said the Gore-Bradley battle is a ``toss-up'' in Texas,
where the primary could be crucial if the race is not decided by
March 14. Democrats in 26 other states will vote before Texans do.
Both campaigns say they are treating Texas as if it will be
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Texas is going to play a major role in the outcome of
this race,'' said Bradley spokesman Tony Wyche.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign could end as early as Feb. 1 if Gore somehow
pulls off a big victory in New Hampshire, something the polls do
not currently foresee. On the GOP side, Gov. George W. Bush is a
prohibitive favorite in his home state's presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. Senate race, Hutchison will also be a strong
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a retired military lawyer and a six-time loser in
statewide races, said Monday he is ``delighted'' to have opposition
for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gandy, former one-term state House member who represented
Mesquite from 1983 through 1984, said he got in the race because it
is important for Texans to have a Democrat and a Republican in the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to be ``the voice for everybody this side of the far
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the Texas House, Gandy has lived in Austin and
worked as executive director of the Texas Bicycle Coalition and,
currently, as a consultant for ``livable communities,'' a concept
that involves new ways of melding the use of public spaces and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Bintliff, a resident of Leonard in Northeast Texas, said his
candidacy was motivated by the lack of response from Hutchison to
his letter about second-hand smoke and schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Bintliff, a retired American Airlines employee who identifies
himself as schizophrenic, said he will run a limited campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I'm still sensitive to smoke and it makes me sick, I
don't know how many places I can really go to speak out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a former Bank of America executive living in Mesquite,
said his campaign will focus on ``issues that pertain to middle-
and lower-class folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Wightman-Cervantes, a gay rights activist, said he is running
because Hutchison ``is oblivious to the people of Texas.'' In 1998,
Wightman-Cervantes unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination
for a state district judgeship in Dallas. In Texas congressional
races, where Democrats hold a 17-13 edge, Lloyd Doggett, D-Austin,
drew a last-minute challenger when Ronnie ``Reeferseed'' Gjemre, a
Spicewood resident and hemp crusader, filed as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Ron Paul, R-Surfside, a physician whose district
includes eastern Williamson and western Travis counties, faces his
second straight challenge from former Matagorda County Judge Loy
Sneary, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
