u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     01-03 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS RESUME IN MOOD OF GUARDED OPTIMISM 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with discussions over for the
day, Barak and al-Sharaa did not meet today, fresh quote from
Rubin; Pickup 7th graf pvs, Barak and al-Sharaa ...) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. _ Talks between Israeli and Syrian leaders
on a comprehensive peace accord opened Monday behind sealed doors.
The meetings opened with a sense of urgency, American officials
said, but they pointed to signs that the path would not be easy and
that a single round of negotiations would probably not conclude the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions resumed where the parties left off three weeks
ago in Washington, with both sides indicating a determination to
engage in days or weeks of round-the-clock discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The thorniest issues are before them, involving security,
borders, water rights and political relations.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the difficulty of the talks, Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak and Syrian Prime Minister Farouk al-Sharaa did not meet
directly with each other at all Monday. President Clinton left
Shepherdstown Monday evening after a secoing with al-Sharaa,
but without hosting a planned session that would have included the
Israeli and Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said he had no
progress to report at the end of the day of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very hard issues,'' Rubin said. ``You can't have a
fully-scripted procedure with talks this complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and al-Sharaa made no publent. Clinton said through
a spokesman that he believed the talks were ``off to a good
start.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are being held in Shepherdstown, a tranquil
town on the Potomac River about 70 miles from Washington. It was
selected for its isolation, depriving the negotiators of
distractions and increasing the pressure for serious talks.
</P>
<P>
   American mediators have successfully used the technique of
enforced isolation in Middle East peace talks before _ with
Israelis and Egyptians at Camp David in 1978, and with Israelis and
Palestinians at Wye River Plantation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israel has sent a delegation of about 55 officials, including
the country's foreign minister, David Levy; the attorney general,
Eliyakim Rubenstein; Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, the minister of tourism
and a former army chief of staff; Zvi Shtauber, the prime
minister's security adviser; and dozens of lawyers, military
officers and technical experts.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's delegation includes 25 to 30 officials, including two
deputy foreign ministers, Yusuf Shakkur and Majeed Abusaleh,
Syria's former ambassador to the United States, Walid Muallim, and
several generals and legal advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Hafez Assad, the president of Syria, is not attending this stage
of the talks but his presence at a more decisive stage has not been
ruled out. Assad has assured Clinton that al-Sharaa carries
``plenipotentiary powers'' to conclude an agreement with the
Israelis, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that delegates were not being held
incommunicado, but the normally talkative Israelis have agreed to
turn off their cellular telephones to lessen the possibility of
news leaks. The Syrian government has never been particularly
leak-prone.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations began at the National Conservation Training
Center, which is operated by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
Rubin and Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, provided
the only public information about Monday's meetings to the press
corps, which is sequestered at Shepherd College.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the talks started, Clinton strolled through the
grounds of the training center with Barak on his right and
al-Sharaa on his left. In what was clearly a made-for-television
moment, the three leaders stepped onto a 200-foot-long pedestrian
bridge over a 25-foot-deep gully, pausing about two-thirds of the
way across to gaze out at the Potomac River about 300 yards to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Cameras clicked and reporters shouted, but Clinton only smiled
and waved. The three men then walked silently into the gray stone
Commons Building, where Clinton met privately with each leader for
about an hour to discuss a negotiating strategy for the next few
days, officials said. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also
met individually with the Israeli and Syrian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The American team that is expected to remain behind for
negotiations included Dennis Ross, the administration's special
Middle East envoy, and his deputy, Aaron Miller; Martin Indyk, the
assistant secretary of state for Middle Eastern affairs; Bruce
Reidel, the senior director for Mideast policy at the National
Security Council, and his deputy, Robert Malley; and a supporting
cast of regional experts, note-takers and translators.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Donald Carrick, military adviser to Albright, was also
present for Monday's talks, and additional Pentagon experts were
expected to arrive on Tuesday as the parties begin to grapple with
regional security arrangements and the expected U.S. role in
monitoring them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these negotiations the devil is in the details, and the
detail men will be the men that are going to play a critical
role,'' Rubin said. ``And we do expect that during this round, that
all of the issues, one way or another, will be discussed in detail.
But that's a very different thing than expecting that, having
discussed them, that they will achieve agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No one would predict how long the talks here might last. Rubin
said he packed enough clean shirts for ``more than a week,'' and
Barak is said to be willing to stay as long as two weeks if
progress is evident. Clinton has said he will return to
Shepherdstown as often as is necessary to help resolve conflicts or
to offer top-level assurances of America support for difficult
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond serving as mediator and broker for the talks, the United
States is certain to emerge as guarantor and paymaster of any
accord reached here. Israel is expected to ask for military
upgrades to compensate for the loss of the strategic Golan Heights
and economic aid to help pay for the resettlement of some 17,000
Israelis who moved into territories seized from Syria in the 1967
war.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, for its part, is looking for a substantial package of
economic and technical aid to boost its dormant economy and bring
it into the age of computers and global trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has not yet begun to consult with
congressional leaders on the terms of any new aid package for the
Middle East. It is not certain whether the Republican-led Congress
will agree to pick up part of the tab, which is estimated to be
between $10 billion and $100 billion over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big, big deal, and a deal this big is going to carry
with it a price tag,'' Rubin said. ``But we believe the peace is so
important, and our vital interests could so be strengthened by a
peace agreement, that it is worth our playing an important role.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
