<SLUG> BC-PENNEY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.C. PENNEY BEGINS SEARCH FOR NEW AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Texas, Ill., N.Y., Ark.)  (jw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last month, Madison Avenue has been wondering
whether holiday sales results would trigger significant shifts in
the advertising plans of the myriad dot-com start-up retailers,
particularly those that poured vast sums into campaigns to attract
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the first big change of the post-Christmas
period is being made by a bricks-and-mortar retailer, the J.C.
Penney Co., rather than an upstart dot-com. Penney, which has been
struggling to improve the performance of its 1,150 department
stores in an increasingly competitive retail field, is dismissing
its agency, Temerlin McClain in Irving, Texas, after almost nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal comes before Penney and other traditional
retailers announce holiday shopping results. But analysts said they
expected the company to continue its recent disappointments and
also lag its primary rival, Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. Sales have
declined for Penney, the nation's fifth largest retailer, as have
earnings, and in December, Penney reduced its quarterly
common-stock dividend for the first time in 40 years. Tellingly,
Sears has just revamped its own ad plans, arranging for its two
principal agencies to collaborate on a national campaign for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   The Penney decision puts into play an account with billings
estimated at $110 million to $115 million, out of a total budget
for Penney estimated at $300 million. That figure includes ads like
preprinted circulars, which Temerlin McClain does not produce.
</P>
<P>
   Temerlin McClain has handled assignments for Penney since the
summer of 1991 like the creation of national corporate campaigns
carrying themes including ``The best place to spend this holiday
season,'' ``Doing it right'' and ``The look. Look who.'' Media
buying has been handled by Mediavest in New York, part of the
MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   Temerlin McClain's hold on the Penney account, one of its
largest, has been slipping as the client continued to encounter
difficulties in finding a niche between specialty chains like Gap,
operated by Gap Inc., and discounters like Wal-Mart Stores and the
Target unit of Dayton Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Temerlin McClain lost two important Penney
tasks to the Dallas office of DDB Worldwide, owned by the Omnicom
Group. One was the Arizona Jeans account, for the denim duds sold
under that brand name at Penney stores, and the other was the
Penney home lines account. Each assignment had billings estimated
at $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.C. Penney is a company with a lot of potential,'' Dennis
McClain, chief executive and executive creative director at
Temerlin McClain, part of True North Communications, said Monday,
confirming a report about the review in the trade publication
Advertising Age, ``andwe had a great relationship for many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there have been tremendous management changes,'' he added,
``and the business was not what we'd all like it to be. This was a
move they felt they had to make in terms of getting their house in
order.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain described the Penney decision to place its account in
review and not ask Temerlin McClain to take part as ``mutually
agreed upon,'' adding that he was formally notified by the retailer
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sad to lose any major piece of business,'' McClain said,
``but changes happen when things aren't working right.''
</P>
<P>
   Penney accounted for about 10 percent of Temerlin McClain's
annual revenue of $80 million. About 100 of the agency's 700
employees have worked on Penney assignments in some fashion; of the
100, 32 to 37 are considered the core group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some modest reduction in staff,'' McClain said,
``but this will not amount to a tremendous economic issue for us.''
The agency will continue creating campaigns for the St. John's Bay
line of apparel sold in Penney stores.
</P>
<P>
   McClain said he was told by Penney executives that True North
would be ``invited to participate'' in the review ``as a holding
company, putting together a group to pursue the business'' that
would not include Temerlin McClain. Among other True North agencies
are the Bozell Group and FCB Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Woods, a spokeswoman in New York for True North, said
the agency company had not heard from Penney but ``would welcome
the opportunity to participate'' in the review. Pat Sloan, a
spokeswoman in New York for DDB, said, ``If asked, we'd be happy to
participate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Brown, a spokeswoman for Penney, which is based in
Plano, Texas, said she could not identify the agencies being asked
to take part in the review, which is to be completed in March.
``Temerlin McClain has been greatly valued for its contributions,''
she added, but ``it's time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to ``hold a review came after several months of
careful consideration regarding the needs of our business,'' Ms.
Brown said, adding that the successor to Temerlin McClain would
handle that agency's duties as well as tasks like media planning
and buying.
</P>
<P>
   Temerlin McClain won its Penney assignments from what is now the
N.W. Ayer &AMP; Partners unit of MacManus, which had worked for the
retailer since 1983. A major makeover for Penney in the 1980s,
emphasizing clothing and home furnishings rather than mass
merchandise like appliances, helped sales throughout most of the
1980s; Ayer conveyed that in campaigns carrying the theme ``Fashion
comes to life.'' However, in the early 1990s, when Penney sales
slumped during the recession, Ayer became a casualty.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who keep track of such things, the Penney Internet
retailing operation (www.jcpenney.com) came in 19th among the
most-visited shopping Web sites from Nov. 14 to Dec. 26, according
to Media Metrix, a market research company. Penney was the only
bricks-and-mortar department store on the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
