<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-U.S.-U.N.-NYT &LR;      01-03 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-U.S.-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AMERICAN LEADERSHIP AT THE U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, Jan. 4: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This month is America's turn to preside over the United Nations
Security Council. That duty rotates among the body's 15 members.
While the powers of the council presidency are limited, the job
involves close coordination with Secretary General Kofi Annan and
considerable control over the council's agenda. Washington can use
this opportunity to press for action on a global front.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the United States' permanent representative,
properly wants to make the long-neglected problems of Africa a
theme of his tenure as council president. But while doing so, he
must also work on trouble spots like Iraq, Kosovo and East Timor,
where timely U.N. action is imperative.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke encountered African issues like ethnic persecution,
brutal civil war and AIDS firsthand on a recent visit to the
continent. On his return, he announced plans to hold council
sessions on such strife-torn countries as Burundi, Congo and Sierra
Leone. He also wants to devote at least one session to the social
and economic devastation wrought by AIDS, especially in southern
Africa. Those sessions are welcome and appropriate, although past
United Nations debates on Africa have offered little more than
pious talk.
</P>
<P>
   But other, non-African issues also demand the council's
attention. In Iraq, the first steps must be taken to put a hard-won
new security council resolution on arms inspections into effect.
Holbrooke needs to ensure that an independent and credible chief is
chosen for the new arms inspection agency that will be created. He
also ought to urge France and Russia to persuade Saddam Hussein to
accept the resolution. It offers the prospect of suspending some
economic sanctions in return for cooperating with the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, start-up problems that have plagued U.N.
administrators, particularly in policing, have to be addressed
before they become intractable. Holbrooke, who knows the Balkans
well, should help Bernard Kouchner, who directs U.N. operations in
Kosovo, get the political backing from U.N. headquarters that he
needs to succeed. Holbrooke should also prod European governments
to follow through on their financial commitments to the Kosovo
operation and urge all countries to live up to their commitments to
provide volunteers for the international police force there.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, some 100,000 East Timorese refugees are still
being terrorized by pro-Indonesian militias in West Timor.
Holbrooke, who played a firsthand part last summer in persuading
Jakarta to accept a more active U.N. role in Timor, can now help
press Indonesia's new democratic government and its military
leaders to disarm those militias and let the refugees return home.
</P>
<P>
   After a long period of estrangement between the United States
and the United Nations, the elements are now in place for a more
constructive relationship. Congress has at last agreed on a plan to
pay most of America's back dues. Annan is showing himself to be one
of the bolder leaders to hold the secretary general's job in recent
years, raising the U.N.'s public profile and helping to restore its
reputation with the release of self-critical reports on past
failings in Bosnia and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke brings political clout and diplomatic skills to the
job of American representative. This month is the Clinton
administration's last chance to preside over the security council
and America's first chance to shape the international diplomacy of
a new millennium. Holbrooke should make bold use of this
opportunity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
