u p BC-NY-GOP-FINE-NYT     01-03 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOP-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE GOP PAYS FINE FOR FAILING TO DETAIL EXPENSES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Republican State Committee has paid a fine of
$128,000 to the Federal Election Commission for making cash
expenditures and failing to disclose their purpose while it
monitored balloting in New York City in 1994 and 1996, the
commission said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, which settled a complaint brought by the FEC, is one
of the largest in the commission's history.
</P>
<P>
   It stems from the committee's move to scrutinize polling in New
York City, where Democrats dominate and some Republican leaders
have long believed that the election results are manipulated to
favor Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to ensure that the balloting was fair, the committee sent
volunteers to polling sites in 1994 and 1996 and often gave them
small amounts of cash for items like food, transportation and child
care, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It lumped those expenditures together on its mandatory
disclosure records as ``Election Day expenses,'' without providing
details.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, party committees and candidates are
generally required to make all but the smallest disbursements by
check and to disclose the purpose of each item.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in this case was a total of roughly $80,000 in
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allen, a spokesman for the Republican State Committee, said
it settled the complaint because it was over a relatively minor
interpretation of the rules. ``We were under the impression that we
did not have to do technical reporting on such small
disbursements,'' Allen said. ``The FEC concluded otherwise. We have
corrected anything that we have done wrong in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee said it would no longer give cash to volunteers,
in most instances relying instead on buying MetroCards, prepaid
phone cards and other items that it could easily track and
disclose.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, whose power base is in the suburbs and upstate
New York, has since the 1989 mayoral election in New York City
called for changes in the way elections are conducted in the city.
It contends that Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican te, lost
that race to David Dinkins, the Democrat, because of fraud _ an
assertion that Democratic leaders call ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   The issue attracted renewed attention in 1998 when Dennis Vacco,
the state attorney general, narrowly lost his bid for re-election
to Eliot Spitzer, and Vacco, a Republican, refused to admit defeat
for weeks on the ground that the Democratic vote total in the city
had been inflated. He could never prove his charges, and eventually
conceded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
