<HEADER>
A5799 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT     01-03 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZURICH LAYOVER  
 JEWISH BUENOS AIRES  
 BANANA BOATS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions may be italicized)  
 (af)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We will have layovers in Zurich on a February trip, the first
giving us an afternoon free and the second overnight. What do you
suggest we do or see? _ Jeffrey Weisman, Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. After you clear customs and take care of luggage, it should
be a 10-minute train ride from the airport to downtown Zurich,
according to Evelyne Mock of Switzerland Tourism in New York. Once
there, she suggests touring the old town.
</P>
<P>
   Two-hour guided walking tours meet at the main tourist office in
the rail station and cost about $11.25, at 1.6 francs to the
dollar. Information and reservations are available from (41-1)
215-40000, fax (41-1) 215-4044, and www.zurichtourism.ch. The
tourist center can also tell you about tours by trolley ($18) and
by cable car combined with a boat trip on Lake Zurich ($24).
</P>
<P>
   You could also take one of four self-guided tours with the free
``Walks Through Zurich'' map offered by Switzerland Tourism, 608
Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10020; (212) 757-5944, fax (212)
262-6116. The easy-to-follow directions lead you from the train
station up the Bahnhofstrasse, the luxury-shopping avenue; along
Augustinergasse past St. Peter's, Zurich's oldest church, to
Lindenhof, a park that was the site of a Roman fort and with views
across the Limmat River; from the National Museum next to the train
station across the river to the Romanesque Grossmunster Cathedral,
and past the Rathaus, the town hall; and back across the river past
Fraumunster Church, noted for its stained-glass windows by Chagall.
</P>
<P>
   When you are hungry, a traditional option is one of the guild
houses, like zur Schmiden, at 20 Marktgasse, (41-1) 250-5844, in a
building dating from 1530. For a snack, Sprungli, 21 Bahnhofstrasse
at Paradeplatz, (41-1) 221-1722, offers chocolate treats and good
cappuccino. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to visit the Swiss National Museum, 2
Museumstrasse, (41-1) 218-6511, which is linked with the train
station by an underpass. This castlelike structure offers a
sweeping overview of Swiss civilization from prehistoric artifacts
to medieval art to handicrafts, weaponry, completely furnished
rooms and musical instruments. Open free 10:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
Tuesday to Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On your second layover, you will have time for a traditional
dinner at Kronenhalle, 4 Ramistrasse, (41-1) 251-6669, near the
Opera House, Zurich's most renowned restaurant. It is known for its
original art, by Chagall, among others, and its superb Zurich
cuisine, like Zurich Geschnetzeltes, veal and rosti in cream sauce.
A three-course meal for two with a good wine will run about $175.
</P>
<P>
   You could use your first layover to look into tickets for an
opera or concert on your return leg, or make the arrangements
before you leave home. Check with the tourist office or at
www.zurichtourism.ch for a schedule of events. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Buenos Aires with an elderly cousin who is
interested in Jewish history and culture. Are there any
Jewish-oriented tours of the city, preferably in English? _ Edward
B. Reich, Greenlawn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. For more than a century, Jews have had a substantial presence
in Argentina. They settled in Buenos Aires (which has about 50
synagogues) and other cities and set up agricultural colonies in
the provinces, including the first, Moises Ville, where a dwindling
few ``Jewish gauchos'' still tend wheat and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   A Buenos Aires agency called Tour-Ar, 408 Libertador,
Departamento A, (1001) Capital Federal, Argentina, telephone and
fax (54-11) 4211-1099 or (54-11) 4328-3254, offers a Jewish
Heritage tour. It lasts about three and a half hours and can be
tailored to personal interests. The cost is $150 for up to three
people.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking this tour or to plan a self-guided one, you might
want to get a 16-page pamphlet, ``Argentina: A Guide for the Jewish
Traveler,'' published by Aerolineas Argentinas and available free
from the Argentina Government Tourist Office, 12 West 56th Street,
New York, N.Y. 10019; (212) 603-0443, fax (212) 315-5545. It
discusses the Jewish heritage in Argentina and lists Jewish sites
and organizations, as well as general sightseeing suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to turn for guidance is a group commonly known as
AMIA _ for the Argentine Israelite Mutual Association _ at 633
Pasteur, Buenos Aires. It has art, film and other cultural
offerings, and if you fax a note to Anita Weinstein there at
(54-11) 4959-8865 saying when you will visit, she can suggest
things to do and places to visit. AMIA's phone number is (54-11)
4953-9595.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the summer has just begun in Argentina and
that vacations may limit access to some places in January and
February. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you shed light on the Geest Line, whose ships transported
bananas and a few passengers between the Caribbean and Britain. Our
mail inquiries have been returned undelivered. _ James F. McNamara,
New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The white Geest ships still ply the banana route, from Le
Havre and Southampton to the Caribbean. The line can be reached at
Windward Terminal, Post Office Box 154, Herbert Walker Avenue,
Western Docks, Southampton, England SO15 1AJ; telephone (44-2380)
333-388, fax (44-2380) 714-025. It also has a Web site,
www.geestline.co.uk, but it isn't much help for potential
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   That may be because the line is to determine only this month
whether it will continue taking passengers, according to Ian
Cameron of Cargo Ship Voyages, an English agent that has handled
Geest cruises. Geest, which has been carrying four or five
passengers a ship for the last few years, is replacing its four
chartered ships this month, he said, and has not decided whether
the new ones will accommodate passengers.
</P>
<P>
   If not, Cameron said, he can book you on several other lines'
cargo ships. Rates for these trips out of Southampton run about
$3,250 a month _ these can be two months or more round trip _ and
include all meals (but not alcoholic drinks) and the use of
officers' lounges.
</P>
<P>
   These ships can spend up to nine days at some ports, offering
plenty of time to explore islands like Antigua, St. Lucia,
Martinique and St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   If your time is more limited, he suggests a cruise from
Southampton on a Fyffes Bananas ship, which you can take one way to
Belize and Costa Rica, then fly back to the United States. The fare
is $1,620. Information: Cargo Ship Voyages Ltd., Hemley,
Woodbridge, Suffolk, England IPI2 4QF; (44-1473) 736-265, fax
(44-1473) 736-726.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-03-00 2253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000103.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-03 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     01-03 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING SAFE ON THE MOUNTAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Vt., Wash.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snowboarding, a sport now 15 years old, is booming, with
resulting major changes at ski resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The National Sporting Goods Association, which estimates that
7.7 million people over age 7 participated in alpine skiing at
least once in 1998, put the number of boarders, with some overlap,
at 3.6 million, an astonishing rise of 29 percent from the group's
1997 figure.
</P>
<P>
   On the association's list of 59 popular sports, topped by
exercise walking and ending with windsurfing, alpine skiing ranked
34th, with snowboarding 46th and closing in. The National Ski Areas
Association expects the totals to converge in five to six years.
</P>
<P>
   This change has had an impact on safety, but not the way
alarmists may believe: the number of injuries caused by boarders
who run into skiers is considered minor by safety experts, and most
ski areas doubt that segregation of the slopes would improve safety
much.
</P>
<P>
   Both sports involve blind spots, skiers to their rear, and
boarders to the side. In either sport, going at high speed might
not cause injury on an early morning empty hillside, while speeding
in an afternoon crowd, whether on skis or a board, could be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   As for the maturity of the boarders, although the vanguard had a
devil-may-care hotdogging image, snowboarders are growing older
with the sport as baby-boomer parents take it up along with their
children. There is even a 60-year-old snowboard instructor out
there.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want fancy stuff, many areas have terrain parks
for skiiers who like tricky maneuvers, as well as snowboard parks
for those who want half-pipes, rails and other challenges. These
attractions divide participants by interests and keep them out of
one another's way.
</P>
<P>
   The major safety trends are in conflict. Injuries to skiers have
been declining, but snowboarding injuries have almost offset the
reduction. In addition, the two sports produce different types of
injuries, although as with bicycling and other sports, head
injuries are a major factor in deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Witt, a spokesman for the Vail Ski Resorts _ Vail, Beaver
Creek, Breckenridge and Keystone _ said about a quarter of the
visits to his resorts last year were by snowboarders. He said that
the growth of the boarding population had not changed the rate of
injuries, but rather the types.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boarders' injuries tend to be in the wrist, shoulder and upper
body,'' he said, ``because the feet are locked in place on one
board.'' Skiers' injuries tend toward the legs and feet, he said,
because they can fly out in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Julie Gilchrist, a pediatrician and medical epidemiologist
in the center for injury control at the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention, says her center has gathered no independent data on
child safety on ski slopes. But she has studied research by the
Federal Consumer Product Safety Commission that supports the
wearing of ski helmets. She recommends common-sense approaches to
safety, focusing on the National Ski Patrol's Responsibility Code.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gilchrist lists year-round physical and cardiovascular
conditioning as a good preparation. Keeping equipment in good
repair, being aware of the effects of altitude on strength and
stamina, and planning the day to avoid exhaustion were among her
other suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   On these last two points, ski operators note that modern
high-speed, high-capacity lifts mean that people can fit in many
more runs than in earlier years, and so should be aware that
exhaustion and dehydration can come earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The National Ski Areas Association, which encompasses 509 major
areas in the United States receiving 95 percent of the skiing
visits annually, has joined this season with the National Ski
Patrol, insurance companies and other organizations to create
Safety Initiative 2000, a program to focus on avoiding injury. The
motto ``Heads Up'' was chosen, but which steps to take is up to
each area.
</P>
<P>
   At Vail, ski patrols have taken away lift passes from those
skiing too fast. But at Ascutney in Brownsville, Vt., said Kim
Jackson, a spokeswoman, the emphasis is on warning and counseling.
Children 8 to 12 in the Young Olympians school get report cards
each day that also bear messages about responsibility _ for
example, that skiers should stop on the side of a trail, not in the
middle, and look uphill before starting down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a family-oriented mountain,'' Ms. Jackson said. ``We
don't get hotdoggers.'' But ski patrols and staff members skiing
for recreation do stop those displaying risky behavior and warn
them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Vail resorts, Witt said, employees identified as Yellow
Jackets warn skiers and boarders who are going too fast, although
Ski Patrol members and employees there also have the power to
remove people.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of safety on the slopes got intense attention two
years ago when Rep. Sonny Bono of California died after hitting a
tree in South Lake Tahoe, Calif., less than a week after Michael L.
Kennedy died the same way in Aspen, Colo. Tim White, head of
education for the ski areas group, said, ``Undoubtedly, it's public
awareness of ski-snowboarding-related accidents, not the injury
rate, that's rising.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The ski-areas group said that for the 1998-99 season, it had 52
million visits _ people entering for a day or part of one. Stacy
Gardner, a spokeswoman, said that there were 39 fatalities at the
group members' areas that season, 33 skiers and 6 snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   She said that over 15 years, fatalities had averaged about 34 a
year, a rate of 3.75 fatalities for each million participants.
Colorado's first fatality of this season came on Nov. 28, when
Steven Ricci, 31, a disabled skier, struck a tree at Winter Park.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gardner, along with others in the industry, said that she
considered the rate no worse than other sports involving ``high
energy participation,'' like bicycling or scuba diving. The ski
areas association has a Web site with safety information and tips
at www.nsaa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment advances seem to be helping. The Consumer Product
Safety Commission monitors injury rates though an electronic coding
system in hospital emergency rooms. In its report early this year,
it estimated that skiing injuries treated in hospitals declined to
84,200 in 1997, from 114,400 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The group said that improved equipment, bindings in particular,
reduced leg injuries. Snowboarding injuries in the same period were
estimated to have tripled, to 37,600 from 12,600, a change linked
to the sport's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1997 total, 18 percent of the injuries to skiers and
boarders combined were estimated to involve children under 15; 30
percent were to 15-to-24-year-olds. Male victims accounted for 63
percent of all cases.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer-product group estimated that the total of head
injuries among alpine skiers and snowboarders in 1998 was 16,000.
In an earlier study, head injuries were estimated to represent 14
percent of skiing and snowboarding injuries; for children under 15,
the figure was 22 percent. These injuries ranged from fractured
skulls to cuts and broken teeth.
</P>
<P>
   From Feb. 1 to March 31, 1998, the Product Safety Commission
studied injuries to see where a helmet would have made a
difference. This study found that 44 percent of 124 injuries would
have been prevented or reduced in severity by a helmet, and 42
percent would not. On the basis of the 1998 figures, the agency
said that 7,000 head injuries could have been avoided or lessened
by a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   No state or resort requires helmets. Expert skiers who go into
back country face added dangers, including avalanches, and they
might follow Forest Service rules for its employees and wear
helmets, in addition to other precautions: skiing with buddies and
leaving information on where they are going. (The consumer-product
commission helmet study may be read on the Web at www.cpsc.gov.
Click on ``search'' and enter ``skiing.'')
</P>
<P>
   The study's conclusions on helmet efficacy have been disputed as
``somewhat optimistic'' by Jasper Shealy, who is chairman of the
industrial engineering department of the Rochester Institute of
Technology and has researched ski injuries since the 1970s. In an
article distributed by the ski areas group, he wrote that 90
percent of all fatally injured skiers die of ``high-speed impact,''
and that no commercially available helmet would be of ``any great
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane C. Thompson at the Harborview Injury Prevention and
Research Center in Seattle, whose organization has done extensive
work researching the value of bicycle helmets and designing safety
campaigns, says it is considering a study on skiing-snowboarding
models. She said they could probably protect the wearer in a
``fairly brutal fall,'' noting that competitors wear helmets.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Gardner says that the ski area managers worry about
requiring helmets because wearers may then feel they are invincible
and take needless chances. ``We want them to have fun and take
responsibility for their own safety,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
