<SLUG> BC-AIDS-GROUP-LEADER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY'S LEADER TAKES THE SUBWAY TO THE FRONT IN THE AIDS BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Ana Oliveira were a psychiatrist, the queue for
couch time in her office might stretch around the block. Her ``I
can fix it'' attitude could throw the toughest neuroses for a loop.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Oliveira, whose altruistic instincts were handed
down like an heirloom from her mother in Sao Paulo, Brazil,
searched for a modern dragon to slay, it was the three-headed hydra
of AIDS, substance abuse and poverty that kept her in the United
States after she received a master's in medical anthropology. She
got her degree as planned, the first in her family to do so. But
she never went back to Sao Paulo. That part was unplanned.
</P>
<P>
   Now 47, Ms. Oliveira is still here on the prowl against AIDS,
and today her salt-and-pepper hair stands at attention, her
silver-ringed hands churn, and the Brazilian accent that wafts
through her textbook English like a whisper of samba is soaring as
she explains why she can't leave. Not when AIDS _ she calls it
``the epidemic'' _ has shifted its focus to women, children and gay
men of black and Latin heritage. ``It hasn't affected my body, but
it has affected my community,'' Ms. Oliveira says. She endured her
own brush with a potentially fatal disease when she had surgery for
thyroid cancer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliveira, a Latina, a lesbian and, for reasons to be
clarified later, an acupuncturist, is the first woman to become
executive director of the Gay Men's Health Crisis, the nation's
oldest and largest AIDS services agency and one in the throes of
its own crisis after a $6 million budget cut and a 33 percent staff
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliveira, whose connection with the agency began in 1996
when she started its women's department, was a unanimous choice as
director. When her appointment was confirmed recently, everybody
stood and whooped like lottery winners.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar had happened when she introduced the women's
program, and it was the reception she got then that convinced her
there was no contradiction in putting a woman at the helm now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we announced the women's department, I was asking
myself, can the agency be large enough to take this thing on?'' Ms.
Oliveira recalls, referring to the agency's open-mindedness, not
its size. ``And how can I make the link?'' she added. She did it by
facing the staff and asking those who provided AIDS services to
women to stand. Then she asked those who provided services
indirectly to rise. ``When it got to that point and there were some
folks still sitting down,'' she says, eyes glinting, ``I asked all
of us who want to bring out the woman inside us to please stand,
and everybody did. We had a tremendous laugh, a tremendous
clapping. That's when I knew I had the support of my gay
brothers,'' she notes, knuckles knocking a wood table for luck.
``When people ask me if AIDS is not about men, not gay, not a
crisis anymore, I tell them it still is. It's just a different
crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, 40,000 new infections appeared in the United States,
and worldwide, 2.5 million deaths were attributed to AIDS. Ms.
Oliveira counts two close friends, both women, among the
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Though hers isn't a post for the faint-hearted (her predecessor,
Dr. Joshua Lipsman, resigned after 10 months), Ms. Oliveira,
insisting that she is accountable to all 8,000 clients of the
agency, is passionate about what brought her here. The primary
vehicle was the No. 6 train to the war zone that was the South
Bronx in 1981. There, amid alcoholics and addicts of the pre-crack
era, Ms. Oliveira did her New School internship at an acupuncture
clinic affiliated with Lincoln Hospital's substance abuse program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into a room and there were 30, 40 people, poor folks,
sitting there with needles sticking in their ears,'' she says. ``I
was completely captivated. My internship was supposed to last six
months. It lasted several years!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oliveira took note when Paul Popham, a founder of the Gay
Men's Health Crisis, who died of AIDS, showed up at her clinic
desperate to find a cure for an ailment so modern it was nameless.
</P>
<P>
   She finished her degree, became a licensed acupuncturist, worked
at Lincoln and other clinics and, with the advent of crack and HIV,
saw a shift in clients. ``We started to see more women.'' After a
stint at Samaritan Village in Queens, Ms. Oliveira arrived at the
Gay Men's Health Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   She says she won't leave until ``we have the same impact on the
prevention side of the epidemic we've had on quality of life.'' She
added, ``Now that folks are living with instead of dying from AIDS,
it's about teaching life, work, relationship and parenting skills
instead of grieving skills; making medicine accessible; finding
medicine for resistant strains.''
</P>
<P>
   Parenting skills may soon come in handy for Ms. Oliveira, who
lives in Morningside Heights with her partner of five years, Julia
Ritchie, a therapist. ``She wants to have a child, and I love
children, so it's a dangerous combination,'' Ms. Oliveira says.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest daughter in a Roman Catholic household she describes
as progressive, Ms. Oliveira was married briefly at 18, and it took
years before she told her parents she was a lesbian. ``They more
accept than understand it,'' she says. ``But the need to make a
difference in the world, and not just any difference, I very much
got that from my parents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
