<HEADER>
A5912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TICKETS-NYT &LR;      01-03 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIBERY FOUND COMMON AMONG N.Y. TICKET BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever wondered why tickets are sold out at the box
office for a basketball game or a Broadway show, but ticket
agencies seem to have a large supply? There is often a reason, says
the New York state attorney general's office: bribery.
</P>
<P>
   A continuing investigation by the office has found that ticket
brokers use bribery to obtain tickets for Broadway shows, concerts
and sporting events, tickets that should be available to the public
at box office prices. The brokers are able to acquire hundreds of
seats, creating a virtual stranglehold on the most-sought tickets,
according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insiders are taking bribes to make tickets available to ticket
brokers, anverage Joe doesn't have a shot,'' said Elizabeth
Block, the attorney general's lead investigator on ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators acknowledged the existence of scalpers
who resell tickets in front of arenas and theaters, those people
are not the focus of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to root out corruption in the box office itself,''
said Attorney General Eliot L. Spitzer. Spitzer said his office was
close to filing a series of criminal complaints against people who
take or pay bribes for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   If the problem of brokers' illegally obtaining large blocs of
tickets could be eliminated, Ssaid, the attorney general's
office would consider supporting the removal of price restrictions
on ticket resales. ``I am certainly tempted by a free market for
tickets once we have eliminated bribery in the ticket office
itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The widespread bribery has inflated prices beyond those that a
free market would bear for three reasons, Spitzer said. First, he
explained, brokers snap up so many tickets that it worsens the
scarcity of tickets in high demand. Then brokers have to recoup the
cost of the bribes. Finally, businesses support the brokers by
paying inflated prices for seats that the companies use to impress
clients. The money that companies spend entertaining is tax
deductible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies can spend virtually unlimited dollars,'' Spitzer
said. One New York brokerage firm spent almost $370,000 on tickets
in a single year, a report issued by the attorney general's office
in May said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not limited to New York. ``I've spoken with
people in other states,'' Spitzer said. ``And this has not become a
multistate enforcement action, but the problem is, in fact,
nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general acknowledged that the problem may be more
apparent in New York. Even though New York has more shows, concerts
and venues than most cities, the audience, fed by tourism,
outstrips demand. There is also a concentration of major companies
willing to pay the high ticket prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Broker markups on tickets commonly range up to 600 percent, but
can go higher depending upon the event.
</P>
<P>
   In August, during the U.S. Open tennis tournament in Queens,
more than 900 people received citations for scalping tickets, said
Michael Mansfield, chief of the Economic Crimes Bureau for the
Queens district attorney. There, $25 tickets were going for $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the New York securities firm cited in the attorney
general's report paid a ticket broker in New Jersey $367,980 for
tickets _ including $3,250 each for four U.S. Open tickets,
according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   Such markups are illegal in New York under a law that restricts
resale price to $5 or 10 percent, whichever is greater, plus tax.
Lobbyists for the East Coast Ticket Brokers Association have
supported a bill that would repeal that provision. Repeated calls
to the organization's lawyers, the firm of Davidoff &AMP; Malito, for
comment about the attorney general's report were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the law in place, brokers skirt New York
statutes, Spitzer said. Many operate in New Jersey, where the
scalping laws do not cover out-of-state sales.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald B. Lefcourt, a criminal defense lawyer in New York, said,
``If brokers do end up in court, they usually get adjourned in
contemplation of dismissal.'' In these cases, as long as the
defendant is not arrested again for six months, the charges are
automaticsmissed.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has seemingly made scalping easier. A search of
eBay under tickets on Monday brought 2,418 responses. Ebay's policy
is that the seller must conform to local laws, which causes
enforcement problems because the seller does not have to list a
location. Ebay will remove any tickets that the police say are
being sold illegally. But that has never happened, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Madison Square Garden conducted an investigation that
led to the dismissal of five employees in the subscription
department and the removal of many brokers from the subscription
list. Some of those brokers were reinstated in 1997. That same
year, state investigators found, 75 percent of the Knicks'
subscriptions were given to people found to have connections with
management. The 25 percent sold to the public were in the upper
tier, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Madison Square Garden said in a statement: ``In
each of the past three years Madison Square Garden, as part of its
ongoing policy regarding the unauthorized resale of season tickets,
revoked an average of more than 500 tickets per year. Reports have
stated that a handful of people who had their subscriptions revoked
have been able to subsequently purchase new subscriptions. The
Garden is investigating and if appropriate, will revoke these
subscriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office has asked for changes in
legislation that deals with scalping. Specifically, the office has
asked that taking or giving bribes for tickets, now a misdemeanor,
be made a felony. It also wants to set up a system to track sales
of individuals tickets, to  easier to identify box office
employees who make illegal sales.
</P>
<P>
   The issue probably will not be taken up by the New York
Legislature until the current state law expires next June. Even
then, it is unclear if there will be a legislative solution.
</P>
<P>
   As the report itself pointed out, New York has regulated resale
and sellers of tickets for 77 years and has not beaten scalping
yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
