<SLUG> BC-GUNS-INJURIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING THE DANGER FROM BULLETS FIRED INTO THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN UHLENHUTH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ What goes up must come down. This fundamental
law of physics was tragically proved in the first four minutes of
New Year's Day, when 32-year-old Anthony Rickman of Kansas City was
killed by a stray bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Rickman was in the 3900 block of Monroe Avenue, where he had
been firing off shots in his own celebration of the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people might think it's OK because everybody
does it,'' said Officer Steve Young, a spokesman for the Kansas
City Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not OK. It's illegal, and very, very irresponsible. That
bullet has to go somewhere. If you shoot it into the air, it
doesn't stay there. It's an asinine thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no other deaths due to random gunfire were reported, in
Overland Park 12-year-old Kevin Lander woke Saturday morning and
realized how close he'd come to danger.
</P>
<P>
   His first sight that morning was a bullet that had come down
through the roof and lodged in the ceiling above his pillow. He
could see the copper-colored tip sticking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked up at the ceiling and said, `Dad, you'd better come
in here and look at this,' '' said Kevin's mother, Charlene Lander.
</P>
<P>
   Police think that the bullet was fired into the air by a
reckless New Year's Eve reveler.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet, which police said was probably a 9 mm, pierced the
wood-shingle roof of the Landers' home at 5711 W. 84th St. and
ended up above Kevin's head in the northeast part of the
single-story house.
</P>
<P>
   Other incidents attributed to festive gunslinging included two
small power outages in southeast Kansas City and the interruption
of cable television service to hundreds of customers in Kansas
City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve is prime time for re-enacting the days of the
Wild, Wild West, according to spokesmen for a few local police
departments, but it is not the only such occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be popular following, of all things, Chiefs
football victories,'' said Bill Pross, speaking for the
Independence Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July, too, brings out the celebratory gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of those occasions lend themselves to drinking,
which then dulls one's common sense,'' Pross said.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of town on New Year's Eve, Young said, ``it sounds
like a war zone. Ninety-nine to 100 percent of the people shooting
their guns have no idea where those bullets are going to end up.''
</P>
<P>
   While detectives were investigating the Rickman death on Monroe
Avenue early New Year's Day, a bullet tore into a nearby shed,
Young said. Another police officer who returned to his car on New
Year's morning after working overnight found a bullet hole in the
hood of his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think the chances are slim'' that a random skyward shot
would cause problems, Young said. ``But shooting a gun and not
knowing where the bullet's going to end up is probably one of the
stupidest things you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stray bullets pose varying levels of threat to bystanders,
depending on factors such as the trajectory, the make of the gun,
the weight of the bullet and the amount of powder used.
</P>
<P>
   A bullet shot straight overhead would be very unlikely to kill
anyone on its way down, said Bill Newhouse, who works in the
firearms section of the Kansas City police crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that particular circumstance, it would hurt like hell, but
almost certainly wouldn't penetrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullets generally need to travel at 200 feet or more feet per
second to break the skin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullets fired along a more horizontal trajectory can do a great
deal more damage. There is a great deal of variation in their
muzzle velocities, or the speed at which bullets leave the weapon.
Bullets from .38-caliber revolvers travel between 600 and 800 feet
per second, Newhouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Rifle bullets generally have much higher velocities than
handguns, traveling between about 1800 and 4000 feet per second,
depending on bullet weight and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   A bullet fired from an AK-47 or similar assault rifle would
hurtle out of the muzzle about 2300 feet per second. After 100
yards, the length of a football field, it would have slowed to
about 2000 feet per second. At 500 yards, or a little more than a
quarter of a mile, it would be traveling at 1200 feet per second,
according to Newhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
