<SLUG> BC-UNION-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW CHIEF USES CONTRACT ISSUES TO RECAPTURE POLITICAL SWAY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Mich., Wash.)   (Subs 7th graf for insert about union's upcoming meeting to
endorse presidential candidate) 
(jw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In the past, presidents of the United Automobile
Workers union, men like Walter Reuther and Douglas Fraser, were
well-known national figures not just because they could shut down
the world's largest companies but because they were politically
influential and frequently on television.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Yokich, the union's president since 1995, has taken a
very different approach, shunning the limelight and focusing on
contract issues. Believing that he can communicate most effectively
with his members through local union leaders, he has said virtually
nothing in public during strikes and other showdowns with
automakers. While he has visited Washington frequently to discuss
issues like trade and global warming, he has favored private
meetings with politicians to parades and news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   But now Yokich is trying to rebuild the political power of the
union, most notably by negotiating paid holidays for 400,000
workers at General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler on Election Day
in 2000 and 2002. The prospect that more union workers might turn
out to vote, hand out pamphlets and drive other Democrats to
polling booths has alarmed Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The tricky part for Yokich, pollsters and politicians said, will
be persuading the rank and file to vote for candidates endorsed by
union leaders. Earning $50,000 to $120,000 a year, the union's
members are too affluent to benefit from many Democratic social
spending programs and are prosperous enough to be concerned about
income tax rates. Many members are conservative on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the leadership has tended to support Democrats, particularly
for president, perceiving them as more friendly on workers' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich said the union must emphasize political concerns that
apply to all members and transcend partisan politics. ``We support
those who support us; the party doesn't matter,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Two such concerns, he said, are international trade and global
warming. The problem is that neither former Sen. Bill Bradley nor
Vice President Al Gore has taken his positions on either issue. The
union will endorse a presidential candidate next month; it had
opposed the AFL-CIO's decision to endorse Gore early in October.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich advocates balancing free trade with what he calls ``fair
trade,'' requiring other countries to follow rules on safety, the
environment, and workers' rights to form unions that are similar to
rules in the United States. He is particularly critical of the
North American Free Trade Agreement, which he says has destroyed
more high-paying jobs than it has created, an assertion questioned
by many economists.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley and Gore have long track records of supporting free
trade. Yokich said he was disappointed that they were not at a
peaceful protest by union members at the recent meeting of the
World Trade Organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Global warming is another difficult issue for Yokich.
Automobiles contribute to global warming with each gallon of
gasoline they burn, so environmentalists have begun lobbying for
more stringent fuel-economy regulations.
</P>
<P>
   But the union contends that tighter fuel economy rules are
unnecessary because many other industries contribute to the problem
and because developing nations have not agreed to limits on their
emissions of the gases linked to global warming. Bradley and
particularly Gore have both called for tighter fuel-economy rules.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley has not been as outspoken as Gore on the
environment, he supported a Senate resolution calling for much
stiffer fuel-economy rules on sport utility vehicles and other
light trucks, which are allowed much worse fuel economy than cars.
The measure was narrowly defeated on Sept. 15 after the union
joined automakers in strenuous lobbying against it.
</P>
<P>
   Yokich said he had expressed concerns to Gore about the Clinton
administration's policies on global warming, but quickly added that
he considered himself a friend of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to the Sierra Club, so you can't just say, `he's about
jobs for his members','' Yokich said. ``I belong to the Sierra
Club, I belong to Ducks Unlimited.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fraser said that Yokich had to become more active politically
because the most pressing issues facing the union _ like
international competition, environmental protections and health
care _ could not be settled at the bargaining table with
automakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of the members of the UAW rests with Congress and
the legislative process more than it ever did in the past,'' Fraser
said. ``That's why you have to get more involved in the political
process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
