<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE RNEW BATTLE IN A WARM-UP FOR A PAIR OF DEBATES
THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President
Al Gore, 1,125 miles apart, argued on Monday about the virtues of
experience and accused each other of having a vision too limited to
deal with problems that concern most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only those who have never left Washington have missed the
lessons of the last decade,'' Bradley told an audience of 400 here.
The audience first giggled and then applauded at the obvious
reference to Gore, who has held office in Washington since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only those who have embodied the ways of Washington have
failed to notice that Americans see Washington as a place that has
nothing to do with their lives,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, before 1,000 students and supporters in
Davenport, Iowa, Gore accused Bradley of a passivity born of a
sense of defeatism and impracticality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is not an academic exercise,'' Gore said.
``It's not a seminar where you get to entertain a single grand
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic presidential hopefuls, who were resuming
their campaigns after the holiday, will debate in person twice this
week, on Wednesday in Manchester and on Saturday in Des Moines,
Iowa. On Monday, they warmed up, in speeches their staffs
advertised as important, with the ideas they think will play best
in Iowa's Jan. 24 caucuses and New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley approach reflected some of the anti-Washington
themes that won primaries here for Jimmy Carter in 1976, Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and Pat Buchanan in 1996. In a line that recalled
Carter's promise to provide a government as ``full of love as the
American people,'' Bradley said, ``I'm not prepared to settle for
anything less than America realizing the potential embodied in our
ideals, in the creativity of our minds and the goodness of our
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Without directly naming his rival, Bradley called the vice
president no more than a tinkerer. He referred briefly to his major
campaign proposals: providing universal access to health insurance,
ending child poverty, putting 600,000 new teachers in public
schools, registering all handguns and reforming the campaign
finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a comment that the audience took to be aimed at Gore,
he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those voices that say we cannot do big things any
more, that we must tinker around the edges offering small solutions
to big problems. But I say now is not the time to be timid. Above
all, now is not the time to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took on his rival much more bluntly, scoffing at his
emphasis on health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley,'' he said, ``seems to believe that America
should address only one thing at a time, or only a very small
number of things at a time, health care is the only challenge
deserving of a comprehensive proposed solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise of America,'' Gore added, ``means more than a
single proposal, done in the wrong way, at a price that leaves us
helpless to take on other great national priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Bradley's approach was, if not un-American, at
least un-Democratic: ``Can you imagine John Kennedy saying, `We
have to fight the cold war; we can't explore the heavens or put a
man on the moon?' He knew we could do more. Can you imagine Lyndon
Johnson saying, `We can wage war on poverty, but we'll have to
postpone the creation of Medicare and Medicaid. He knew we could do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The characterization of Bradley as a man of ``limited vision''
was meant to puncture the altitude that the former senator has
gained with his call for universal health insurance. The Gore
campaign is worried that this is undermining support for the vice
president, who is offering a more incremental approach.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gore seized on Bradley's self-proclaimed affinity
for Ronald Reagan as an advocate for a few big ideas, belittling a
Bradley administration as lacking the kind of can-do American
spirit that Gore promised to bring to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As he chastised Bradley for having only one big idea in health
care, he promoted his own education plan in hyperbolic terms,
saying it would ``bring the greatest single increase in our federal
commitment to education since the G.I. Bill, and the greatest
single increase in our federal comitment to pre-K through 12
education since the beginning of public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He then turned Bradley's language against him, dismissing
Bradley's education proposals in nearly identical phrasing that
Bradley has used to describe the vice president. ``We can't settle
for the minor extension of a few existing programs,'' Gore said.
``We can't settle for simply nibbling around the edges.''
</P>
<P>
   And he emphasized the theme that he is a fighter, fighting both
for the nomination and suggesting that as president he would fight
for the country. In an aside that revealed something of his
combative strategy, Gore told the audience: ``How one campaigns is
some prediction of how one might serve.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, cultivating the rocky New Hampshire soil of
anti-Washington feeling requires a bit of juggling, since he served
in the Senate for 18 years and boasts of his experience there as
evidence that he can get things done. So he emphasizes the years
since he retired in 1995 as a time when he got reacquainted with a
nation that has ``an abiding sense that Washington -doesn't have a
clue as to where people really live their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a state where he may be ahead because independents
can vote in the Democratic primary, Bradley attacked Washington,
and, by implication, Gore, for excessive partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only those who have been mired in the battles of partisanship
have failed to realize that Americans are tired of partisanship,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he has before, Gore suggested on Monday that Bradley made a
cowardly retreat, not an intellectual exploration, when he retired
from the Senate. Speaking of the seven-year Clinton-Gore economic
record, he said, ``There were many good individuals _ even in high
places in our own party _ who thought that it couldn't be done.
When Senator Bradley retired from the Senate during President
Clinton's first term, he spoke about a `budget stalemate,' of a
political process that was, and I quote, `paralyzed' . . . on
creating jobs, on reforming welfare . . . a continual deadlock. And
he said that part of the problem was that Democrats `cling to old
programs.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's other main topic on Monday, raised perhaps as a
counter to Gore's experience in the area, was the contradictions of
technology, which ``brings us closer and makes us distant at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With cell phones and pagers and e-mail, we're never out of
touch, but we're not face-to-face, either,'' he said. ``We're both
more connected and more isolated. Now we have so many different
avenues of communication that about the only thing Americans do at
the same time any more is watch the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said this did not worry him because ``every new form of
information and knowledge creates more liberty, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy always benefits from more information, more
transparency, more ideas,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate closed with an effort at inspiration, though
Gore's was more programmatic. The vice president said, ``Imagine
what this country will be like when every child has health
coverage, when we save Medicare and Social Security, when we invest
in world-class public schools, when we make bold new strides for
opportunity and justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us raise our sights and broaden our vision. Let us reach
for the America that is in our dreams _ and also within our
grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley concluded by saying, ``What does it profit us to expand
the boundaries of knowledge if we don't expand the circle of
justice. For though we're expanding the frontiers of knowledge, the
coordinates of the human heart remain the same, and that is the
ultimate challenge of politics, to touch the goodness that is in
all our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living in an age of new possibilities,'' he said.
``Some people say we can never achieve our special destiny, but I
say, in a world of new possibilities, guided by goodness, we can
and we will.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
