<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEINBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESHAJAHU WEINBERG, 81, LED JEWISH MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jeshajahu Weinberg, the first director of the U.S.
Holocaust Memorial Museum here and one of the principal forces
behind its creation, died on Saturday in Ichilov Hospital in Tel
Aviv, Israel. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg served as the museum's director from its beginning in
1989 until 1995, as it became one of Washington's leading tourist
attractions. He also helped to create museums in Israel and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Reich, who succeeded Weinberg as director of the
Washington museum, said Monday that Weinberg's interests in it went
from inducing a British television documentary maker to design the
exhibitions to worrying about the impact that a museum depicting
the Nazi horrors might have on children who visit it and curators
who work there.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg, whose first name was pronounced ye-sha-YAH-hu but who
was known as Shaike (pronounced SHY-ka), was born in Warsaw and
educated in Germany until his family fled to Palestine in the 1930s
with the rise of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg served from 1935 to 1948 in the Jewish underground
army, the Haganah, and from 1942 to 1946 in the Jewish Brigade of
the British army, although the Haganah and the British army were
frequently at odds. He fought in Italy while in the British army
and became a sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Smith, the documentary filmmaker who designed the
exhibitions, said from his home in Bristol, England, that Albert
Abramson, one of the museum's founders, had suggested to Weinberg
that Smith would make the ideal designer of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't Jewish, I wasn't museum inclined, and I wasn't
American,'' Smith said, but Weinberg was persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He encouraged me to look at how the techniques of documentary
filmmaking could be used in a museum setting,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's architect, James I. Freed, also described how
Weinberg had driven the design and construction of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   After a section had been built, Freed said, ``Shaike was
insistent _ he wanted a railroad freight car to be included. We had
to change the building to accommodate it. He never accepted `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   Freed added that Weinberg worked to bring together competing
constituencies that wanted to make sure their groups' sufferings
were not ignored. The groups included European Jews, Gypsies and
other ethnic groups as well as members of dissenting religions and
political parties, homosexuals and the physically and mentally
handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg was also an official of the Israeli government and
director of the Cameri Theater in Tel Aviv. He helped create the
Beth Hatefutsoth Museum of the Jewish Diaspora in Tel Aviv, where
he served as director, and the Museum of the History of the City of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, even while slowed by vascular illness, Weinberg
was working on the design of Jewish museums in Warsaw and Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Washington museum said that Weinberg's wife,
Hanna, died in 1992. Survivors include three daughters, Michal,
Mei're and Ruthie Weinberg, all of Israel; a son, Na'aman Weinberg
of California; and a grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
